Book II. An Unfortunate Gathering\
\
\
\
Chapter I. They Arrive At The Monastery\
\
\
It was a warm, bright day at the end of August. The interview with the\
elder had been fixed for half\uc0\u8208 past eleven, immediately after late mass.\
Our visitors did not take part in the service, but arrived just as it was\
over. First an elegant open carriage, drawn by two valuable horses, drove\
up with Mi\'fcsov and a distant relative of his, a young man of twenty,\
called Pyotr Fomitch Kalganov. This young man was preparing to enter the\
university. Mi\'fcsov, with whom he was staying for the time, was trying to\
persuade him to go abroad to the university of Zurich or Jena. The young\
man was still undecided. He was thoughtful and absent\uc0\u8208 minded. He was nice\u8208 \
looking, strongly built, and rather tall. There was a strange fixity in\
his gaze at times. Like all very absent\uc0\u8208 minded people he would sometimes\
stare at a person without seeing him. He was silent and rather awkward,\
but sometimes, when he was alone with any one, he became talkative and\
effusive, and would laugh at anything or nothing. But his animation\
vanished as quickly as it appeared. He was always well and even\
elaborately dressed; he had already some independent fortune and\
expectations of much more. He was a friend of Alyosha\'92s.\
\
In an ancient, jolting, but roomy, hired carriage, with a pair of old\
pinkish\uc0\u8208 gray horses, a long way behind Mi\'fcsov\'92s carriage, came Fyodor\
Pavlovitch, with his son Ivan. Dmitri was late, though he had been\
informed of the time the evening before. The visitors left their carriage\
at the hotel, outside the precincts, and went to the gates of the\
monastery on foot. Except Fyodor Pavlovitch, none of the party had ever\
seen the monastery, and Mi\'fcsov had probably not even been to church for\
thirty years. He looked about him with curiosity, together with assumed\
ease. But, except the church and the domestic buildings, though these too\
were ordinary enough, he found nothing of interest in the interior of the\
monastery. The last of the worshippers were coming out of the church,\
bareheaded and crossing themselves. Among the humbler people were a few of\
higher rank\'97two or three ladies and a very old general. They were all\
staying at the hotel. Our visitors were at once surrounded by beggars, but\
none of them gave them anything, except young Kalganov, who took a ten\uc0\u8208 \
copeck piece out of his purse, and, nervous and embarrassed\'97God knows\
why!\'97hurriedly gave it to an old woman, saying: \'93Divide it equally.\'94 None\
of his companions made any remark upon it, so that he had no reason to be\
embarrassed; but, perceiving this, he was even more overcome.\
\
It was strange that their arrival did not seem expected, and that they\
were not received with special honor, though one of them had recently made\
a donation of a thousand roubles, while another was a very wealthy and\
highly cultured landowner, upon whom all in the monastery were in a sense\
dependent, as a decision of the lawsuit might at any moment put their\
fishing rights in his hands. Yet no official personage met them.\
\
Mi\'fcsov looked absent\uc0\u8208 mindedly at the tombstones round the church, and was\
on the point of saying that the dead buried here must have paid a pretty\
penny for the right of lying in this \'93holy place,\'94 but refrained. His\
liberal irony was rapidly changing almost into anger.\
\
\'93Who the devil is there to ask in this imbecile place? We must find out,\
for time is passing,\'94 he observed suddenly, as though speaking to himself.\
\
All at once there came up a bald\uc0\u8208 headed, elderly man with ingratiating\
little eyes, wearing a full, summer overcoat. Lifting his hat, he\
introduced himself with a honeyed lisp as Maximov, a landowner of Tula. He\
at once entered into our visitors\'92 difficulty.\
\
\'93Father Zossima lives in the hermitage, apart, four hundred paces from the\
monastery, the other side of the copse.\'94\
\
\'93I know it\'92s the other side of the copse,\'94 observed Fyodor Pavlovitch,\
\'93but we don\'92t remember the way. It is a long time since we\'92ve been here.\'94\
\
\'93This way, by this gate, and straight across the copse ... the copse. Come\
with me, won\'92t you? I\'92ll show you. I have to go.... I am going myself.\
This way, this way.\'94\
\
They came out of the gate and turned towards the copse. Maximov, a man of\
sixty, ran rather than walked, turning sideways to stare at them all, with\
an incredible degree of nervous curiosity. His eyes looked starting out of\
his head.\
\
\'93You see, we have come to the elder upon business of our own,\'94 observed\
Mi\'fcsov severely. \'93That personage has granted us an audience, so to speak,\
and so, though we thank you for showing us the way, we cannot ask you to\
accompany us.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92ve been there. I\'92ve been already; _un chevalier parfait_,\'94 and Maximov\
snapped his fingers in the air.\
\
\'93Who is a _chevalier_?\'94 asked Mi\'fcsov.\
\
\'93The elder, the splendid elder, the elder! The honor and glory of the\
monastery, Zossima. Such an elder!\'94\
\
But his incoherent talk was cut short by a very pale, wan\uc0\u8208 looking monk of\
medium height, wearing a monk\'92s cap, who overtook them. Fyodor Pavlovitch\
and Mi\'fcsov stopped.\
\
The monk, with an extremely courteous, profound bow, announced:\
\
\'93The Father Superior invites all of you gentlemen to dine with him after\
your visit to the hermitage. At one o\'92clock, not later. And you also,\'94 he\
added, addressing Maximov.\
\
\'93That I certainly will, without fail,\'94 cried Fyodor Pavlovitch, hugely\
delighted at the invitation. \'93And, believe me, we\'92ve all given our word to\
behave properly here.... And you, Pyotr Alexandrovitch, will you go, too?\'94\
\
\'93Yes, of course. What have I come for but to study all the customs here?\
The only obstacle to me is your company....\'94\
\
\'93Yes, Dmitri Fyodorovitch is non\uc0\u8208 existent as yet.\'94\
\
\'93It would be a capital thing if he didn\'92t turn up. Do you suppose I like\
all this business, and in your company, too? So we will come to dinner.\
Thank the Father Superior,\'94 he said to the monk.\
\
\'93No, it is my duty now to conduct you to the elder,\'94 answered the monk.\
\
\'93If so I\'92ll go straight to the Father Superior\'97to the Father Superior,\'94\
babbled Maximov.\
\
\'93The Father Superior is engaged just now. But as you please\'97\'94 the monk\
hesitated.\
\
\'93Impertinent old man!\'94 Mi\'fcsov observed aloud, while Maximov ran back to\
the monastery.\
\
\'93He\'92s like von Sohn,\'94 Fyodor Pavlovitch said suddenly.\
\
\'93Is that all you can think of?... In what way is he like von Sohn? Have\
you ever seen von Sohn?\'94\
\
\'93I\'92ve seen his portrait. It\'92s not the features, but something indefinable.\
He\'92s a second von Sohn. I can always tell from the physiognomy.\'94\
\
\'93Ah, I dare say you are a connoisseur in that. But, look here, Fyodor\
Pavlovitch, you said just now that we had given our word to behave\
properly. Remember it. I advise you to control yourself. But, if you begin\
to play the fool I don\'92t intend to be associated with you here.... You see\
what a man he is\'94\'97he turned to the monk\'97\'93I\'92m afraid to go among decent\
people with him.\'94 A fine smile, not without a certain slyness, came on to\
the pale, bloodless lips of the monk, but he made no reply, and was\
evidently silent from a sense of his own dignity. Mi\'fcsov frowned more than\
ever.\
\
\'93Oh, devil take them all! An outer show elaborated through centuries, and\
nothing but charlatanism and nonsense underneath,\'94 flashed through\
Mi\'fcsov\'92s mind.\
\
\'93Here\'92s the hermitage. We\'92ve arrived,\'94 cried Fyodor Pavlovitch. \'93The gates\
are shut.\'94\
\
And he repeatedly made the sign of the cross to the saints painted above\
and on the sides of the gates.\
\
\'93When you go to Rome you must do as the Romans do. Here in this hermitage\
there are twenty\uc0\u8208 five saints being saved. They look at one another, and\
eat cabbages. And not one woman goes in at this gate. That\'92s what is\
remarkable. And that really is so. But I did hear that the elder receives\
ladies,\'94 he remarked suddenly to the monk.\
\
\'93Women of the people are here too now, lying in the portico there waiting.\
But for ladies of higher rank two rooms have been built adjoining the\
portico, but outside the precincts\'97you can see the windows\'97and the elder\
goes out to them by an inner passage when he is well enough. They are\
always outside the precincts. There is a Harkov lady, Madame Hohlakov,\
waiting there now with her sick daughter. Probably he has promised to come\
out to her, though of late he has been so weak that he has hardly shown\
himself even to the people.\'94\
\
\'93So then there are loopholes, after all, to creep out of the hermitage to\
the ladies. Don\'92t suppose, holy father, that I mean any harm. But do you\
know that at Athos not only the visits of women are not allowed, but no\
creature of the female sex\'97no hens, nor turkey\uc0\u8208 hens, nor cows.\'94\
\
\'93Fyodor Pavlovitch, I warn you I shall go back and leave you here. They\'92ll\
turn you out when I\'92m gone.\'94\
\
\'93But I\'92m not interfering with you, Pyotr Alexandrovitch. Look,\'94 he cried\
suddenly, stepping within the precincts, \'93what a vale of roses they live\
in!\'94\
\
Though there were no roses now, there were numbers of rare and beautiful\
autumn flowers growing wherever there was space for them, and evidently\
tended by a skillful hand; there were flower\uc0\u8208 beds round the church, and\
between the tombs; and the one\uc0\u8208 storied wooden house where the elder lived\
was also surrounded with flowers.\
\
\'93And was it like this in the time of the last elder, Varsonofy? He didn\'92t\
care for such elegance. They say he used to jump up and thrash even ladies\
with a stick,\'94 observed Fyodor Pavlovitch, as he went up the steps.\
\
\'93The elder Varsonofy did sometimes seem rather strange, but a great deal\
that\'92s told is foolishness. He never thrashed any one,\'94 answered the monk.\
\'93Now, gentlemen, if you will wait a minute I will announce you.\'94\
\
\'93Fyodor Pavlovitch, for the last time, your compact, do you hear? Behave\
properly or I will pay you out!\'94 Mi\'fcsov had time to mutter again.\
\
\'93I can\'92t think why you are so agitated,\'94 Fyodor Pavlovitch observed\
sarcastically. \'93Are you uneasy about your sins? They say he can tell by\
one\'92s eyes what one has come about. And what a lot you think of their\
opinion! you, a Parisian, and so advanced. I\'92m surprised at you.\'94\
\
But Mi\'fcsov had no time to reply to this sarcasm. They were asked to come\
in. He walked in, somewhat irritated.\
\
\'93Now, I know myself, I am annoyed, I shall lose my temper and begin to\
quarrel\'97and lower myself and my ideas,\'94 he reflected.\
\
\
\
Chapter II. The Old Buffoon\
\
\
They entered the room almost at the same moment that the elder came in\
from his bedroom. There were already in the cell, awaiting the elder, two\
monks of the hermitage, one the Father Librarian, and the other Father\
Pa\'efssy, a very learned man, so they said, in delicate health, though not\
old. There was also a tall young man, who looked about two and twenty,\
standing in the corner throughout the interview. He had a broad, fresh\
face, and clever, observant, narrow brown eyes, and was wearing ordinary\
dress. He was a divinity student, living under the protection of the\
monastery. His expression was one of unquestioning, but self\uc0\u8208 respecting,\
reverence. Being in a subordinate and dependent position, and so not on an\
equality with the guests, he did not greet them with a bow.\
\
Father Zossima was accompanied by a novice, and by Alyosha. The two monks\
rose and greeted him with a very deep bow, touching the ground with their\
fingers; then kissed his hand. Blessing them, the elder replied with as\
deep a reverence to them, and asked their blessing. The whole ceremony was\
performed very seriously and with an appearance of feeling, not like an\
everyday rite. But Mi\'fcsov fancied that it was all done with intentional\
impressiveness. He stood in front of the other visitors. He ought\'97he had\
reflected upon it the evening before\'97from simple politeness, since it was\
the custom here, to have gone up to receive the elder\'92s blessing, even if\
he did not kiss his hand. But when he saw all this bowing and kissing on\
the part of the monks he instantly changed his mind. With dignified\
gravity he made a rather deep, conventional bow, and moved away to a\
chair. Fyodor Pavlovitch did the same, mimicking Mi\'fcsov like an ape. Ivan\
bowed with great dignity and courtesy, but he too kept his hands at his\
sides, while Kalganov was so confused that he did not bow at all. The\
elder let fall the hand raised to bless them, and bowing to them again,\
asked them all to sit down. The blood rushed to Alyosha\'92s cheeks. He was\
ashamed. His forebodings were coming true.\
\
Father Zossima sat down on a very old\uc0\u8208 fashioned mahogany sofa, covered\
with leather, and made his visitors sit down in a row along the opposite\
wall on four mahogany chairs, covered with shabby black leather. The monks\
sat, one at the door and the other at the window. The divinity student,\
the novice, and Alyosha remained standing. The cell was not very large and\
had a faded look. It contained nothing but the most necessary furniture,\
of coarse and poor quality. There were two pots of flowers in the window,\
and a number of holy pictures in the corner. Before one huge ancient ikon\
of the Virgin a lamp was burning. Near it were two other holy pictures in\
shining settings, and, next them, carved cherubims, china eggs, a Catholic\
cross of ivory, with a Mater Dolorosa embracing it, and several foreign\
engravings from the great Italian artists of past centuries. Next to these\
costly and artistic engravings were several of the roughest Russian prints\
of saints and martyrs, such as are sold for a few farthings at all the\
fairs. On the other walls were portraits of Russian bishops, past and\
present.\
\
Mi\'fcsov took a cursory glance at all these \'93conventional\'94 surroundings and\
bent an intent look upon the elder. He had a high opinion of his own\
insight, a weakness excusable in him as he was fifty, an age at which a\
clever man of the world of established position can hardly help taking\
himself rather seriously. At the first moment he did not like Zossima.\
There was, indeed, something in the elder\'92s face which many people besides\
Mi\'fcsov might not have liked. He was a short, bent, little man, with very\
weak legs, and though he was only sixty\uc0\u8208 five, he looked at least ten years\
older. His face was very thin and covered with a network of fine wrinkles,\
particularly numerous about his eyes, which were small, light\uc0\u8208 colored,\
quick, and shining like two bright points. He had a sprinkling of gray\
hair about his temples. His pointed beard was small and scanty, and his\
lips, which smiled frequently, were as thin as two threads. His nose was\
not long, but sharp, like a bird\'92s beak.\
\
\'93To all appearances a malicious soul, full of petty pride,\'94 thought\
Mi\'fcsov. He felt altogether dissatisfied with his position.\
\
A cheap little clock on the wall struck twelve hurriedly, and served to\
begin the conversation.\
\
\'93Precisely to our time,\'94 cried Fyodor Pavlovitch, \'93but no sign of my son,\
Dmitri. I apologize for him, sacred elder!\'94 (Alyosha shuddered all over at\
\'93sacred elder.\'94) \'93I am always punctual myself, minute for minute,\
remembering that punctuality is the courtesy of kings....\'94\
\
\'93But you are not a king, anyway,\'94 Mi\'fcsov muttered, losing his self\uc0\u8208 \
restraint at once.\
\
\'93Yes; that\'92s true. I\'92m not a king, and, would you believe it, Pyotr\
Alexandrovitch, I was aware of that myself. But, there! I always say the\
wrong thing. Your reverence,\'94 he cried, with sudden pathos, \'93you behold\
before you a buffoon in earnest! I introduce myself as such. It\'92s an old\
habit, alas! And if I sometimes talk nonsense out of place it\'92s with an\
object, with the object of amusing people and making myself agreeable. One\
must be agreeable, mustn\'92t one? I was seven years ago in a little town\
where I had business, and I made friends with some merchants there. We\
went to the captain of police because we had to see him about something,\
and to ask him to dine with us. He was a tall, fat, fair, sulky man, the\
most dangerous type in such cases. It\'92s their liver. I went straight up to\
him, and with the ease of a man of the world, you know, \'91Mr. Ispravnik,\'92\
said I, \'91be our Napravnik.\'92 \'91What do you mean by Napravnik?\'92 said he. I\
saw, at the first half\uc0\u8208 second, that it had missed fire. He stood there so\
glum. \'91I wanted to make a joke,\'92 said I, \'91for the general diversion, as\
Mr. Napravnik is our well\uc0\u8208 known Russian orchestra conductor and what we\
need for the harmony of our undertaking is some one of that sort.\'92 And I\
explained my comparison very reasonably, didn\'92t I? \'91Excuse me,\'92 said he,\
\'91I am an Ispravnik, and I do not allow puns to be made on my calling.\'92 He\
turned and walked away. I followed him, shouting, \'91Yes, yes, you are an\
Ispravnik, not a Napravnik.\'92 \'91No,\'92 he said, \'91since you called me a\
Napravnik I am one.\'92 And would you believe it, it ruined our business! And\
I\'92m always like that, always like that. Always injuring myself with my\
politeness. Once, many years ago, I said to an influential person: \'91Your\
wife is a ticklish lady,\'92 in an honorable sense, of the moral qualities,\
so to speak. But he asked me, \'91Why, have you tickled her?\'92 I thought I\'92d\
be polite, so I couldn\'92t help saying, \'91Yes,\'92 and he gave me a fine\
tickling on the spot. Only that happened long ago, so I\'92m not ashamed to\
tell the story. I\'92m always injuring myself like that.\'94\
\
\'93You\'92re doing it now,\'94 muttered Mi\'fcsov, with disgust.\
\
Father Zossima scrutinized them both in silence.\
\
\'93Am I? Would you believe it, I was aware of that, too, Pyotr\
Alexandrovitch, and let me tell you, indeed, I foresaw I should as soon as\
I began to speak. And do you know I foresaw, too, that you\'92d be the first\
to remark on it. The minute I see my joke isn\'92t coming off, your\
reverence, both my cheeks feel as though they were drawn down to the lower\
jaw and there is almost a spasm in them. That\'92s been so since I was young,\
when I had to make jokes for my living in noblemen\'92s families. I am an\
inveterate buffoon, and have been from birth up, your reverence, it\'92s as\
though it were a craze in me. I dare say it\'92s a devil within me. But only\
a little one. A more serious one would have chosen another lodging. But\
not your soul, Pyotr Alexandrovitch; you\'92re not a lodging worth having\
either. But I do believe\'97I believe in God, though I have had doubts of\
late. But now I sit and await words of wisdom. I\'92m like the philosopher,\
Diderot, your reverence. Did you ever hear, most Holy Father, how Diderot\
went to see the Metropolitan Platon, in the time of the Empress Catherine?\
He went in and said straight out, \'91There is no God.\'92 To which the great\
bishop lifted up his finger and answered, \'91The fool hath said in his heart\
there is no God.\'92 And he fell down at his feet on the spot. \'91I believe,\'92\
he cried, \'91and will be christened.\'92 And so he was. Princess Dashkov was\
his godmother, and Potyomkin his godfather.\'94\
\
\'93Fyodor Pavlovitch, this is unbearable! You know you\'92re telling lies and\
that that stupid anecdote isn\'92t true. Why are you playing the fool?\'94 cried\
Mi\'fcsov in a shaking voice.\
\
\'93I suspected all my life that it wasn\'92t true,\'94 Fyodor Pavlovitch cried\
with conviction. \'93But I\'92ll tell you the whole truth, gentlemen. Great\
elder! Forgive me, the last thing about Diderot\'92s christening I made up\
just now. I never thought of it before. I made it up to add piquancy. I\
play the fool, Pyotr Alexandrovitch, to make myself agreeable. Though I\
really don\'92t know myself, sometimes, what I do it for. And as for Diderot,\
I heard as far as \'91the fool hath said in his heart\'92 twenty times from the\
gentry about here when I was young. I heard your aunt, Pyotr\
Alexandrovitch, tell the story. They all believe to this day that the\
infidel Diderot came to dispute about God with the Metropolitan\
Platon....\'94\
\
Mi\'fcsov got up, forgetting himself in his impatience. He was furious, and\
conscious of being ridiculous.\
\
What was taking place in the cell was really incredible. For forty or\
fifty years past, from the times of former elders, no visitors had entered\
that cell without feelings of the profoundest veneration. Almost every one\
admitted to the cell felt that a great favor was being shown him. Many\
remained kneeling during the whole visit. Of those visitors, many had been\
men of high rank and learning, some even freethinkers, attracted by\
curiosity, but all without exception had shown the profoundest reverence\
and delicacy, for here there was no question of money, but only, on the\
one side love and kindness, and on the other penitence and eager desire to\
decide some spiritual problem or crisis. So that such buffoonery amazed\
and bewildered the spectators, or at least some of them. The monks, with\
unchanged countenances, waited, with earnest attention, to hear what the\
elder would say, but seemed on the point of standing up, like Mi\'fcsov.\
Alyosha stood, with hanging head, on the verge of tears. What seemed to\
him strangest of all was that his brother Ivan, on whom alone he had\
rested his hopes, and who alone had such influence on his father that he\
could have stopped him, sat now quite unmoved, with downcast eyes,\
apparently waiting with interest to see how it would end, as though he had\
nothing to do with it. Alyosha did not dare to look at Rakitin, the\
divinity student, whom he knew almost intimately. He alone in the\
monastery knew Rakitin\'92s thoughts.\
\
\'93Forgive me,\'94 began Mi\'fcsov, addressing Father Zossima, \'93for perhaps I seem\
to be taking part in this shameful foolery. I made a mistake in believing\
that even a man like Fyodor Pavlovitch would understand what was due on a\
visit to so honored a personage. I did not suppose I should have to\
apologize simply for having come with him....\'94\
\
Pyotr Alexandrovitch could say no more, and was about to leave the room,\
overwhelmed with confusion.\
\
\'93Don\'92t distress yourself, I beg.\'94 The elder got on to his feeble legs, and\
taking Pyotr Alexandrovitch by both hands, made him sit down again. \'93I beg\
you not to disturb yourself. I particularly beg you to be my guest.\'94 And\
with a bow he went back and sat down again on his little sofa.\
\
\'93Great elder, speak! Do I annoy you by my vivacity?\'94 Fyodor Pavlovitch\
cried suddenly, clutching the arms of his chair in both hands, as though\
ready to leap up from it if the answer were unfavorable.\
\
\'93I earnestly beg you, too, not to disturb yourself, and not to be uneasy,\'94\
the elder said impressively. \'93Do not trouble. Make yourself quite at home.\
And, above all, do not be so ashamed of yourself, for that is at the root\
of it all.\'94\
\
\'93Quite at home? To be my natural self? Oh, that is much too much, but I\
accept it with grateful joy. Do you know, blessed Father, you\'92d better not\
invite me to be my natural self. Don\'92t risk it.... I will not go so far as\
that myself. I warn you for your own sake. Well, the rest is still plunged\
in the mists of uncertainty, though there are people who\'92d be pleased to\
describe me for you. I mean that for you, Pyotr Alexandrovitch. But as for\
you, holy being, let me tell you, I am brimming over with ecstasy.\'94\
\
He got up, and throwing up his hands, declaimed, \'93Blessed be the womb that\
bare thee, and the paps that gave thee suck\'97the paps especially. When you\
said just now, \'91Don\'92t be so ashamed of yourself, for that is at the root\
of it all,\'92 you pierced right through me by that remark, and read me to\
the core. Indeed, I always feel when I meet people that I am lower than\
all, and that they all take me for a buffoon. So I say, \'91Let me really\
play the buffoon. I am not afraid of your opinion, for you are every one\
of you worse than I am.\'92 That is why I am a buffoon. It is from shame,\
great elder, from shame; it\'92s simply over\uc0\u8208 sensitiveness that makes me\
rowdy. If I had only been sure that every one would accept me as the\
kindest and wisest of men, oh, Lord, what a good man I should have been\
then! Teacher!\'94 he fell suddenly on his knees, \'93what must I do to gain\
eternal life?\'94\
\
It was difficult even now to decide whether he was joking or really moved.\
\
Father Zossima, lifting his eyes, looked at him, and said with a smile:\
\
\'93You have known for a long time what you must do. You have sense enough:\
don\'92t give way to drunkenness and incontinence of speech; don\'92t give way\
to sensual lust; and, above all, to the love of money. And close your\
taverns. If you can\'92t close all, at least two or three. And, above\
all\'97don\'92t lie.\'94\
\
\'93You mean about Diderot?\'94\
\
\'93No, not about Diderot. Above all, don\'92t lie to yourself. The man who lies\
to himself and listens to his own lie comes to such a pass that he cannot\
distinguish the truth within him, or around him, and so loses all respect\
for himself and for others. And having no respect he ceases to love, and\
in order to occupy and distract himself without love he gives way to\
passions and coarse pleasures, and sinks to bestiality in his vices, all\
from continual lying to other men and to himself. The man who lies to\
himself can be more easily offended than any one. You know it is sometimes\
very pleasant to take offense, isn\'92t it? A man may know that nobody has\
insulted him, but that he has invented the insult for himself, has lied\
and exaggerated to make it picturesque, has caught at a word and made a\
mountain out of a molehill\'97he knows that himself, yet he will be the first\
to take offense, and will revel in his resentment till he feels great\
pleasure in it, and so pass to genuine vindictiveness. But get up, sit\
down, I beg you. All this, too, is deceitful posturing....\'94\
\
\'93Blessed man! Give me your hand to kiss.\'94\
\
Fyodor Pavlovitch skipped up, and imprinted a rapid kiss on the elder\'92s\
thin hand. \'93It is, it is pleasant to take offense. You said that so well,\
as I never heard it before. Yes, I have been all my life taking offense,\
to please myself, taking offense on esthetic grounds, for it is not so\
much pleasant as distinguished sometimes to be insulted\'97that you had\
forgotten, great elder, it is distinguished! I shall make a note of that.\
But I have been lying, lying positively my whole life long, every day and\
hour of it. Of a truth, I am a lie, and the father of lies. Though I\
believe I am not the father of lies. I am getting mixed in my texts. Say,\
the son of lies, and that will be enough. Only ... my angel ... I may\
sometimes talk about Diderot! Diderot will do no harm, though sometimes a\
word will do harm. Great elder, by the way, I was forgetting, though I had\
been meaning for the last two years to come here on purpose to ask and to\
find out something. Only do tell Pyotr Alexandrovitch not to interrupt me.\
Here is my question: Is it true, great Father, that the story is told\
somewhere in the _Lives of the Saints_ of a holy saint martyred for his\
faith who, when his head was cut off at last, stood up, picked up his\
head, and, \'91courteously kissing it,\'92 walked a long way, carrying it in his\
hands. Is that true or not, honored Father?\'94\
\
\'93No, it is untrue,\'94 said the elder.\
\
\'93There is nothing of the kind in all the lives of the saints. What saint\
do you say the story is told of?\'94 asked the Father Librarian.\
\
\'93I do not know what saint. I do not know, and can\'92t tell. I was deceived.\
I was told the story. I had heard it, and do you know who told it? Pyotr\
Alexandrovitch Mi\'fcsov here, who was so angry just now about Diderot. He it\
was who told the story.\'94\
\
\'93I have never told it you, I never speak to you at all.\'94\
\
\'93It is true you did not tell me, but you told it when I was present. It\
was three years ago. I mentioned it because by that ridiculous story you\
shook my faith, Pyotr Alexandrovitch. You knew nothing of it, but I went\
home with my faith shaken, and I have been getting more and more shaken\
ever since. Yes, Pyotr Alexandrovitch, you were the cause of a great fall.\
That was not a Diderot!\'94\
\
Fyodor Pavlovitch got excited and pathetic, though it was perfectly clear\
to every one by now that he was playing a part again. Yet Mi\'fcsov was stung\
by his words.\
\
\'93What nonsense, and it is all nonsense,\'94 he muttered. \'93I may really have\
told it, some time or other ... but not to you. I was told it myself. I\
heard it in Paris from a Frenchman. He told me it was read at our mass\
from the _Lives of the Saints_ ... he was a very learned man who had made\
a special study of Russian statistics and had lived a long time in\
Russia.... I have not read the _Lives of the Saints_ myself, and I am not\
going to read them ... all sorts of things are said at dinner\'97we were\
dining then.\'94\
\
\'93Yes, you were dining then, and so I lost my faith!\'94 said Fyodor\
Pavlovitch, mimicking him.\
\
\'93What do I care for your faith?\'94 Mi\'fcsov was on the point of shouting, but\
he suddenly checked himself, and said with contempt, \'93You defile\
everything you touch.\'94\
\
The elder suddenly rose from his seat. \'93Excuse me, gentlemen, for leaving\
you a few minutes,\'94 he said, addressing all his guests. \'93I have visitors\
awaiting me who arrived before you. But don\'92t you tell lies all the same,\'94\
he added, turning to Fyodor Pavlovitch with a good\uc0\u8208 humored face. He went\
out of the cell. Alyosha and the novice flew to escort him down the steps.\
Alyosha was breathless: he was glad to get away, but he was glad, too,\
that the elder was good\uc0\u8208 humored and not offended. Father Zossima was going\
towards the portico to bless the people waiting for him there. But Fyodor\
Pavlovitch persisted in stopping him at the door of the cell.\
\
\'93Blessed man!\'94 he cried, with feeling. \'93Allow me to kiss your hand once\
more. Yes, with you I could still talk, I could still get on. Do you think\
I always lie and play the fool like this? Believe me, I have been acting\
like this all the time on purpose to try you. I have been testing you all\
the time to see whether I could get on with you. Is there room for my\
humility beside your pride? I am ready to give you a testimonial that one\
can get on with you! But now, I\'92ll be quiet; I will keep quiet all the\
time. I\'92ll sit in a chair and hold my tongue. Now it is for you to speak,\
Pyotr Alexandrovitch. You are the principal person left now\'97for ten\
minutes.\'94\
\
