them already. And how has that Ivan won you all, so that you all worship\
him? He is laughing at you, and enjoying himself at your expense.\'94\
\
\'93How do you know? How can you speak so confidently?\'94 Alyosha asked\
sharply, frowning.\
\
\'93Why do you ask, and are frightened at my answer? It shows that you know\
I\'92m speaking the truth.\'94\
\
\'93You don\'92t like Ivan. Ivan wouldn\'92t be tempted by money.\'94\
\
\'93Really? And the beauty of Katerina Ivanovna? It\'92s not only the money,\
though a fortune of sixty thousand is an attraction.\'94\
\
\'93Ivan is above that. He wouldn\'92t make up to any one for thousands. It is\
not money, it\'92s not comfort Ivan is seeking. Perhaps it\'92s suffering he is\
seeking.\'94\
\
\'93What wild dream now? Oh, you\'97aristocrats!\'94\
\
\'93Ah, Misha, he has a stormy spirit. His mind is in bondage. He is haunted\
by a great, unsolved doubt. He is one of those who don\'92t want millions,\
but an answer to their questions.\'94\
\
\'93That\'92s plagiarism, Alyosha. You\'92re quoting your elder\'92s phrases. Ah, Ivan\
has set you a problem!\'94 cried Rakitin, with undisguised malice. His face\
changed, and his lips twitched. \'93And the problem\'92s a stupid one. It is no\
good guessing it. Rack your brains\'97you\'92ll understand it. His article is\
absurd and ridiculous. And did you hear his stupid theory just now: if\
