\
\'93There would have been no civilization if they hadn\'92t invented God.\'94\
\
\'93Wouldn\'92t there have been? Without God?\'94\
\
\'93No. And there would have been no brandy either. But I must take your\
brandy away from you, anyway.\'94\
\
\'93Stop, stop, stop, dear boy, one more little glass. I\'92ve hurt Alyosha\'92s\
feelings. You\'92re not angry with me, Alyosha? My dear little Alexey!\'94\
\
\'93No, I am not angry. I know your thoughts. Your heart is better than your\
head.\'94\
\
\'93My heart better than my head, is it? Oh, Lord! And that from you. Ivan,\
do you love Alyosha?\'94\
\
\'93Yes.\'94\
\
\'93You must love him\'94 (Fyodor Pavlovitch was by this time very drunk).\
\'93Listen, Alyosha, I was rude to your elder this morning. But I was\
excited. But there\'92s wit in that elder, don\'92t you think, Ivan?\'94\
\
\'93Very likely.\'94\
\
\'93There is, there is. _Il y a du Piron l\'e0\uc0\u8208 dedans._ He\'92s a Jesuit, a Russian\
one, that is. As he\'92s an honorable person there\'92s a hidden indignation\
