The old man persisted. He had reached that state of drunkenness when the\
drunkard who has till then been inoffensive tries to pick a quarrel and to\
assert himself.\
\
\'93Why are you looking at me? Why do you look like that? Your eyes look at\
me and say, \'91You ugly drunkard!\'92 Your eyes are mistrustful. They\'92re\
contemptuous.... You\'92ve come here with some design. Alyosha, here, looks\
at me and his eyes shine. Alyosha doesn\'92t despise me. Alexey, you mustn\'92t\
love Ivan.\'94\
\
\'93Don\'92t be ill\uc0\u8208 tempered with my brother. Leave off attacking him,\'94 Alyosha\
said emphatically.\
\
\'93Oh, all right. Ugh, my head aches. Take away the brandy, Ivan. It\'92s the\
third time I\'92ve told you.\'94\
\
He mused, and suddenly a slow, cunning grin spread over his face.\
\
\'93Don\'92t be angry with a feeble old man, Ivan. I know you don\'92t love me, but\
don\'92t be angry all the same. You\'92ve nothing to love me for. You go to\
Tchermashnya. I\'92ll come to you myself and bring you a present. I\'92ll show\
you a little wench there. I\'92ve had my eye on her a long time. She\'92s still\
running about bare\uc0\u8208 foot. Don\'92t be afraid of bare\u8208 footed wenches\'97don\'92t\
despise them\'97they\'92re pearls!\'94\
\
And he kissed his hand with a smack.\
\
\'93To my thinking,\'94 he revived at once, seeming to grow sober the instant he\
touched on his favorite topic. \'93To my thinking ... Ah, you boys! You\
children, little sucking\uc0\u8208 pigs, to my thinking ... I never thought a woman\
