\
Chapter V. A Laceration In The Drawing\uc0\u8208 Room\
\
\
But in the drawing\uc0\u8208 room the conversation was already over. Katerina\
Ivanovna was greatly excited, though she looked resolute. At the moment\
Alyosha and Madame Hohlakov entered, Ivan Fyodorovitch stood up to take\
leave. His face was rather pale, and Alyosha looked at him anxiously. For\
this moment was to solve a doubt, a harassing enigma which had for some\
time haunted Alyosha. During the preceding month it had been several times\
suggested to him that his brother Ivan was in love with Katerina Ivanovna,\
and, what was more, that he meant \'93to carry her off\'94 from Dmitri. Until\
quite lately the idea seemed to Alyosha monstrous, though it worried him\
extremely. He loved both his brothers, and dreaded such rivalry between\
them. Meantime, Dmitri had said outright on the previous day that he was\
glad that Ivan was his rival, and that it was a great assistance to him,\
Dmitri. In what way did it assist him? To marry Grushenka? But that\
Alyosha considered the worst thing possible. Besides all this, Alyosha had\
till the evening before implicitly believed that Katerina Ivanovna had a\
steadfast and passionate love for Dmitri; but he had only believed it till\
the evening before. He had fancied, too, that she was incapable of loving\
a man like Ivan, and that she did love Dmitri, and loved him just as he\
was, in spite of all the strangeness of such a passion.\
\
But during yesterday\'92s scene with Grushenka another idea had struck him.\
The word \'93lacerating,\'94 which Madame Hohlakov had just uttered, almost made\
him start, because half waking up towards daybreak that night he had cried\
out \'93Laceration, laceration,\'94 probably applying it to his dream. He had\
been dreaming all night of the previous day\'92s scene at Katerina\
Ivanovna\'92s. Now Alyosha was impressed by Madame Hohlakov\'92s blunt and\
persistent assertion that Katerina Ivanovna was in love with Ivan, and\
only deceived herself through some sort of pose, from \'93self\uc0\u8208 laceration,\'94\
and tortured herself by her pretended love for Dmitri from some fancied\
duty of gratitude. \'93Yes,\'94 he thought, \'93perhaps the whole truth lies in\
those words.\'94 But in that case what was Ivan\'92s position? Alyosha felt\
instinctively that a character like Katerina Ivanovna\'92s must dominate, and\
she could only dominate some one like Dmitri, and never a man like Ivan.\
For Dmitri might at last submit to her domination \'93to his own happiness\'94\
(which was what Alyosha would have desired), but Ivan\'97no, Ivan could not\
submit to her, and such submission would not give him happiness. Alyosha\
could not help believing that of Ivan. And now all these doubts and\
reflections flitted through his mind as he entered the drawing\uc0\u8208 room.\
Another idea, too, forced itself upon him: \'93What if she loved neither of\
them\'97neither Ivan nor Dmitri?\'94\
\
It must be noted that Alyosha felt as it were ashamed of his own thoughts\
and blamed himself when they kept recurring to him during the last month.\
\'93What do I know about love and women and how can I decide such questions?\'94\
he thought reproachfully, after such doubts and surmises. And yet it was\
impossible not to think about it. He felt instinctively that this rivalry\
was of immense importance in his brothers\'92 lives and that a great deal\
depended upon it.\
\
\'93One reptile will devour the other,\'94 Ivan had pronounced the day before,\
speaking in anger of his father and Dmitri. So Ivan looked upon Dmitri as\
a reptile, and perhaps had long done so. Was it perhaps since he had known\
Katerina Ivanovna? That phrase had, of course, escaped Ivan unawares\
yesterday, but that only made it more important. If he felt like that,\
what chance was there of peace? Were there not, on the contrary, new\
grounds for hatred and hostility in their family? And with which of them\
was Alyosha to sympathize? And what was he to wish for each of them? He\
loved them both, but what could he desire for each in the midst of these\
conflicting interests? He might go quite astray in this maze, and\
Alyosha\'92s heart could not endure uncertainty, because his love was always\
of an active character. He was incapable of passive love. If he loved any\
one, he set to work at once to help him. And to do so he must know what he\
was aiming at; he must know for certain what was best for each, and having\
ascertained this it was natural for him to help them both. But instead of\
a definite aim, he found nothing but uncertainty and perplexity on all\
sides. \'93It was lacerating,\'94 as was said just now. But what could he\
understand even in this \'93laceration\'94? He did not understand the first word\
in this perplexing maze.\
\
Seeing Alyosha, Katerina Ivanovna said quickly and joyfully to Ivan, who\
had already got up to go, \'93A minute! Stay another minute! I want to hear\
the opinion of this person here whom I trust absolutely. Don\'92t go away,\'94\
she added, addressing Madame Hohlakov. She made Alyosha sit down beside\
her, and Madame Hohlakov sat opposite, by Ivan.\
\
\'93You are all my friends here, all I have in the world, my dear friends,\'94\
she began warmly, in a voice which quivered with genuine tears of\
suffering, and Alyosha\'92s heart warmed to her at once. \'93You, Alexey\
Fyodorovitch, were witness yesterday of that abominable scene, and saw\
what I did. You did not see it, Ivan Fyodorovitch, he did. What he thought\
of me yesterday I don\'92t know. I only know one thing, that if it were\
repeated to\uc0\u8208 day, this minute, I should express the same feelings again as\
yesterday\'97the same feelings, the same words, the same actions. You\
remember my actions, Alexey Fyodorovitch; you checked me in one of them\'94\
... (as she said that, she flushed and her eyes shone). \'93I must tell you\
that I can\'92t get over it. Listen, Alexey Fyodorovitch. I don\'92t even know\
whether I still love _him_. I feel _pity_ for him, and that is a poor sign\
of love. If I loved him, if I still loved him, perhaps I shouldn\'92t be\
sorry for him now, but should hate him.\'94\
\
Her voice quivered, and tears glittered on her eyelashes. Alyosha\
shuddered inwardly. \'93That girl is truthful and sincere,\'94 he thought, \'93and\
she does not love Dmitri any more.\'94\
\
\'93That\'92s true, that\'92s true,\'94 cried Madame Hohlakov.\
\
\'93Wait, dear. I haven\'92t told you the chief, the final decision I came to\
during the night. I feel that perhaps my decision is a terrible one\'97for\
me, but I foresee that nothing will induce me to change it\'97nothing. It\
will be so all my life. My dear, kind, ever\uc0\u8208 faithful and generous adviser,\
the one friend I have in the world, Ivan Fyodorovitch, with his deep\
insight into the heart, approves and commends my decision. He knows it.\'94\
\
\'93Yes, I approve of it,\'94 Ivan assented, in a subdued but firm voice.\
\
\'93But I should like Alyosha, too (Ah! Alexey Fyodorovitch, forgive my\
calling you simply Alyosha), I should like Alexey Fyodorovitch, too, to\
tell me before my two friends whether I am right. I feel instinctively\
that you, Alyosha, my dear brother (for you are a dear brother to me),\'94\
she said again ecstatically, taking his cold hand in her hot one, \'93I\
foresee that your decision, your approval, will bring me peace, in spite\
of all my sufferings, for, after your words, I shall be calm and submit\'97I\
feel that.\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t know what you are asking me,\'94 said Alyosha, flushing. \'93I only\
know that I love you and at this moment wish for your happiness more than\
my own!... But I know nothing about such affairs,\'94 something impelled him\
to add hurriedly.\
\
\'93In such affairs, Alexey Fyodorovitch, in such affairs, the chief thing is\
honor and duty and something higher\'97I don\'92t know what\'97but higher perhaps\
even than duty. I am conscious of this irresistible feeling in my heart,\
and it compels me irresistibly. But it may all be put in two words. I\'92ve\
already decided, even if he marries that\'97creature,\'94 she began solemnly,\
\'93whom I never, never can forgive, _even then I will not abandon him_.\
Henceforward I will never, never abandon him!\'94 she cried, breaking into a\
sort of pale, hysterical ecstasy. \'93Not that I would run after him\
continually, get in his way and worry him. Oh, no! I will go away to\
another town\'97where you like\'97but I will watch over him all my life\'97I will\
watch over him all my life unceasingly. When he becomes unhappy with that\
woman, and that is bound to happen quite soon, let him come to me and he\
will find a friend, a sister.... Only a sister, of course, and so for\
ever; but he will learn at least that that sister is really his sister,\
who loves him and has sacrificed all her life to him. I will gain my\
point. I will insist on his knowing me and confiding entirely in me,\
without reserve,\'94 she cried, in a sort of frenzy. \'93I will be a god to whom\
he can pray\'97and that, at least, he owes me for his treachery and for what\
I suffered yesterday through him. And let him see that all my life I will\
be true to him and the promise I gave him, in spite of his being untrue\
and betraying me. I will\'97I will become nothing but a means for his\
happiness, or\'97how shall I say?\'97an instrument, a machine for his happiness,\
and that for my whole life, my whole life, and that he may see that all\
his life! That\'92s my decision. Ivan Fyodorovitch fully approves me.\'94\
\
She was breathless. She had perhaps intended to express her idea with more\
dignity, art and naturalness, but her speech was too hurried and crude. It\
was full of youthful impulsiveness, it betrayed that she was still\
smarting from yesterday\'92s insult, and that her pride craved satisfaction.\
She felt this herself. Her face suddenly darkened, an unpleasant look came\
into her eyes. Alyosha at once saw it and felt a pang of sympathy. His\
brother Ivan made it worse by adding:\
\
\'93I\'92ve only expressed my own view,\'94 he said. \'93From any one else, this would\
have been affected and overstrained, but from you\'97no. Any other woman\
would have been wrong, but you are right. I don\'92t know how to explain it,\
but I see that you are absolutely genuine and, therefore, you are right.\'94\
\
\'93But that\'92s only for the moment. And what does this moment stand for?\
Nothing but yesterday\'92s insult.\'94 Madame Hohlakov obviously had not\
intended to interfere, but she could not refrain from this very just\
comment.\
\
\'93Quite so, quite so,\'94 cried Ivan, with peculiar eagerness, obviously\
annoyed at being interrupted, \'93in any one else this moment would be only\
due to yesterday\'92s impression and would be only a moment. But with\
Katerina Ivanovna\'92s character, that moment will last all her life. What\
for any one else would be only a promise is for her an everlasting\
