without saying good\uc0\u8208 by even to his hostess, Madame Hohlakov. Alyosha\
clasped his hands.\
\
\'93Ivan!\'94 he cried desperately after him. \'93Come back, Ivan! No, nothing will\
induce him to come back now!\'94 he cried again, regretfully realizing it;\
\'93but it\'92s my fault, my fault. I began it! Ivan spoke angrily, wrongly.\
Unjustly and angrily. He must come back here, come back,\'94 Alyosha kept\
exclaiming frantically.\
\
Katerina Ivanovna went suddenly into the next room.\
\
\'93You have done no harm. You behaved beautifully, like an angel,\'94 Madame\
Hohlakov whispered rapidly and ecstatically to Alyosha. \'93I will do my\
utmost to prevent Ivan Fyodorovitch from going.\'94\
\
Her face beamed with delight, to the great distress of Alyosha, but\
Katerina Ivanovna suddenly returned. She had two hundred\uc0\u8208 rouble notes in\
her hand.\
\
\'93I have a great favor to ask of you, Alexey Fyodorovitch,\'94 she began,\
addressing Alyosha with an apparently calm and even voice, as though\
nothing had happened. \'93A week\'97yes, I think it was a week ago\'97Dmitri\
Fyodorovitch was guilty of a hasty and unjust action\'97a very ugly action.\
There is a low tavern here, and in it he met that discharged officer, that\
captain, whom your father used to employ in some business. Dmitri\
Fyodorovitch somehow lost his temper with this captain, seized him by the\
beard and dragged him out into the street and for some distance along it,\
in that insulting fashion. And I am told that his son, a boy, quite a\
child, who is at the school here, saw it and ran beside them crying and\
begging for his father, appealing to every one to defend him, while every\
one laughed. You must forgive me, Alexey Fyodorovitch, I cannot think\
without indignation of that disgraceful action of _his_ ... one of those\
actions of which only Dmitri Fyodorovitch would be capable in his anger\
... and in his passions! I can\'92t describe it even.... I can\'92t find my\
words. I\'92ve made inquiries about his victim, and find he is quite a poor\
man. His name is Snegiryov. He did something wrong in the army and was\
discharged. I can\'92t tell you what. And now he has sunk into terrible\
destitution, with his family\'97an unhappy family of sick children, and, I\
believe, an insane wife. He has been living here a long time; he used to\
work as a copying clerk, but now he is getting nothing. I thought if you\
... that is I thought ... I don\'92t know. I am so confused. You see, I\
wanted to ask you, my dear Alexey Fyodorovitch, to go to him, to find some\
excuse to go to them\'97I mean to that captain\'97oh, goodness, how badly I\
