\
Chapter VII. And In The Open Air\
\
\
\'93The air is fresh, but in my apartment it is not so in any sense of the\
word. Let us walk slowly, sir. I should be glad of your kind interest.\'94\
\
\'93I too have something important to say to you,\'94 observed Alyosha, \'93only I\
don\'92t know how to begin.\'94\
\
\'93To be sure you must have business with me. You would never have looked in\
upon me without some object. Unless you come simply to complain of the\
boy, and that\'92s hardly likely. And, by the way, about the boy: I could not\
explain to you in there, but here I will describe that scene to you. My\
tow was thicker a week ago\'97I mean my beard. That\'92s the nickname they give\
to my beard, the schoolboys most of all. Well, your brother Dmitri\
Fyodorovitch was pulling me by my beard, I\'92d done nothing, he was in a\
towering rage and happened to come upon me. He dragged me out of the\
tavern into the market\uc0\u8208 place; at that moment the boys were coming out of\
school, and with them Ilusha. As soon as he saw me in such a state he\
rushed up to me. \'91Father,\'92 he cried, \'91father!\'92 He caught hold of me,\
hugged me, tried to pull me away, crying to my assailant, \'91Let go, let go,\
it\'92s my father, forgive him!\'92\'97yes, he actually cried \'91forgive him.\'92 He\
clutched at that hand, that very hand, in his little hands and kissed\
it.... I remember his little face at that moment, I haven\'92t forgotten it\
and I never shall!\'94\
\
\'93I swear,\'94 cried Alyosha, \'93that my brother will express his most deep and\
sincere regret, even if he has to go down on his knees in that same\
market\uc0\u8208 place.... I\'92ll make him or he is no brother of mine!\'94\
\
\'93Aha, then it\'92s only a suggestion! And it does not come from him but\
simply from the generosity of your own warm heart. You should have said\
so. No, in that case allow me to tell you of your brother\'92s highly\
chivalrous soldierly generosity, for he did give expression to it at the\
time. He left off dragging me by my beard and released me: \'91You are an\
officer,\'92 he said, \'91and I am an officer, if you can find a decent man to\
be your second send me your challenge. I will give satisfaction, though\
you are a scoundrel.\'92 That\'92s what he said. A chivalrous spirit indeed! I\
retired with Ilusha, and that scene is a family record imprinted for ever\
on Ilusha\'92s soul. No, it\'92s not for us to claim the privileges of noblemen.\
Judge for yourself. You\'92ve just been in our mansion, what did you see\
there? Three ladies, one a cripple and weak\uc0\u8208 minded, another a cripple and\
hunchback and the third not crippled but far too clever. She is a student,\
dying to get back to Petersburg, to work for the emancipation of the\
Russian woman on the banks of the Neva. I won\'92t speak of Ilusha, he is\
only nine. I am alone in the world, and if I die, what will become of all\
of them? I simply ask you that. And if I challenge him and he kills me on\
the spot, what then? What will become of them? And worse still, if he\
doesn\'92t kill me but only cripples me: I couldn\'92t work, but I should still\
be a mouth to feed. Who would feed it and who would feed them all? Must I\
take Ilusha from school and send him to beg in the streets? That\'92s what it\
means for me to challenge him to a duel. It\'92s silly talk and nothing\
else.\'94\
\
\'93He will beg your forgiveness, he will bow down at your feet in the middle\
of the market\uc0\u8208 place,\'94 cried Alyosha again, with glowing eyes.\
\
\'93I did think of prosecuting him,\'94 the captain went on, \'93but look in our\
code, could I get much compensation for a personal injury? And then\
Agrafena Alexandrovna(3) sent for me and shouted at me: \'91Don\'92t dare to\
dream of it! If you proceed against him, I\'92ll publish it to all the world\
that he beat you for your dishonesty, and then you will be prosecuted.\'92 I\
call God to witness whose was the dishonesty and by whose commands I\
acted, wasn\'92t it by her own and Fyodor Pavlovitch\'92s? \'91And what\'92s more,\'92\
she went on, \'91I\'92ll dismiss you for good and you\'92ll never earn another\
penny from me. I\'92ll speak to my merchant too\'92 (that\'92s what she calls her\
old man) \'91and he will dismiss you!\'92 And if he dismisses me, what can I\
earn then from any one? Those two are all I have to look to, for your\
Fyodor Pavlovitch has not only given over employing me, for another\
reason, but he means to make use of papers I\'92ve signed to go to law\
against me. And so I kept quiet, and you have seen our retreat. But now\
let me ask you: did Ilusha hurt your finger much? I didn\'92t like to go into\
it in our mansion before him.\'94\
\
\'93Yes, very much, and he was in a great fury. He was avenging you on me as\
a Karamazov, I see that now. But if only you had seen how he was throwing\
stones at his school\uc0\u8208 fellows! It\'92s very dangerous. They might kill him.\
They are children and stupid. A stone may be thrown and break somebody\'92s\
head.\'94\
\
\'93That\'92s just what has happened. He has been bruised by a stone to\uc0\u8208 day. Not\
on the head but on the chest, just above the heart. He came home crying\
and groaning and now he is ill.\'94\
\
\'93And you know he attacks them first. He is bitter against them on your\
account. They say he stabbed a boy called Krassotkin with a pen\uc0\u8208 knife not\
long ago.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92ve heard about that too, it\'92s dangerous. Krassotkin is an official\
here, we may hear more about it.\'94\
\
\'93I would advise you,\'94 Alyosha went on warmly, \'93not to send him to school\
at all for a time till he is calmer ... and his anger is passed.\'94\
\
\'93Anger!\'94 the captain repeated, \'93that\'92s just what it is. He is a little\
creature, but it\'92s a mighty anger. You don\'92t know all, sir. Let me tell\
you more. Since that incident all the boys have been teasing him about the\
\'91wisp of tow.\'92 Schoolboys are a merciless race, individually they are\
angels, but together, especially in schools, they are often merciless.\
Their teasing has stirred up a gallant spirit in Ilusha. An ordinary boy,\
a weak son, would have submitted, have felt ashamed of his father, sir,\
but he stood up for his father against them all. For his father and for\
truth and justice. For what he suffered when he kissed your brother\'92s hand\
and cried to him \'91Forgive father, forgive him,\'92\'97that only God knows\'97and I,\
his father. For our children\'97not your children, but ours\'97the children of\
the poor gentlemen looked down upon by every one\'97know what justice means,\
sir, even at nine years old. How should the rich know? They don\'92t explore\
such depths once in their lives. But at that moment in the square when he\
kissed his hand, at that moment my Ilusha had grasped all that justice\
means. That truth entered into him and crushed him for ever, sir,\'94 the\
captain said hotly again with a sort of frenzy, and he struck his right\
fist against his left palm as though he wanted to show how \'93the truth\'94\
crushed Ilusha. \'93That very day, sir, he fell ill with fever and was\
delirious all night. All that day he hardly said a word to me, but I\
noticed he kept watching me from the corner, though he turned to the\
window and pretended to be learning his lessons. But I could see his mind\
was not on his lessons. Next day I got drunk to forget my troubles, sinful\
man as I am, and I don\'92t remember much. Mamma began crying, too\'97I am very\
fond of mamma\'97well, I spent my last penny drowning my troubles. Don\'92t\
despise me for that, sir, in Russia men who drink are the best. The best\
men amongst us are the greatest drunkards. I lay down and I don\'92t remember\
about Ilusha, though all that day the boys had been jeering at him at\
school. \'91Wisp of tow,\'92 they shouted, \'91your father was pulled out of the\
tavern by his wisp of tow, you ran by and begged forgiveness.\'92 \'94\
\
\'93On the third day when he came back from school, I saw he looked pale and\
wretched. \'91What is it?\'92 I asked. He wouldn\'92t answer. Well, there\'92s no\
talking in our mansion without mamma and the girls taking part in it.\
What\'92s more, the girls had heard about it the very first day. Varvara had\
begun snarling. \'91You fools and buffoons, can you ever do anything\
