And I told briefly what I\'92ve just told you. He listened. \'91Father,\'92 he\
said, \'91anyway don\'92t forgive it. When I grow up I\'92ll call him out myself\
and kill him.\'92 His eyes shone and glowed. And of course I am his father,\
and I had to put in a word: \'91It\'92s a sin to kill,\'92 I said, \'91even in a\
duel.\'92 \'91Father,\'92 he said, \'91when I grow up, I\'92ll knock him down, knock the\
sword out of his hand, I\'92ll fall on him, wave my sword over him and say:\
\'93I could kill you, but I forgive you, so there!\'94 \'92 You see what the\
workings of his little mind have been during these two days; he must have\
been planning that vengeance all day, and raving about it at night.\
\
\'93But he began to come home from school badly beaten, I found out about it\
the day before yesterday, and you are right, I won\'92t send him to that\
school any more. I heard that he was standing up against all the class\
alone and defying them all, that his heart was full of resentment, of\
