\
Book V. Pro And Contra\
\
\
\
Chapter I. The Engagement\
\
\
Madame Hohlakov was again the first to meet Alyosha. She was flustered;\
something important had happened. Katerina Ivanovna\'92s hysterics had ended\
in a fainting fit, and then \'93a terrible, awful weakness had followed, she\
lay with her eyes turned up and was delirious. Now she was in a fever.\
They had sent for Herzenstube; they had sent for the aunts. The aunts were\
already here, but Herzenstube had not yet come. They were all sitting in\
her room, waiting. She was unconscious now, and what if it turned to brain\
fever!\'94\
\
Madame Hohlakov looked gravely alarmed. \'93This is serious, serious,\'94 she\
added at every word, as though nothing that had happened to her before had\
been serious. Alyosha listened with distress, and was beginning to\
describe his adventures, but she interrupted him at the first words. She\
had not time to listen. She begged him to sit with Lise and wait for her\
there.\
\
\'93Lise,\'94 she whispered almost in his ear, \'93Lise has greatly surprised me\
just now, dear Alexey Fyodorovitch. She touched me, too, and so my heart\
forgives her everything. Only fancy, as soon as you had gone, she began to\
be truly remorseful for having laughed at you to\uc0\u8208 day and yesterday, though\
she was not laughing at you, but only joking. But she was seriously sorry\
for it, almost ready to cry, so that I was quite surprised. She has never\
been really sorry for laughing at me, but has only made a joke of it. And\
you know she is laughing at me every minute. But this time she was in\
earnest. She thinks a great deal of your opinion, Alexey Fyodorovitch, and\
don\'92t take offense or be wounded by her if you can help it. I am never\
hard upon her, for she\'92s such a clever little thing. Would you believe it?\
She said just now that you were a friend of her childhood, \'91the greatest\
friend of her childhood\'92\'97just think of that\'97\'91greatest friend\'92\'97and what\
about me? She has very strong feelings and memories, and, what\'92s more, she\
uses these phrases, most unexpected words, which come out all of a sudden\
when you least expect them. She spoke lately about a pine\uc0\u8208 tree, for\
instance: there used to be a pine\uc0\u8208 tree standing in our garden in her early\
childhood. Very likely it\'92s standing there still; so there\'92s no need to\
speak in the past tense. Pine\uc0\u8208 trees are not like people, Alexey\
Fyodorovitch, they don\'92t change quickly. \'91Mamma,\'92 she said, \'91I remember\
this pine\uc0\u8208 tree as in a dream,\'92 only she said something so original about\
it that I can\'92t repeat it. Besides, I\'92ve forgotten it. Well, good\uc0\u8208 by! I am\
so worried I feel I shall go out of my mind. Ah! Alexey Fyodorovitch, I\'92ve\
been out of my mind twice in my life. Go to Lise, cheer her up, as you\
always can so charmingly. Lise,\'94 she cried, going to her door, \'93here I\'92ve\
brought you Alexey Fyodorovitch, whom you insulted so. He is not at all\
angry, I assure you; on the contrary, he is surprised that you could\
suppose so.\'94\
\
\'93_Merci, maman._ Come in, Alexey Fyodorovitch.\'94\
\
Alyosha went in. Lise looked rather embarrassed, and at once flushed\
crimson. She was evidently ashamed of something, and, as people always do\
in such cases, she began immediately talking of other things, as though\
they were of absorbing interest to her at the moment.\
\
\'93Mamma has just told me all about the two hundred roubles, Alexey\
Fyodorovitch, and your taking them to that poor officer ... and she told\
me all the awful story of how he had been insulted ... and you know,\
although mamma muddles things ... she always rushes from one thing to\
another ... I cried when I heard. Well, did you give him the money and how\
is that poor man getting on?\'94\
\
\'93The fact is I didn\'92t give it to him, and it\'92s a long story,\'94 answered\
Alyosha, as though he, too, could think of nothing but his regret at\
having failed, yet Lise saw perfectly well that he, too, looked away, and\
that he, too, was trying to talk of other things.\
\
Alyosha sat down to the table and began to tell his story, but at the\
first words he lost his embarrassment and gained the whole of Lise\'92s\
attention as well. He spoke with deep feeling, under the influence of the\
strong impression he had just received, and he succeeded in telling his\
story well and circumstantially. In old days in Moscow he had been fond of\
coming to Lise and describing to her what had just happened to him, what\
he had read, or what he remembered of his childhood. Sometimes they had\
made day\uc0\u8208 dreams and woven whole romances together\'97generally cheerful and\
amusing ones. Now they both felt suddenly transported to the old days in\
Moscow, two years before. Lise was extremely touched by his story. Alyosha\
described Ilusha with warm feeling. When he finished describing how the\
luckless man trampled on the money, Lise could not help clasping her hands\
and crying out:\
\
\'93So you didn\'92t give him the money! So you let him run away! Oh, dear, you\
ought to have run after him!\'94\
\
\'93No, Lise; it\'92s better I didn\'92t run after him,\'94 said Alyosha, getting up\
from his chair and walking thoughtfully across the room.\
\
\'93How so? How is it better? Now they are without food and their case is\
hopeless?\'94\
\
\'93Not hopeless, for the two hundred roubles will still come to them. He\'92ll\
take the money to\uc0\u8208 morrow. To\u8208 morrow he will be sure to take it,\'94 said\
Alyosha, pacing up and down, pondering. \'93You see, Lise,\'94 he went on,\
stopping suddenly before her, \'93I made one blunder, but that, even that, is\
all for the best.\'94\
\
\'93What blunder, and why is it for the best?\'94\
\
\'93I\'92ll tell you. He is a man of weak and timorous character; he has\
suffered so much and is very good\uc0\u8208 natured. I keep wondering why he took\
offense so suddenly, for I assure you, up to the last minute, he did not\
know that he was going to trample on the notes. And I think now that there\
was a great deal to offend him ... and it could not have been otherwise in\
his position.... To begin with, he was sore at having been so glad of the\
money in my presence and not having concealed it from me. If he had been\
pleased, but not so much; if he had not shown it; if he had begun\
affecting scruples and difficulties, as other people do when they take\
money, he might still endure to take it. But he was too genuinely\
delighted, and that was mortifying. Ah, Lise, he is a good and truthful\
man\'97that\'92s the worst of the whole business. All the while he talked, his\
voice was so weak, so broken, he talked so fast, so fast, he kept laughing\
such a laugh, or perhaps he was crying\'97yes, I am sure he was crying, he\
was so delighted\'97and he talked about his daughters\'97and about the situation\
he could get in another town.... And when he had poured out his heart, he\
felt ashamed at having shown me his inmost soul like that. So he began to\
hate me at once. He is one of those awfully sensitive poor people. What\
had made him feel most ashamed was that he had given in too soon and\
accepted me as a friend, you see. At first he almost flew at me and tried\
to intimidate me, but as soon as he saw the money he had begun embracing\
me; he kept touching me with his hands. This must have been how he came to\
feel it all so humiliating, and then I made that blunder, a very important\
one. I suddenly said to him that if he had not money enough to move to\
another town, we would give it to him, and, indeed, I myself would give\
him as much as he wanted out of my own money. That struck him all at once.\
Why, he thought, did I put myself forward to help him? You know, Lise,\
it\'92s awfully hard for a man who has been injured, when other people look\
at him as though they were his benefactors.... I\'92ve heard that; Father\
Zossima told me so. I don\'92t know how to put it, but I have often seen it\
myself. And I feel like that myself, too. And the worst of it was that\
though he did not know, up to the very last minute, that he would trample\
on the notes, he had a kind of presentiment of it, I am sure of that.\
That\'92s just what made him so ecstatic, that he had that presentiment....\
And though it\'92s so dreadful, it\'92s all for the best. In fact, I believe\
nothing better could have happened.\'94\
\
\'93Why, why could nothing better have happened?\'94 cried Lise, looking with\
great surprise at Alyosha.\
\
\'93Because if he had taken the money, in an hour after getting home, he\
would be crying with mortification, that\'92s just what would have happened.\
And most likely he would have come to me early to\uc0\u8208 morrow, and perhaps have\
flung the notes at me and trampled upon them as he did just now. But now\
he has gone home awfully proud and triumphant, though he knows he has\
\'91ruined himself.\'92 So now nothing could be easier than to make him accept\
the two hundred roubles by to\uc0\u8208 morrow, for he has already vindicated his\
honor, tossed away the money, and trampled it under foot.... He couldn\'92t\
know when he did it that I should bring it to him again to\uc0\u8208 morrow, and yet\
he is in terrible need of that money. Though he is proud of himself now,\
yet even to\uc0\u8208 day he\'92ll be thinking what a help he has lost. He will think\
of it more than ever at night, will dream of it, and by to\uc0\u8208 morrow morning\
he may be ready to run to me to ask forgiveness. It\'92s just then that I\'92ll\
appear. \'91Here, you are a proud man,\'92 I shall say: \'91you have shown it; but\
now take the money and forgive us!\'92 And then he will take it!\'94\
\
Alyosha was carried away with joy as he uttered his last words, \'93And then\
he will take it!\'94 Lise clapped her hands.\
\
\'93Ah, that\'92s true! I understand that perfectly now. Ah, Alyosha, how do you\
know all this? So young and yet he knows what\'92s in the heart.... I should\
never have worked it out.\'94\
\
\'93The great thing now is to persuade him that he is on an equal footing\
with us, in spite of his taking money from us,\'94 Alyosha went on in his\
excitement, \'93and not only on an equal, but even on a higher footing.\'94\
\
\'93 \'91On a higher footing\'92 is charming, Alexey Fyodorovitch; but go on, go\
on!\'94\
\
\'93You mean there isn\'92t such an expression as \'91on a higher footing\'92; but\
that doesn\'92t matter because\'97\'94\
\
\'93Oh, no, of course it doesn\'92t matter. Forgive me, Alyosha, dear.... You\
know, I scarcely respected you till now\'97that is I respected you but on an\
equal footing; but now I shall begin to respect you on a higher footing.\
Don\'92t be angry, dear, at my joking,\'94 she put in at once, with strong\
feeling. \'93I am absurd and small, but you, you! Listen, Alexey\
Fyodorovitch. Isn\'92t there in all our analysis\'97I mean your analysis ... no,\
better call it ours\'97aren\'92t we showing contempt for him, for that poor\
man\'97in analyzing his soul like this, as it were, from above, eh? In\
deciding so certainly that he will take the money?\'94\
\
\'93No, Lise, it\'92s not contempt,\'94 Alyosha answered, as though he had prepared\
himself for the question. \'93I was thinking of that on the way here. How can\
it be contempt when we are all like him, when we are all just the same as\
he is? For you know we are just the same, no better. If we are better, we\
should have been just the same in his place.... I don\'92t know about you,\
Lise, but I consider that I have a sordid soul in many ways, and his soul\
is not sordid; on the contrary, full of fine feeling.... No, Lise, I have\
no contempt for him. Do you know, Lise, my elder told me once to care for\
most people exactly as one would for children, and for some of them as one\
would for the sick in hospitals.\'94\
\
\'93Ah, Alexey Fyodorovitch, dear, let us care for people as we would for the\
sick!\'94\
\
\'93Let us, Lise; I am ready. Though I am not altogether ready in myself. I\
am sometimes very impatient and at other times I don\'92t see things. It\'92s\
different with you.\'94\
\
\'93Ah, I don\'92t believe it! Alexey Fyodorovitch, how happy I am!\'94\
\
\'93I am so glad you say so, Lise.\'94\
\
\'93Alexey Fyodorovitch, you are wonderfully good, but you are sometimes sort\
of formal.... And yet you are not a bit formal really. Go to the door,\
open it gently, and see whether mamma is listening,\'94 said Lise, in a\
nervous, hurried whisper.\
\
Alyosha went, opened the door, and reported that no one was listening.\
\
\'93Come here, Alexey Fyodorovitch,\'94 Lise went on, flushing redder and\
redder. \'93Give me your hand\'97that\'92s right. I have to make a great\
confession, I didn\'92t write to you yesterday in joke, but in earnest,\'94 and\
she hid her eyes with her hand. It was evident that she was greatly\
ashamed of the confession.\
\
Suddenly she snatched his hand and impulsively kissed it three times.\
\
\'93Ah, Lise, what a good thing!\'94 cried Alyosha joyfully. \'93You know, I was\
perfectly sure you were in earnest.\'94\
\
\'93Sure? Upon my word!\'94 She put aside his hand, but did not leave go of it,\
blushing hotly, and laughing a little happy laugh. \'93I kiss his hand and he\
says, \'91What a good thing!\'92 \'94\
\
But her reproach was undeserved. Alyosha, too, was greatly overcome.\
\
\'93I should like to please you always, Lise, but I don\'92t know how to do it,\'94\
he muttered, blushing too.\
\
\'93Alyosha, dear, you are cold and rude. Do you see? He has chosen me as his\
wife and is quite settled about it. He is sure I was in earnest. What a\
thing to say! Why, that\'92s impertinence\'97that\'92s what it is.\'94\
\
\'93Why, was it wrong of me to feel sure?\'94 Alyosha asked, laughing suddenly.\
\
\'93Ah, Alyosha, on the contrary, it was delightfully right,\'94 cried Lise,\
looking tenderly and happily at him.\
\
Alyosha stood still, holding her hand in his. Suddenly he stooped down and\
kissed her on her lips.\
\
\'93Oh, what are you doing?\'94 cried Lise. Alyosha was terribly abashed.\
\
\'93Oh, forgive me if I shouldn\'92t.... Perhaps I\'92m awfully stupid.... You said\
I was cold, so I kissed you.... But I see it was stupid.\'94\
\
Lise laughed, and hid her face in her hands. \'93And in that dress!\'94 she\
ejaculated in the midst of her mirth. But she suddenly ceased laughing and\
became serious, almost stern.\
\
\'93Alyosha, we must put off kissing. We are not ready for that yet, and we\
shall have a long time to wait,\'94 she ended suddenly. \'93Tell me rather why\
you who are so clever, so intellectual, so observant, choose a little\
idiot, an invalid like me? Ah, Alyosha, I am awfully happy, for I don\'92t\
deserve you a bit.\'94\
\
\'93You do, Lise. I shall be leaving the monastery altogether in a few days.\
If I go into the world, I must marry. I know that. _He_ told me to marry,\
too. Whom could I marry better than you\'97and who would have me except you?\
I have been thinking it over. In the first place, you\'92ve known me from a\
child and you\'92ve a great many qualities I haven\'92t. You are more light\uc0\u8208 \
hearted than I am; above all, you are more innocent than I am. I have been\
brought into contact with many, many things already.... Ah, you don\'92t\
know, but I, too, am a Karamazov. What does it matter if you do laugh and\
make jokes, and at me, too? Go on laughing. I am so glad you do. You laugh\
like a little child, but you think like a martyr.\'94\
\
\'93Like a martyr? How?\'94\
\
\'93Yes, Lise, your question just now: whether we weren\'92t showing contempt\
for that poor man by dissecting his soul\'97that was the question of a\
sufferer.... You see, I don\'92t know how to express it, but any one who\
thinks of such questions is capable of suffering. Sitting in your invalid\
chair you must have thought over many things already.\'94\
\
\'93Alyosha, give me your hand. Why are you taking it away?\'94 murmured Lise in\
a failing voice, weak with happiness. \'93Listen, Alyosha. What will you wear\
when you come out of the monastery? What sort of suit? Don\'92t laugh, don\'92t\
be angry, it\'92s very, very important to me.\'94\
\
\'93I haven\'92t thought about the suit, Lise; but I\'92ll wear whatever you like.\'94\
\
\'93I should like you to have a dark blue velvet coat, a white piqu\'e9\
waistcoat, and a soft gray felt hat.... Tell me, did you believe that I\
didn\'92t care for you when I said I didn\'92t mean what I wrote?\'94\
\
\'93No, I didn\'92t believe it.\'94\
\
\'93Oh, you insupportable person, you are incorrigible.\'94\
\
\'93You see, I knew that you\'97seemed to care for me, but I pretended to\
believe that you didn\'92t care for me to make it\'97easier for you.\'94\
\
\'93That makes it worse! Worse and better than all! Alyosha, I am awfully\
fond of you. Just before you came this morning, I tried my fortune. I\
decided I would ask you for my letter, and if you brought it out calmly\
and gave it to me (as might have been expected from you) it would mean\
that you did not love me at all, that you felt nothing, and were simply a\
stupid boy, good for nothing, and that I am ruined. But you left the\
letter at home and that cheered me. You left it behind on purpose, so as\
not to give it back, because you knew I would ask for it? That was it,\
wasn\'92t it?\'94\
\
\'93Ah, Lise, it was not so a bit. The letter is with me now, and it was this\
morning, in this pocket. Here it is.\'94\
\
Alyosha pulled the letter out laughing, and showed it her at a distance.\
\
\'93But I am not going to give it to you. Look at it from here.\'94\
\
\'93Why, then you told a lie? You, a monk, told a lie!\'94\
\
\'93I told a lie if you like,\'94 Alyosha laughed, too. \'93I told a lie so as not\
to give you back the letter. It\'92s very precious to me,\'94 he added suddenly,\
with strong feeling, and again he flushed. \'93It always will be, and I won\'92t\
give it up to any one!\'94\
\
Lise looked at him joyfully. \'93Alyosha,\'94 she murmured again, \'93look at the\
door. Isn\'92t mamma listening?\'94\
\
\'93Very well, Lise, I\'92ll look; but wouldn\'92t it be better not to look? Why\
suspect your mother of such meanness?\'94\
\
\'93What meanness? As for her spying on her daughter, it\'92s her right, it\'92s\
not meanness!\'94 cried Lise, firing up. \'93You may be sure, Alexey\
Fyodorovitch, that when I am a mother, if I have a daughter like myself I\
