I\'92m her mother. Hold it in your hand, if you like, and I will read it so.\'94\
\
\'93No, I won\'92t show it to you. Even if she sanctioned it, I wouldn\'92t. I am\
coming to\uc0\u8208 morrow, and if you like, we can talk over many things, but now\
good\uc0\u8208 by!\'94\
\
And Alyosha ran downstairs and into the street.\
\
\
\
Chapter II. Smerdyakov With A Guitar\
\
\
He had no time to lose indeed. Even while he was saying good\uc0\u8208 by to Lise,\
the thought had struck him that he must attempt some stratagem to find his\
brother Dmitri, who was evidently keeping out of his way. It was getting\
late, nearly three o\'92clock. Alyosha\'92s whole soul turned to the monastery,\
to his dying saint, but the necessity of seeing Dmitri outweighed\
everything. The conviction that a great inevitable catastrophe was about\
to happen grew stronger in Alyosha\'92s mind with every hour. What that\
catastrophe was, and what he would say at that moment to his brother, he\
could perhaps not have said definitely. \'93Even if my benefactor must die\
without me, anyway I won\'92t have to reproach myself all my life with the\
thought that I might have saved something and did not, but passed by and\
hastened home. If I do as I intend, I shall be following his great\
precept.\'94\
\
His plan was to catch his brother Dmitri unawares, to climb over the\
fence, as he had the day before, get into the garden and sit in the\
summer\uc0\u8208 house. If Dmitri were not there, thought Alyosha, he would not\
announce himself to Foma or the women of the house, but would remain\
hidden in the summer\uc0\u8208 house, even if he had to wait there till evening. If,\
as before, Dmitri were lying in wait for Grushenka to come, he would be\
very likely to come to the summer\uc0\u8208 house. Alyosha did not, however, give\
much thought to the details of his plan, but resolved to act upon it, even\
if it meant not getting back to the monastery that day.\
\
Everything happened without hindrance, he climbed over the hurdle almost\
in the same spot as the day before, and stole into the summer\uc0\u8208 house\
unseen. He did not want to be noticed. The woman of the house and Foma\
too, if he were here, might be loyal to his brother and obey his\
instructions, and so refuse to let Alyosha come into the garden, or might\
warn Dmitri that he was being sought and inquired for.\
\
There was no one in the summer\uc0\u8208 house. Alyosha sat down and began to wait.\
He looked round the summer\uc0\u8208 house, which somehow struck him as a great deal\
more ancient than before. Though the day was just as fine as yesterday, it\
seemed a wretched little place this time. There was a circle on the table,\
left no doubt from the glass of brandy having been spilt the day before.\
Foolish and irrelevant ideas strayed about his mind, as they always do in\
a time of tedious waiting. He wondered, for instance, why he had sat down\
precisely in the same place as before, why not in the other seat. At last\
he felt very depressed\'97depressed by suspense and uncertainty. But he had\
not sat there more than a quarter of an hour, when he suddenly heard the\
thrum of a guitar somewhere quite close. People were sitting, or had only\
just sat down, somewhere in the bushes not more than twenty paces away.\
Alyosha suddenly recollected that on coming out of the summer\uc0\u8208 house the\
day before, he had caught a glimpse of an old green low garden\uc0\u8208 seat among\
the bushes on the left, by the fence. The people must be sitting on it\
now. Who were they?\
\
A man\'92s voice suddenly began singing in a sugary falsetto, accompanying\
himself on the guitar:\
\
\
    With invincible force\
    I am bound to my dear.\
    O Lord, have mercy\
    On her and on me!\
    On her and on me!\
    On her and on me!\
\
\
The voice ceased. It was a lackey\'92s tenor and a lackey\'92s song. Another\
voice, a woman\'92s, suddenly asked insinuatingly and bashfully, though with\
mincing affectation:\
\
\'93Why haven\'92t you been to see us for so long, Pavel Fyodorovitch? Why do\
you always look down upon us?\'94\
\
\'93Not at all,\'94 answered a man\'92s voice politely, but with emphatic dignity.\
It was clear that the man had the best of the position, and that the woman\
was making advances. \'93I believe the man must be Smerdyakov,\'94 thought\
Alyosha, \'93from his voice. And the lady must be the daughter of the house\
here, who has come from Moscow, the one who wears the dress with a tail\
and goes to Marfa for soup.\'94\
\
\'93I am awfully fond of verses of all kinds, if they rhyme,\'94 the woman\'92s\
voice continued. \'93Why don\'92t you go on?\'94\
\
The man sang again:\
\
\
    What do I care for royal wealth\
    If but my dear one be in health?\
    Lord have mercy\
    On her and on me!\
    On her and on me!\
    On her and on me!\
\
\
\'93It was even better last time,\'94 observed the woman\'92s voice. \'93You sang \'91If\
my darling be in health\'92; it sounded more tender. I suppose you\'92ve\
forgotten to\uc0\u8208 day.\'94\
\
\'93Poetry is rubbish!\'94 said Smerdyakov curtly.\
\
\'93Oh, no! I am very fond of poetry.\'94\
\
\'93So far as it\'92s poetry, it\'92s essential rubbish. Consider yourself, who\
ever talks in rhyme? And if we were all to talk in rhyme, even though it\
were decreed by government, we shouldn\'92t say much, should we? Poetry is no\
good, Marya Kondratyevna.\'94\
\
\'93How clever you are! How is it you\'92ve gone so deep into everything?\'94 The\
woman\'92s voice was more and more insinuating.\
\
\'93I could have done better than that. I could have known more than that, if\
it had not been for my destiny from my childhood up. I would have shot a\
man in a duel if he called me names because I am descended from a filthy\
beggar and have no father. And they used to throw it in my teeth in\
Moscow. It had reached them from here, thanks to Grigory Vassilyevitch.\
Grigory Vassilyevitch blames me for rebelling against my birth, but I\
would have sanctioned their killing me before I was born that I might not\
have come into the world at all. They used to say in the market, and your\
mamma too, with great lack of delicacy, set off telling me that her hair\
was like a mat on her head, and that she was short of five foot by a wee\
bit. Why talk of a wee bit while she might have said \'91a little bit,\'92 like\
every one else? She wanted to make it touching, a regular peasant\'92s\
feeling. Can a Russian peasant be said to feel, in comparison with an\
educated man? He can\'92t be said to have feeling at all, in his ignorance.\
From my childhood up when I hear \'91a wee bit,\'92 I am ready to burst with\
rage. I hate all Russia, Marya Kondratyevna.\'94\
\
\'93If you\'92d been a cadet in the army, or a young hussar, you wouldn\'92t have\
talked like that, but would have drawn your saber to defend all Russia.\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t want to be a hussar, Marya Kondratyevna, and, what\'92s more, I\
should like to abolish all soldiers.\'94\
\
\'93And when an enemy comes, who is going to defend us?\'94\
\
\'93There\'92s no need of defense. In 1812 there was a great invasion of Russia\
by Napoleon, first Emperor of the French, father of the present one, and\
it would have been a good thing if they had conquered us. A clever nation\
would have conquered a very stupid one and annexed it. We should have had\
quite different institutions.\'94\
\
\'93Are they so much better in their own country than we are? I wouldn\'92t\
change a dandy I know of for three young Englishmen,\'94 observed Marya\
Kondratyevna tenderly, doubtless accompanying her words with a most\
languishing glance.\
\
\'93That\'92s as one prefers.\'94\
\
\'93But you are just like a foreigner\'97just like a most gentlemanly foreigner.\
I tell you that, though it makes me bashful.\'94\
\
\'93If you care to know, the folks there and ours here are just alike in\
their vice. They are swindlers, only there the scoundrel wears polished\
boots and here he grovels in filth and sees no harm in it. The Russian\
people want thrashing, as Fyodor Pavlovitch said very truly yesterday,\
though he is mad, and all his children.\'94\
\
\'93You said yourself you had such a respect for Ivan Fyodorovitch.\'94\
\
\'93But he said I was a stinking lackey. He thinks that I might be unruly. He\
is mistaken there. If I had a certain sum in my pocket, I would have left\
here long ago. Dmitri Fyodorovitch is lower than any lackey in his\
behavior, in his mind, and in his poverty. He doesn\'92t know how to do\
anything, and yet he is respected by every one. I may be only a soup\uc0\u8208 \
maker, but with luck I could open a caf\'e9 restaurant in Petrovka, in\
Moscow, for my cookery is something special, and there\'92s no one in Moscow,\
except the foreigners, whose cookery is anything special. Dmitri\
Fyodorovitch is a beggar, but if he were to challenge the son of the first\
count in the country, he\'92d fight him. Though in what way is he better than\
I am? For he is ever so much stupider than I am. Look at the money he has\
wasted without any need!\'94\
\
\'93It must be lovely, a duel,\'94 Marya Kondratyevna observed suddenly.\
\
\'93How so?\'94\
\
\'93It must be so dreadful and so brave, especially when young officers with\
pistols in their hands pop at one another for the sake of some lady. A\
perfect picture! Ah, if only girls were allowed to look on, I\'92d give\
anything to see one!\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s all very well when you are firing at some one, but when he is firing\
straight in your mug, you must feel pretty silly. You\'92d be glad to run\
away, Marya Kondratyevna.\'94\
\
\'93You don\'92t mean you would run away?\'94 But Smerdyakov did not deign to\
reply. After a moment\'92s silence the guitar tinkled again, and he sang\
again in the same falsetto:\
\
\
    Whatever you may say,\
    I shall go far away.\
    Life will be bright and gay\
    In the city far away.\
    I shall not grieve,\
    I shall not grieve at all,\
    I don\'92t intend to grieve at all.\
\
\
Then something unexpected happened. Alyosha suddenly sneezed. They were\
silent. Alyosha got up and walked towards them. He found Smerdyakov\
dressed up and wearing polished boots, his hair pomaded, and perhaps\
curled. The guitar lay on the garden\uc0\u8208 seat. His companion was the daughter\
of the house, wearing a light\uc0\u8208 blue dress with a train two yards long. She\
was young and would not have been bad\uc0\u8208 looking, but that her face was so\
round and terribly freckled.\
\
\'93Will my brother Dmitri soon be back?\'94 asked Alyosha with as much\
composure as he could.\
\
Smerdyakov got up slowly; Marya Kondratyevna rose too.\
\
\'93How am I to know about Dmitri Fyodorovitch? It\'92s not as if I were his\
keeper,\'94 answered Smerdyakov quietly, distinctly, and superciliously.\
\
\'93But I simply asked whether you do know?\'94 Alyosha explained.\
\
\'93I know nothing of his whereabouts and don\'92t want to.\'94\
\
\'93But my brother told me that you let him know all that goes on in the\
house, and promised to let him know when Agrafena Alexandrovna comes.\'94\
\
Smerdyakov turned a deliberate, unmoved glance upon him.\
\
\'93And how did you get in this time, since the gate was bolted an hour ago?\'94\
he asked, looking at Alyosha.\
\
\'93I came in from the back\uc0\u8208 alley, over the fence, and went straight to the\
summer\uc0\u8208 house. I hope you\'92ll forgive me,\'94 he added, addressing Marya\
Kondratyevna. \'93I was in a hurry to find my brother.\'94\
\
\'93Ach, as though we could take it amiss in you!\'94 drawled Marya\
Kondratyevna, flattered by Alyosha\'92s apology. \'93For Dmitri Fyodorovitch\
often goes to the summer\uc0\u8208 house in that way. We don\'92t know he is here and\
he is sitting in the summer\uc0\u8208 house.\'94\
\
\'93I am very anxious to find him, or to learn from you where he is now.\
Believe me, it\'92s on business of great importance to him.\'94\
\
\'93He never tells us,\'94 lisped Marya Kondratyevna.\
\
\'93Though I used to come here as a friend,\'94 Smerdyakov began again, \'93Dmitri\
Fyodorovitch has pestered me in a merciless way even here by his incessant\
questions about the master. \'91What news?\'92 he\'92ll ask. \'91What\'92s going on in\
there now? Who\'92s coming and going?\'92 and can\'92t I tell him something more.\
Twice already he\'92s threatened me with death.\'94\
\
\'93With death?\'94 Alyosha exclaimed in surprise.\
\
\'93Do you suppose he\'92d think much of that, with his temper, which you had a\
chance of observing yourself yesterday? He says if I let Agrafena\
Alexandrovna in and she passes the night there, I\'92ll be the first to\
suffer for it. I am terribly afraid of him, and if I were not even more\
afraid of doing so, I ought to let the police know. God only knows what he\
might not do!\'94\
\
\'93His honor said to him the other day, \'91I\'92ll pound you in a mortar!\'92 \'94\
added Marya Kondratyevna.\
\
\'93Oh, if it\'92s pounding in a mortar, it may be only talk,\'94 observed Alyosha.\
\'93If I could meet him, I might speak to him about that too.\'94\
\
\'93Well, the only thing I can tell you is this,\'94 said Smerdyakov, as though\
thinking better of it; \'93I am here as an old friend and neighbor, and it\
would be odd if I didn\'92t come. On the other hand, Ivan Fyodorovitch sent\
me first thing this morning to your brother\'92s lodging in Lake Street,\
