with him at the restaurant here, in the market\uc0\u8208 place. I went, but didn\'92t\
find Dmitri Fyodorovitch at home, though it was eight o\'92clock. \'91He\'92s been\
here, but he is quite gone,\'92 those were the very words of his landlady.\
It\'92s as though there was an understanding between them. Perhaps at this\
moment he is in the restaurant with Ivan Fyodorovitch, for Ivan\
Fyodorovitch has not been home to dinner and Fyodor Pavlovitch dined alone\
an hour ago, and is gone to lie down. But I beg you most particularly not\
to speak of me and of what I have told you, for he\'92d kill me for nothing\
at all.\'94\
\
\'93Brother Ivan invited Dmitri to the restaurant to\uc0\u8208 day?\'94 repeated Alyosha\
quickly.\
\
\'93That\'92s so.\'94\
\
\'93The Metropolis tavern in the market\uc0\u8208 place?\'94\
\
\'93The very same.\'94\
\
\'93That\'92s quite likely,\'94 cried Alyosha, much excited. \'93Thank you,\
Smerdyakov; that\'92s important. I\'92ll go there at once.\'94\
\
\'93Don\'92t betray me,\'94 Smerdyakov called after him.\
\
\'93Oh, no, I\'92ll go to the tavern as though by chance. Don\'92t be anxious.\'94\
\
\'93But wait a minute, I\'92ll open the gate to you,\'94 cried Marya Kondratyevna.\
\
\'93No; it\'92s a short cut, I\'92ll get over the fence again.\'94\
\
What he had heard threw Alyosha into great agitation. He ran to the\
tavern. It was impossible for him to go into the tavern in his monastic\
dress, but he could inquire at the entrance for his brothers and call them\
down. But just as he reached the tavern, a window was flung open, and his\
brother Ivan called down to him from it.\
\
\'93Alyosha, can\'92t you come up here to me? I shall be awfully grateful.\'94\
\
\'93To be sure I can, only I don\'92t quite know whether in this dress\'97\'94\
\
\'93But I am in a room apart. Come up the steps; I\'92ll run down to meet you.\'94\
\
A minute later Alyosha was sitting beside his brother. Ivan was alone\
dining.\
\
\
\
Chapter III. The Brothers Make Friends\
\
\
Ivan was not, however, in a separate room, but only in a place shut off by\
a screen, so that it was unseen by other people in the room. It was the\
first room from the entrance with a buffet along the wall. Waiters were\
continually darting to and fro in it. The only customer in the room was an\
old retired military man drinking tea in a corner. But there was the usual\
bustle going on in the other rooms of the tavern; there were shouts for\
the waiters, the sound of popping corks, the click of billiard balls, the\
drone of the organ. Alyosha knew that Ivan did not usually visit this\
tavern and disliked taverns in general. So he must have come here, he\
reflected, simply to meet Dmitri by arrangement. Yet Dmitri was not there.\
\
\'93Shall I order you fish, soup or anything. You don\'92t live on tea alone, I\
suppose,\'94 cried Ivan, apparently delighted at having got hold of Alyosha.\
He had finished dinner and was drinking tea.\
\
\'93Let me have soup, and tea afterwards, I am hungry,\'94 said Alyosha gayly.\
\
\'93And cherry jam? They have it here. You remember how you used to love\
cherry jam when you were little?\'94\
\
\'93You remember that? Let me have jam too, I like it still.\'94\
\
Ivan rang for the waiter and ordered soup, jam and tea.\
\
\'93I remember everything, Alyosha, I remember you till you were eleven, I\
was nearly fifteen. There\'92s such a difference between fifteen and eleven\
that brothers are never companions at those ages. I don\'92t know whether I\
was fond of you even. When I went away to Moscow for the first few years I\
never thought of you at all. Then, when you came to Moscow yourself, we\
only met once somewhere, I believe. And now I\'92ve been here more than three\
months, and so far we have scarcely said a word to each other. To\uc0\u8208 morrow I\
am going away, and I was just thinking as I sat here how I could see you\
to say good\uc0\u8208 by and just then you passed.\'94\
\
\'93Were you very anxious to see me, then?\'94\
\
\'93Very. I want to get to know you once for all, and I want you to know me.\
And then to say good\uc0\u8208 by. I believe it\'92s always best to get to know people\
just before leaving them. I\'92ve noticed how you\'92ve been looking at me these\
three months. There has been a continual look of expectation in your eyes,\
and I can\'92t endure that. That\'92s how it is I\'92ve kept away from you. But in\
the end I have learned to respect you. The little man stands firm, I\
thought. Though I am laughing, I am serious. You do stand firm, don\'92t you?\
I like people who are firm like that whatever it is they stand by, even if\
they are such little fellows as you. Your expectant eyes ceased to annoy\
me, I grew fond of them in the end, those expectant eyes. You seem to love\
me for some reason, Alyosha?\'94\
\
\'93I do love you, Ivan. Dmitri says of you\'97Ivan is a tomb! I say of you,\
Ivan is a riddle. You are a riddle to me even now. But I understand\
something in you, and I did not understand it till this morning.\'94\
\
\'93What\'92s that?\'94 laughed Ivan.\
\
\'93You won\'92t be angry?\'94 Alyosha laughed too.\
\
\'93Well?\'94\
\
\'93That you are just as young as other young men of three and twenty, that\
you are just a young and fresh and nice boy, green in fact! Now, have I\
insulted you dreadfully?\'94\
\
\'93On the contrary, I am struck by a coincidence,\'94 cried Ivan, warmly and\
good\uc0\u8208 humoredly. \'93Would you believe it that ever since that scene with her,\
I have thought of nothing else but my youthful greenness, and just as\
though you guessed that, you begin about it. Do you know I\'92ve been sitting\
here thinking to myself: that if I didn\'92t believe in life, if I lost faith\
in the woman I love, lost faith in the order of things, were convinced in\
fact that everything is a disorderly, damnable, and perhaps devil\uc0\u8208 ridden\
chaos, if I were struck by every horror of man\'92s disillusionment\'97still I\
should want to live and, having once tasted of the cup, I would not turn\
away from it till I had drained it! At thirty, though, I shall be sure to\
leave the cup, even if I\'92ve not emptied it, and turn away\'97where I don\'92t\
know. But till I am thirty, I know that my youth will triumph over\
everything\'97every disillusionment, every disgust with life. I\'92ve asked\
myself many times whether there is in the world any despair that would\
overcome this frantic and perhaps unseemly thirst for life in me, and I\'92ve\
come to the conclusion that there isn\'92t, that is till I am thirty, and\
then I shall lose it of myself, I fancy. Some driveling consumptive\
moralists\'97and poets especially\'97often call that thirst for life base. It\'92s\
a feature of the Karamazovs, it\'92s true, that thirst for life regardless of\
everything; you have it no doubt too, but why is it base? The centripetal\
force on our planet is still fearfully strong, Alyosha. I have a longing\
for life, and I go on living in spite of logic. Though I may not believe\
in the order of the universe, yet I love the sticky little leaves as they\
open in spring. I love the blue sky, I love some people, whom one loves\
you know sometimes without knowing why. I love some great deeds done by\
men, though I\'92ve long ceased perhaps to have faith in them, yet from old\
habit one\'92s heart prizes them. Here they have brought the soup for you,\
eat it, it will do you good. It\'92s first\uc0\u8208 rate soup, they know how to make\
it here. I want to travel in Europe, Alyosha, I shall set off from here.\
And yet I know that I am only going to a graveyard, but it\'92s a most\
precious graveyard, that\'92s what it is! Precious are the dead that lie\
there, every stone over them speaks of such burning life in the past, of\
such passionate faith in their work, their truth, their struggle and their\
science, that I know I shall fall on the ground and kiss those stones and\
weep over them; though I\'92m convinced in my heart that it\'92s long been\
nothing but a graveyard. And I shall not weep from despair, but simply\
because I shall be happy in my tears, I shall steep my soul in my emotion.\
I love the sticky leaves in spring, the blue sky\'97that\'92s all it is. It\'92s\
not a matter of intellect or logic, it\'92s loving with one\'92s inside, with\
one\'92s stomach. One loves the first strength of one\'92s youth. Do you\
understand anything of my tirade, Alyosha?\'94 Ivan laughed suddenly.\
\
\'93I understand too well, Ivan. One longs to love with one\'92s inside, with\
one\'92s stomach. You said that so well and I am awfully glad that you have\
such a longing for life,\'94 cried Alyosha. \'93I think every one should love\
life above everything in the world.\'94\
\
\'93Love life more than the meaning of it?\'94\
\
\'93Certainly, love it, regardless of logic as you say, it must be regardless\
of logic, and it\'92s only then one will understand the meaning of it. I have\
thought so a long time. Half your work is done, Ivan, you love life, now\
you\'92ve only to try to do the second half and you are saved.\'94\
\
\'93You are trying to save me, but perhaps I am not lost! And what does your\
second half mean?\'94\
\
\'93Why, one has to raise up your dead, who perhaps have not died after all.\
Come, let me have tea. I am so glad of our talk, Ivan.\'94\
\
\'93I see you are feeling inspired. I am awfully fond of such _professions de\
foi_ from such\'97novices. You are a steadfast person, Alexey. Is it true\
that you mean to leave the monastery?\'94\
\
\'93Yes, my elder sends me out into the world.\'94\
\
\'93We shall see each other then in the world. We shall meet before I am\
thirty, when I shall begin to turn aside from the cup. Father doesn\'92t want\
to turn aside from his cup till he is seventy, he dreams of hanging on to\
eighty in fact, so he says. He means it only too seriously, though he is a\
buffoon. He stands on a firm rock, too, he stands on his sensuality\'97though\
after we are thirty, indeed, there may be nothing else to stand on.... But\
to hang on to seventy is nasty, better only to thirty; one might retain \'91a\
shadow of nobility\'92 by deceiving oneself. Have you seen Dmitri to\uc0\u8208 day?\'94\
\
\'93No, but I saw Smerdyakov,\'94 and Alyosha rapidly, though minutely,\
described his meeting with Smerdyakov. Ivan began listening anxiously and\
questioned him.\
\
\'93But he begged me not to tell Dmitri that he had told me about him,\'94 added\
Alyosha. Ivan frowned and pondered.\
\
\'93Are you frowning on Smerdyakov\'92s account?\'94 asked Alyosha.\
\
\'93Yes, on his account. Damn him, I certainly did want to see Dmitri, but\
now there\'92s no need,\'94 said Ivan reluctantly.\
\
\'93But are you really going so soon, brother?\'94\
\
\'93Yes.\'94\
\
\'93What of Dmitri and father? how will it end?\'94 asked Alyosha anxiously.\
\
\'93You are always harping upon it! What have I to do with it? Am I my\
brother Dmitri\'92s keeper?\'94 Ivan snapped irritably, but then he suddenly\
smiled bitterly. \'93Cain\'92s answer about his murdered brother, wasn\'92t it?\
Perhaps that\'92s what you\'92re thinking at this moment? Well, damn it all, I\
can\'92t stay here to be their keeper, can I? I\'92ve finished what I had to do,\
and I am going. Do you imagine I am jealous of Dmitri, that I\'92ve been\
trying to steal his beautiful Katerina Ivanovna for the last three months?\
Nonsense, I had business of my own. I finished it. I am going. I finished\
it just now, you were witness.\'94\
\
\'93At Katerina Ivanovna\'92s?\'94\
\
\'93Yes, and I\'92ve released myself once for all. And after all, what have I to\
do with Dmitri? Dmitri doesn\'92t come in. I had my own business to settle\
with Katerina Ivanovna. You know, on the contrary, that Dmitri behaved as\
though there was an understanding between us. I didn\'92t ask him to do it,\
but he solemnly handed her over to me and gave us his blessing. It\'92s all\
too funny. Ah, Alyosha, if you only knew how light my heart is now! Would\
you believe, it, I sat here eating my dinner and was nearly ordering\
champagne to celebrate my first hour of freedom. Tfoo! It\'92s been going on\
nearly six months, and all at once I\'92ve thrown it off. I could never have\
guessed even yesterday, how easy it would be to put an end to it if I\
wanted.\'94\
\
\'93You are speaking of your love, Ivan?\'94\
\
\'93Of my love, if you like. I fell in love with the young lady, I worried\
myself over her and she worried me. I sat watching over her ... and all at\
once it\'92s collapsed! I spoke this morning with inspiration, but I went\
away and roared with laughter. Would you believe it? Yes, it\'92s the literal\
truth.\'94\
\
\'93You seem very merry about it now,\'94 observed Alyosha, looking into his\
face, which had suddenly grown brighter.\
\
\'93But how could I tell that I didn\'92t care for her a bit! Ha ha! It appears\
after all I didn\'92t. And yet how she attracted me! How attractive she was\
just now when I made my speech! And do you know she attracts me awfully\
even now, yet how easy it is to leave her. Do you think I am boasting?\'94\
\
\'93No, only perhaps it wasn\'92t love.\'94\
\
\'93Alyosha,\'94 laughed Ivan, \'93don\'92t make reflections about love, it\'92s unseemly\
for you. How you rushed into the discussion this morning! I\'92ve forgotten\
to kiss you for it.... But how she tormented me! It certainly was sitting\
by a \'91laceration.\'92 Ah, she knew how I loved her! She loved me and not\
Dmitri,\'94 Ivan insisted gayly. \'93Her feeling for Dmitri was simply a self\uc0\u8208 \
laceration. All I told her just now was perfectly true, but the worst of\
it is, it may take her fifteen or twenty years to find out that she\
doesn\'92t care for Dmitri, and loves me whom she torments, and perhaps she\
may never find it out at all, in spite of her lesson to\uc0\u8208 day. Well, it\'92s\
better so; I can simply go away for good. By the way, how is she now? What\
happened after I departed?\'94\
\
Alyosha told him she had been hysterical, and that she was now, he heard,\
unconscious and delirious.\
\
\'93Isn\'92t Madame Hohlakov laying it on?\'94\
\
\'93I think not.\'94\
\
\'93I must find out. Nobody dies of hysterics, though. They don\'92t matter. God\
gave woman hysterics as a relief. I won\'92t go to her at all. Why push\
myself forward again?\'94\
\
\'93But you told her that she had never cared for you.\'94\
\
\'93I did that on purpose. Alyosha, shall I call for some champagne? Let us\
drink to my freedom. Ah, if only you knew how glad I am!\'94\
\
\'93No, brother, we had better not drink,\'94 said Alyosha suddenly. \'93Besides I\
feel somehow depressed.\'94\
\
\'93Yes, you\'92ve been depressed a long time, I\'92ve noticed it.\'94\
\
\'93Have you settled to go to\uc0\u8208 morrow morning, then?\'94\
\
\'93Morning? I didn\'92t say I should go in the morning.... But perhaps it may\
be the morning. Would you believe it, I dined here to\uc0\u8208 day only to avoid\
dining with the old man, I loathe him so. I should have left long ago, so\
far as he is concerned. But why are you so worried about my going away?\
We\'92ve plenty of time before I go, an eternity!\'94\
\
\'93If you are going away to\uc0\u8208 morrow, what do you mean by an eternity?\'94\
\
\'93But what does it matter to us?\'94 laughed Ivan. \'93We\'92ve time enough for our\
talk, for what brought us here. Why do you look so surprised? Answer: why\
have we met here? To talk of my love for Katerina Ivanovna, of the old man\
and Dmitri? of foreign travel? of the fatal position of Russia? Of the\
Emperor Napoleon? Is that it?\'94\
\
\'93No.\'94\
\
\'93Then you know what for. It\'92s different for other people; but we in our\
green youth have to settle the eternal questions first of all. That\'92s what\
we care about. Young Russia is talking about nothing but the eternal\
questions now. Just when the old folks are all taken up with practical\
questions. Why have you been looking at me in expectation for the last\
three months? To ask me, \'91What do you believe, or don\'92t you believe at\
all?\'92 That\'92s what your eyes have been meaning for these three months,\
haven\'92t they?\'94\
\
\'93Perhaps so,\'94 smiled Alyosha. \'93You are not laughing at me, now, Ivan?\'94\
\
\'93Me laughing! I don\'92t want to wound my little brother who has been\
watching me with such expectation for three months. Alyosha, look straight\
at me! Of course I am just such a little boy as you are, only not a\
novice. And what have Russian boys been doing up till now, some of them, I\
mean? In this stinking tavern, for instance, here, they meet and sit down\
in a corner. They\'92ve never met in their lives before and, when they go out\
of the tavern, they won\'92t meet again for forty years. And what do they\
talk about in that momentary halt in the tavern? Of the eternal questions,\
of the existence of God and immortality. And those who do not believe in\
God talk of socialism or anarchism, of the transformation of all humanity\
on a new pattern, so that it all comes to the same, they\'92re the same\
questions turned inside out. And masses, masses of the most original\
Russian boys do nothing but talk of the eternal questions! Isn\'92t it so?\'94\
\
\'93Yes, for real Russians the questions of God\'92s existence and of\
immortality, or, as you say, the same questions turned inside out, come\
first and foremost, of course, and so they should,\'94 said Alyosha, still\
watching his brother with the same gentle and inquiring smile.\
\
\'93Well, Alyosha, it\'92s sometimes very unwise to be a Russian at all, but\
anything stupider than the way Russian boys spend their time one can\
hardly imagine. But there\'92s one Russian boy called Alyosha I am awfully\
fond of.\'94\
\
\'93How nicely you put that in!\'94 Alyosha laughed suddenly.\
\
\'93Well, tell me where to begin, give your orders. The existence of God,\
eh?\'94\
\
\'93Begin where you like. You declared yesterday at father\'92s that there was\
no God.\'94 Alyosha looked searchingly at his brother.\
\
\'93I said that yesterday at dinner on purpose to tease you and I saw your\
eyes glow. But now I\'92ve no objection to discussing with you, and I say so\
very seriously. I want to be friends with you, Alyosha, for I have no\
friends and want to try it. Well, only fancy, perhaps I too accept God,\'94\
laughed Ivan; \'93that\'92s a surprise for you, isn\'92t it?\'94\
\
\'93Yes, of course, if you are not joking now.\'94\
\
\'93Joking? I was told at the elder\'92s yesterday that I was joking. You know,\
dear boy, there was an old sinner in the eighteenth century who declared\
that, if there were no God, he would have to be invented. _S\'92il n\'92existait\
pas Dieu, il faudrait l\'92inventer._ And man has actually invented God. And\
what\'92s strange, what would be marvelous, is not that God should really\
exist; the marvel is that such an idea, the idea of the necessity of God,\
could enter the head of such a savage, vicious beast as man. So holy it\
is, so touching, so wise and so great a credit it does to man. As for me,\
I\'92ve long resolved not to think whether man created God or God man. And I\
won\'92t go through all the axioms laid down by Russian boys on that subject,\
all derived from European hypotheses; for what\'92s a hypothesis there, is an\
axiom with the Russian boy, and not only with the boys but with their\
teachers too, for our Russian professors are often just the same boys\
themselves. And so I omit all the hypotheses. For what are we aiming at\
now? I am trying to explain as quickly as possible my essential nature,\
that is what manner of man I am, what I believe in, and for what I hope,\
that\'92s it, isn\'92t it? And therefore I tell you that I accept God simply.\
But you must note this: if God exists and if He really did create the\
world, then, as we all know, He created it according to the geometry of\
Euclid and the human mind with the conception of only three dimensions in\
space. Yet there have been and still are geometricians and philosophers,\
and even some of the most distinguished, who doubt whether the whole\
universe, or to speak more widely the whole of being, was only created in\
Euclid\'92s geometry; they even dare to dream that two parallel lines, which\
according to Euclid can never meet on earth, may meet somewhere in\
infinity. I have come to the conclusion that, since I can\'92t understand\
even that, I can\'92t expect to understand about God. I acknowledge humbly\
that I have no faculty for settling such questions, I have a Euclidian\
earthly mind, and how could I solve problems that are not of this world?\
And I advise you never to think about it either, my dear Alyosha,\
especially about God, whether He exists or not. All such questions are\
utterly inappropriate for a mind created with an idea of only three\
dimensions. And so I accept God and am glad to, and what\'92s more, I accept\
His wisdom, His purpose\'97which are utterly beyond our ken; I believe in the\
underlying order and the meaning of life; I believe in the eternal harmony\
in which they say we shall one day be blended. I believe in the Word to\
Which the universe is striving, and Which Itself was \'91with God,\'92 and Which\
Itself is God and so on, and so on, to infinity. There are all sorts of\
phrases for it. I seem to be on the right path, don\'92t I? Yet would you\
believe it, in the final result I don\'92t accept this world of God\'92s, and,\
although I know it exists, I don\'92t accept it at all. It\'92s not that I don\'92t\
accept God, you must understand, it\'92s the world created by Him I don\'92t and\
cannot accept. Let me make it plain. I believe like a child that suffering\
will be healed and made up for, that all the humiliating absurdity of\
human contradictions will vanish like a pitiful mirage, like the\
despicable fabrication of the impotent and infinitely small Euclidian mind\
of man, that in the world\'92s finale, at the moment of eternal harmony,\
something so precious will come to pass that it will suffice for all\
hearts, for the comforting of all resentments, for the atonement of all\
the crimes of humanity, of all the blood they\'92ve shed; that it will make\
it not only possible to forgive but to justify all that has happened with\
men\'97but though all that may come to pass, I don\'92t accept it. I won\'92t\
accept it. Even if parallel lines do meet and I see it myself, I shall see\
it and say that they\'92ve met, but still I won\'92t accept it. That\'92s what\'92s at\
the root of me, Alyosha; that\'92s my creed. I am in earnest in what I say. I\
began our talk as stupidly as I could on purpose, but I\'92ve led up to my\
confession, for that\'92s all you want. You didn\'92t want to hear about God,\
but only to know what the brother you love lives by. And so I\'92ve told\
you.\'94\
\
Ivan concluded his long tirade with marked and unexpected feeling.\
\
\'93And why did you begin \'91as stupidly as you could\'92?\'94 asked Alyosha, looking\
dreamily at him.\
\
\'93To begin with, for the sake of being Russian. Russian conversations on\
such subjects are always carried on inconceivably stupidly. And secondly,\
the stupider one is, the closer one is to reality. The stupider one is,\
the clearer one is. Stupidity is brief and artless, while intelligence\
wriggles and hides itself. Intelligence is a knave, but stupidity is\
honest and straightforward. I\'92ve led the conversation to my despair, and\
the more stupidly I have presented it, the better for me.\'94\
\
\'93You will explain why you don\'92t accept the world?\'94 said Alyosha.\
\
\'93To be sure I will, it\'92s not a secret, that\'92s what I\'92ve been leading up\
to. Dear little brother, I don\'92t want to corrupt you or to turn you from\
your stronghold, perhaps I want to be healed by you.\'94 Ivan smiled suddenly\
quite like a little gentle child. Alyosha had never seen such a smile on\
his face before.\
\
\
\
Chapter IV. Rebellion\
\
\
\'93I must make you one confession,\'94 Ivan began. \'93I could never understand\
how one can love one\'92s neighbors. It\'92s just one\'92s neighbors, to my mind,\
that one can\'92t love, though one might love those at a distance. I once\
read somewhere of John the Merciful, a saint, that when a hungry, frozen\
beggar came to him, he took him into his bed, held him in his arms, and\
began breathing into his mouth, which was putrid and loathsome from some\
awful disease. I am convinced that he did that from \'91self\uc0\u8208 laceration,\'92\
from the self\uc0\u8208 laceration of falsity, for the sake of the charity imposed\
by duty, as a penance laid on him. For any one to love a man, he must be\
hidden, for as soon as he shows his face, love is gone.\'94\
\
\'93Father Zossima has talked of that more than once,\'94 observed Alyosha; \'93he,\
too, said that the face of a man often hinders many people not practiced\
in love, from loving him. But yet there\'92s a great deal of love in mankind,\
and almost Christ\uc0\u8208 like love. I know that myself, Ivan.\'94\
\
\'93Well, I know nothing of it so far, and can\'92t understand it, and the\
innumerable mass of mankind are with me there. The question is, whether\
that\'92s due to men\'92s bad qualities or whether it\'92s inherent in their\
nature. To my thinking, Christ\uc0\u8208 like love for men is a miracle impossible\
on earth. He was God. But we are not gods. Suppose I, for instance, suffer\
intensely. Another can never know how much I suffer, because he is another\
and not I. And what\'92s more, a man is rarely ready to admit another\'92s\
suffering (as though it were a distinction). Why won\'92t he admit it, do you\
think? Because I smell unpleasant, because I have a stupid face, because I\
once trod on his foot. Besides, there is suffering and suffering;\
degrading, humiliating suffering such as humbles me\'97hunger, for\
instance\'97my benefactor will perhaps allow me; but when you come to higher\
suffering\'97for an idea, for instance\'97he will very rarely admit that,\
perhaps because my face strikes him as not at all what he fancies a man\
should have who suffers for an idea. And so he deprives me instantly of\
his favor, and not at all from badness of heart. Beggars, especially\
genteel beggars, ought never to show themselves, but to ask for charity\
through the newspapers. One can love one\'92s neighbors in the abstract, or\
even at a distance, but at close quarters it\'92s almost impossible. If it\
were as on the stage, in the ballet, where if beggars come in, they wear\
silken rags and tattered lace and beg for alms dancing gracefully, then\
one might like looking at them. But even then we should not love them. But\
enough of that. I simply wanted to show you my point of view. I meant to\
speak of the suffering of mankind generally, but we had better confine\
ourselves to the sufferings of the children. That reduces the scope of my\
argument to a tenth of what it would be. Still we\'92d better keep to the\
children, though it does weaken my case. But, in the first place, children\
can be loved even at close quarters, even when they are dirty, even when\
they are ugly (I fancy, though, children never are ugly). The second\
reason why I won\'92t speak of grown\uc0\u8208 up people is that, besides being\
disgusting and unworthy of love, they have a compensation\'97they\'92ve eaten\
the apple and know good and evil, and they have become \'91like gods.\'92 They\
go on eating it still. But the children haven\'92t eaten anything, and are so\
far innocent. Are you fond of children, Alyosha? I know you are, and you\
will understand why I prefer to speak of them. If they, too, suffer\
horribly on earth, they must suffer for their fathers\'92 sins, they must be\
punished for their fathers, who have eaten the apple; but that reasoning\
is of the other world and is incomprehensible for the heart of man here on\
earth. The innocent must not suffer for another\'92s sins, and especially\
such innocents! You may be surprised at me, Alyosha, but I am awfully fond\
of children, too. And observe, cruel people, the violent, the rapacious,\
the Karamazovs are sometimes very fond of children. Children while they\
are quite little\'97up to seven, for instance\'97are so remote from grown\uc0\u8208 up\
people; they are different creatures, as it were, of a different species.\
I knew a criminal in prison who had, in the course of his career as a\
burglar, murdered whole families, including several children. But when he\
was in prison, he had a strange affection for them. He spent all his time\
at his window, watching the children playing in the prison yard. He\
trained one little boy to come up to his window and made great friends\
with him.... You don\'92t know why I am telling you all this, Alyosha? My\
head aches and I am sad.\'94\
\
\'93You speak with a strange air,\'94 observed Alyosha uneasily, \'93as though you\
were not quite yourself.\'94\
\
\'93By the way, a Bulgarian I met lately in Moscow,\'94 Ivan went on, seeming\
not to hear his brother\'92s words, \'93told me about the crimes committed by\
Turks and Circassians in all parts of Bulgaria through fear of a general\
rising of the Slavs. They burn villages, murder, outrage women and\
children, they nail their prisoners by the ears to the fences, leave them\
so till morning, and in the morning they hang them\'97all sorts of things you\
can\'92t imagine. People talk sometimes of bestial cruelty, but that\'92s a\
great injustice and insult to the beasts; a beast can never be so cruel as\
a man, so artistically cruel. The tiger only tears and gnaws, that\'92s all\
he can do. He would never think of nailing people by the ears, even if he\
were able to do it. These Turks took a pleasure in torturing children,\
too; cutting the unborn child from the mother\'92s womb, and tossing babies\
up in the air and catching them on the points of their bayonets before\
their mothers\'92 eyes. Doing it before the mothers\'92 eyes was what gave zest\
to the amusement. Here is another scene that I thought very interesting.\
Imagine a trembling mother with her baby in her arms, a circle of invading\
Turks around her. They\'92ve planned a diversion: they pet the baby, laugh to\
make it laugh. They succeed, the baby laughs. At that moment a Turk points\
a pistol four inches from the baby\'92s face. The baby laughs with glee,\
holds out its little hands to the pistol, and he pulls the trigger in the\
baby\'92s face and blows out its brains. Artistic, wasn\'92t it? By the way,\
Turks are particularly fond of sweet things, they say.\'94\
\
\'93Brother, what are you driving at?\'94 asked Alyosha.\
\
\'93I think if the devil doesn\'92t exist, but man has created him, he has\
created him in his own image and likeness.\'94\
\
\'93Just as he did God, then?\'94 observed Alyosha.\
\
\'93 \'91It\'92s wonderful how you can turn words,\'92 as Polonius says in _Hamlet_,\'94\
laughed Ivan. \'93You turn my words against me. Well, I am glad. Yours must\
be a fine God, if man created Him in his image and likeness. You asked\
just now what I was driving at. You see, I am fond of collecting certain\
facts, and, would you believe, I even copy anecdotes of a certain sort\
from newspapers and books, and I\'92ve already got a fine collection. The\
Turks, of course, have gone into it, but they are foreigners. I have\
specimens from home that are even better than the Turks. You know we\
prefer beating\'97rods and scourges\'97that\'92s our national institution. Nailing\
ears is unthinkable for us, for we are, after all, Europeans. But the rod\
and the scourge we have always with us and they cannot be taken from us.\
Abroad now they scarcely do any beating. Manners are more humane, or laws\
have been passed, so that they don\'92t dare to flog men now. But they make\
up for it in another way just as national as ours. And so national that it\
would be practically impossible among us, though I believe we are being\
inoculated with it, since the religious movement began in our aristocracy.\
I have a charming pamphlet, translated from the French, describing how,\
quite recently, five years ago, a murderer, Richard, was executed\'97a young\
man, I believe, of three and twenty, who repented and was converted to the\
Christian faith at the very scaffold. This Richard was an illegitimate\
child who was given as a child of six by his parents to some shepherds on\
the Swiss mountains. They brought him up to work for them. He grew up like\
a little wild beast among them. The shepherds taught him nothing, and\
scarcely fed or clothed him, but sent him out at seven to herd the flock\
in cold and wet, and no one hesitated or scrupled to treat him so. Quite\
the contrary, they thought they had every right, for Richard had been\
given to them as a chattel, and they did not even see the necessity of\
feeding him. Richard himself describes how in those years, like the\
Prodigal Son in the Gospel, he longed to eat of the mash given to the\
pigs, which were fattened for sale. But they wouldn\'92t even give him that,\
and beat him when he stole from the pigs. And that was how he spent all\
his childhood and his youth, till he grew up and was strong enough to go\
away and be a thief. The savage began to earn his living as a day laborer\
in Geneva. He drank what he earned, he lived like a brute, and finished by\
killing and robbing an old man. He was caught, tried, and condemned to\
death. They are not sentimentalists there. And in prison he was\
immediately surrounded by pastors, members of Christian brotherhoods,\
philanthropic ladies, and the like. They taught him to read and write in\
prison, and expounded the Gospel to him. They exhorted him, worked upon\
him, drummed at him incessantly, till at last he solemnly confessed his\
crime. He was converted. He wrote to the court himself that he was a\
monster, but that in the end God had vouchsafed him light and shown grace.\
All Geneva was in excitement about him\'97all philanthropic and religious\
Geneva. All the aristocratic and well\uc0\u8208 bred society of the town rushed to\
the prison, kissed Richard and embraced him; \'91You are our brother, you\
have found grace.\'92 And Richard does nothing but weep with emotion, \'91Yes,\
I\'92ve found grace! All my youth and childhood I was glad of pigs\'92 food, but\
now even I have found grace. I am dying in the Lord.\'92 \'91Yes, Richard, die\
in the Lord; you have shed blood and must die. Though it\'92s not your fault\
that you knew not the Lord, when you coveted the pigs\'92 food and were\
beaten for stealing it (which was very wrong of you, for stealing is\
forbidden); but you\'92ve shed blood and you must die.\'92 And on the last day,\
Richard, perfectly limp, did nothing but cry and repeat every minute:\
\'91This is my happiest day. I am going to the Lord.\'92 \'91Yes,\'92 cry the pastors\
and the judges and philanthropic ladies. \'91This is the happiest day of your\
life, for you are going to the Lord!\'92 They all walk or drive to the\
scaffold in procession behind the prison van. At the scaffold they call to\
