\
Chapter III. An Onion\
\
\
Grushenka lived in the busiest part of the town, near the cathedral\
square, in a small wooden lodge in the courtyard belonging to the house of\
the widow Morozov. The house was a large stone building of two stories,\
old and very ugly. The widow led a secluded life with her two unmarried\
nieces, who were also elderly women. She had no need to let her lodge, but\
every one knew that she had taken in Grushenka as a lodger, four years\
before, solely to please her kinsman, the merchant Samsonov, who was known\
to be the girl\'92s protector. It was said that the jealous old man\'92s object\
in placing his \'93favorite\'94 with the widow Morozov was that the old woman\
should keep a sharp eye on her new lodger\'92s conduct. But this sharp eye\
soon proved to be unnecessary, and in the end the widow Morozov seldom met\
Grushenka and did not worry her by looking after her in any way. It is\
true that four years had passed since the old man had brought the slim,\
delicate, shy, timid, dreamy, and sad girl of eighteen from the chief town\
of the province, and much had happened since then. Little was known of the\
girl\'92s history in the town and that little was vague. Nothing more had\
been learnt during the last four years, even after many persons had become\
interested in the beautiful young woman into whom Agrafena Alexandrovna\
had meanwhile developed. There were rumors that she had been at seventeen\
betrayed by some one, some sort of officer, and immediately afterwards\
abandoned by him. The officer had gone away and afterwards married, while\
Grushenka had been left in poverty and disgrace. It was said, however,\
that though Grushenka had been raised from destitution by the old man,\
Samsonov, she came of a respectable family belonging to the clerical\
class, that she was the daughter of a deacon or something of the sort.\
\
And now after four years the sensitive, injured and pathetic little orphan\
had become a plump, rosy beauty of the Russian type, a woman of bold and\
determined character, proud and insolent. She had a good head for\
business, was acquisitive, saving and careful, and by fair means or foul\
had succeeded, it was said, in amassing a little fortune. There was only\
one point on which all were agreed. Grushenka was not easily to be\
approached and except her aged protector there had not been one man who\
could boast of her favors during those four years. It was a positive fact,\
for there had been a good many, especially during the last two years, who\
had attempted to obtain those favors. But all their efforts had been in\
vain and some of these suitors had been forced to beat an undignified and\
even comic retreat, owing to the firm and ironical resistance they met\
from the strong\uc0\u8208 willed young person. It was known, too, that the young\
person had, especially of late, been given to what is called\
\'93speculation,\'94 and that she had shown marked abilities in that direction,\
so that many people began to say that she was no better than a Jew. It was\
not that she lent money on interest, but it was known, for instance, that\
she had for some time past, in partnership with old Karamazov, actually\
invested in the purchase of bad debts for a trifle, a tenth of their\
nominal value, and afterwards had made out of them ten times their value.\
\
The old widower Samsonov, a man of large fortune, was stingy and\
merciless. He tyrannized over his grown\uc0\u8208 up sons, but, for the last year\
during which he had been ill and lost the use of his swollen legs, he had\
fallen greatly under the influence of his prot\'e9g\'e9e, whom he had at first\
kept strictly and in humble surroundings, \'93on Lenten fare,\'94 as the wits\
said at the time. But Grushenka had succeeded in emancipating herself,\
while she established in him a boundless belief in her fidelity. The old\
man, now long since dead, had had a large business in his day and was also\
a noteworthy character, miserly and hard as flint. Though Grushenka\'92s hold\
upon him was so strong that he could not live without her (it had been so\
especially for the last two years), he did not settle any considerable\
fortune on her and would not have been moved to do so, if she had\
threatened to leave him. But he had presented her with a small sum, and\
even that was a surprise to every one when it became known.\
\
\'93You are a wench with brains,\'94 he said to her, when he gave her eight\
thousand roubles, \'93and you must look after yourself, but let me tell you\
that except your yearly allowance as before, you\'92ll get nothing more from\
me to the day of my death, and I\'92ll leave you nothing in my will either.\'94\
\
And he kept his word; he died and left everything to his sons, whom, with\
their wives and children, he had treated all his life as servants.\
Grushenka was not even mentioned in his will. All this became known\
afterwards. He helped Grushenka with his advice to increase her capital\
and put business in her way.\
\
When Fyodor Pavlovitch, who first came into contact with Grushenka over a\
piece of speculation, ended to his own surprise by falling madly in love\
with her, old Samsonov, gravely ill as he was, was immensely amused. It is\
remarkable that throughout their whole acquaintance Grushenka was\
absolutely and spontaneously open with the old man, and he seems to have\
been the only person in the world with whom she was so. Of late, when\
Dmitri too had come on the scene with his love, the old man left off\
laughing. On the contrary, he once gave Grushenka a stern and earnest\
piece of advice.\
\
\'93If you have to choose between the two, father or son, you\'92d better choose\
the old man, if only you make sure the old scoundrel will marry you and\
settle some fortune on you beforehand. But don\'92t keep on with the captain,\
you\'92ll get no good out of that.\'94\
\
These were the very words of the old profligate, who felt already that his\
death was not far off and who actually died five months later.\
\
I will note, too, in passing, that although many in our town knew of the\
grotesque and monstrous rivalry of the Karamazovs, father and son, the\
object of which was Grushenka, scarcely any one understood what really\
underlay her attitude to both of them. Even Grushenka\'92s two servants\
(after the catastrophe of which we will speak later) testified in court\
that she received Dmitri Fyodorovitch simply from fear because \'93he\
threatened to murder her.\'94 These servants were an old cook, invalidish and\
almost deaf, who came from Grushenka\'92s old home, and her granddaughter, a\
smart young girl of twenty, who performed the duties of a maid. Grushenka\
lived very economically and her surroundings were anything but luxurious.\
Her lodge consisted of three rooms furnished with mahogany furniture in\
the fashion of 1820, belonging to her landlady.\
\
It was quite dark when Rakitin and Alyosha entered her rooms, yet they\
were not lighted up. Grushenka was lying down in her drawing\uc0\u8208 room on the\
big, hard, clumsy sofa, with a mahogany back. The sofa was covered with\
shabby and ragged leather. Under her head she had two white down pillows\
taken from her bed. She was lying stretched out motionless on her back\
with her hands behind her head. She was dressed as though expecting some\
one, in a black silk dress, with a dainty lace fichu on her head, which\
was very becoming. Over her shoulders was thrown a lace shawl pinned with\
a massive gold brooch. She certainly was expecting some one. She lay as\
though impatient and weary, her face rather pale and her lips and eyes\
hot, restlessly tapping the arm of the sofa with the tip of her right\
foot. The appearance of Rakitin and Alyosha caused a slight excitement.\
From the hall they could hear Grushenka leap up from the sofa and cry out\
in a frightened voice, \'93Who\'92s there?\'94 But the maid met the visitors and at\
once called back to her mistress.\
\
\'93It\'92s not he, it\'92s nothing, only other visitors.\'94\
\
\'93What can be the matter?\'94 muttered Rakitin, leading Alyosha into the\
drawing\uc0\u8208 room.\
\
Grushenka was standing by the sofa as though still alarmed. A thick coil\
of her dark brown hair escaped from its lace covering and fell on her\
right shoulder, but she did not notice it and did not put it back till she\
had gazed at her visitors and recognized them.\
\
\'93Ah, it\'92s you, Rakitin? You quite frightened me. Whom have you brought?\
Who is this with you? Good heavens, you have brought him!\'94 she exclaimed,\
recognizing Alyosha.\
\
\'93Do send for candles!\'94 said Rakitin, with the free\uc0\u8208 and\u8208 easy air of a most\
intimate friend, who is privileged to give orders in the house.\
\
\'93Candles ... of course, candles.... Fenya, fetch him a candle.... Well,\
you have chosen a moment to bring him!\'94 she exclaimed again, nodding\
towards Alyosha, and turning to the looking\uc0\u8208 glass she began quickly\
fastening up her hair with both hands. She seemed displeased.\
\
\'93Haven\'92t I managed to please you?\'94 asked Rakitin, instantly almost\
offended.\
\
\'93You frightened me, Rakitin, that\'92s what it is.\'94 Grushenka turned with a\
smile to Alyosha. \'93Don\'92t be afraid of me, my dear Alyosha, you cannot\
think how glad I am to see you, my unexpected visitor. But you frightened\
me, Rakitin, I thought it was Mitya breaking in. You see, I deceived him\
just now, I made him promise to believe me and I told him a lie. I told\
him that I was going to spend the evening with my old man, Kuzma Kuzmitch,\
and should be there till late counting up his money. I always spend one\
whole evening a week with him making up his accounts. We lock ourselves in\
and he counts on the reckoning beads while I sit and put things down in\
the book. I am the only person he trusts. Mitya believes that I am there,\
but I came back and have been sitting locked in here, expecting some news.\
How was it Fenya let you in? Fenya, Fenya, run out to the gate, open it\
and look about whether the captain is to be seen! Perhaps he is hiding and\
spying, I am dreadfully frightened.\'94\
\
\'93There\'92s no one there, Agrafena Alexandrovna, I\'92ve just looked out, I keep\
running to peep through the crack, I am in fear and trembling myself.\'94\
\
\'93Are the shutters fastened, Fenya? And we must draw the curtains\'97that\'92s\
better!\'94 She drew the heavy curtains herself. \'93He\'92d rush in at once if he\
saw a light. I am afraid of your brother Mitya to\uc0\u8208 day, Alyosha.\'94\
\
Grushenka spoke aloud, and, though she was alarmed, she seemed very happy\
about something.\
\
\'93Why are you so afraid of Mitya to\uc0\u8208 day?\'94 inquired Rakitin. \'93I should have\
thought you were not timid with him, you\'92d twist him round your little\
finger.\'94\
\
\'93I tell you, I am expecting news, priceless news, so I don\'92t want Mitya at\
all. And he didn\'92t believe, I feel he didn\'92t, that I should stay at Kuzma\
Kuzmitch\'92s. He must be in his ambush now, behind Fyodor Pavlovitch\'92s, in\
the garden, watching for me. And if he\'92s there, he won\'92t come here, so\
much the better! But I really have been to Kuzma Kuzmitch\'92s, Mitya\
escorted me there. I told him I should stay there till midnight, and I\
asked him to be sure to come at midnight to fetch me home. He went away\
and I sat ten minutes with Kuzma Kuzmitch and came back here again. Ugh, I\
was afraid, I ran for fear of meeting him.\'94\
\
\'93And why are you so dressed up? What a curious cap you\'92ve got on!\'94\
\
\'93How curious you are yourself, Rakitin! I tell you, I am expecting a\
message. If the message comes, I shall fly, I shall gallop away and you\
will see no more of me. That\'92s why I am dressed up, so as to be ready.\'94\
\
\'93And where are you flying to?\'94\
\
\'93If you know too much, you\'92ll get old too soon.\'94\
\
\'93Upon my word! You are highly delighted ... I\'92ve never seen you like this\
before. You are dressed up as if you were going to a ball.\'94 Rakitin looked\
her up and down.\
\
\'93Much you know about balls.\'94\
\
\'93And do you know much about them?\'94\
\
\'93I have seen a ball. The year before last, Kuzma Kuzmitch\'92s son was\
married and I looked on from the gallery. Do you suppose I want to be\
talking to you, Rakitin, while a prince like this is standing here. Such a\
visitor! Alyosha, my dear boy, I gaze at you and can\'92t believe my eyes.\
Good heavens, can you have come here to see me! To tell you the truth, I\
never had a thought of seeing you and I didn\'92t think that you would ever\
come and see me. Though this is not the moment now, I am awfully glad to\
see you. Sit down on the sofa, here, that\'92s right, my bright young moon. I\
really can\'92t take it in even now.... Eh, Rakitin, if only you had brought\
him yesterday or the day before! But I am glad as it is! Perhaps it\'92s\
better he has come now, at such a moment, and not the day before\
yesterday.\'94\
\
She gayly sat down beside Alyosha on the sofa, looking at him with\
positive delight. And she really was glad, she was not lying when she said\
so. Her eyes glowed, her lips laughed, but it was a good\uc0\u8208 hearted merry\
laugh. Alyosha had not expected to see such a kind expression in her\
face.... He had hardly met her till the day before, he had formed an\
alarming idea of her, and had been horribly distressed the day before by\
the spiteful and treacherous trick she had played on Katerina Ivanovna. He\
was greatly surprised to find her now altogether different from what he\
had expected. And, crushed as he was by his own sorrow, his eyes\
involuntarily rested on her with attention. Her whole manner seemed\
changed for the better since yesterday, there was scarcely any trace of\
that mawkish sweetness in her speech, of that voluptuous softness in her\
movements. Everything was simple and good\uc0\u8208 natured, her gestures were\
rapid, direct, confiding, but she was greatly excited.\
\
\'93Dear me, how everything comes together to\uc0\u8208 day!\'94 she chattered on again.\
\'93And why I am so glad to see you, Alyosha, I couldn\'92t say myself! If you\
ask me, I couldn\'92t tell you.\'94\
\
\'93Come, don\'92t you know why you\'92re glad?\'94 said Rakitin, grinning. \'93You used\
to be always pestering me to bring him, you\'92d some object, I suppose.\'94\
\
\'93I had a different object once, but now that\'92s over, this is not the\
moment. I say, I want you to have something nice. I am so good\uc0\u8208 natured\
now. You sit down, too, Rakitin; why are you standing? You\'92ve sat down\
already? There\'92s no fear of Rakitin\'92s forgetting to look after himself.\
Look, Alyosha, he\'92s sitting there opposite us, so offended that I didn\'92t\
ask him to sit down before you. Ugh, Rakitin is such a one to take\
offense!\'94 laughed Grushenka. \'93Don\'92t be angry, Rakitin, I\'92m kind to\uc0\u8208 day.\
Why are you so depressed, Alyosha? Are you afraid of me?" She peeped into\
his eyes with merry mockery\'94\
\
\'93He\'92s sad. The promotion has not been given,\'94 boomed Rakitin.\
\
\'93What promotion?\'94\
\
\'93His elder stinks.\'94\
\
\'93What? You are talking some nonsense, you want to say something nasty. Be\
quiet, you stupid! Let me sit on your knee, Alyosha, like this.\'94 She\
suddenly skipped forward and jumped, laughing, on his knee, like a\
nestling kitten, with her right arm about his neck. \'93I\'92ll cheer you up, my\
pious boy. Yes, really, will you let me sit on your knee? You won\'92t be\
angry? If you tell me, I\'92ll get off?\'94\
\
Alyosha did not speak. He sat afraid to move, he heard her words, \'93If you\
tell me, I\'92ll get off,\'94 but he did not answer. But there was nothing in\
his heart such as Rakitin, for instance, watching him malignantly from his\
corner, might have expected or fancied. The great grief in his heart\
swallowed up every sensation that might have been aroused, and, if only he\
could have thought clearly at that moment, he would have realized that he\
had now the strongest armor to protect him from every lust and temptation.\
Yet in spite of the vague irresponsiveness of his spiritual condition and\
the sorrow that overwhelmed him, he could not help wondering at a new and\
strange sensation in his heart. This woman, this \'93dreadful\'94 woman, had no\
terror for him now, none of that terror that had stirred in his soul at\
any passing thought of woman. On the contrary, this woman, dreaded above\
all women, sitting now on his knee, holding him in her arms, aroused in\
him now a quite different, unexpected, peculiar feeling, a feeling of the\
intensest and purest interest without a trace of fear, of his former\
terror. That was what instinctively surprised him.\
\
\'93You\'92ve talked nonsense enough,\'94 cried Rakitin, \'93you\'92d much better give us\
some champagne. You owe it me, you know you do!\'94\
\
\'93Yes, I really do. Do you know, Alyosha, I promised him champagne on the\
top of everything, if he\'92d bring you? I\'92ll have some too! Fenya, Fenya,\
bring us the bottle Mitya left! Look sharp! Though I am so stingy, I\'92ll\
stand a bottle, not for you, Rakitin, you\'92re a toadstool, but he is a\
falcon! And though my heart is full of something very different, so be it,\
I\'92ll drink with you. I long for some dissipation.\'94\
\
\'93But what is the matter with you? And what is this message, may I ask, or\
is it a secret?\'94 Rakitin put in inquisitively, doing his best to pretend\
not to notice the snubs that were being continually aimed at him.\
\
\'93Ech, it\'92s not a secret, and you know it, too,\'94 Grushenka said, in a voice\
suddenly anxious, turning her head towards Rakitin, and drawing a little\
away from Alyosha, though she still sat on his knee with her arm round his\
neck. \'93My officer is coming, Rakitin, my officer is coming.\'94\
\
\'93I heard he was coming, but is he so near?\'94\
\
\'93He is at Mokroe now; he\'92ll send a messenger from there, so he wrote; I\
got a letter from him to\uc0\u8208 day. I am expecting the messenger every minute.\'94\
\
\'93You don\'92t say so! Why at Mokroe?\'94\
\
\'93That\'92s a long story, I\'92ve told you enough.\'94\
\
\'93Mitya\'92ll be up to something now\'97I say! Does he know or doesn\'92t he?\'94\
\
\'93He know! Of course he doesn\'92t. If he knew, there would be murder. But I\
am not afraid of that now, I am not afraid of his knife. Be quiet,\
Rakitin, don\'92t remind me of Dmitri Fyodorovitch, he has bruised my heart.\
And I don\'92t want to think of that at this moment. I can think of Alyosha\
here, I can look at Alyosha ... smile at me, dear, cheer up, smile at my\
foolishness, at my pleasure.... Ah, he\'92s smiling, he\'92s smiling! How kindly\
he looks at me! And you know, Alyosha, I\'92ve been thinking all this time\
you were angry with me, because of the day before yesterday, because of\
that young lady. I was a cur, that\'92s the truth.... But it\'92s a good thing\
it happened so. It was a horrid thing, but a good thing too.\'94 Grushenka\
smiled dreamily and a little cruel line showed in her smile. \'93Mitya told\
me that she screamed out that I \'91ought to be flogged.\'92 I did insult her\
dreadfully. She sent for me, she wanted to make a conquest of me, to win\
me over with her chocolate.... No, it\'92s a good thing it did end like\
that.\'94 She smiled again. \'93But I am still afraid of your being angry.\'94\
\
\'93Yes, that\'92s really true,\'94 Rakitin put in suddenly with genuine surprise.\
\'93Alyosha, she is really afraid of a chicken like you.\'94\
\
\'93He is a chicken to you, Rakitin ... because you\'92ve no conscience, that\'92s\
what it is! You see, I love him with all my soul, that\'92s how it is!\
Alyosha, do you believe I love you with all my soul?\'94\
\
\'93Ah, you shameless woman! She is making you a declaration, Alexey!\'94\
\
\'93Well, what of it, I love him!\'94\
\
\'93And what about your officer? And the priceless message from Mokroe?\'94\
\
\'93That is quite different.\'94\
\
\'93That\'92s a woman\'92s way of looking at it!\'94\
\
\'93Don\'92t you make me angry, Rakitin.\'94 Grushenka caught him up hotly. \'93This\
is quite different. I love Alyosha in a different way. It\'92s true, Alyosha,\
I had sly designs on you before. For I am a horrid, violent creature. But\
at other times I\'92ve looked upon you, Alyosha, as my conscience. I\'92ve kept\
thinking \'91how any one like that must despise a nasty thing like me.\'92 I\
thought that the day before yesterday, as I ran home from the young\
lady\'92s. I have thought of you a long time in that way, Alyosha, and Mitya\
knows, I\'92ve talked to him about it. Mitya understands. Would you believe\
it, I sometimes look at you and feel ashamed, utterly ashamed of\
myself.... And how, and since when, I began to think about you like that,\
I can\'92t say, I don\'92t remember....\'94\
\
Fenya came in and put a tray with an uncorked bottle and three glasses of\
champagne on the table.\
\
\'93Here\'92s the champagne!\'94 cried Rakitin. \'93You\'92re excited, Agrafena\
Alexandrovna, and not yourself. When you\'92ve had a glass of champagne,\
you\'92ll be ready to dance. Eh, they can\'92t even do that properly,\'94 he added,\
looking at the bottle. \'93The old woman\'92s poured it out in the kitchen and\
the bottle\'92s been brought in warm and without a cork. Well, let me have\
some, anyway.\'94\
\
He went up to the table, took a glass, emptied it at one gulp and poured\
himself out another.\
\
\'93One doesn\'92t often stumble upon champagne,\'94 he said, licking his lips.\
\'93Now, Alyosha, take a glass, show what you can do! What shall we drink to?\
The gates of paradise? Take a glass, Grushenka, you drink to the gates of\
paradise, too.\'94\
\
\'93What gates of paradise?\'94\
\
She took a glass, Alyosha took his, tasted it and put it back.\
\
\'93No, I\'92d better not,\'94 he smiled gently.\
\
\'93And you bragged!\'94 cried Rakitin.\
\
\'93Well, if so, I won\'92t either,\'94 chimed in Grushenka, \'93I really don\'92t want\
any. You can drink the whole bottle alone, Rakitin. If Alyosha has some, I\
will.\'94\
\
\'93What touching sentimentality!\'94 said Rakitin tauntingly; \'93and she\'92s\
sitting on his knee, too! He\'92s got something to grieve over, but what\'92s\
the matter with you? He is rebelling against his God and ready to eat\
sausage....\'94\
\
\'93How so?\'94\
\
\'93His elder died to\uc0\u8208 day, Father Zossima, the saint.\'94\
\
\'93So Father Zossima is dead,\'94 cried Grushenka. \'93Good God, I did not know!\'94\
She crossed herself devoutly. \'93Goodness, what have I been doing, sitting\
on his knee like this at such a moment!\'94 She started up as though in\
dismay, instantly slipped off his knee and sat down on the sofa.\
\
Alyosha bent a long wondering look upon her and a light seemed to dawn in\
his face.\
\
\'93Rakitin,\'94 he said suddenly, in a firm and loud voice; \'93don\'92t taunt me\
with having rebelled against God. I don\'92t want to feel angry with you, so\
you must be kinder, too, I\'92ve lost a treasure such as you have never had,\
and you cannot judge me now. You had much better look at her\'97do you see\
how she has pity on me? I came here to find a wicked soul\'97I felt drawn to\
evil because I was base and evil myself, and I\'92ve found a true sister, I\
have found a treasure\'97a loving heart. She had pity on me just now....\
Agrafena Alexandrovna, I am speaking of you. You\'92ve raised my soul from\
the depths.\'94\
\
Alyosha\'92s lips were quivering and he caught his breath.\
\
\'93She has saved you, it seems,\'94 laughed Rakitin spitefully. \'93And she meant\
to get you in her clutches, do you realize that?\'94\
\
\'93Stay, Rakitin.\'94 Grushenka jumped up. \'93Hush, both of you. Now I\'92ll tell\
you all about it. Hush, Alyosha, your words make me ashamed, for I am bad\
and not good\'97that\'92s what I am. And you hush, Rakitin, because you are\
telling lies. I had the low idea of trying to get him in my clutches, but\
now you are lying, now it\'92s all different. And don\'92t let me hear anything\
more from you, Rakitin.\'94\
\
All this Grushenka said with extreme emotion.\
\
\'93They are both crazy,\'94 said Rakitin, looking at them with amazement. \'93I\
feel as though I were in a madhouse. They\'92re both getting so feeble\
they\'92ll begin crying in a minute.\'94\
\
\'93I shall begin to cry, I shall,\'94 repeated Grushenka. \'93He called me his\
sister and I shall never forget that. Only let me tell you, Rakitin,\
though I am bad, I did give away an onion.\'94\
\
\'93An onion? Hang it all, you really are crazy.\'94\
\
Rakitin wondered at their enthusiasm. He was aggrieved and annoyed, though\
he might have reflected that each of them was just passing through a\
spiritual crisis such as does not come often in a lifetime. But though\
Rakitin was very sensitive about everything that concerned himself, he was\
very obtuse as regards the feelings and sensations of others\'97partly from\
his youth and inexperience, partly from his intense egoism.\
\
\'93You see, Alyosha,\'94 Grushenka turned to him with a nervous laugh. \'93I was\
boasting when I told Rakitin I had given away an onion, but it\'92s not to\
boast I tell you about it. It\'92s only a story, but it\'92s a nice story. I\
used to hear it when I was a child from Matryona, my cook, who is still\
with me. It\'92s like this. Once upon a time there was a peasant woman and a\
very wicked woman she was. And she died and did not leave a single good\
deed behind. The devils caught her and plunged her into the lake of fire.\
So her guardian angel stood and wondered what good deed of hers he could\
remember to tell to God; \'91She once pulled up an onion in her garden,\'92 said\
he, \'91and gave it to a beggar woman.\'92 And God answered: \'91You take that\
onion then, hold it out to her in the lake, and let her take hold and be\
pulled out. And if you can pull her out of the lake, let her come to\
Paradise, but if the onion breaks, then the woman must stay where she is.\'92\
The angel ran to the woman and held out the onion to her. \'91Come,\'92 said he,\
\'91catch hold and I\'92ll pull you out.\'92 And he began cautiously pulling her\
out. He had just pulled her right out, when the other sinners in the lake,\
seeing how she was being drawn out, began catching hold of her so as to be\
pulled out with her. But she was a very wicked woman and she began kicking\
them. \'91I\'92m to be pulled out, not you. It\'92s my onion, not yours.\'92 As soon\
as she said that, the onion broke. And the woman fell into the lake and\
she is burning there to this day. So the angel wept and went away. So\
that\'92s the story, Alyosha; I know it by heart, for I am that wicked woman\
myself. I boasted to Rakitin that I had given away an onion, but to you\
I\'92ll say: \'91I\'92ve done nothing but give away one onion all my life, that\'92s\
the only good deed I\'92ve done.\'92 So don\'92t praise me, Alyosha, don\'92t think me\
good, I am bad, I am a wicked woman and you make me ashamed if you praise\
me. Eh, I must confess everything. Listen, Alyosha. I was so anxious to\
get hold of you that I promised Rakitin twenty\uc0\u8208 five roubles if he would\
bring you to me. Stay, Rakitin, wait!\'94\
\
She went with rapid steps to the table, opened a drawer, pulled out a\
purse and took from it a twenty\uc0\u8208 five rouble note.\
\
\'93What nonsense! What nonsense!\'94 cried Rakitin, disconcerted.\
\
\'93Take it. Rakitin, I owe it you, there\'92s no fear of your refusing it, you\
asked for it yourself.\'94 And she threw the note to him.\
\
\'93Likely I should refuse it,\'94 boomed Rakitin, obviously abashed, but\
carrying off his confusion with a swagger. \'93That will come in very handy;\
fools are made for wise men\'92s profit.\'94\
\
\'93And now hold your tongue, Rakitin, what I am going to say now is not for\
your ears. Sit down in that corner and keep quiet. You don\'92t like us, so\
hold your tongue.\'94\
\
\'93What should I like you for?\'94 Rakitin snarled, not concealing his ill\uc0\u8208 \
humor. He put the twenty\uc0\u8208 five rouble note in his pocket and he felt\
ashamed at Alyosha\'92s seeing it. He had reckoned on receiving his payment\
later, without Alyosha\'92s knowing of it, and now, feeling ashamed, he lost\
his temper. Till that moment he had thought it discreet not to contradict\
Grushenka too flatly in spite of her snubbing, since he had something to\
get out of her. But now he, too, was angry:\
\
\'93One loves people for some reason, but what have either of you done for\
me?\'94\
\
\'93You should love people without a reason, as Alyosha does.\'94\
\
\'93How does he love you? How has he shown it, that you make such a fuss\
about it?\'94\
\
Grushenka was standing in the middle of the room; she spoke with heat and\
there were hysterical notes in her voice.\
\
\'93Hush, Rakitin, you know nothing about us! And don\'92t dare to speak to me\
like that again. How dare you be so familiar! Sit in that corner and be\
quiet, as though you were my footman! And now, Alyosha, I\'92ll tell you the\
whole truth, that you may see what a wretch I am! I am not talking to\
Rakitin, but to you. I wanted to ruin you, Alyosha, that\'92s the holy truth;\
I quite meant to. I wanted to so much, that I bribed Rakitin to bring you.\
And why did I want to do such a thing? You knew nothing about it, Alyosha,\
you turned away from me; if you passed me, you dropped your eyes. And I\'92ve\
looked at you a hundred times before to\uc0\u8208 day; I began asking every one\
about you. Your face haunted my heart. \'91He despises me,\'92 I thought; \'91he\
won\'92t even look at me.\'92 And I felt it so much at last that I wondered at\
myself for being so frightened of a boy. I\'92ll get him in my clutches and\
laugh at him. I was full of spite and anger. Would you believe it, nobody\
here dares talk or think of coming to Agrafena Alexandrovna with any evil\
purpose. Old Kuzma is the only man I have anything to do with here; I was\
bound and sold to him; Satan brought us together, but there has been no\
one else. But looking at you, I thought, I\'92ll get him in my clutches and\
laugh at him. You see what a spiteful cur I am, and you called me your\
sister! And now that man who wronged me has come; I sit here waiting for a\
message from him. And do you know what that man has been to me? Five years\
ago, when Kuzma brought me here, I used to shut myself up, that no one\
might have sight or sound of me. I was a silly slip of a girl; I used to\
sit here sobbing; I used to lie awake all night, thinking: \'91Where is he\
now, the man who wronged me? He is laughing at me with another woman, most\
likely. If only I could see him, if I could meet him again, I\'92d pay him\
out, I\'92d pay him out!\'92 At night I used to lie sobbing into my pillow in\
the dark, and I used to brood over it; I used to tear my heart on purpose\
and gloat over my anger. \'91I\'92ll pay him out, I\'92ll pay him out!\'92 That\'92s what\
I used to cry out in the dark. And when I suddenly thought that I should\
really do nothing to him, and that he was laughing at me then, or perhaps\
had utterly forgotten me, I would fling myself on the floor, melt into\
helpless tears, and lie there shaking till dawn. In the morning I would\
get up more spiteful than a dog, ready to tear the whole world to pieces.\
And then what do you think? I began saving money, I became hard\uc0\u8208 hearted,\
grew stout\'97grew wiser, would you say? No, no one in the whole world sees\
it, no one knows it, but when night comes on, I sometimes lie as I did\
five years ago, when I was a silly girl, clenching my teeth and crying all\
night, thinking, \'91I\'92ll pay him out, I\'92ll pay him out!\'92 Do you hear? Well\
then, now you understand me. A month ago a letter came to me\'97he was\
coming, he was a widower, he wanted to see me. It took my breath away;\
then I suddenly thought: \'91If he comes and whistles to call me, I shall\
creep back to him like a beaten dog.\'92 I couldn\'92t believe myself. Am I so\
abject? Shall I run to him or not? And I\'92ve been in such a rage with\
myself all this month that I am worse than I was five years ago. Do you\
see now, Alyosha, what a violent, vindictive creature I am? I have shown\
you the whole truth! I played with Mitya to keep me from running to that\
other. Hush, Rakitin, it\'92s not for you to judge me, I am not speaking to\
you. Before you came in, I was lying here waiting, brooding, deciding my\
whole future life, and you can never know what was in my heart. Yes,\
Alyosha, tell your young lady not to be angry with me for what happened\
the day before yesterday.... Nobody in the whole world knows what I am\
going through now, and no one ever can know.... For perhaps I shall take a\
knife with me to\uc0\u8208 day, I can\'92t make up my mind ...\'94\
\
And at this \'93tragic\'94 phrase Grushenka broke down, hid her face in her\
hands, flung herself on the sofa pillows, and sobbed like a little child.\
\
Alyosha got up and went to Rakitin.\
\
\'93Misha,\'94 he said, \'93don\'92t be angry. She wounded you, but don\'92t be angry.\
You heard what she said just now? You mustn\'92t ask too much of human\
endurance, one must be merciful.\'94\
\
Alyosha said this at the instinctive prompting of his heart. He felt\
obliged to speak and he turned to Rakitin. If Rakitin had not been there,\
he would have spoken to the air. But Rakitin looked at him ironically and\
Alyosha stopped short.\
\
\'93You were so primed up with your elder\'92s teaching last night that now you\
have to let it off on me, Alexey, man of God!\'94 said Rakitin, with a smile\
of hatred.\
\
\'93Don\'92t laugh, Rakitin, don\'92t smile, don\'92t talk of the dead\'97he was better\
than any one in the world!\'94 cried Alyosha, with tears in his voice. \'93I\
didn\'92t speak to you as a judge but as the lowest of the judged. What am I\
beside her? I came here seeking my ruin, and said to myself, \'91What does it\
matter?\'92 in my cowardliness, but she, after five years in torment, as soon\
as any one says a word from the heart to her\'97it makes her forget\
everything, forgive everything, in her tears! The man who has wronged her\
has come back, he sends for her and she forgives him everything, and\
hastens joyfully to meet him and she won\'92t take a knife with her. She\
won\'92t! No, I am not like that. I don\'92t know whether you are, Misha, but I\
am not like that. It\'92s a lesson to me.... She is more loving than we....\
Have you heard her speak before of what she has just told us? No, you\
haven\'92t; if you had, you\'92d have understood her long ago ... and the person\
insulted the day before yesterday must forgive her, too! She will, when\
she knows ... and she shall know.... This soul is not yet at peace with\
itself, one must be tender with it ... there may be a treasure in that\
soul....\'94\
\
Alyosha stopped, because he caught his breath. In spite of his ill\uc0\u8208 humor\
Rakitin looked at him with astonishment. He had never expected such a\
tirade from the gentle Alyosha.\
\
\'93She\'92s found some one to plead her cause! Why, are you in love with her?\
Agrafena Alexandrovna, our monk\'92s really in love with you, you\'92ve made a\
conquest!\'94 he cried, with a coarse laugh.\
\
Grushenka lifted her head from the pillow and looked at Alyosha with a\
tender smile shining on her tear\uc0\u8208 stained face.\
\
\'93Let him alone, Alyosha, my cherub; you see what he is, he is not a person\
for you to speak to. Mihail Osipovitch,\'94 she turned to Rakitin, \'93I meant\
to beg your pardon for being rude to you, but now I don\'92t want to.\
Alyosha, come to me, sit down here.\'94 She beckoned to him with a happy\
smile. \'93That\'92s right, sit here. Tell me,\'94 she shook him by the hand and\
peeped into his face, smiling, \'93tell me, do I love that man or not? the\
man who wronged me, do I love him or not? Before you came, I lay here in\
the dark, asking my heart whether I loved him. Decide for me, Alyosha, the\
time has come, it shall be as you say. Am I to forgive him or not?\'94\
\
\'93But you have forgiven him already,\'94 said Alyosha, smiling.\
\
\'93Yes, I really have forgiven him,\'94 Grushenka murmured thoughtfully. \'93What\
an abject heart! To my abject heart!\'94 She snatched up a glass from the\
table, emptied it at a gulp, lifted it in the air and flung it on the\
floor. The glass broke with a crash. A little cruel line came into her\
smile.\
\
\'93Perhaps I haven\'92t forgiven him, though,\'94 she said, with a sort of menace\
in her voice, and she dropped her eyes to the ground as though she were\
talking to herself. \'93Perhaps my heart is only getting ready to forgive. I\
shall struggle with my heart. You see, Alyosha, I\'92ve grown to love my\
tears in these five years.... Perhaps I only love my resentment, not him\
...\'94\
\
\'93Well, I shouldn\'92t care to be in his shoes,\'94 hissed Rakitin.\
\
\'93Well, you won\'92t be, Rakitin, you\'92ll never be in his shoes. You shall\
black my shoes, Rakitin, that\'92s the place you are fit for. You\'92ll never\
get a woman like me ... and he won\'92t either, perhaps ...\'94\
\
\'93Won\'92t he? Then why are you dressed up like that?\'94 said Rakitin, with a\
venomous sneer.\
\
\'93Don\'92t taunt me with dressing up, Rakitin, you don\'92t know all that is in\
my heart! If I choose to tear off my finery, I\'92ll tear it off at once,\
this minute,\'94 she cried in a resonant voice. \'93You don\'92t know what that\
finery is for, Rakitin! Perhaps I shall see him and say: \'91Have you ever\
seen me look like this before?\'92 He left me a thin, consumptive cry\uc0\u8208 baby of\
seventeen. I\'92ll sit by him, fascinate him and work him up. \'91Do you see\
what I am like now?\'92 I\'92ll say to him; \'91well, and that\'92s enough for you, my\
dear sir, there\'92s many a slip twixt the cup and the lip!\'92 That may be what\
the finery is for, Rakitin.\'94 Grushenka finished with a malicious laugh.\
\'93I\'92m violent and resentful, Alyosha, I\'92ll tear off my finery, I\'92ll destroy\
my beauty, I\'92ll scorch my face, slash it with a knife, and turn beggar. If\
I choose, I won\'92t go anywhere now to see any one. If I choose, I\'92ll send\
Kuzma back all he has ever given me, to\uc0\u8208 morrow, and all his money and I\'92ll\
go out charing for the rest of my life. You think I wouldn\'92t do it,\
Rakitin, that I would not dare to do it? I would, I would, I could do it\
directly, only don\'92t exasperate me ... and I\'92ll send him about his\
business, I\'92ll snap my fingers in his face, he shall never see me again!\'94\
\
She uttered the last words in an hysterical scream, but broke down again,\
hid her face in her hands, buried it in the pillow and shook with sobs.\
\
Rakitin got up.\
\
\'93It\'92s time we were off,\'94 he said, \'93it\'92s late, we shall be shut out of the\
monastery.\'94\
\
Grushenka leapt up from her place.\
\
\'93Surely you don\'92t want to go, Alyosha!\'94 she cried, in mournful surprise.\
\'93What are you doing to me? You\'92ve stirred up my feeling, tortured me, and\
now you\'92ll leave me to face this night alone!\'94\
\
\'93He can hardly spend the night with you! Though if he wants to, let him!\
I\'92ll go alone,\'94 Rakitin scoffed jeeringly.\
\
\'93Hush, evil tongue!\'94 Grushenka cried angrily at him; \'93you never said such\
words to me as he has come to say.\'94\
\
\'93What has he said to you so special?\'94 asked Rakitin irritably.\
\
\'93I can\'92t say, I don\'92t know. I don\'92t know what he said to me, it went\
straight to my heart; he has wrung my heart.... He is the first, the only\
one who has pitied me, that\'92s what it is. Why did you not come before, you\
angel?\'94 She fell on her knees before him as though in a sudden frenzy.\
\'93I\'92ve been waiting all my life for some one like you, I knew that some one\
like you would come and forgive me. I believed that, nasty as I am, some\
one would really love me, not only with a shameful love!\'94\
\
\'93What have I done to you?\'94 answered Alyosha, bending over her with a\
tender smile, and gently taking her by the hands; \'93I only gave you an\
onion, nothing but a tiny little onion, that was all!\'94\
\
He was moved to tears himself as he said it. At that moment there was a\
sudden noise in the passage, some one came into the hall. Grushenka jumped\
up, seeming greatly alarmed. Fenya ran noisily into the room, crying out:\
\
\'93Mistress, mistress darling, a messenger has galloped up,\'94 she cried,\
breathless and joyful. \'93A carriage from Mokroe for you, Timofey the\
driver, with three horses, they are just putting in fresh horses.... A\
letter, here\'92s the letter, mistress.\'94\
\
A letter was in her hand and she waved it in the air all the while she\
talked. Grushenka snatched the letter from her and carried it to the\
candle. It was only a note, a few lines. She read it in one instant.\
\
\'93He has sent for me,\'94 she cried, her face white and distorted, with a wan\
smile; \'93he whistles! Crawl back, little dog!\'94\
\
But only for one instant she stood as though hesitating; suddenly the\
blood rushed to her head and sent a glow to her cheeks.\
\
\'93I will go,\'94 she cried; \'93five years of my life! Good\uc0\u8208 by! Good\u8208 by, Alyosha,\
my fate is sealed. Go, go, leave me all of you, don\'92t let me see you\
again! Grushenka is flying to a new life.... Don\'92t you remember evil\
against me either, Rakitin. I may be going to my death! Ugh! I feel as\
though I were drunk!\'94\
\
She suddenly left them and ran into her bedroom.\
\
\'93Well, she has no thoughts for us now!\'94 grumbled Rakitin. \'93Let\'92s go, or we\
may hear that feminine shriek again. I am sick of all these tears and\
cries.\'94\
\
Alyosha mechanically let himself be led out. In the yard stood a covered\
cart. Horses were being taken out of the shafts, men were running to and\
fro with a lantern. Three fresh horses were being led in at the open gate.\
But when Alyosha and Rakitin reached the bottom of the steps, Grushenka\'92s\
bedroom window was suddenly opened and she called in a ringing voice after\
Alyosha:\
\
\'93Alyosha, give my greetings to your brother Mitya and tell him not to\
remember evil against me, though I have brought him misery. And tell him,\
too, in my words: \'91Grushenka has fallen to a scoundrel, and not to you,\
noble heart.\'92 And add, too, that Grushenka loved him only one hour, only\
one short hour she loved him\'97so let him remember that hour all his\
life\'97say, \'91Grushenka tells you to!\'92 \'94\
\
She ended in a voice full of sobs. The window was shut with a slam.\
\
\'93H\'92m, h\'92m!\'94 growled Rakitin, laughing, \'93she murders your brother Mitya and\
then tells him to remember it all his life! What ferocity!\'94\
\
Alyosha made no reply, he seemed not to have heard. He walked fast beside\
Rakitin as though in a terrible hurry. He was lost in thought and moved\
mechanically. Rakitin felt a sudden twinge as though he had been touched\
on an open wound. He had expected something quite different by bringing\
Grushenka and Alyosha together. Something very different from what he had\
hoped for had happened.\
\
\'93He is a Pole, that officer of hers,\'94 he began again, restraining himself;\
\'93and indeed he is not an officer at all now. He served in the customs in\
Siberia, somewhere on the Chinese frontier, some puny little beggar of a\
Pole, I expect. Lost his job, they say. He\'92s heard now that Grushenka\'92s\
saved a little money, so he\'92s turned up again\'97that\'92s the explanation of\
the mystery.\'94\
\
Again Alyosha seemed not to hear. Rakitin could not control himself.\
\
\'93Well, so you\'92ve saved the sinner?\'94 he laughed spitefully. \'93Have you\
turned the Magdalene into the true path? Driven out the seven devils, eh?\
So you see the miracles you were looking out for just now have come to\
pass!\'94\
\
\'93Hush, Rakitin,\'94 Alyosha answered with an aching heart.\
\
\'93So you despise me now for those twenty\uc0\u8208 five roubles? I\'92ve sold my friend,\
you think. But you are not Christ, you know, and I am not Judas.\'94\
\
\'93Oh, Rakitin, I assure you I\'92d forgotten about it,\'94 cried Alyosha, \'93you\
remind me of it yourself....\'94\
\
But this was the last straw for Rakitin.\
\
\'93Damnation take you all and each of you!\'94 he cried suddenly, \'93why the\
devil did I take you up? I don\'92t want to know you from this time forward.\
Go alone, there\'92s your road!\'94\
\
And he turned abruptly into another street, leaving Alyosha alone in the\
dark. Alyosha came out of the town and walked across the fields to the\
monastery.\
\
\
\
Chapter IV. Cana Of Galilee\
\
\
It was very late, according to the monastery ideas, when Alyosha returned\
to the hermitage; the door\uc0\u8208 keeper let him in by a special entrance. It had\
struck nine o\'92clock\'97the hour of rest and repose after a day of such\
agitation for all. Alyosha timidly opened the door and went into the\
elder\'92s cell where his coffin was now standing. There was no one in the\
cell but Father Pa\'efssy, reading the Gospel in solitude over the coffin,\
and the young novice Porfiry, who, exhausted by the previous night\'92s\
conversation and the disturbing incidents of the day, was sleeping the\
deep sound sleep of youth on the floor of the other room. Though Father\
Pa\'efssy heard Alyosha come in, he did not even look in his direction.\
Alyosha turned to the right from the door to the corner, fell on his knees\
and began to pray.\
\
His soul was overflowing but with mingled feelings; no single sensation\
stood out distinctly; on the contrary, one drove out another in a slow,\
continual rotation. But there was a sweetness in his heart and, strange to\
say, Alyosha was not surprised at it. Again he saw that coffin before him,\
the hidden dead figure so precious to him, but the weeping and poignant\
grief of the morning was no longer aching in his soul. As soon as he came\
in, he fell down before the coffin as before a holy shrine, but joy, joy\
was glowing in his mind and in his heart. The one window of the cell was\
open, the air was fresh and cool. \'93So the smell must have become stronger,\
if they opened the window,\'94 thought Alyosha. But even this thought of the\
smell of corruption, which had seemed to him so awful and humiliating a\
few hours before, no longer made him feel miserable or indignant. He began\
quietly praying, but he soon felt that he was praying almost mechanically.\
Fragments of thought floated through his soul, flashed like stars and went\
out again at once, to be succeeded by others. But yet there was reigning\
in his soul a sense of the wholeness of things\'97something steadfast and\
comforting\'97and he was aware of it himself. Sometimes he began praying\
ardently, he longed to pour out his thankfulness and love....\
\
But when he had begun to pray, he passed suddenly to something else, and\
sank into thought, forgetting both the prayer and what had interrupted it.\
He began listening to what Father Pa\'efssy was reading, but worn out with\
exhaustion he gradually began to doze.\
\
\'93_And the third day there was a marriage in Cana of Galilee;_\'94 read Father\
Pa\'efssy. \'93_And the mother of Jesus was there; And both Jesus was called,\
and his disciples, to the marriage._\'94\
\
\'93Marriage? What\'92s that?... A marriage!\'94 floated whirling through Alyosha\'92s\
mind. \'93There is happiness for her, too.... She has gone to the feast....\
No, she has not taken the knife.... That was only a tragic phrase.... Well\
... tragic phrases should be forgiven, they must be. Tragic phrases\
comfort the heart.... Without them, sorrow would be too heavy for men to\
bear. Rakitin has gone off to the back alley. As long as Rakitin broods\
over his wrongs, he will always go off to the back alley.... But the high\
road ... The road is wide and straight and bright as crystal, and the sun\
is at the end of it.... Ah!... What\'92s being read?\'94...\
\
\'93_And when they wanted wine, the mother of Jesus saith unto him, They have\
no wine_\'94 ... Alyosha heard.\
\
\'93Ah, yes, I was missing that, and I didn\'92t want to miss it, I love that\
passage: it\'92s Cana of Galilee, the first miracle.... Ah, that miracle! Ah,\
that sweet miracle! It was not men\'92s grief, but their joy Christ visited,\
He worked His first miracle to help men\'92s gladness.... \'91He who loves men\
loves their gladness, too\'92 ... He was always repeating that, it was one of\
his leading ideas.... \'91There\'92s no living without joy,\'92 Mitya says.... Yes,\
Mitya.... \'91Everything that is true and good is always full of\
forgiveness,\'92 he used to say that, too\'94 ...\
\
\'93_Jesus saith unto her, Woman, what has it to do with thee or me? Mine\
hour is not yet come._\
\
\'93_His mother saith unto the servants, Whatsoever he saith unto you, do\
it_\'94 ...\
\
\'93Do it.... Gladness, the gladness of some poor, very poor, people.... Of\
course they were poor, since they hadn\'92t wine enough even at a wedding....\
The historians write that, in those days, the people living about the Lake\
of Gennesaret were the poorest that can possibly be imagined ... and\
another great heart, that other great being, His Mother, knew that He had\
come not only to make His great terrible sacrifice. She knew that His\
heart was open even to the simple, artless merrymaking of some obscure and\
unlearned people, who had warmly bidden Him to their poor wedding. \'91Mine\
hour is not yet come,\'92 He said, with a soft smile (He must have smiled\
gently to her). And, indeed, was it to make wine abundant at poor weddings\
He had come down to earth? And yet He went and did as she asked Him....\
Ah, he is reading again\'94....\
\
\'93_Jesus saith unto them, Fill the waterpots with water. And they filled\
them up to the brim._\
\
\'93_And he saith unto them, Draw out now and bear unto the governor of the\
feast. And they bare it._\
\
\'93_When the ruler of the feast had tasted the water that was made wine, and\
knew not whence it was; (but the servants which drew the water knew;) the\
governor of the feast called the bridegroom,_\
\
\'93_And saith unto him, Every man at the beginning doth set forth good wine;\
and when men have well drunk, that which is worse; but thou hast kept the\
good wine until now._\'94\
\
\'93But what\'92s this, what\'92s this? Why is the room growing wider?... Ah, yes\
... It\'92s the marriage, the wedding ... yes, of course. Here are the\
guests, here are the young couple sitting, and the merry crowd and ...\
Where is the wise governor of the feast? But who is this? Who? Again the\
walls are receding.... Who is getting up there from the great table?\
What!... He here, too? But he\'92s in the coffin ... but he\'92s here, too. He\
has stood up, he sees me, he is coming here.... God!\'94...\
\
Yes, he came up to him, to him, he, the little, thin old man, with tiny\
wrinkles on his face, joyful and laughing softly. There was no coffin now,\
and he was in the same dress as he had worn yesterday sitting with them,\
when the visitors had gathered about him. His face was uncovered, his eyes\
were shining. How was this, then? He, too, had been called to the feast.\
He, too, at the marriage of Cana in Galilee....\
\
\'93Yes, my dear, I am called, too, called and bidden,\'94 he heard a soft voice\
saying over him. \'93Why have you hidden yourself here, out of sight? You\
come and join us too.\'94\
\
It was his voice, the voice of Father Zossima. And it must be he, since he\
called him!\
\
The elder raised Alyosha by the hand and he rose from his knees.\
\
\'93We are rejoicing,\'94 the little, thin old man went on. \'93We are drinking the\
new wine, the wine of new, great gladness; do you see how many guests?\
Here are the bride and bridegroom, here is the wise governor of the feast,\
he is tasting the new wine. Why do you wonder at me? I gave an onion to a\
beggar, so I, too, am here. And many here have given only an onion\
each\'97only one little onion.... What are all our deeds? And you, my gentle\
one, you, my kind boy, you too have known how to give a famished woman an\
onion to\uc0\u8208 day. Begin your work, dear one, begin it, gentle one!... Do you\
see our Sun, do you see Him?\'94\
\
\'93I am afraid ... I dare not look,\'94 whispered Alyosha.\
\
\'93Do not fear Him. He is terrible in His greatness, awful in His sublimity,\
but infinitely merciful. He has made Himself like unto us from love and\
rejoices with us. He is changing the water into wine that the gladness of\
the guests may not be cut short. He is expecting new guests, He is calling\
new ones unceasingly for ever and ever.... There they are bringing new\
wine. Do you see they are bringing the vessels....\'94\
\
Something glowed in Alyosha\'92s heart, something filled it till it ached,\
tears of rapture rose from his soul.... He stretched out his hands,\
uttered a cry and waked up.\
\
Again the coffin, the open window, and the soft, solemn, distinct reading\
of the Gospel. But Alyosha did not listen to the reading. It was strange,\
he had fallen asleep on his knees, but now he was on his feet, and\
suddenly, as though thrown forward, with three firm rapid steps he went\
right up to the coffin. His shoulder brushed against Father Pa\'efssy without\
his noticing it. Father Pa\'efssy raised his eyes for an instant from his\
book, but looked away again at once, seeing that something strange was\
happening to the boy. Alyosha gazed for half a minute at the coffin, at\
the covered, motionless dead man that lay in the coffin, with the ikon on\
his breast and the peaked cap with the octangular cross, on his head. He\
had only just been hearing his voice, and that voice was still ringing in\
his ears. He was listening, still expecting other words, but suddenly he\
turned sharply and went out of the cell.\
\
He did not stop on the steps either, but went quickly down; his soul,\
overflowing with rapture, yearned for freedom, space, openness. The vault\
of heaven, full of soft, shining stars, stretched vast and fathomless\
above him. The Milky Way ran in two pale streams from the zenith to the\
horizon. The fresh, motionless, still night enfolded the earth. The white\
towers and golden domes of the cathedral gleamed out against the sapphire\
sky. The gorgeous autumn flowers, in the beds round the house, were\
slumbering till morning. The silence of earth seemed to melt into the\
silence of the heavens. The mystery of earth was one with the mystery of\
the stars....\
\
Alyosha stood, gazed, and suddenly threw himself down on the earth. He did\
not know why he embraced it. He could not have told why he longed so\
irresistibly to kiss it, to kiss it all. But he kissed it weeping, sobbing\
and watering it with his tears, and vowed passionately to love it, to love\
it for ever and ever. \'93Water the earth with the tears of your joy and love\
those tears,\'94 echoed in his soul.\
\
What was he weeping over?\
\
Oh! in his rapture he was weeping even over those stars, which were\
shining to him from the abyss of space, and \'93he was not ashamed of that\
ecstasy.\'94 There seemed to be threads from all those innumerable worlds of\
God, linking his soul to them, and it was trembling all over \'93in contact\
with other worlds.\'94 He longed to forgive every one and for everything, and\
to beg forgiveness. Oh, not for himself, but for all men, for all and for\
everything. \'93And others are praying for me too,\'94 echoed again in his soul.\
But with every instant he felt clearly and, as it were, tangibly, that\
something firm and unshakable as that vault of heaven had entered into his\
soul. It was as though some idea had seized the sovereignty of his\
mind\'97and it was for all his life and for ever and ever. He had fallen on\
the earth a weak boy, but he rose up a resolute champion, and he knew and\
felt it suddenly at the very moment of his ecstasy. And never, never, all\
his life long, could Alyosha forget that minute.\
\
\'93Some one visited my soul in that hour,\'94 he used to say afterwards, with\
implicit faith in his words.\
\
Within three days he left the monastery in accordance with the words of\
his elder, who had bidden him \'93sojourn in the world.\'94\
