house. He walked on, and not knowing what he was doing, wiped away his\
tears with his fist. In this way he reached the square, and suddenly\
became aware that he had stumbled against something. He heard a piercing\
wail from an old woman whom he had almost knocked down.\
\
\'93Good Lord, you\'92ve nearly killed me! Why don\'92t you look where you\'92re\
going, scapegrace?\'94\
\
\'93Why, it\'92s you!\'94 cried Mitya, recognizing the old woman in the dark. It\
was the old servant who waited on Samsonov, whom Mitya had particularly\
noticed the day before.\
\
\'93And who are you, my good sir?\'94 said the old woman, in quite a different\
voice. \'93I don\'92t know you in the dark.\'94\
\
\'93You live at Kuzma Kuzmitch\'92s. You\'92re the servant there?\'94\
\
\'93Just so, sir, I was only running out to Prohoritch\'92s.... But I don\'92t know\
you now.\'94\
\
\'93Tell me, my good woman, is Agrafena Alexandrovna there now?\'94 said Mitya,\
