stepping aside, I\'92m punishing myself?\'92 It\'92ll come to nothing! He\'92s shouted\
such phrases a thousand times, drunk, in the taverns. But now he\'92s not\
drunk. \'91Drunk in spirit\'92\'97they\'92re fond of fine phrases, the villains. Am I\
his nurse? He must have been fighting, his face was all over blood. With\
whom? I shall find out at the \'91Metropolis.\'92 And his handkerchief was\
soaked in blood.... It\'92s still lying on my floor.... Hang it!\'94\
\
He reached the tavern in a bad humor and at once made up a game. The game\
cheered him. He played a second game, and suddenly began telling one of\
his partners that Dmitri Karamazov had come in for some cash\
again\'97something like three thousand roubles, and had gone to Mokroe again\
to spend it with Grushenka.... This news roused singular interest in his\
