They left off playing.\
\
\'93Three thousand? But where can he have got three thousand?\'94\
\
Questions were asked. The story of Madame Hohlakov\'92s present was received\
with skepticism.\
\
\'93Hasn\'92t he robbed his old father?\'97that\'92s the question.\'94\
\
\'93Three thousand! There\'92s something odd about it.\'94\
\
\'93He boasted aloud that he would kill his father; we all heard him, here.\
And it was three thousand he talked about ...\'94\
\
Pyotr Ilyitch listened. All at once he became short and dry in his\
answers. He said not a word about the blood on Mitya\'92s face and hands,\
though he had meant to speak of it at first.\
\
They began a third game, and by degrees the talk about Mitya died away.\
But by the end of the third game, Pyotr Ilyitch felt no more desire for\
billiards; he laid down the cue, and without having supper as he had\
intended, he walked out of the tavern. When he reached the market\uc0\u8208 place he\
stood still in perplexity, wondering at himself. He realized that what he\
wanted was to go to Fyodor Pavlovitch\'92s and find out if anything had\
happened there. \'93On account of some stupid nonsense\'97as it\'92s sure to turn\
out\'97am I going to wake up the household and make a scandal? Fooh! damn it,\
is it my business to look after them?\'94\
\
In a very bad humor he went straight home, and suddenly remembered Fenya.\
\'93Damn it all! I ought to have questioned her just now,\'94 he thought with\
vexation, \'93I should have heard everything.\'94 And the desire to speak to\
her, and so find out, became so pressing and importunate that when he was\
half\uc0\u8208 way home he turned abruptly and went towards the house where\
Grushenka lodged. Going up to the gate he knocked. The sound of the knock\
in the silence of the night sobered him and made him feel annoyed. And no\
one answered him; every one in the house was asleep.\
\
\'93And I shall be making a fuss!\'94 he thought, with a feeling of positive\
discomfort. But instead of going away altogether, he fell to knocking\
again with all his might, filling the street with clamor.\
\
\'93Not coming? Well, I will knock them up, I will!\'94 he muttered at each\
knock, fuming at himself, but at the same time he redoubled his knocks on\
the gate.\
\
\
\
Chapter VI. \'93I Am Coming, Too!\'94\
\
\
But Dmitri Fyodorovitch was speeding along the road. It was a little more\
than twenty versts to Mokroe, but Andrey\'92s three horses galloped at such a\
pace that the distance might be covered in an hour and a quarter. The\
swift motion revived Mitya. The air was fresh and cool, there were big\
stars shining in the sky. It was the very night, and perhaps the very\
hour, in which Alyosha fell on the earth, and rapturously swore to love it\
for ever and ever.\
\
All was confusion, confusion, in Mitya\'92s soul, but although many things\
were goading his heart, at that moment his whole being was yearning for\
her, his queen, to whom he was flying to look on her for the last time.\
One thing I can say for certain; his heart did not waver for one instant.\
I shall perhaps not be believed when I say that this jealous lover felt\
not the slightest jealousy of this new rival, who seemed to have sprung\
out of the earth. If any other had appeared on the scene, he would have\
been jealous at once, and would perhaps have stained his fierce hands with\
blood again. But as he flew through the night, he felt no envy, no\
hostility even, for the man who had been her first lover.... It is true he\
had not yet seen him.\
\
\'93Here there was no room for dispute: it was her right and his; this was\
her first love which, after five years, she had not forgotten; so she had\
loved him only for those five years, and I, how do I come in? What right\
have I? Step aside, Mitya, and make way! What am I now? Now everything is\
over apart from the officer\'97even if he had not appeared, everything would\
be over ...\'94\
\
These words would roughly have expressed his feelings, if he had been\
capable of reasoning. But he could not reason at that moment. His present\
plan of action had arisen without reasoning. At Fenya\'92s first words, it\
had sprung from feeling, and been adopted in a flash, with all its\
consequences. And yet, in spite of his resolution, there was confusion in\
his soul, an agonizing confusion: his resolution did not give him peace.\
There was so much behind that tortured him. And it seemed strange to him,\
at moments, to think that he had written his own sentence of death with\
pen and paper: \'93I punish myself,\'94 and the paper was lying there in his\
pocket, ready; the pistol was loaded; he had already resolved how, next\
morning, he would meet the first warm ray of \'93golden\uc0\u8208 haired Ph\'9cbus.\'94\
\
And yet he could not be quit of the past, of all that he had left behind\
and that tortured him. He felt that miserably, and the thought of it sank\
into his heart with despair. There was one moment when he felt an impulse\
to stop Andrey, to jump out of the cart, to pull out his loaded pistol,\
and to make an end of everything without waiting for the dawn. But that\
moment flew by like a spark. The horses galloped on, \'93devouring space,\'94\
and as he drew near his goal, again the thought of her, of her alone, took\
more and more complete possession of his soul, chasing away the fearful\
images that had been haunting it. Oh, how he longed to look upon her, if\
only for a moment, if only from a distance!\
\
\'93She\'92s now with _him_,\'94 he thought, \'93now I shall see what she looks like\
with him, her first love, and that\'92s all I want.\'94 Never had this woman,\
who was such a fateful influence in his life, aroused such love in his\
breast, such new and unknown feeling, surprising even to himself, a\
feeling tender to devoutness, to self\uc0\u8208 effacement before her! \'93I will\
efface myself!\'94 he said, in a rush of almost hysterical ecstasy.\
\
They had been galloping nearly an hour. Mitya was silent, and though\
Andrey was, as a rule, a talkative peasant, he did not utter a word,\
either. He seemed afraid to talk, he only whipped up smartly his three\
lean, but mettlesome, bay horses. Suddenly Mitya cried out in horrible\
anxiety:\
\
\'93Andrey! What if they\'92re asleep?\'94\
\
This thought fell upon him like a blow. It had not occurred to him before.\
\
\'93It may well be that they\'92re gone to bed, by now, Dmitri Fyodorovitch.\'94\
\
Mitya frowned as though in pain. Yes, indeed ... he was rushing there ...\
with such feelings ... while they were asleep ... she was asleep, perhaps,\
there too.... An angry feeling surged up in his heart.\
\
\'93Drive on, Andrey! Whip them up! Look alive!\'94 he cried, beside himself.\
\
\'93But maybe they\'92re not in bed!\'94 Andrey went on after a pause. \'93Timofey\
said they were a lot of them there\'97\'94\
\
\'93At the station?\'94\
\
\'93Not at the posting\uc0\u8208 station, but at Plastunov\'92s, at the inn, where they\
let out horses, too.\'94\
\
\'93I know. So you say there are a lot of them? How\'92s that? Who are they?\'94\
cried Mitya, greatly dismayed at this unexpected news.\
\
\'93Well, Timofey was saying they\'92re all gentlefolk. Two from our town\'97who\
they are I can\'92t say\'97and there are two others, strangers, maybe more\
besides. I didn\'92t ask particularly. They\'92ve set to playing cards, so\
Timofey said.\'94\
\
\'93Cards?\'94\
\
\'93So, maybe they\'92re not in bed if they\'92re at cards. It\'92s most likely not\
more than eleven.\'94\
\
\'93Quicker, Andrey! Quicker!\'94 Mitya cried again, nervously.\
\
\'93May I ask you something, sir?\'94 said Andrey, after a pause. \'93Only I\'92m\
afraid of angering you, sir.\'94\
\
\'93What is it?\'94\
\
\'93Why, Fenya threw herself at your feet just now, and begged you not to\
harm her mistress, and some one else, too ... so you see, sir\'97 It\'92s I am\
taking you there ... forgive me, sir, it\'92s my conscience ... maybe it\'92s\
stupid of me to speak of it\'97\'94\
\
Mitya suddenly seized him by the shoulders from behind.\
\
\'93Are you a driver?\'94 he asked frantically.\
\
\'93Yes, sir.\'94\
\
\'93Then you know that one has to make way. What would you say to a driver\
who wouldn\'92t make way for any one, but would just drive on and crush\
people? No, a driver mustn\'92t run over people. One can\'92t run over a man.\
One can\'92t spoil people\'92s lives. And if you have spoilt a life\'97punish\
yourself.... If only you\'92ve spoilt, if only you\'92ve ruined any one\'92s\
life\'97punish yourself and go away.\'94\
\
These phrases burst from Mitya almost hysterically. Though Andrey was\
surprised at him, he kept up the conversation.\
\
\'93That\'92s right, Dmitri Fyodorovitch, you\'92re quite right, one mustn\'92t crush\
or torment a man, or any kind of creature, for every creature is created\
by God. Take a horse, for instance, for some folks, even among us drivers,\
drive anyhow. Nothing will restrain them, they just force it along.\'94\
\
\'93To hell?\'94 Mitya interrupted, and went off into his abrupt, short laugh.\
\'93Andrey, simple soul,\'94 he seized him by the shoulders again, \'93tell me,\
will Dmitri Fyodorovitch Karamazov go to hell, or not, what do you think?\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t know, darling, it depends on you, for you are ... you see, sir,\
when the Son of God was nailed on the Cross and died, He went straight\
down to hell from the Cross, and set free all sinners that were in agony.\
And the devil groaned, because he thought that he would get no more\
sinners in hell. And God said to him, then, \'91Don\'92t groan, for you shall\
have all the mighty of the earth, the rulers, the chief judges, and the\
rich men, and shall be filled up as you have been in all the ages till I\
come again.\'92 Those were His very words ...\'94\
\
\'93A peasant legend! Capital! Whip up the left, Andrey!\'94\
\
\'93So you see, sir, who it is hell\'92s for,\'94 said Andrey, whipping up the left\
horse, \'93but you\'92re like a little child ... that\'92s how we look on you ...\
and though you\'92re hasty\uc0\u8208 tempered, sir, yet God will forgive you for your\
kind heart.\'94\
\
\'93And you, do you forgive me, Andrey?\'94\
\
\'93What should I forgive you for, sir? You\'92ve never done me any harm.\'94\
\
\'93No, for every one, for every one, you here alone, on the road, will you\
forgive me for every one? Speak, simple peasant heart!\'94\
\
\'93Oh, sir! I feel afraid of driving you, your talk is so strange.\'94\
\
But Mitya did not hear. He was frantically praying and muttering to\
himself.\
\
\'93Lord, receive me, with all my lawlessness, and do not condemn me. Let me\
pass by Thy judgment ... do not condemn me, for I have condemned myself,\
do not condemn me, for I love Thee, O Lord. I am a wretch, but I love\
Thee. If Thou sendest me to hell, I shall love Thee there, and from there\
I shall cry out that I love Thee for ever and ever.... But let me love to\
the end.... Here and now for just five hours ... till the first light of\
Thy day ... for I love the queen of my soul ... I love her and I cannot\
help loving her. Thou seest my whole heart.... I shall gallop up, I shall\
fall before her and say, \'91You are right to pass on and leave me. Farewell\
and forget your victim ... never fret yourself about me!\'92 \'94\
\
\'93Mokroe!\'94 cried Andrey, pointing ahead with his whip.\
\
Through the pale darkness of the night loomed a solid black mass of\
buildings, flung down, as it were, in the vast plain. The village of\
Mokroe numbered two thousand inhabitants, but at that hour all were\
asleep, and only here and there a few lights still twinkled.\
\
\'93Drive on, Andrey, I come!\'94 Mitya exclaimed, feverishly.\
\
\'93They\'92re not asleep,\'94 said Andrey again, pointing with his whip to the\
Plastunovs\'92 inn, which was at the entrance to the village. The six\
windows, looking on the street, were all brightly lighted up.\
\
\'93They\'92re not asleep,\'94 Mitya repeated joyously. \'93Quicker, Andrey! Gallop!\
Drive up with a dash! Set the bells ringing! Let all know that I have\
come. I\'92m coming! I\'92m coming, too!\'94\
\
Andrey lashed his exhausted team into a gallop, drove with a dash and\
pulled up his steaming, panting horses at the high flight of steps.\
\
Mitya jumped out of the cart just as the innkeeper, on his way to bed,\
peeped out from the steps curious to see who had arrived.\
\
\'93Trifon Borissovitch, is that you?\'94\
\
The innkeeper bent down, looked intently, ran down the steps, and rushed\
up to the guest with obsequious delight.\
\
\'93Dmitri Fyodorovitch, your honor! Do I see you again?\'94\
\
Trifon Borissovitch was a thick\uc0\u8208 set, healthy peasant, of middle height,\
with a rather fat face. His expression was severe and uncompromising,\
especially with the peasants of Mokroe, but he had the power of assuming\
the most obsequious countenance, when he had an inkling that it was to his\
interest. He dressed in Russian style, with a shirt buttoning down on one\
side, and a full\uc0\u8208 skirted coat. He had saved a good sum of money, but was\
for ever dreaming of improving his position. More than half the peasants\
were in his clutches, every one in the neighborhood was in debt to him.\
From the neighboring landowners he bought and rented lands which were\
worked by the peasants, in payment of debts which they could never shake\
off. He was a widower, with four grown\uc0\u8208 up daughters. One of them was\
already a widow and lived in the inn with her two children, his\
grandchildren, and worked for him like a charwoman. Another of his\
daughters was married to a petty official, and in one of the rooms of the\
inn, on the wall could be seen, among the family photographs, a miniature\
photograph of this official in uniform and official epaulettes. The two\
younger daughters used to wear fashionable blue or green dresses, fitting\
tight at the back, and with trains a yard long, on Church holidays or when\
they went to pay visits. But next morning they would get up at dawn, as\
usual, sweep out the rooms with a birch\uc0\u8208 broom, empty the slops, and clean\
up after lodgers.\
\
In spite of the thousands of roubles he had saved, Trifon Borissovitch was\
very fond of emptying the pockets of a drunken guest, and remembering that\
not a month ago he had, in twenty\uc0\u8208 four hours, made two if not three\
hundred roubles out of Dmitri, when he had come on his escapade with\
Grushenka, he met him now with eager welcome, scenting his prey the moment\
Mitya drove up to the steps.\
\
\'93Dmitri Fyodorovitch, dear sir, we see you once more!\'94\
\
\'93Stay, Trifon Borissovitch,\'94 began Mitya, \'93first and foremost, where is\
she?\'94\
\
\'93Agrafena Alexandrovna?\'94 The inn\uc0\u8208 keeper understood at once, looking\
sharply into Mitya\'92s face. \'93She\'92s here, too ...\'94\
\
\'93With whom? With whom?\'94\
\
\'93Some strangers. One is an official gentleman, a Pole, to judge from his\
speech. He sent the horses for her from here; and there\'92s another with\
him, a friend of his, or a fellow traveler, there\'92s no telling. They\'92re\
dressed like civilians.\'94\
\
\'93Well, are they feasting? Have they money?\'94\
\
\'93Poor sort of a feast! Nothing to boast of, Dmitri Fyodorovitch.\'94\
\
\'93Nothing to boast of? And who are the others?\'94\
\
\'93They\'92re two gentlemen from the town.... They\'92ve come back from Tcherny,\
and are putting up here. One\'92s quite a young gentleman, a relative of Mr.\
Mi\'fcsov, he must be, but I\'92ve forgotten his name ... and I expect you know\
the other, too, a gentleman called Maximov. He\'92s been on a pilgrimage, so\
he says, to the monastery in the town. He\'92s traveling with this young\
relation of Mr. Mi\'fcsov.\'94\
\
\'93Is that all?\'94\
\
\'93Yes.\'94\
\
\'93Stay, listen, Trifon Borissovitch. Tell me the chief thing: What of her?\
How is she?\'94\
\
\'93Oh, she\'92s only just come. She\'92s sitting with them.\'94\
\
\'93Is she cheerful? Is she laughing?\'94\
\
\'93No, I think she\'92s not laughing much. She\'92s sitting quite dull. She\'92s\
combing the young gentleman\'92s hair.\'94\
\
\'93The Pole\'97the officer?\'94\
\
\'93He\'92s not young, and he\'92s not an officer, either. Not him, sir. It\'92s the\
young gentleman that\'92s Mr. Mi\'fcsov\'92s relation ... I\'92ve forgotten his name.\'94\
\
\'93Kalganov.\'94\
\
\'93That\'92s it, Kalganov!\'94\
\
\'93All right. I\'92ll see for myself. Are they playing cards?\'94\
\
\'93They have been playing, but they\'92ve left off. They\'92ve been drinking tea,\
the official gentleman asked for liqueurs.\'94\
\
\'93Stay, Trifon Borissovitch, stay, my good soul, I\'92ll see for myself. Now\
answer one more question: are the gypsies here?\'94\
\
\'93You can\'92t have the gypsies now, Dmitri Fyodorovitch. The authorities have\
sent them away. But we\'92ve Jews that play the cymbals and the fiddle in the\
village, so one might send for them. They\'92d come.\'94\
\
\'93Send for them. Certainly send for them!\'94 cried Mitya. \'93And you can get\
the girls together as you did then, Marya especially, Stepanida, too, and\
Arina. Two hundred roubles for a chorus!\'94\
\
\'93Oh, for a sum like that I can get all the village together, though by now\
they\'92re asleep. Are the peasants here worth such kindness, Dmitri\
Fyodorovitch, or the girls either? To spend a sum like that on such\
coarseness and rudeness! What\'92s the good of giving a peasant a cigar to\
smoke, the stinking ruffian! And the girls are all lousy. Besides, I\'92ll\
get my daughters up for nothing, let alone a sum like that. They\'92ve only\
just gone to bed, I\'92ll give them a kick and set them singing for you. You\
gave the peasants champagne to drink the other day, e\'97ech!\'94\
\
For all his pretended compassion for Mitya, Trifon Borissovitch had hidden\
half a dozen bottles of champagne on that last occasion, and had picked up\
a hundred\uc0\u8208 rouble note under the table, and it had remained in his\
clutches.\
\
\'93Trifon Borissovitch, I sent more than one thousand flying last time I was\
here. Do you remember?\'94\
\
\'93You did send it flying. I may well remember. You must have left three\
thousand behind you.\'94\
\
\'93Well, I\'92ve come to do the same again, do you see?\'94\
\
And he pulled out his roll of notes, and held them up before the\
innkeeper\'92s nose.\
\
\'93Now, listen and remember. In an hour\'92s time the wine will arrive,\
savories, pies, and sweets\'97bring them all up at once. That box Andrey has\
got is to be brought up at once, too. Open it, and hand champagne\
immediately. And the girls, we must have the girls, Marya especially.\'94\
\
He turned to the cart and pulled out the box of pistols.\
\
\'93Here, Andrey, let\'92s settle. Here\'92s fifteen roubles for the drive, and\
fifty for vodka ... for your readiness, for your love.... Remember\
Karamazov!\'94\
\
\'93I\'92m afraid, sir,\'94 faltered Andrey. \'93Give me five roubles extra, but more\
I won\'92t take. Trifon Borissovitch, bear witness. Forgive my foolish words\
...\'94\
\
\'93What are you afraid of?\'94 asked Mitya, scanning him. \'93Well, go to the\
devil, if that\'92s it!\'94 he cried, flinging him five roubles. \'93Now, Trifon\
Borissovitch, take me up quietly and let me first get a look at them, so\
that they don\'92t see me. Where are they? In the blue room?\'94\
\
Trifon Borissovitch looked apprehensively at Mitya, but at once obediently\
did his bidding. Leading him into the passage, he went himself into the\
first large room, adjoining that in which the visitors were sitting, and\
took the light away. Then he stealthily led Mitya in, and put him in a\
corner in the dark, whence he could freely watch the company without being\
seen. But Mitya did not look long, and, indeed, he could not see them, he\
saw her, his heart throbbed violently, and all was dark before his eyes.\
\
She was sitting sideways to the table in a low chair, and beside her, on\
the sofa, was the pretty youth, Kalganov. She was holding his hand and\
seemed to be laughing, while he, seeming vexed and not looking at her, was\
saying something in a loud voice to Maximov, who sat the other side of the\
table, facing Grushenka. Maximov was laughing violently at something. On\
the sofa sat _he_, and on a chair by the sofa there was another stranger.\
The one on the sofa was lolling backwards, smoking a pipe, and Mitya had\
an impression of a stoutish, broad\uc0\u8208 faced, short little man, who was\
apparently angry about something. His friend, the other stranger, struck\
Mitya as extraordinarily tall, but he could make out nothing more. He\
caught his breath. He could not bear it for a minute, he put the pistol\uc0\u8208 \
case on a chest, and with a throbbing heart he walked, feeling cold all\
over, straight into the blue room to face the company.\
\
\'93Aie!\'94 shrieked Grushenka, the first to notice him.\
\
\
\
Chapter VII. The First And Rightful Lover\
\
\
With his long, rapid strides, Mitya walked straight up to the table.\
\
\'93Gentlemen,\'94 he said in a loud voice, almost shouting, yet stammering at\
every word, \'93I ... I\'92m all right! Don\'92t be afraid!\'94 he exclaimed,\
\'93I\'97there\'92s nothing the matter,\'94 he turned suddenly to Grushenka, who had\
shrunk back in her chair towards Kalganov, and clasped his hand tightly.\
\'93I ... I\'92m coming, too. I\'92m here till morning. Gentlemen, may I stay with\
you till morning? Only till morning, for the last time, in this same\
room?\'94\
\
So he finished, turning to the fat little man, with the pipe, sitting on\
the sofa. The latter removed his pipe from his lips with dignity and\
observed severely:\
\
\'93_Panie_, we\'92re here in private. There are other rooms.\'94\
\
\'93Why, it\'92s you, Dmitri Fyodorovitch! What do you mean?\'94 answered Kalganov\
suddenly. \'93Sit down with us. How are you?\'94\
\
\'93Delighted to see you, dear ... and precious fellow, I always thought a\
lot of you.\'94 Mitya responded, joyfully and eagerly, at once holding out\
his hand across the table.\
\
\'93Aie! How tight you squeeze! You\'92ve quite broken my fingers,\'94 laughed\
Kalganov.\
\
\'93He always squeezes like that, always,\'94 Grushenka put in gayly, with a\
timid smile, seeming suddenly convinced from Mitya\'92s face that he was not\
going to make a scene. She was watching him with intense curiosity and\
still some uneasiness. She was impressed by something about him, and\
indeed the last thing she expected of him was that he would come in and\
speak like this at such a moment.\
\
\'93Good evening,\'94 Maximov ventured blandly on the left. Mitya rushed up to\
him, too.\
\
\'93Good evening. You\'92re here, too! How glad I am to find you here, too!\
Gentlemen, gentlemen, I\'97\'94 (He addressed the Polish gentleman with the pipe\
again, evidently taking him for the most important person present.) \'93I\
flew here.... I wanted to spend my last day, my last hour in this room, in\
this very room ... where I, too, adored ... my queen.... Forgive me,\
_panie_,\'94 he cried wildly, \'93I flew here and vowed\'97 Oh, don\'92t be afraid,\
it\'92s my last night! Let\'92s drink to our good understanding. They\'92ll bring\
the wine at once.... I brought this with me.\'94 (Something made him pull out\
his bundle of notes.) \'93Allow me, _panie_! I want to have music, singing, a\
revel, as we had before. But the worm, the unnecessary worm, will crawl\
away, and there\'92ll be no more of him. I will commemorate my day of joy on\
my last night.\'94\
\
He was almost choking. There was so much, so much he wanted to say, but\
strange exclamations were all that came from his lips. The Pole gazed\
fixedly at him, at the bundle of notes in his hand; looked at Grushenka,\
and was in evident perplexity.\
\
\'93If my suverin lady is permitting\'97\'94 he was beginning.\
\
\'93What does \'91suverin\'92 mean? \'91Sovereign,\'92 I suppose?\'94 interrupted Grushenka.\
\'93I can\'92t help laughing at you, the way you talk. Sit down, Mitya, what are\
you talking about? Don\'92t frighten us, please. You won\'92t frighten us, will\
you? If you won\'92t, I am glad to see you ...\'94\
\
\'93Me, me frighten you?\'94 cried Mitya, flinging up his hands. \'93Oh, pass me\
by, go your way, I won\'92t hinder you!...\'94\
\
And suddenly he surprised them all, and no doubt himself as well, by\
flinging himself on a chair, and bursting into tears, turning his head\
away to the opposite wall, while his arms clasped the back of the chair\
tight, as though embracing it.\
\
\'93Come, come, what a fellow you are!\'94 cried Grushenka reproachfully.\
\'93That\'92s just how he comes to see me\'97he begins talking, and I can\'92t make\
out what he means. He cried like that once before, and now he\'92s crying\
again! It\'92s shameful! Why are you crying? _As though you had anything to\
cry for!_\'94 she added enigmatically, emphasizing each word with some\
irritability.\
\
\'93I ... I\'92m not crying.... Well, good evening!\'94 He instantly turned round\
in his chair, and suddenly laughed, not his abrupt wooden laugh, but a\
long, quivering, inaudible nervous laugh.\
\
\'93Well, there you are again.... Come, cheer up, cheer up!\'94 Grushenka said\
to him persuasively. \'93I\'92m very glad you\'92ve come, very glad, Mitya, do you\
hear, I\'92m very glad! I want him to stay here with us,\'94 she said\
peremptorily, addressing the whole company, though her words were\
obviously meant for the man sitting on the sofa. \'93I wish it, I wish it!\
And if he goes away I shall go, too!\'94 she added with flashing eyes.\
\
\'93What my queen commands is law!\'94 pronounced the Pole, gallantly kissing\
Grushenka\'92s hand. \'93I beg you, _panie_, to join our company,\'94 he added\
politely, addressing Mitya.\
\
Mitya was jumping up with the obvious intention of delivering another\
tirade, but the words did not come.\
\
\'93Let\'92s drink, _panie_,\'94 he blurted out instead of making a speech. Every\
one laughed.\
\
\'93Good heavens! I thought he was going to begin again!\'94 Grushenka exclaimed\
nervously. \'93Do you hear, Mitya,\'94 she went on insistently, \'93don\'92t prance\
about, but it\'92s nice you\'92ve brought the champagne. I want some myself, and\
I can\'92t bear liqueurs. And best of all, you\'92ve come yourself. We were\
fearfully dull here.... You\'92ve come for a spree again, I suppose? But put\
your money in your pocket. Where did you get such a lot?\'94\
\
Mitya had been, all this time, holding in his hand the crumpled bundle of\
notes on which the eyes of all, especially of the Poles, were fixed. In\
confusion he thrust them hurriedly into his pocket. He flushed. At that\
moment the innkeeper brought in an uncorked bottle of champagne, and\
glasses on a tray. Mitya snatched up the bottle, but he was so bewildered\
that he did not know what to do with it. Kalganov took it from him and\
poured out the champagne.\
\
\'93Another! Another bottle!\'94 Mitya cried to the innkeeper, and, forgetting\
to clink glasses with the Pole whom he had so solemnly invited to drink to\
their good understanding, he drank off his glass without waiting for any\
one else. His whole countenance suddenly changed. The solemn and tragic\
expression with which he had entered vanished completely, and a look of\
something childlike came into his face. He seemed to have become suddenly\
gentle and subdued. He looked shyly and happily at every one, with a\
continual nervous little laugh, and the blissful expression of a dog who\
has done wrong, been punished, and forgiven. He seemed to have forgotten\
everything, and was looking round at every one with a childlike smile of\
delight. He looked at Grushenka, laughing continually, and bringing his\
chair close up to her. By degrees he had gained some idea of the two\
Poles, though he had formed no definite conception of them yet.\
\
The Pole on the sofa struck him by his dignified demeanor and his Polish\
accent; and, above all, by his pipe. \'93Well, what of it? It\'92s a good thing\
he\'92s smoking a pipe,\'94 he reflected. The Pole\'92s puffy, middle\uc0\u8208 aged face,\
with its tiny nose and two very thin, pointed, dyed and impudent\uc0\u8208 looking\
mustaches, had not so far roused the faintest doubts in Mitya. He was not\
even particularly struck by the Pole\'92s absurd wig made in Siberia, with\
love\uc0\u8208 locks foolishly combed forward over the temples. \'93I suppose it\'92s all\
right since he wears a wig,\'94 he went on, musing blissfully. The other,\
younger Pole, who was staring insolently and defiantly at the company and\
listening to the conversation with silent contempt, still only impressed\
Mitya by his great height, which was in striking contrast to the Pole on\
the sofa. \'93If he stood up he\'92d be six foot three.\'94 The thought flitted\
through Mitya\'92s mind. It occurred to him, too, that this Pole must be the\
friend of the other, as it were, a \'93bodyguard,\'94 and no doubt the big Pole\
was at the disposal of the little Pole with the pipe. But this all seemed\
to Mitya perfectly right and not to be questioned. In his mood of doglike\
submissiveness all feeling of rivalry had died away.\
\
Grushenka\'92s mood and the enigmatic tone of some of her words he completely\
failed to grasp. All he understood, with thrilling heart, was that she was\
kind to him, that she had forgiven him, and made him sit by her. He was\
beside himself with delight, watching her sip her glass of champagne. The\
silence of the company seemed somehow to strike him, however, and he\
looked round at every one with expectant eyes.\
\
\'93Why are we sitting here though, gentlemen? Why don\'92t you begin doing\
something?\'94 his smiling eyes seemed to ask.\
\
\'93He keeps talking nonsense, and we were all laughing,\'94 Kalganov began\
suddenly, as though divining his thought, and pointing to Maximov.\
\
Mitya immediately stared at Kalganov and then at Maximov.\
\
\'93He\'92s talking nonsense?\'94 he laughed, his short, wooden laugh, seeming\
suddenly delighted at something\'97\'93ha ha!\'94\
\
\'93Yes. Would you believe it, he will have it that all our cavalry officers\
in the twenties married Polish women. That\'92s awful rot, isn\'92t it?\'94\
\
\'93Polish women?\'94 repeated Mitya, perfectly ecstatic.\
\
Kalganov was well aware of Mitya\'92s attitude to Grushenka, and he guessed\
about the Pole, too, but that did not so much interest him, perhaps did\
not interest him at all; what he was interested in was Maximov. He had\
come here with Maximov by chance, and he met the Poles here at the inn for\
the first time in his life. Grushenka he knew before, and had once been\
with some one to see her; but she had not taken to him. But here she\
looked at him very affectionately: before Mitya\'92s arrival, she had been\
making much of him, but he seemed somehow to be unmoved by it. He was a\
boy, not over twenty, dressed like a dandy, with a very charming fair\uc0\u8208 \
skinned face, and splendid thick, fair hair. From his fair face looked out\
beautiful pale blue eyes, with an intelligent and sometimes even deep\
expression, beyond his age indeed, although the young man sometimes looked\
and talked quite like a child, and was not at all ashamed of it, even when\
he was aware of it himself. As a rule he was very willful, even\
capricious, though always friendly. Sometimes there was something fixed\
and obstinate in his expression. He would look at you and listen, seeming\
all the while to be persistently dreaming over something else. Often he\
was listless and lazy, at other times he would grow excited, sometimes,\
apparently, over the most trivial matters.\
\
\'93Only imagine, I\'92ve been taking him about with me for the last four days,\'94\
he went on, indolently drawling his words, quite naturally though, without\
the slightest affectation. \'93Ever since your brother, do you remember,\
shoved him off the carriage and sent him flying. That made me take an\
interest in him at the time, and I took him into the country, but he keeps\
talking such rot I\'92m ashamed to be with him. I\'92m taking him back.\'94\
\
\'93The gentleman has not seen Polish ladies, and says what is impossible,\'94\
the Pole with the pipe observed to Maximov.\
\
He spoke Russian fairly well, much better, anyway, than he pretended. If\
he used Russian words, he always distorted them into a Polish form.\
\
\'93But I was married to a Polish lady myself,\'94 tittered Maximov.\
\
\'93But did you serve in the cavalry? You were talking about the cavalry.\
Were you a cavalry officer?\'94 put in Kalganov at once.\
\
\'93Was he a cavalry officer indeed? Ha ha!\'94 cried Mitya, listening eagerly,\
and turning his inquiring eyes to each as he spoke, as though there were\
no knowing what he might hear from each.\
\
\'93No, you see,\'94 Maximov turned to him. \'93What I mean is that those pretty\
Polish ladies ... when they danced the mazurka with our Uhlans ... when\
one of them dances a mazurka with a Uhlan she jumps on his knee like a\
kitten ... a little white one ... and the _pan_\uc0\u8208 father and _pan_\u8208 mother\
look on and allow it.... They allow it ... and next day the Uhlan comes\
and offers her his hand.... That\'92s how it is ... offers her his hand, he\
he!\'94 Maximov ended, tittering.\
\
\'93The _pan_ is a _lajdak_!\'94 the tall Pole on the chair growled suddenly and\
crossed one leg over the other. Mitya\'92s eye was caught by his huge greased\
boot, with its thick, dirty sole. The dress of both the Poles looked\
rather greasy.\
\
\'93Well, now it\'92s _lajdak_! What\'92s he scolding about?\'94 said Grushenka,\
suddenly vexed.\
\
\'93_Pani_ Agrippina, what the gentleman saw in Poland were servant girls,\
and not ladies of good birth,\'94 the Pole with the pipe observed to\
Grushenka.\
\
\'93You can reckon on that,\'94 the tall Pole snapped contemptuously.\
\
\'93What next! Let him talk! People talk, why hinder them? It makes it\
cheerful,\'94 Grushenka said crossly.\
\
\'93I\'92m not hindering them, _pani_,\'94 said the Pole in the wig, with a long\
look at Grushenka, and relapsing into dignified silence he sucked his pipe\
again.\
\
\'93No, no. The Polish gentleman spoke the truth.\'94 Kalganov got excited\
again, as though it were a question of vast import. \'93He\'92s never been in\
Poland, so how can he talk about it? I suppose you weren\'92t married in\
Poland, were you?\'94\
\
\'93No, in the Province of Smolensk. Only, a Uhlan had brought her to Russia\
before that, my future wife, with her mamma and her aunt, and another\
female relation with a grown\uc0\u8208 up son. He brought her straight from Poland\
and gave her up to me. He was a lieutenant in our regiment, a very nice\
young man. At first he meant to marry her himself. But he didn\'92t marry\
her, because she turned out to be lame.\'94\
\
\'93So you married a lame woman?\'94 cried Kalganov.\
\
\'93Yes. They both deceived me a little bit at the time, and concealed it. I\
thought she was hopping; she kept hopping.... I thought it was for fun.\'94\
\
\'93So pleased she was going to marry you!\'94 yelled Kalganov, in a ringing,\
childish voice.\
\
\'93Yes, so pleased. But it turned out to be quite a different cause.\
Afterwards, when we were married, after the wedding, that very evening,\
she confessed, and very touchingly asked forgiveness. \'91I once jumped over\
a puddle when I was a child,\'92 she said, \'91and injured my leg.\'92 He he!\'94\
\
Kalganov went off into the most childish laughter, almost falling on the\
sofa. Grushenka, too, laughed. Mitya was at the pinnacle of happiness.\
\
\'93Do you know, that\'92s the truth, he\'92s not lying now,\'94 exclaimed Kalganov,\
turning to Mitya; \'93and do you know, he\'92s been married twice; it\'92s his\
first wife he\'92s talking about. But his second wife, do you know, ran away,\
and is alive now.\'94\
\
\'93Is it possible?\'94 said Mitya, turning quickly to Maximov with an\
expression of the utmost astonishment.\
\
\'93Yes. She did run away. I\'92ve had that unpleasant experience,\'94 Maximov\
modestly assented, \'93with a _monsieur_. And what was worse, she\'92d had all\
my little property transferred to her beforehand. \'91You\'92re an educated\
man,\'92 she said to me. \'91You can always get your living.\'92 She settled my\
business with that. A venerable bishop once said to me: \'91One of your wives\
was lame, but the other was too light\uc0\u8208 footed.\'92 He he!\'94\
\
\'93Listen, listen!\'94 cried Kalganov, bubbling over, \'93if he\'92s telling lies\'97and\
he often is\'97he\'92s only doing it to amuse us all. There\'92s no harm in that,\
is there? You know, I sometimes like him. He\'92s awfully low, but it\'92s\
natural to him, eh? Don\'92t you think so? Some people are low from self\uc0\u8208 \
interest, but he\'92s simply so, from nature. Only fancy, he claims (he was\
arguing about it all the way yesterday) that Gogol wrote _Dead Souls_\
about him. Do you remember, there\'92s a landowner called Maximov in it, whom\
Nozdryov thrashed. He was charged, do you remember, \'91for inflicting bodily\
injury with rods on the landowner Maximov in a drunken condition.\'92 Would\
you believe it, he claims that he was that Maximov and that he was beaten!\
Now can it be so? Tchitchikov made his journey, at the very latest, at the\
beginning of the twenties, so that the dates don\'92t fit. He couldn\'92t have\
been thrashed then, he couldn\'92t, could he?\'94\
\
It was difficult to imagine what Kalganov was excited about, but his\
excitement was genuine. Mitya followed his lead without protest.\
\
\'93Well, but if they did thrash him!\'94 he cried, laughing.\
\
\'93It\'92s not that they thrashed me exactly, but what I mean is\'97\'94 put in\
Maximov.\
\
\'93What do you mean? Either they thrashed you or they didn\'92t.\'94\
\
\'93What o\'92clock is it, _panie_?\'94 the Pole, with the pipe, asked his tall\
friend, with a bored expression. The other shrugged his shoulders in\
reply. Neither of them had a watch.\
\
\'93Why not talk? Let other people talk. Mustn\'92t other people talk because\
you\'92re bored?\'94 Grushenka flew at him with evident intention of finding\
fault. Something seemed for the first time to flash upon Mitya\'92s mind.\
This time the Pole answered with unmistakable irritability.\
\
\'93_Pani_, I didn\'92t oppose it. I didn\'92t say anything.\'94\
\
\'93All right then. Come, tell us your story,\'94 Grushenka cried to Maximov.\
\'93Why are you all silent?\'94\
\
\'93There\'92s nothing to tell, it\'92s all so foolish,\'94 answered Maximov at once,\
with evident satisfaction, mincing a little. \'93Besides, all that\'92s by way\
of allegory in Gogol, for he\'92s made all the names have a meaning. Nozdryov\
was really called Nosov, and Kuvshinikov had quite a different name, he\
was called Shkvornev. Fenardi really was called Fenardi, only he wasn\'92t an\
Italian but a Russian, and Mamsel Fenardi was a pretty girl with her\
pretty little legs in tights, and she had a little short skirt with\
spangles, and she kept turning round and round, only not for four hours\
but for four minutes only, and she bewitched every one...\'94\
\
\'93But what were you beaten for?\'94 cried Kalganov.\
\
\'93For Piron!\'94 answered Maximov.\
\
\'93What Piron?\'94 cried Mitya.\
\
\'93The famous French writer, Piron. We were all drinking then, a big party\
of us, in a tavern at that very fair. They\'92d invited me, and first of all\
I began quoting epigrams. \'91Is that you, Boileau? What a funny get\uc0\u8208 up!\'92 and\
Boileau answers that he\'92s going to a masquerade, that is to the baths, he\
he! And they took it to themselves, so I made haste to repeat another,\
very sarcastic, well known to all educated people:\
\
\
    Yes, Sappho and Phaon are we!\
    But one grief is weighing on me.\
    You don\'92t know your way to the sea!\
\
\
They were still more offended and began abusing me in the most unseemly\
way for it. And as ill\uc0\u8208 luck would have it, to set things right, I began\
telling a very cultivated anecdote about Piron, how he was not accepted\
into the French Academy, and to revenge himself wrote his own epitaph:\
\
\
    Ci\uc0\u8208 g\'eet Piron qui ne fut rien,\
    Pas m\'eame acad\'e9micien.\
\
\
They seized me and thrashed me.\'94\
\
\'93But what for? What for?\'94\
\
\'93For my education. People can thrash a man for anything,\'94 Maximov\
concluded, briefly and sententiously.\
\
\'93Eh, that\'92s enough! That\'92s all stupid, I don\'92t want to listen. I thought\
it would be amusing,\'94 Grushenka cut them short, suddenly.\
\
Mitya started, and at once left off laughing. The tall Pole rose upon his\
feet, and with the haughty air of a man, bored and out of his element,\
began pacing from corner to corner of the room, his hands behind his back.\
\
\'93Ah, he can\'92t sit still,\'94 said Grushenka, looking at him contemptuously.\
Mitya began to feel anxious. He noticed besides, that the Pole on the sofa\
was looking at him with an irritable expression.\
\
\'93_Panie!_\'94 cried Mitya, \'93let\'92s drink! and the other _pan_, too! Let us\
drink.\'94\
\
In a flash he had pulled three glasses towards him, and filled them with\
champagne.\
\
\'93To Poland, _panovie_, I drink to your Poland!\'94 cried Mitya.\
\
\'93I shall be delighted, _panie_,\'94 said the Pole on the sofa, with dignity\
and affable condescension, and he took his glass.\
\
\'93And the other _pan_, what\'92s his name? Drink, most illustrious, take your\
glass!\'94 Mitya urged.\
\
\'93Pan Vrublevsky,\'94 put in the Pole on the sofa.\
\
Pan Vrublevsky came up to the table, swaying as he walked.\
\
\'93To Poland, _panovie!_\'94 cried Mitya, raising his glass. \'93Hurrah!\'94\
\
All three drank. Mitya seized the bottle and again poured out three\
glasses.\
\
\'93Now to Russia, _panovie_, and let us be brothers!\'94\
\
\'93Pour out some for us,\'94 said Grushenka; \'93I\'92ll drink to Russia, too!\'94\
\
\'93So will I,\'94 said Kalganov.\
\
\'93And I would, too ... to Russia, the old grandmother!\'94 tittered Maximov.\
\
\'93All! All!\'94 cried Mitya. \'93Trifon Borissovitch, some more bottles!\'94\
\
The other three bottles Mitya had brought with him were put on the table.\
Mitya filled the glasses.\
\
\'93To Russia! Hurrah!\'94 he shouted again. All drank the toast except the\
Poles, and Grushenka tossed off her whole glass at once. The Poles did not\
touch theirs.\
\
\'93How\'92s this, _panovie_?\'94 cried Mitya, \'93won\'92t you drink it?\'94\
\
Pan Vrublevsky took the glass, raised it and said with a resonant voice:\
\
\'93To Russia as she was before 1772.\'94\
\
\'93Come, that\'92s better!\'94 cried the other Pole, and they both emptied their\
glasses at once.\
\
\'93You\'92re fools, you _panovie_,\'94 broke suddenly from Mitya.\
\
\'93_Panie!_\'94 shouted both the Poles, menacingly, setting on Mitya like a\
couple of cocks. Pan Vrublevsky was specially furious.\
\
\'93Can one help loving one\'92s own country?\'94 he shouted.\
\
\'93Be silent! Don\'92t quarrel! I won\'92t have any quarreling!\'94 cried Grushenka\
imperiously, and she stamped her foot on the floor. Her face glowed, her\
eyes were shining. The effects of the glass she had just drunk were\
apparent. Mitya was terribly alarmed.\
\
\'93_Panovie_, forgive me! It was my fault, I\'92m sorry. Vrublevsky, _panie_\
Vrublevsky, I\'92m sorry.\'94\
\
\'93Hold your tongue, you, anyway! Sit down, you stupid!\'94 Grushenka scolded\
with angry annoyance.\
\
Every one sat down, all were silent, looking at one another.\
\
\'93Gentlemen, I was the cause of it all,\'94 Mitya began again, unable to make\
anything of Grushenka\'92s words. \'93Come, why are we sitting here? What shall\
we do ... to amuse ourselves again?\'94\
\
\'93Ach, it\'92s certainly anything but amusing!\'94 Kalganov mumbled lazily.\
\
\'93Let\'92s play faro again, as we did just now,\'94 Maximov tittered suddenly.\
\
\'93Faro? Splendid!\'94 cried Mitya. \'93If only the _panovie_\'97\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s lite, _panovie_,\'94 the Pole on the sofa responded, as it were\
unwillingly.\
\
\'93That\'92s true,\'94 assented Pan Vrublevsky.\
\
\'93Lite? What do you mean by \'91lite\'92?\'94 asked Grushenka.\
\
\'93Late, _pani_! \'91a late hour\'92 I mean,\'94 the Pole on the sofa explained.\
\
\'93It\'92s always late with them. They can never do anything!\'94 Grushenka almost\
shrieked in her anger. \'93They\'92re dull themselves, so they want others to be\
dull. Before you came, Mitya, they were just as silent and kept turning up\
their noses at me.\'94\
\
\'93My goddess!\'94 cried the Pole on the sofa, \'93I see you\'92re not well\uc0\u8208 disposed\
to me, that\'92s why I\'92m gloomy. I\'92m ready, _panie_,\'94 added he, addressing\
Mitya.\
\
\'93Begin, _panie_,\'94 Mitya assented, pulling his notes out of his pocket, and\
laying two hundred\uc0\u8208 rouble notes on the table. \'93I want to lose a lot to\
you. Take your cards. Make the bank.\'94\
\
\'93We\'92ll have cards from the landlord, _panie_,\'94 said the little Pole,\
gravely and emphatically.\
\
\'93That\'92s much the best way,\'94 chimed in Pan Vrublevsky.\
\
\'93From the landlord? Very good, I understand, let\'92s get them from him.\
Cards!\'94 Mitya shouted to the landlord.\
\
The landlord brought in a new, unopened pack, and informed Mitya that the\
girls were getting ready, and that the Jews with the cymbals would most\
likely be here soon; but the cart with the provisions had not yet arrived.\
Mitya jumped up from the table and ran into the next room to give orders,\
but only three girls had arrived, and Marya was not there yet. And he did\
not know himself what orders to give and why he had run out. He only told\
them to take out of the box the presents for the girls, the sweets, the\
toffee and the fondants. \'93And vodka for Andrey, vodka for Andrey!\'94 he\
cried in haste. \'93I was rude to Andrey!\'94\
\
Suddenly Maximov, who had followed him out, touched him on the shoulder.\
\
\'93Give me five roubles,\'94 he whispered to Mitya. \'93I\'92ll stake something at\
faro, too, he he!\'94\
\
\'93Capital! Splendid! Take ten, here!\'94\
\
Again he took all the notes out of his pocket and picked out one for ten\
roubles. \'93And if you lose that, come again, come again.\'94\
\
\'93Very good,\'94 Maximov whispered joyfully, and he ran back again. Mitya,\
too, returned, apologizing for having kept them waiting. The Poles had\
already sat down, and opened the pack. They looked much more amiable,\
almost cordial. The Pole on the sofa had lighted another pipe and was\
preparing to throw. He wore an air of solemnity.\
\
\'93To your places, gentlemen,\'94 cried Pan Vrublevsky.\
\
\'93No, I\'92m not going to play any more,\'94 observed Kalganov, \'93I\'92ve lost fifty\
roubles to them just now.\'94\
\
\'93The _pan_ had no luck, perhaps he\'92ll be lucky this time,\'94 the Pole on the\
sofa observed in his direction.\
\
\'93How much in the bank? To correspond?\'94 asked Mitya.\
\
\'93That\'92s according, _panie_, maybe a hundred, maybe two hundred, as much as\
you will stake.\'94\
\
\'93A million!\'94 laughed Mitya.\
\
\'93The Pan Captain has heard of Pan Podvysotsky, perhaps?\'94\
\
\'93What Podvysotsky?\'94\
\
\'93In Warsaw there was a bank and any one comes and stakes against it.\
Podvysotsky comes, sees a thousand gold pieces, stakes against the bank.\
The banker says, \'91_Panie_ Podvysotsky, are you laying down the gold, or\
must we trust to your honor?\'92 \'91To my honor, _panie_,\'92 says Podvysotsky.\
\'91So much the better.\'92 The banker throws the dice. Podvysotsky wins. \'91Take\
it, _panie_,\'92 says the banker, and pulling out the drawer he gives him a\
million. \'91Take it, _panie_, this is your gain.\'92 There was a million in the\
bank. \'91I didn\'92t know that,\'92 says Podvysotsky. \'91_Panie_ Podvysotsky,\'92 said\
the banker, \'91you pledged your honor and we pledged ours.\'92 Podvysotsky took\
the million.\'94\
\
\'93That\'92s not true,\'94 said Kalganov.\
\
\'93_Panie_ Kalganov, in gentlemanly society one doesn\'92t say such things.\'94\
\
\'93As if a Polish gambler would give away a million!\'94 cried Mitya, but\
checked himself at once. \'93Forgive me, _panie_, it\'92s my fault again, he\
would, he would give away a million, for honor, for Polish honor. You see\
how I talk Polish, ha ha! Here, I stake ten roubles, the knave leads.\'94\
\
\'93And I put a rouble on the queen, the queen of hearts, the pretty little\
_panienotchka_, he he!\'94 laughed Maximov, pulling out his queen, and, as\
though trying to conceal it from every one, he moved right up and crossed\
himself hurriedly under the table. Mitya won. The rouble won, too.\
\
\'93A corner!\'94 cried Mitya.\
\
\'93I\'92ll bet another rouble, a \'91single\'92 stake,\'94 Maximov muttered gleefully,\
hugely delighted at having won a rouble.\
\
\'93Lost!\'94 shouted Mitya. \'93A \'91double\'92 on the seven!\'94\
\
The seven too was trumped.\
\
\'93Stop!\'94 cried Kalganov suddenly.\
\
\'93Double! Double!\'94 Mitya doubled his stakes, and each time he doubled the\
stake, the card he doubled was trumped by the Poles. The rouble stakes\
kept winning.\
\
\'93On the double!\'94 shouted Mitya furiously.\
\
\'93You\'92ve lost two hundred, _panie_. Will you stake another hundred?\'94 the\
Pole on the sofa inquired.\
\
\'93What? Lost two hundred already? Then another two hundred! All doubles!\'94\
\
And pulling his money out of his pocket, Mitya was about to fling two\
hundred roubles on the queen, but Kalganov covered it with his hand.\
\
\'93That\'92s enough!\'94 he shouted in his ringing voice.\
\
\'93What\'92s the matter?\'94 Mitya stared at him.\
\
\'93That\'92s enough! I don\'92t want you to play any more. Don\'92t!\'94\
\
\'93Why?\'94\
\
\'93Because I don\'92t. Hang it, come away. That\'92s why. I won\'92t let you go on\
playing.\'94\
\
Mitya gazed at him in astonishment.\
\
\'93Give it up, Mitya. He may be right. You\'92ve lost a lot as it is,\'94 said\
Grushenka, with a curious note in her voice. Both the Poles rose from\
their seats with a deeply offended air.\
\
\'93Are you joking, _panie_?\'94 said the short man, looking severely at\
Kalganov.\
\
\'93How dare you!\'94 Pan Vrublevsky, too, growled at Kalganov.\
\
\'93Don\'92t dare to shout like that,\'94 cried Grushenka. \'93Ah, you turkey\uc0\u8208 cocks!\'94\
\
Mitya looked at each of them in turn. But something in Grushenka\'92s face\
suddenly struck him, and at the same instant something new flashed into\
his mind\'97a strange new thought!\
\
\'93_Pani_ Agrippina,\'94 the little Pole was beginning, crimson with anger,\
when Mitya suddenly went up to him and slapped him on the shoulder.\
\
\'93Most illustrious, two words with you.\'94\
\
\'93What do you want?\'94\
\
\'93In the next room, I\'92ve two words to say to you, something pleasant, very\
pleasant. You\'92ll be glad to hear it.\'94\
\
The little _pan_ was taken aback and looked apprehensively at Mitya. He\
agreed at once, however, on condition that Pan Vrublevsky went with them.\
\
\'93The bodyguard? Let him come, and I want him, too. I must have him!\'94 cried\
Mitya. \'93March, _panovie_!\'94\
\
\'93Where are you going?\'94 asked Grushenka, anxiously.\
\
\'93We\'92ll be back in one moment,\'94 answered Mitya.\
\
There was a sort of boldness, a sudden confidence shining in his eyes. His\
face had looked very different when he entered the room an hour before.\
\
He led the Poles, not into the large room where the chorus of girls was\
assembling and the table was being laid, but into the bedroom on the\
right, where the trunks and packages were kept, and there were two large\
beds, with pyramids of cotton pillows on each. There was a lighted candle\
on a small deal table in the corner. The small man and Mitya sat down to\
this table, facing each other, while the huge Vrublevsky stood beside\
them, his hands behind his back. The Poles looked severe but were\
evidently inquisitive.\
\
\'93What can I do for you, _panie_?\'94 lisped the little Pole.\
\
\'93Well, look here, _panie_, I won\'92t keep you long. There\'92s money for you,\'94\
he pulled out his notes. \'93Would you like three thousand? Take it and go\
your way.\'94\
\
The Pole gazed open\uc0\u8208 eyed at Mitya, with a searching look.\
\
\'93Three thousand, _panie_?\'94 He exchanged glances with Vrublevsky.\
\
\'93Three, _panovie_, three! Listen, _panie_, I see you\'92re a sensible man.\
Take three thousand and go to the devil, and Vrublevsky with you\'97d\'92you\
hear? But, at once, this very minute, and for ever. You understand that,\
_panie_, for ever. Here\'92s the door, you go out of it. What have you got\
there, a great\uc0\u8208 coat, a fur coat? I\'92ll bring it out to you. They\'92ll get the\
horses out directly, and then\'97good\uc0\u8208 by, _panie_!\'94\
\
Mitya awaited an answer with assurance. He had no doubts. An expression of\
extraordinary resolution passed over the Pole\'92s face.\
\
\'93And the money, _panie_?\'94\
\
\'93The money, _panie_? Five hundred roubles I\'92ll give you this moment for\
the journey, and as a first installment, and two thousand five hundred to\uc0\u8208 \
morrow, in the town\'97I swear on my honor, I\'92ll get it, I\'92ll get it at any\
cost!\'94 cried Mitya.\
\
The Poles exchanged glances again. The short man\'92s face looked more\
forbidding.\
\
\'93Seven hundred, seven hundred, not five hundred, at once, this minute,\
cash down!\'94 Mitya added, feeling something wrong. \'93What\'92s the matter,\
_panie_? Don\'92t you trust me? I can\'92t give you the whole three thousand\
straight off. If I give it, you may come back to her to\uc0\u8208 morrow....\
Besides, I haven\'92t the three thousand with me. I\'92ve got it at home in the\
town,\'94 faltered Mitya, his spirit sinking at every word he uttered. \'93Upon\
my word, the money\'92s there, hidden.\'94\
\
In an instant an extraordinary sense of personal dignity showed itself in\
the little man\'92s face.\
\
\'93What next?\'94 he asked ironically. \'93For shame!\'94 and he spat on the floor.\
Pan Vrublevsky spat too.\
\
\'93You do that, _panie_,\'94 said Mitya, recognizing with despair that all was\
over, \'93because you hope to make more out of Grushenka? You\'92re a couple of\
capons, that\'92s what you are!\'94\
\
\'93This is a mortal insult!\'94 The little Pole turned as red as a crab, and he\
went out of the room, briskly, as though unwilling to hear another word.\
Vrublevsky swung out after him, and Mitya followed, confused and\
crestfallen. He was afraid of Grushenka, afraid that the _pan_ would at\
once raise an outcry. And so indeed he did. The Pole walked into the room\
and threw himself in a theatrical attitude before Grushenka.\
\
\'93_Pani_ Agrippina, I have received a mortal insult!\'94 he exclaimed. But\
Grushenka suddenly lost all patience, as though they had wounded her in\
the tenderest spot.\
\
\'93Speak Russian! Speak Russian!\'94 she cried, \'93not another word of Polish!\
You used to talk Russian. You can\'92t have forgotten it in five years.\'94\
\
She was red with passion.\
\
\'93_Pani_ Agrippina\'97\'94\
\
\'93My name\'92s Agrafena, Grushenka, speak Russian or I won\'92t listen!\'94\
\
The Pole gasped with offended dignity, and quickly and pompously delivered\
himself in broken Russian:\
\
\'93_Pani_ Agrafena, I came here to forget the past and forgive it, to forget\
all that has happened till to\uc0\u8208 day\'97\'94\
\
\'93Forgive? Came here to forgive me?\'94 Grushenka cut him short, jumping up\
from her seat.\
\
\'93Just so, _pani_, I\'92m not pusillanimous, I\'92m magnanimous. But I was\
astounded when I saw your lovers. Pan Mitya offered me three thousand, in\
the other room to depart. I spat in the _pan\'92s_ face.\'94\
\
\'93What? He offered you money for me?\'94 cried Grushenka, hysterically. \'93Is it\
true, Mitya? How dare you? Am I for sale?\'94\
\
\'93_Panie, panie!_\'94 yelled Mitya, \'93she\'92s pure and shining, and I have never\
been her lover! That\'92s a lie....\'94\
\
\'93How dare you defend me to him?\'94 shrieked Grushenka. \'93It wasn\'92t virtue\
kept me pure, and it wasn\'92t that I was afraid of Kuzma, but that I might\
hold up my head when I met him, and tell him he\'92s a scoundrel. And he did\
actually refuse the money?\'94\
\
\'93He took it! He took it!\'94 cried Mitya; \'93only he wanted to get the whole\
three thousand at once, and I could only give him seven hundred straight\
off.\'94\
\
\'93I see: he heard I had money, and came here to marry me!\'94\
\
\'93_Pani_ Agrippina!\'94 cried the little Pole. \'93I\'92m\'97a knight, I\'92m\'97a nobleman,\
and not a _lajdak_. I came here to make you my wife and I find you a\
different woman, perverse and shameless.\'94\
\
\'93Oh, go back where you came from! I\'92ll tell them to turn you out and\
you\'92ll be turned out,\'94 cried Grushenka, furious. \'93I\'92ve been a fool, a\
fool, to have been miserable these five years! And it wasn\'92t for his sake,\
it was my anger made me miserable. And this isn\'92t he at all! Was he like\
this? It might be his father! Where did you get your wig from? He was a\
falcon, but this is a gander. He used to laugh and sing to me.... And I\'92ve\
been crying for five years, damned fool, abject, shameless I was!\'94\
\
She sank back in her low chair and hid her face in her hands. At that\
instant the chorus of Mokroe began singing in the room on the left\'97a\
rollicking dance song.\
\
\'93A regular Sodom!\'94 Vrublevsky roared suddenly. \'93Landlord, send the\
shameless hussies away!\'94\
\
The landlord, who had been for some time past inquisitively peeping in at\
the door, hearing shouts and guessing that his guests were quarreling, at\
once entered the room.\
\
\'93What are you shouting for? D\'92you want to split your throat?\'94 he said,\
addressing Vrublevsky, with surprising rudeness.\
\
\'93Animal!\'94 bellowed Pan Vrublevsky.\
\
\'93Animal? And what sort of cards were you playing with just now? I gave you\
a pack and you hid it. You played with marked cards! I could send you to\
Siberia for playing with false cards, d\'92you know that, for it\'92s just the\
same as false banknotes....\'94\
\
And going up to the sofa he thrust his fingers between the sofa back and\
the cushion, and pulled out an unopened pack of cards.\
\
\'93Here\'92s my pack unopened!\'94\
\
He held it up and showed it to all in the room. \'93From where I stood I saw\
him slip my pack away, and put his in place of it\'97you\'92re a cheat and not a\
gentleman!\'94\
\
\'93And I twice saw the _pan_ change a card!\'94 cried Kalganov.\
\
\'93How shameful! How shameful!\'94 exclaimed Grushenka, clasping her hands, and\
blushing for genuine shame. \'93Good Lord, he\'92s come to that!\'94\
\
\'93I thought so, too!\'94 said Mitya. But before he had uttered the words,\
Vrublevsky, with a confused and infuriated face, shook his fist at\
Grushenka, shouting:\
\
\'93You low harlot!\'94\
\
Mitya flew at him at once, clutched him in both hands, lifted him in the\
air, and in one instant had carried him into the room on the right, from\
which they had just come.\
\
\'93I\'92ve laid him on the floor, there,\'94 he announced, returning at once,\
gasping with excitement. \'93He\'92s struggling, the scoundrel! But he won\'92t\
come back, no fear of that!...\'94\
\
He closed one half of the folding doors, and holding the other ajar called\
out to the little Pole:\
\
\'93Most illustrious, will you be pleased to retire as well?\'94\
\
\'93My dear Dmitri Fyodorovitch,\'94 said Trifon Borissovitch, \'93make them give\
you back the money you lost. It\'92s as good as stolen from you.\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t want my fifty roubles back,\'94 Kalganov declared suddenly.\
\
\'93I don\'92t want my two hundred, either,\'94 cried Mitya, \'93I wouldn\'92t take it\
for anything! Let him keep it as a consolation.\'94\
\
\'93Bravo, Mitya! You\'92re a trump, Mitya!\'94 cried Grushenka, and there was a\
note of fierce anger in the exclamation.\
\
The little _pan_, crimson with fury but still mindful of his dignity, was\
making for the door, but he stopped short and said suddenly, addressing\
Grushenka:\
\
\'93_Pani_, if you want to come with me, come. If not, good\uc0\u8208 by.\'94\
\
And swelling with indignation and importance he went to the door. This was\
a man of character: he had so good an opinion of himself that after all\
that had passed, he still expected that she would marry him. Mitya slammed\
the door after him.\
\
\'93Lock it,\'94 said Kalganov. But the key clicked on the other side, they had\
locked it from within.\
\
\'93That\'92s capital!\'94 exclaimed Grushenka relentlessly. \'93Serve them right!\'94\
\
\
\
Chapter VIII. Delirium\
\
\
What followed was almost an orgy, a feast to which all were welcome.\
Grushenka was the first to call for wine.\
\
\'93I want to drink. I want to be quite drunk, as we were before. Do you\
remember, Mitya, do you remember how we made friends here last time!\'94\
\
Mitya himself was almost delirious, feeling that his happiness was at\
hand. But Grushenka was continually sending him away from her.\
\
\'93Go and enjoy yourself. Tell them to dance, to make merry, \'91let the stove\
and cottage dance\'92; as we had it last time,\'94 she kept exclaiming. She was\
tremendously excited. And Mitya hastened to obey her. The chorus were in\
the next room. The room in which they had been sitting till that moment\
was too small, and was divided in two by cotton curtains, behind which was\
a huge bed with a puffy feather mattress and a pyramid of cotton pillows.\
In the four rooms for visitors there were beds. Grushenka settled herself\
just at the door. Mitya set an easy chair for her. She had sat in the same\
place to watch the dancing and singing \'93the time before,\'94 when they had\
made merry there. All the girls who had come had been there then; the\
Jewish band with fiddles and zithers had come, too, and at last the long\
expected cart had arrived with the wines and provisions.\
\
Mitya bustled about. All sorts of people began coming into the room to\
look on, peasants and their women, who had been roused from sleep and\
attracted by the hopes of another marvelous entertainment such as they had\
enjoyed a month before. Mitya remembered their faces, greeting and\
embracing every one he knew. He uncorked bottles and poured out wine for\
every one who presented himself. Only the girls were very eager for the\
champagne. The men preferred rum, brandy, and, above all, hot punch. Mitya\
had chocolate made for all the girls, and ordered that three samovars\
should be kept boiling all night to provide tea and punch for everyone to\
help himself.\
\
An absurd chaotic confusion followed, but Mitya was in his natural\
element, and the more foolish it became, the more his spirits rose. If the\
peasants had asked him for money at that moment, he would have pulled out\
his notes and given them away right and left. This was probably why the\
landlord, Trifon Borissovitch, kept hovering about Mitya to protect him.\
He seemed to have given up all idea of going to bed that night; but he\
drank little, only one glass of punch, and kept a sharp look\uc0\u8208 out on\
Mitya\'92s interests after his own fashion. He intervened in the nick of\
time, civilly and obsequiously persuading Mitya not to give away \'93cigars\
and Rhine wine,\'94 and, above all, money to the peasants as he had done\
before. He was very indignant, too, at the peasant girls drinking liqueur,\
and eating sweets.\
\
\'93They\'92re a lousy lot, Dmitri Fyodorovitch,\'94 he said. \'93I\'92d give them a\
kick, every one of them, and they\'92d take it as an honor\'97that\'92s all they\'92re\
worth!\'94\
\
Mitya remembered Andrey again, and ordered punch to be sent out to him. \'93I\
was rude to him just now,\'94 he repeated with a sinking, softened voice.\
Kalganov did not want to drink, and at first did not care for the girls\'92\
singing; but after he had drunk a couple of glasses of champagne he became\
extraordinarily lively, strolling about the room, laughing and praising\
the music and the songs, admiring every one and everything. Maximov,\
blissfully drunk, never left his side. Grushenka, too, was beginning to\
get drunk. Pointing to Kalganov, she said to Mitya:\
\
\'93What a dear, charming boy he is!\'94\
\
And Mitya, delighted, ran to kiss Kalganov and Maximov. Oh, great were his\
hopes! She had said nothing yet, and seemed, indeed, purposely to refrain\
from speaking. But she looked at him from time to time with caressing and\
passionate eyes. At last she suddenly gripped his hand and drew him\
vigorously to her. She was sitting at the moment in the low chair by the\
door.\
\
\'93How was it you came just now, eh? Have you walked in!... I was\
frightened. So you wanted to give me up to him, did you? Did you really\
want to?\'94\
\
\'93I didn\'92t want to spoil your happiness!\'94 Mitya faltered blissfully. But\
she did not need his answer.\
\
\'93Well, go and enjoy yourself ...\'94 she sent him away once more. \'93Don\'92t cry,\
I\'92ll call you back again.\'94\
\
He would run away, and she listened to the singing and looked at the\
dancing, though her eyes followed him wherever he went. But in another\
quarter of an hour she would call him once more and again he would run\
back to her.\
\
\'93Come, sit beside me, tell me, how did you hear about me, and my coming\
here yesterday? From whom did you first hear it?\'94\
\
And Mitya began telling her all about it, disconnectedly, incoherently,\
feverishly. He spoke strangely, often frowning, and stopping abruptly.\
\
\'93What are you frowning at?\'94 she asked.\
\
\'93Nothing.... I left a man ill there. I\'92d give ten years of my life for him\
to get well, to know he was all right!\'94\
\
\'93Well, never mind him, if he\'92s ill. So you meant to shoot yourself to\uc0\u8208 \
morrow! What a silly boy! What for? I like such reckless fellows as you,\'94\
she lisped, with a rather halting tongue. \'93So you would go any length for\
me, eh? Did you really mean to shoot yourself to\uc0\u8208 morrow, you stupid? No,\
wait a little. To\uc0\u8208 morrow I may have something to say to you.... I won\'92t\
say it to\uc0\u8208 day, but to\u8208 morrow. You\'92d like it to be to\u8208 day? No, I don\'92t want\
to to\uc0\u8208 day. Come, go along now, go and amuse yourself.\'94\
\
Once, however, she called him, as it were, puzzled and uneasy.\
\
\'93Why are you sad? I see you\'92re sad.... Yes, I see it,\'94 she added, looking\
intently into his eyes. \'93Though you keep kissing the peasants and\
shouting, I see something. No, be merry. I\'92m merry; you be merry, too....\
I love somebody here. Guess who it is. Ah, look, my boy has fallen asleep,\
poor dear, he\'92s drunk.\'94\
\
She meant Kalganov. He was, in fact, drunk, and had dropped asleep for a\
moment, sitting on the sofa. But he was not merely drowsy from drink; he\
felt suddenly dejected, or, as he said, \'93bored.\'94 He was intensely\
depressed by the girls\'92 songs, which, as the drinking went on, gradually\
became coarse and more reckless. And the dances were as bad. Two girls\
dressed up as bears, and a lively girl, called Stepanida, with a stick in\
her hand, acted the part of keeper, and began to \'93show them.\'94\
\
\'93Look alive, Marya, or you\'92ll get the stick!\'94\
\
The bears rolled on the ground at last in the most unseemly fashion, amid\
roars of laughter from the closely\uc0\u8208 packed crowd of men and women.\
\
\'93Well, let them! Let them!\'94 said Grushenka sententiously, with an ecstatic\
expression on her face. \'93When they do get a day to enjoy themselves, why\
shouldn\'92t folks be happy?\'94\
\
Kalganov looked as though he had been besmirched with dirt.\
\
\'93It\'92s swinish, all this peasant foolery,\'94 he murmured, moving away; \'93it\'92s\
the game they play when it\'92s light all night in summer.\'94\
\
He particularly disliked one \'93new\'94 song to a jaunty dance\uc0\u8208 tune. It\
described how a gentleman came and tried his luck with the girls, to see\
whether they would love him:\
\
\
    The master came to try the girls:\
    Would they love him, would they not?\
\
\
But the girls could not love the master:\
\
\
    He would beat me cruelly\
    And such love won\'92t do for me.\
\
\
Then a gypsy comes along and he, too, tries:\
\
\
    The gypsy came to try the girls:\
    Would they love him, would they not?\
\
\
But they couldn\'92t love the gypsy either:\
\
\
    He would be a thief, I fear,\
    And would cause me many a tear.\
\
\
And many more men come to try their luck, among them a soldier:\
\
\
    The soldier came to try the girls:\
    Would they love him, would they not?\
\
\
But the soldier is rejected with contempt, in two indecent lines, sung\
with absolute frankness and producing a furore in the audience. The song\
ends with a merchant:\
\
\
    The merchant came to try the girls:\
    Would they love him, would they not?\
\
\
And it appears that he wins their love because:\
\
\
    The merchant will make gold for me\
    And his queen I\'92ll gladly be.\
\
\
Kalvanov was positively indignant.\
\
\'93That\'92s just a song of yesterday,\'94 he said aloud. \'93Who writes such things\
for them? They might just as well have had a railwayman or a Jew come to\
try his luck with the girls; they\'92d have carried all before them.\'94\
\
And, almost as though it were a personal affront, he declared, on the\
spot, that he was bored, sat down on the sofa and immediately fell asleep.\
His pretty little face looked rather pale, as it fell back on the sofa\
cushion.\
\
\'93Look how pretty he is,\'94 said Grushenka, taking Mitya up to him. \'93I was\
combing his hair just now; his hair\'92s like flax, and so thick....\'94\
\
And, bending over him tenderly, she kissed his forehead. Kalganov\
instantly opened his eyes, looked at her, stood up, and with the most\
anxious air inquired where was Maximov?\
\
\'93So that\'92s who it is you want.\'94 Grushenka laughed. \'93Stay with me a minute.\
Mitya, run and find his Maximov.\'94\
\
Maximov, it appeared, could not tear himself away from the girls, only\
running away from time to time to pour himself out a glass of liqueur. He\
had drunk two cups of chocolate. His face was red, and his nose was\
crimson; his eyes were moist and mawkishly sweet. He ran up and announced\
that he was going to dance the \'93saboti\'e8re.\'94\
\
\'93They taught me all those well\uc0\u8208 bred, aristocratic dances when I was\
little....\'94\
\
\'93Go, go with him, Mitya, and I\'92ll watch from here how he dances,\'94 said\
Grushenka.\
\
\'93No, no, I\'92m coming to look on, too,\'94 exclaimed Kalganov, brushing aside\
in the most na\'efve way Grushenka\'92s offer to sit with him. They all went to\
look on. Maximov danced his dance. But it roused no great admiration in\
any one but Mitya. It consisted of nothing but skipping and hopping,\
kicking up the feet, and at every skip Maximov slapped the upturned sole\
of his foot. Kalganov did not like it at all, but Mitya kissed the dancer.\
\
\'93Thanks. You\'92re tired perhaps? What are you looking for here? Would you\
like some sweets? A cigar, perhaps?\'94\
\
\'93A cigarette.\'94\
\
\'93Don\'92t you want a drink?\'94\
\
\'93I\'92ll just have a liqueur.... Have you any chocolates?\'94\
\
\'93Yes, there\'92s a heap of them on the table there. Choose one, my dear\
soul!\'94\
\
\'93I like one with vanilla ... for old people. He he!\'94\
\
\'93No, brother, we\'92ve none of that special sort.\'94\
\
\'93I say,\'94 the old man bent down to whisper in Mitya\'92s ear. \'93That girl\
there, little Marya, he he! How would it be if you were to help me make\
friends with her?\'94\
\
\'93So that\'92s what you\'92re after! No, brother, that won\'92t do!\'94\
\
\'93I\'92d do no harm to any one,\'94 Maximov muttered disconsolately.\
\
\'93Oh, all right, all right. They only come here to dance and sing, you\
know, brother. But damn it all, wait a bit!... Eat and drink and be merry,\
meanwhile. Don\'92t you want money?\'94\
\
\'93Later on, perhaps,\'94 smiled Maximov.\
\
\'93All right, all right....\'94\
\
Mitya\'92s head was burning. He went outside to the wooden balcony which ran\
round the whole building on the inner side, overlooking the courtyard. The\
fresh air revived him. He stood alone in a dark corner, and suddenly\
clutched his head in both hands. His scattered thoughts came together; his\
sensations blended into a whole and threw a sudden light into his mind. A\
fearful and terrible light! \'93If I\'92m to shoot myself, why not now?\'94 passed\
through his mind. \'93Why not go for the pistols, bring them here, and here,\
in this dark dirty corner, make an end?\'94 Almost a minute he stood,\
undecided. A few hours earlier, when he had been dashing here, he was\
pursued by disgrace, by the theft he had committed, and that blood, that\
blood!... But yet it was easier for him then. Then everything was over: he\
had lost her, given her up. She was gone, for him\'97oh, then his death\
sentence had been easier for him; at least it had seemed necessary,\
inevitable, for what had he to stay on earth for?\
\
But now? Was it the same as then? Now one phantom, one terror at least was\
at an end: that first, rightful lover, that fateful figure had vanished,\
leaving no trace. The terrible phantom had turned into something so small,\
so comic; it had been carried into the bedroom and locked in. It would\
never return. She was ashamed, and from her eyes he could see now whom she\
loved. Now he had everything to make life happy ... but he could not go on\
living, he could not; oh, damnation! \'93O God! restore to life the man I\
knocked down at the fence! Let this fearful cup pass from me! Lord, thou\
hast wrought miracles for such sinners as me! But what, what if the old\
man\'92s alive? Oh, then the shame of the other disgrace I would wipe away. I\
would restore the stolen money. I\'92d give it back; I\'92d get it somehow....\
No trace of that shame will remain except in my heart for ever! But no,\
no; oh, impossible cowardly dreams! Oh, damnation!\'94\
\
Yet there was a ray of light and hope in his darkness. He jumped up and\
ran back to the room\'97to her, to her, his queen for ever! Was not one\
moment of her love worth all the rest of life, even in the agonies of\
disgrace? This wild question clutched at his heart. \'93To her, to her alone,\
to see her, to hear her, to think of nothing, to forget everything, if\
only for that night, for an hour, for a moment!\'94 Just as he turned from\
the balcony into the passage, he came upon the landlord, Trifon\
Borissovitch. He thought he looked gloomy and worried, and fancied he had\
come to find him.\
\
\'93What is it, Trifon Borissovitch? are you looking for me?\'94\
\
\'93No, sir.\'94 The landlord seemed disconcerted. \'93Why should I be looking for\
you? Where have you been?\'94\
\
\'93Why do you look so glum? You\'92re not angry, are you? Wait a bit, you shall\
soon get to bed.... What\'92s the time?\'94\
\
\'93It\'92ll be three o\'92clock. Past three, it must be.\'94\
\
\'93We\'92ll leave off soon. We\'92ll leave off.\'94\
\
\'93Don\'92t mention it; it doesn\'92t matter. Keep it up as long as you like....\'94\
\
\'93What\'92s the matter with him?\'94 Mitya wondered for an instant, and he ran\
back to the room where the girls were dancing. But she was not there. She\
was not in the blue room either; there was no one but Kalganov asleep on\
the sofa. Mitya peeped behind the curtain\'97she was there. She was sitting\
in the corner, on a trunk. Bent forward, with her head and arms on the bed\
close by, she was crying bitterly, doing her utmost to stifle her sobs\
that she might not be heard. Seeing Mitya, she beckoned him to her, and\
when he ran to her, she grasped his hand tightly.\
\
\'93Mitya, Mitya, I loved him, you know. How I have loved him these five\
years, all that time! Did I love him or only my own anger? No, him, him!\
It\'92s a lie that it was my anger I loved and not him. Mitya, I was only\
seventeen then; he was so kind to me, so merry; he used to sing to me....\
Or so it seemed to a silly girl like me.... And now, O Lord, it\'92s not the\
same man. Even his face is not the same; he\'92s different altogether. I\
shouldn\'92t have known him. I drove here with Timofey, and all the way I was\
thinking how I should meet him, what I should say to him, how we should\
look at one another. My soul was faint, and all of a sudden it was just as\
though he had emptied a pail of dirty water over me. He talked to me like\
a schoolmaster, all so grave and learned; he met me so solemnly that I was\
struck dumb. I couldn\'92t get a word in. At first I thought he was ashamed\
to talk before his great big Pole. I sat staring at him and wondering why\
I couldn\'92t say a word to him now. It must have been his wife that ruined\
him; you know he threw me up to get married. She must have changed him\
like that. Mitya, how shameful it is! Oh, Mitya, I\'92m ashamed, I\'92m ashamed\
for all my life. Curse it, curse it, curse those five years!\'94\
\
And again she burst into tears, but clung tight to Mitya\'92s hand and did\
not let it go.\
\
\'93Mitya, darling, stay, don\'92t go away. I want to say one word to you,\'94 she\
whispered, and suddenly raised her face to him. \'93Listen, tell me who it is\
I love? I love one man here. Who is that man? That\'92s what you must tell\
me.\'94\
\
A smile lighted up her face that was swollen with weeping, and her eyes\
shone in the half darkness.\
\
\'93A falcon flew in, and my heart sank. \'91Fool! that\'92s the man you love!\'92\
That was what my heart whispered to me at once. You came in and all grew\
bright. What\'92s he afraid of? I wondered. For you were frightened; you\
couldn\'92t speak. It\'92s not them he\'92s afraid of\'97could you be frightened of\
any one? It\'92s me he\'92s afraid of, I thought, only me. So Fenya told you,\
you little stupid, how I called to Alyosha out of the window that I\'92d\
loved Mityenka for one hour, and that I was going now to love ... another.\
Mitya, Mitya, how could I be such a fool as to think I could love any one\
after you? Do you forgive me, Mitya? Do you forgive me or not? Do you love\
me? Do you love me?\'94 She jumped up and held him with both hands on his\
shoulders. Mitya, dumb with rapture, gazed into her eyes, at her face, at\
her smile, and suddenly clasped her tightly in his arms and kissed her\
passionately.\
\
\'93You will forgive me for having tormented you? It was through spite I\
tormented you all. It was for spite I drove the old man out of his\
mind.... Do you remember how you drank at my house one day and broke the\
wine\uc0\u8208 glass? I remembered that and I broke a glass to\u8208 day and drank \'91to my\
vile heart.\'92 Mitya, my falcon, why don\'92t you kiss me? He kissed me once,\
and now he draws back and looks and listens. Why listen to me? Kiss me,\
kiss me hard, that\'92s right. If you love, well, then, love! I\'92ll be your\
slave now, your slave for the rest of my life. It\'92s sweet to be a slave.\
Kiss me! Beat me, ill\uc0\u8208 treat me, do what you will with me.... And I do\
deserve to suffer. Stay, wait, afterwards, I won\'92t have that....\'94 she\
suddenly thrust him away. \'93Go along, Mitya, I\'92ll come and have some wine,\
I want to be drunk, I\'92m going to get drunk and dance; I must, I must!\'94 She\
tore herself away from him and disappeared behind the curtain. Mitya\
followed like a drunken man.\
\
\'93Yes, come what may\'97whatever may happen now, for one minute I\'92d give the\
whole world,\'94 he thought. Grushenka did, in fact, toss off a whole glass\
of champagne at one gulp, and became at once very tipsy. She sat down in\
the same chair as before, with a blissful smile on her face. Her cheeks\
were glowing, her lips were burning, her flashing eyes were moist; there\
was passionate appeal in her eyes. Even Kalganov felt a stir at the heart\
and went up to her.\
\
\'93Did you feel how I kissed you when you were asleep just now?\'94 she said\
thickly. \'93I\'92m drunk now, that\'92s what it is.... And aren\'92t you drunk? And\
why isn\'92t Mitya drinking? Why don\'92t you drink, Mitya? I\'92m drunk, and you\
don\'92t drink....\'94\
\
\'93I am drunk! I\'92m drunk as it is ... drunk with you ... and now I\'92ll be\
drunk with wine, too.\'94\
\
He drank off another glass, and\'97he thought it strange himself\'97that glass\
made him completely drunk. He was suddenly drunk, although till that\
moment he had been quite sober, he remembered that. From that moment\
everything whirled about him, as though he were delirious. He walked,\
laughed, talked to everybody, without knowing what he was doing. Only one\
persistent burning sensation made itself felt continually, \'93like a red\uc0\u8208 hot\
coal in his heart,\'94 he said afterwards. He went up to her, sat beside her,\
gazed at her, listened to her.... She became very talkative, kept calling\
every one to her, and beckoned to different girls out of the chorus. When\
the girl came up, she either kissed her, or made the sign of the cross\
over her. In another minute she might have cried. She was greatly amused\
by the \'93little old man,\'94 as she called Maximov. He ran up every minute to\
kiss her hands, \'93each little finger,\'94 and finally he danced another dance\
to an old song, which he sang himself. He danced with special vigor to the\
refrain:\
\
\
    The little pig says\'97umph! umph! umph!\
    The little calf says\'97moo, moo, moo,\
    The little duck says\'97quack, quack, quack,\
    The little goose says\'97ga, ga, ga.\
    The hen goes strutting through the porch;\
    Troo\uc0\u8208 roo\u8208 roo\u8208 roo\u8208 roo, she\'92ll say,\
    Troo\uc0\u8208 roo\u8208 roo\u8208 roo\u8208 roo, she\'92ll say!\
\
\
\'93Give him something, Mitya,\'94 said Grushenka. \'93Give him a present, he\'92s\
poor, you know. Ah, the poor, the insulted!... Do you know, Mitya, I shall\
go into a nunnery. No, I really shall one day, Alyosha said something to\
me to\uc0\u8208 day that I shall remember all my life.... Yes.... But to\u8208 day let us\
dance. To\uc0\u8208 morrow to the nunnery, but to\u8208 day we\'92ll dance. I want to play\
to\uc0\u8208 day, good people, and what of it? God will forgive us. If I were God,\
I\'92d forgive every one: \'91My dear sinners, from this day forth I forgive\
you.\'92 I\'92m going to beg forgiveness: \'91Forgive me, good people, a silly\
wench.\'92 I\'92m a beast, that\'92s what I am. But I want to pray. I gave a little\
onion. Wicked as I\'92ve been, I want to pray. Mitya, let them dance, don\'92t\
stop them. Every one in the world is good. Every one\'97even the worst of\
them. The world\'92s a nice place. Though we\'92re bad the world\'92s all right.\
We\'92re good and bad, good and bad.... Come, tell me, I\'92ve something to ask\
you: come here every one, and I\'92ll ask you: Why am I so good? You know I\
am good. I\'92m very good.... Come, why am I so good?\'94\
\
So Grushenka babbled on, getting more and more drunk. At last she\
announced that she was going to dance, too. She got up from her chair,\
staggering. \'93Mitya, don\'92t give me any more wine\'97if I ask you, don\'92t give\
it to me. Wine doesn\'92t give peace. Everything\'92s going round, the stove,\
and everything. I want to dance. Let every one see how I dance ... let\
them see how beautifully I dance....\'94\
\
She really meant it. She pulled a white cambric handkerchief out of her\
pocket, and took it by one corner in her right hand, to wave it in the\
dance. Mitya ran to and fro, the girls were quiet, and got ready to break\
into a dancing song at the first signal. Maximov, hearing that Grushenka\
wanted to dance, squealed with delight, and ran skipping about in front of\
her, humming:\
\
\
    With legs so slim and sides so trim\
    And its little tail curled tight.\
\
\
But Grushenka waved her handkerchief at him and drove him away.\
\
\'93Sh\uc0\u8208 h! Mitya, why don\'92t they come? Let every one come ... to look on. Call\
them in, too, that were locked in.... Why did you lock them in? Tell them\
I\'92m going to dance. Let them look on, too....\'94\
\
Mitya walked with a drunken swagger to the locked door, and began knocking\
to the Poles with his fist.\
\
\'93Hi, you ... Podvysotskys! Come, she\'92s going to dance. She calls you.\'94\
\
\'93_Lajdak!_\'94 one of the Poles shouted in reply.\
\
\'93You\'92re a _lajdak_ yourself! You\'92re a little scoundrel, that\'92s what you\
are.\'94\
\
\'93Leave off laughing at Poland,\'94 said Kalganov sententiously. He too was\
drunk.\
\
\'93Be quiet, boy! If I call him a scoundrel, it doesn\'92t mean that I called\
all Poland so. One _lajdak_ doesn\'92t make a Poland. Be quiet, my pretty\
boy, eat a sweetmeat.\'94\
\
\'93Ach, what fellows! As though they were not men. Why won\'92t they make\
friends?\'94 said Grushenka, and went forward to dance. The chorus broke into\
\'93Ah, my porch, my new porch!\'94 Grushenka flung back her head, half opened\
her lips, smiled, waved her handkerchief, and suddenly, with a violent\
lurch, stood still in the middle of the room, looking bewildered.\
\
\'93I\'92m weak....\'94 she said in an exhausted voice. \'93Forgive me.... I\'92m weak, I\
can\'92t.... I\'92m sorry.\'94\
\
She bowed to the chorus, and then began bowing in all directions.\
\
\'93I\'92m sorry.... Forgive me....\'94\
\
\'93The lady\'92s been drinking. The pretty lady has been drinking,\'94 voices were\
heard saying.\
\
\'93The lady\'92s drunk too much,\'94 Maximov explained to the girls, giggling.\
\
\'93Mitya, lead me away ... take me,\'94 said Grushenka helplessly. Mitya\
pounced on her, snatched her up in his arms, and carried the precious\
burden through the curtains.\
\
\'93Well, now I\'92ll go,\'94 thought Kalganov, and walking out of the blue room,\
he closed the two halves of the door after him. But the orgy in the larger\
room went on and grew louder and louder. Mitya laid Grushenka on the bed\
and kissed her on the lips.\
\
\'93Don\'92t touch me....\'94 she faltered, in an imploring voice. \'93Don\'92t touch me,\
till I\'92m yours.... I\'92ve told you I\'92m yours, but don\'92t touch me ... spare\
me.... With them here, with them close, you mustn\'92t. He\'92s here. It\'92s nasty\
here....\'94\
\
\'93I\'92ll obey you! I won\'92t think of it ... I worship you!\'94 muttered Mitya.\
\'93Yes, it\'92s nasty here, it\'92s abominable.\'94\
\
And still holding her in his arms, he sank on his knees by the bedside.\
\
\'93I know, though you\'92re a brute, you\'92re generous,\'94 Grushenka articulated\
with difficulty. \'93It must be honorable ... it shall be honorable for the\
future ... and let us be honest, let us be good, not brutes, but good ...\
take me away, take me far away, do you hear? I don\'92t want it to be here,\
but far, far away....\'94\
\
\'93Oh, yes, yes, it must be!\'94 said Mitya, pressing her in his arms. \'93I\'92ll\
take you and we\'92ll fly away.... Oh, I\'92d give my whole life for one year\
only to know about that blood!\'94\
\
\'93What blood?\'94 asked Grushenka, bewildered.\
\
\'93Nothing,\'94 muttered Mitya, through his teeth. \'93Grusha, you wanted to be\
honest, but I\'92m a thief. But I\'92ve stolen money from Katya.... Disgrace, a\
disgrace!\'94\
\
\'93From Katya, from that young lady? No, you didn\'92t steal it. Give it her\
back, take it from me.... Why make a fuss? Now everything of mine is\
yours. What does money matter? We shall waste it anyway.... Folks like us\
are bound to waste money. But we\'92d better go and work the land. I want to\
dig the earth with my own hands. We must work, do you hear? Alyosha said\
so. I won\'92t be your mistress, I\'92ll be faithful to you, I\'92ll be your slave,\
I\'92ll work for you. We\'92ll go to the young lady and bow down to her\
together, so that she may forgive us, and then we\'92ll go away. And if she\
won\'92t forgive us, we\'92ll go, anyway. Take her her money and love me....\
Don\'92t love her.... Don\'92t love her any more. If you love her, I shall\
strangle her.... I\'92ll put out both her eyes with a needle....\'94\
\
\'93I love you. I love only you. I\'92ll love you in Siberia....\'94\
\
\'93Why Siberia? Never mind, Siberia, if you like. I don\'92t care ... we\'92ll\
work ... there\'92s snow in Siberia.... I love driving in the snow ... and\
must have bells.... Do you hear, there\'92s a bell ringing? Where is that\
bell ringing? There are people coming.... Now it\'92s stopped.\'94\
\
She closed her eyes, exhausted, and suddenly fell asleep for an instant.\
There had certainly been the sound of a bell in the distance, but the\
ringing had ceased. Mitya let his head sink on her breast. He did not\
notice that the bell had ceased ringing, nor did he notice that the songs\
had ceased, and that instead of singing and drunken clamor there was\
absolute stillness in the house. Grushenka opened her eyes.\
\
\'93What\'92s the matter? Was I asleep? Yes ... a bell ... I\'92ve been asleep and\
dreamt I was driving over the snow with bells, and I dozed. I was with\
some one I loved, with you. And far, far away. I was holding you and\
kissing you, nestling close to you. I was cold, and the snow glistened....\
You know how the snow glistens at night when the moon shines. It was as\
though I was not on earth. I woke up, and my dear one is close to me. How\
sweet that is!...\'94\
\
\'93Close to you,\'94 murmured Mitya, kissing her dress, her bosom, her hands.\
And suddenly he had a strange fancy: it seemed to him that she was looking\
straight before her, not at him, not into his face, but over his head,\
with an intent, almost uncanny fixity. An expression of wonder, almost of\
alarm, came suddenly into her face.\
\
\'93Mitya, who is that looking at us?\'94 she whispered.\
\
Mitya turned, and saw that some one had, in fact, parted the curtains and\
seemed to be watching them. And not one person alone, it seemed.\
\
He jumped up and walked quickly to the intruder.\
\
\'93Here, come to us, come here,\'94 said a voice, speaking not loudly, but\
firmly and peremptorily.\
\
Mitya passed to the other side of the curtain and stood stock still. The\
room was filled with people, but not those who had been there before. An\
instantaneous shiver ran down his back, and he shuddered. He recognized\
all those people instantly. That tall, stout old man in the overcoat and\
forage\uc0\u8208 cap with a cockade\'97was the police captain, Mihail Makarovitch. And\
that \'93consumptive\uc0\u8208 looking\'94 trim dandy, \'93who always has such polished\
boots\'94\'97that was the deputy prosecutor. \'93He has a chronometer worth four\
hundred roubles; he showed it to me.\'94 And that small young man in\
spectacles.... Mitya forgot his surname though he knew him, had seen him:\
he was the \'93investigating lawyer,\'94 from the \'93school of jurisprudence,\'94 who\
had only lately come to the town. And this man\'97the inspector of police,\
Mavriky Mavrikyevitch, a man he knew well. And those fellows with the\
brass plates on, why are they here? And those other two ... peasants....\
And there at the door Kalganov with Trifon Borissovitch....\
\
\'93Gentlemen! What\'92s this for, gentlemen?\'94 began Mitya, but suddenly, as\
though beside himself, not knowing what he was doing, he cried aloud, at\
the top of his voice:\
\
\'93I un\'97der\'97stand!\'94\
\
The young man in spectacles moved forward suddenly, and stepping up to\
Mitya, began with dignity, though hurriedly:\
\
\'93We have to make ... in brief, I beg you to come this way, this way to the\
sofa.... It is absolutely imperative that you should give an explanation.\'94\
\
\'93The old man!\'94 cried Mitya frantically. \'93The old man and his blood!... I\
understand.\'94\
\
And he sank, almost fell, on a chair close by, as though he had been mown\
down by a scythe.\
\
\'93You understand? He understands it! Monster and parricide! Your father\'92s\
blood cries out against you!\'94 the old captain of police roared suddenly,\
stepping up to Mitya.\
\
He was beside himself, crimson in the face and quivering all over.\
\
\'93This is impossible!\'94 cried the small young man. \'93Mihail Makarovitch,\
Mihail Makarovitch, this won\'92t do!... I beg you\'92ll allow me to speak. I\
should never have expected such behavior from you....\'94\
\
\'93This is delirium, gentlemen, raving delirium,\'94 cried the captain of\
police; \'93look at him: drunk, at this time of night, in the company of a\
disreputable woman, with the blood of his father on his hands.... It\'92s\
delirium!...\'94\
\
\'93I beg you most earnestly, dear Mihail Makarovitch, to restrain your\
feelings,\'94 the prosecutor said in a rapid whisper to the old police\
captain, \'93or I shall be forced to resort to\'97\'94\
\
But the little lawyer did not allow him to finish. He turned to Mitya, and\
delivered himself in a loud, firm, dignified voice:\
\
\'93Ex\uc0\u8208 Lieutenant Karamazov, it is my duty to inform you that you are charged\
with the murder of your father, Fyodor Pavlovitch Karamazov, perpetrated\
this night....\'94\
\
He said something more, and the prosecutor, too, put in something, but\
though Mitya heard them he did not understand them. He stared at them all\
with wild eyes.\
\
\
\
\
Book IX. The Preliminary Investigation\
\
\
\
Chapter I. The Beginning Of Perhotin\'92s Official Career\
\
\
Pyotr Ilyitch Perhotin, whom we left knocking at the strong locked gates\
of the widow Morozov\'92s house, ended, of course, by making himself heard.\
Fenya, who was still excited by the fright she had had two hours before,\
and too much \'93upset\'94 to go to bed, was almost frightened into hysterics on\
hearing the furious knocking at the gate. Though she had herself seen him\
drive away, she fancied that it must be Dmitri Fyodorovitch knocking\
again, no one else could knock so savagely. She ran to the house\uc0\u8208 porter,\
who had already waked up and gone out to the gate, and began imploring him\
not to open it. But having questioned Pyotr Ilyitch, and learned that he\
wanted to see Fenya on very \'93important business,\'94 the man made up his mind\
at last to open. Pyotr Ilyitch was admitted into Fenya\'92s kitchen, but the\
girl begged him to allow the house\uc0\u8208 porter to be present, \'93because of her\
misgivings.\'94 He began questioning her and at once learnt the most vital\
fact, that is, that when Dmitri Fyodorovitch had run out to look for\
Grushenka, he had snatched up a pestle from the mortar, and that when he\
returned, the pestle was not with him and his hands were smeared with\
blood.\
\
\'93And the blood was simply flowing, dripping from him, dripping!\'94 Fenya\
kept exclaiming. This horrible detail was simply the product of her\
disordered imagination. But although not \'93dripping,\'94 Pyotr Ilyitch had\
himself seen those hands stained with blood, and had helped to wash them.\
Moreover, the question he had to decide was not how soon the blood had\
dried, but where Dmitri Fyodorovitch had run with the pestle, or rather,\
whether it really was to Fyodor Pavlovitch\'92s, and how he could\
satisfactorily ascertain. Pyotr Ilyitch persisted in returning to this\
point, and though he found out nothing conclusive, yet he carried away a\
conviction that Dmitri Fyodorovitch could have gone nowhere but to his\
father\'92s house, and that therefore something must have happened there.\
\
\'93And when he came back,\'94 Fenya added with excitement, \'93I told him the\
whole story, and then I began asking him, \'91Why have you got blood on your\
hands, Dmitri Fyodorovitch?\'92 and he answered that that was human blood,\
and that he had just killed some one. He confessed it all to me, and\
suddenly ran off like a madman. I sat down and began thinking, where\'92s he\
run off to now like a madman? He\'92ll go to Mokroe, I thought, and kill my\
mistress there. I ran out to beg him not to kill her. I was running to his\
lodgings, but I looked at Plotnikov\'92s shop, and saw him just setting off,\
and there was no blood on his hands then.\'94 (Fenya had noticed this and\
remembered it.) Fenya\'92s old grandmother confirmed her evidence as far as\
she was capable. After asking some further questions, Pyotr Ilyitch left\
the house, even more upset and uneasy than he had been when he entered it.\
\
The most direct and the easiest thing for him to do would have been to go\
straight to Fyodor Pavlovitch\'92s, to find out whether anything had happened\
there, and if so, what; and only to go to the police captain, as Pyotr\
Ilyitch firmly intended doing, when he had satisfied himself of the fact.\
But the night was dark, Fyodor Pavlovitch\'92s gates were strong, and he\
would have to knock again. His acquaintance with Fyodor Pavlovitch was of\
the slightest, and what if, after he had been knocking, they opened to\
him, and nothing had happened? Then Fyodor Pavlovitch in his jeering way\
would go telling the story all over the town, how a stranger, called\
Perhotin, had broken in upon him at midnight to ask if any one had killed\
him. It would make a scandal. And scandal was what Pyotr Ilyitch dreaded\
more than anything in the world.\
\
Yet the feeling that possessed him was so strong, that though he stamped\
his foot angrily and swore at himself, he set off again, not to Fyodor\
Pavlovitch\'92s but to Madame Hohlakov\'92s. He decided that if she denied\
having just given Dmitri Fyodorovitch three thousand roubles, he would go\
straight to the police captain, but if she admitted having given him the\
money, he would go home and let the matter rest till next morning.\
\
It is, of course, perfectly evident that there was even more likelihood of\
causing scandal by going at eleven o\'92clock at night to a fashionable lady,\
a complete stranger, and perhaps rousing her from her bed to ask her an\
amazing question, than by going to Fyodor Pavlovitch. But that is just how\
it is, sometimes, especially in cases like the present one, with the\
decisions of the most precise and phlegmatic people. Pyotr Ilyitch was by\
no means phlegmatic at that moment. He remembered all his life how a\
haunting uneasiness gradually gained possession of him, growing more and\
more painful and driving him on, against his will. Yet he kept cursing\
himself, of course, all the way for going to this lady, but \'93I will get to\
the bottom of it, I will!\'94 he repeated for the tenth time, grinding his\
teeth, and he carried out his intention.\
\
It was exactly eleven o\'92clock when he entered Madame Hohlakov\'92s house. He\
was admitted into the yard pretty quickly, but, in response to his inquiry\
whether the lady was still up, the porter could give no answer, except\
that she was usually in bed by that time.\
\
\'93Ask at the top of the stairs. If the lady wants to receive you, she\'92ll\
receive you. If she won\'92t, she won\'92t.\'94\
\
Pyotr Ilyitch went up, but did not find things so easy here. The footman\
was unwilling to take in his name, but finally called a maid. Pyotr\
Ilyitch politely but insistently begged her to inform her lady that an\
official, living in the town, called Perhotin, had called on particular\
business, and that if it were not of the greatest importance he would not\
have ventured to come. \'93Tell her in those words, in those words exactly,\'94\
he asked the girl.\
\
She went away. He remained waiting in the entry. Madame Hohlakov herself\
was already in her bedroom, though not yet asleep. She had felt upset ever\
since Mitya\'92s visit, and had a presentiment that she would not get through\
the night without the sick headache which always, with her, followed such\
excitement. She was surprised on hearing the announcement from the maid.\
She irritably declined to see him, however, though the unexpected visit at\
such an hour, of an \'93official living in the town,\'94 who was a total\
stranger, roused her feminine curiosity intensely. But this time Pyotr\
Ilyitch was as obstinate as a mule. He begged the maid most earnestly to\
take another message in these very words:\
\
\'93That he had come on business of the greatest importance, and that Madame\
Hohlakov might have cause to regret it later, if she refused to see him\
now.\'94\
\
\'93I plunged headlong,\'94 he described it afterwards.\
\
The maid, gazing at him in amazement, went to take his message again.\
Madame Hohlakov was impressed. She thought a little, asked what he looked\
like, and learned that he was \'93very well dressed, young and so polite.\'94 We\
may note, parenthetically, that Pyotr Ilyitch was a rather good\uc0\u8208 looking\
young man, and well aware of the fact. Madame Hohlakov made up her mind to\
see him. She was in her dressing\uc0\u8208 gown and slippers, but she flung a black\
shawl over her shoulders. \'93The official\'94 was asked to walk into the\
drawing\uc0\u8208 room, the very room in which Mitya had been received shortly\
before. The lady came to meet her visitor, with a sternly inquiring\
countenance, and, without asking him to sit down, began at once with the\
question:\
\
\'93What do you want?\'94\
\
\'93I have ventured to disturb you, madam, on a matter concerning our common\
acquaintance, Dmitri Fyodorovitch Karamazov,\'94 Perhotin began.\
\
But he had hardly uttered the name, when the lady\'92s face showed signs of\
acute irritation. She almost shrieked, and interrupted him in a fury:\
\
\'93How much longer am I to be worried by that awful man?\'94 she cried\
hysterically. \'93How dare you, sir, how could you venture to disturb a lady\
who is a stranger to you, in her own house at such an hour!... And to\
force yourself upon her to talk of a man who came here, to this very\
drawing\uc0\u8208 room, only three hours ago, to murder me, and went stamping out of\
the room, as no one would go out of a decent house. Let me tell you, sir,\
that I shall lodge a complaint against you, that I will not let it pass.\
Kindly leave me at once.... I am a mother.... I ... I\'97\'94\
\
\'93Murder! then he tried to murder you, too?\'94\
\
\'93Why, has he killed somebody else?\'94 Madame Hohlakov asked impulsively.\
\
\'93If you would kindly listen, madam, for half a moment, I\'92ll explain it all\
in a couple of words,\'94 answered Perhotin, firmly. \'93At five o\'92clock this\
afternoon Dmitri Fyodorovitch borrowed ten roubles from me, and I know for\
a fact he had no money. Yet at nine o\'92clock, he came to see me with a\
bundle of hundred\uc0\u8208 rouble notes in his hand, about two or three thousand\
roubles. His hands and face were all covered with blood, and he looked\
like a madman. When I asked him where he had got so much money, he\
answered that he had just received it from you, that you had given him a\
sum of three thousand to go to the gold\uc0\u8208 mines....\'94\
\
Madame Hohlakov\'92s face assumed an expression of intense and painful\
excitement.\
\
\'93Good God! He must have killed his old father!\'94 she cried, clasping her\
hands. \'93I have never given him money, never! Oh, run, run!... Don\'92t say\
another word! Save the old man ... run to his father ... run!\'94\
\
\'93Excuse me, madam, then you did not give him money? You remember for a\
fact that you did not give him any money?\'94\
\
\'93No, I didn\'92t, I didn\'92t! I refused to give it him, for he could not\
appreciate it. He ran out in a fury, stamping. He rushed at me, but I\
slipped away.... And let me tell you, as I wish to hide nothing from you\
now, that he positively spat at me. Can you fancy that! But why are we\
standing? Ah, sit down.\'94\
\
\'93Excuse me, I....\'94\
\
\'93Or better run, run, you must run and save the poor old man from an awful\
death!\'94\
\
\'93But if he has killed him already?\'94\
\
\'93Ah, good heavens, yes! Then what are we to do now? What do you think we\
must do now?\'94\
\
Meantime she had made Pyotr Ilyitch sit down and sat down herself, facing\
him. Briefly, but fairly clearly, Pyotr Ilyitch told her the history of\
the affair, that part of it at least which he had himself witnessed. He\
described, too, his visit to Fenya, and told her about the pestle. All\
these details produced an overwhelming effect on the distracted lady, who\
kept uttering shrieks, and covering her face with her hands....\
\
\'93Would you believe it, I foresaw all this! I have that special faculty,\
whatever I imagine comes to pass. And how often I\'92ve looked at that awful\
man and always thought, that man will end by murdering me. And now it\'92s\
happened ... that is, if he hasn\'92t murdered me, but only his own father,\
it\'92s only because the finger of God preserved me, and what\'92s more, he was\
ashamed to murder me because, in this very place, I put the holy ikon from\
the relics of the holy martyr, Saint Varvara, on his neck.... And to think\
how near I was to death at that minute, I went close up to him and he\
stretched out his neck to me!... Do you know, Pyotr Ilyitch (I think you\
said your name was Pyotr Ilyitch), I don\'92t believe in miracles, but that\
ikon and this unmistakable miracle with me now\'97that shakes me, and I\'92m\
ready to believe in anything you like. Have you heard about Father\
Zossima?... But I don\'92t know what I\'92m saying ... and only fancy, with the\
ikon on his neck he spat at me.... He only spat, it\'92s true, he didn\'92t\
murder me and ... he dashed away! But what shall we do, what must we do\
now? What do you think?\'94\
\
Pyotr Ilyitch got up, and announced that he was going straight to the\
police captain, to tell him all about it, and leave him to do what he\
thought fit.\
\
\'93Oh, he\'92s an excellent man, excellent! Mihail Makarovitch, I know him. Of\
course, he\'92s the person to go to. How practical you are, Pyotr Ilyitch!\
How well you\'92ve thought of everything! I should never have thought of it\
in your place!\'94\
\
\'93Especially as I know the police captain very well, too,\'94 observed Pyotr\
Ilyitch, who still continued to stand, and was obviously anxious to escape\
as quickly as possible from the impulsive lady, who would not let him say\
good\uc0\u8208 by and go away.\
\
\'93And be sure, be sure,\'94 she prattled on, \'93to come back and tell me what\
you see there, and what you find out ... what comes to light ... how\
they\'92ll try him ... and what he\'92s condemned to.... Tell me, we have no\
capital punishment, have we? But be sure to come, even if it\'92s at three\
o\'92clock at night, at four, at half\uc0\u8208 past four.... Tell them to wake me, to\
wake me, to shake me, if I don\'92t get up.... But, good heavens, I shan\'92t\
sleep! But wait, hadn\'92t I better come with you?\'94\
\
\'93N\'97no. But if you would write three lines with your own hand, stating that\
you did not give Dmitri Fyodorovitch money, it might, perhaps, be of use\
... in case it\'92s needed....\'94\
\
\'93To be sure!\'94 Madame Hohlakov skipped, delighted, to her bureau. \'93And you\
know I\'92m simply struck, amazed at your resourcefulness, your good sense in\
such affairs. Are you in the service here? I\'92m delighted to think that\
you\'92re in the service here!\'94\
\
And still speaking, she scribbled on half a sheet of notepaper the\
following lines:\
\
\
    I\'92ve never in my life lent to that unhappy man, Dmitri\
    Fyodorovitch Karamazov (for, in spite of all, he is unhappy),\
    three thousand roubles to\uc0\u8208 day. I\'92ve never given him money, never:\
    That I swear by all that\'92s holy!\
\
    K. HOHLAKOV.\
\
\
\'93Here\'92s the note!\'94 she turned quickly to Pyotr Ilyitch. \'93Go, save him.\
It\'92s a noble deed on your part!\'94\
\
And she made the sign of the cross three times over him. She ran out to\
accompany him to the passage.\
\
\'93How grateful I am to you! You can\'92t think how grateful I am to you for\
having come to me, first. How is it I haven\'92t met you before? I shall feel\
flattered at seeing you at my house in the future. How delightful it is\
that you are living here!... Such precision! Such practical ability!...\
They must appreciate you, they must understand you. If there\'92s anything I\
can do, believe me ... oh, I love young people! I\'92m in love with young\
people! The younger generation are the one prop of our suffering country.\
Her one hope.... Oh, go, go!...\'94\
\
But Pyotr Ilyitch had already run away or she would not have let him go so\
soon. Yet Madame Hohlakov had made a rather agreeable impression on him,\
which had somewhat softened his anxiety at being drawn into such an\
unpleasant affair. Tastes differ, as we all know. \'93She\'92s by no means so\
elderly,\'94 he thought, feeling pleased, \'93on the contrary I should have\
taken her for her daughter.\'94\
\
As for Madame Hohlakov, she was simply enchanted by the young man. \'93Such\
sense! such exactness! in so young a man! in our day! and all that with\
such manners and appearance! People say the young people of to\uc0\u8208 day are no\
good for anything, but here\'92s an example!\'94 etc. So she simply forgot this\
\'93dreadful affair,\'94 and it was only as she was getting into bed, that,\
suddenly recalling \'93how near death she had been,\'94 she exclaimed: \'93Ah, it\
is awful, awful!\'94\
\
But she fell at once into a sound, sweet sleep.\
\
I would not, however, have dwelt on such trivial and irrelevant details,\
if this eccentric meeting of the young official with the by no means\
elderly widow had not subsequently turned out to be the foundation of the\
whole career of that practical and precise young man. His story is\
remembered to this day with amazement in our town, and I shall perhaps\
have something to say about it, when I have finished my long history of\
the Brothers Karamazov.\
\
\
\
Chapter II. The Alarm\
\
\
Our police captain, Mihail Makarovitch Makarov, a retired lieutenant\uc0\u8208 \
colonel, was a widower and an excellent man. He had only come to us three\
years previously, but had won general esteem, chiefly because he \'93knew how\
to keep society together.\'94 He was never without visitors, and could not\
have got on without them. Some one or other was always dining with him; he\
never sat down to table without guests. He gave regular dinners, too, on\
all sorts of occasions, sometimes most surprising ones. Though the fare\
was not _recherch\'e9_, it was abundant. The fish\uc0\u8208 pies were excellent, and\
the wine made up in quantity for what it lacked in quality.\
\
The first room his guests entered was a well\uc0\u8208 fitted billiard\u8208 room, with\
pictures of English race\uc0\u8208 horses, in black frames on the walls, an\
essential decoration, as we all know, for a bachelor\'92s billiard\uc0\u8208 room.\
There was card\uc0\u8208 playing every evening at his house, if only at one table.\
But at frequent intervals, all the society of our town, with the mammas\
and young ladies, assembled at his house to dance. Though Mihail\
Makarovitch was a widower, he did not live alone. His widowed daughter\
lived with him, with her two unmarried daughters, grown\uc0\u8208 up girls, who had\
finished their education. They were of agreeable appearance and lively\
character, and though every one knew they would have no dowry, they\
attracted all the young men of fashion to their grandfather\'92s house.\
\
Mihail Makarovitch was by no means very efficient in his work, though he\
performed his duties no worse than many others. To speak plainly, he was a\
man of rather narrow education. His understanding of the limits of his\
administrative power could not always be relied upon. It was not so much\
that he failed to grasp certain reforms enacted during the present reign,\
as that he made conspicuous blunders in his interpretation of them. This\
was not from any special lack of intelligence, but from carelessness, for\
he was always in too great a hurry to go into the subject.\
\
\'93I have the heart of a soldier rather than of a civilian,\'94 he used to say\
of himself. He had not even formed a definite idea of the fundamental\
principles of the reforms connected with the emancipation of the serfs,\
and only picked it up, so to speak, from year to year, involuntarily\
increasing his knowledge by practice. And yet he was himself a landowner.\
Pyotr Ilyitch knew for certain that he would meet some of Mihail\
Makarovitch\'92s visitors there that evening, but he didn\'92t know which. As it\
happened, at that moment the prosecutor, and Varvinsky, our district\
doctor, a young man, who had only just come to us from Petersburg after\
taking a brilliant degree at the Academy of Medicine, were playing whist\
at the police captain\'92s. Ippolit Kirillovitch, the prosecutor (he was\
really the deputy prosecutor, but we always called him the prosecutor),\
was rather a peculiar man, of about five and thirty, inclined to be\
consumptive, and married to a fat and childless woman. He was vain and\
irritable, though he had a good intellect, and even a kind heart. It\
seemed that all that was wrong with him was that he had a better opinion\
of himself than his ability warranted. And that made him seem constantly\
uneasy. He had, moreover, certain higher, even artistic, leanings, towards\
psychology, for instance, a special study of the human heart, a special\
knowledge of the criminal and his crime. He cherished a grievance on this\
ground, considering that he had been passed over in the service, and being\
firmly persuaded that in higher spheres he had not been properly\
appreciated, and had enemies. In gloomy moments he even threatened to give\
up his post, and practice as a barrister in criminal cases. The unexpected\
Karamazov case agitated him profoundly: \'93It was a case that might well be\
talked about all over Russia.\'94 But I am anticipating.\
\
Nikolay Parfenovitch Nelyudov, the young investigating lawyer, who had\
only come from Petersburg two months before, was sitting in the next room\
with the young ladies. People talked about it afterwards and wondered that\
all the gentlemen should, as though intentionally, on the evening of \'93the\
crime\'94 have been gathered together at the house of the executive\
authority. Yet it was perfectly simple and happened quite naturally.\
\
Ippolit Kirillovitch\'92s wife had had toothache for the last two days, and\
he was obliged to go out to escape from her groans. The doctor, from the\
very nature of his being, could not spend an evening except at cards.\
Nikolay Parfenovitch Nelyudov had been intending for three days past to\
drop in that evening at Mihail Makarovitch\'92s, so to speak casually, so as\
slyly to startle the eldest granddaughter, Olga Mihailovna, by showing\
that he knew her secret, that he knew it was her birthday, and that she\
was trying to conceal it on purpose, so as not to be obliged to give a\
dance. He anticipated a great deal of merriment, many playful jests about\
her age, and her being afraid to reveal it, about his knowing her secret\
and telling everybody, and so on. The charming young man was a great adept\
at such teasing; the ladies had christened him \'93the naughty man,\'94 and he\
seemed to be delighted at the name. He was extremely well\uc0\u8208 bred, however,\
of good family, education and feelings, and, though leading a life of\
pleasure, his sallies were always innocent and in good taste. He was\
short, and delicate\uc0\u8208 looking. On his white, slender, little fingers he\
always wore a number of big, glittering rings. When he was engaged in his\
official duties, he always became extraordinarily grave, as though\
realizing his position and the sanctity of the obligations laid upon him.\
He had a special gift for mystifying murderers and other criminals of the\
peasant class during interrogation, and if he did not win their respect,\
he certainly succeeded in arousing their wonder.\
\
Pyotr Ilyitch was simply dumbfounded when he went into the police\
captain\'92s. He saw instantly that every one knew. They had positively\
thrown down their cards, all were standing up and talking. Even Nikolay\
Parfenovitch had left the young ladies and run in, looking strenuous and\
ready for action. Pyotr Ilyitch was met with the astounding news that old\
Fyodor Pavlovitch really had been murdered that evening in his own house,\
murdered and robbed. The news had only just reached them in the following\
manner.\
\
Marfa Ignatyevna, the wife of old Grigory, who had been knocked senseless\
near the fence, was sleeping soundly in her bed and might well have slept\
till morning after the draught she had taken. But, all of a sudden she\
waked up, no doubt roused by a fearful epileptic scream from Smerdyakov,\
who was lying in the next room unconscious. That scream always preceded\
his fits, and always terrified and upset Marfa Ignatyevna. She could never\
get accustomed to it. She jumped up and ran half\uc0\u8208 awake to Smerdyakov\'92s\
room. But it was dark there, and she could only hear the invalid beginning\
to gasp and struggle. Then Marfa Ignatyevna herself screamed out and was\
going to call her husband, but suddenly realized that when she had got up,\
he was not beside her in bed. She ran back to the bedstead and began\
groping with her hands, but the bed was really empty. Then he must have\
gone out\'97where? She ran to the steps and timidly called him. She got no\
answer, of course, but she caught the sound of groans far away in the\
garden in the darkness. She listened. The groans were repeated, and it was\
evident they came from the garden.\
\
\'93Good Lord! Just as it was with Lizaveta Smerdyastchaya!\'94 she thought\
distractedly. She went timidly down the steps and saw that the gate into\
the garden was open.\
\
\'93He must be out there, poor dear,\'94 she thought. She went up to the gate\
and all at once she distinctly heard Grigory calling her by name, \'93Marfa!\
Marfa!\'94 in a weak, moaning, dreadful voice.\
\
\'93Lord, preserve us from harm!\'94 Marfa Ignatyevna murmured, and ran towards\
the voice, and that was how she found Grigory. But she found him not by\
the fence where he had been knocked down, but about twenty paces off. It\
appeared later, that he had crawled away on coming to himself, and\
probably had been a long time getting so far, losing consciousness several\
times. She noticed at once that he was covered with blood, and screamed at\
the top of her voice. Grigory was muttering incoherently:\
\
\'93He has murdered ... his father murdered.... Why scream, silly ... run ...\
fetch some one....\'94\
\
But Marfa continued screaming, and seeing that her master\'92s window was\
open and that there was a candle alight in the window, she ran there and\
began calling Fyodor Pavlovitch. But peeping in at the window, she saw a\
fearful sight. Her master was lying on his back, motionless, on the floor.\
His light\uc0\u8208 colored dressing\u8208 gown and white shirt were soaked with blood.\
The candle on the table brightly lighted up the blood and the motionless\
dead face of Fyodor Pavlovitch. Terror\uc0\u8208 stricken, Marfa rushed away from\
the window, ran out of the garden, drew the bolt of the big gate and ran\
headlong by the back way to the neighbor, Marya Kondratyevna. Both mother\
and daughter were asleep, but they waked up at Marfa\'92s desperate and\
persistent screaming and knocking at the shutter. Marfa, shrieking and\
screaming incoherently, managed to tell them the main fact, and to beg for\
assistance. It happened that Foma had come back from his wanderings and\
was staying the night with them. They got him up immediately and all three\
ran to the scene of the crime. On the way, Marya Kondratyevna remembered\
that at about eight o\'92clock she heard a dreadful scream from their garden,\
and this was no doubt Grigory\'92s scream, \'93Parricide!\'94 uttered when he\
caught hold of Mitya\'92s leg.\
\
\'93Some one person screamed out and then was silent,\'94 Marya Kondratyevna\
explained as she ran. Running to the place where Grigory lay, the two\
women with the help of Foma carried him to the lodge. They lighted a\
candle and saw that Smerdyakov was no better, that he was writhing in\
convulsions, his eyes fixed in a squint, and that foam was flowing from\
his lips. They moistened Grigory\'92s forehead with water mixed with vinegar,\
and the water revived him at once. He asked immediately:\
\
\'93Is the master murdered?\'94\
\
Then Foma and both the women ran to the house and saw this time that not\
only the window, but also the door into the garden was wide open, though\
Fyodor Pavlovitch had for the last week locked himself in every night and\
did not allow even Grigory to come in on any pretext. Seeing that door\
open, they were afraid to go in to Fyodor Pavlovitch \'93for fear anything\
should happen afterwards.\'94 And when they returned to Grigory, the old man\
told them to go straight to the police captain. Marya Kondratyevna ran\
there and gave the alarm to the whole party at the police captain\'92s. She\
arrived only five minutes before Pyotr Ilyitch, so that his story came,\
not as his own surmise and theory, but as the direct confirmation, by a\
witness, of the theory held by all, as to the identity of the criminal (a\
theory he had in the bottom of his heart refused to believe till that\
moment).\
\
It was resolved to act with energy. The deputy police inspector of the\
town was commissioned to take four witnesses, to enter Fyodor Pavlovitch\'92s\
house and there to open an inquiry on the spot, according to the regular\
forms, which I will not go into here. The district doctor, a zealous man,\
new to his work, almost insisted on accompanying the police captain, the\
prosecutor, and the investigating lawyer.\
\
I will note briefly that Fyodor Pavlovitch was found to be quite dead,\
with his skull battered in. But with what? Most likely with the same\
weapon with which Grigory had been attacked. And immediately that weapon\
was found, Grigory, to whom all possible medical assistance was at once\
given, described in a weak and breaking voice how he had been knocked\
down. They began looking with a lantern by the fence and found the brass\
pestle dropped in a most conspicuous place on the garden path. There were\
no signs of disturbance in the room where Fyodor Pavlovitch was lying. But\
by the bed, behind the screen, they picked up from the floor a big and\
thick envelope with the inscription: \'93A present of three thousand roubles\
for my angel Grushenka, if she is willing to come.\'94 And below had been\
added by Fyodor Pavlovitch, \'93For my little chicken.\'94 There were three\
seals of red sealing\uc0\u8208 wax on the envelope, but it had been torn open and\
was empty: the money had been removed. They found also on the floor a\
piece of narrow pink ribbon, with which the envelope had been tied up.\
\
One piece of Pyotr Ilyitch\'92s evidence made a great impression on the\
prosecutor and the investigating magistrate, namely, his idea that Dmitri\
Fyodorovitch would shoot himself before daybreak, that he had resolved to\
do so, had spoken of it to Ilyitch, had taken the pistols, loaded them\
before him, written a letter, put it in his pocket, etc. When Pyotr\
Ilyitch, though still unwilling to believe in it, threatened to tell some\
one so as to prevent the suicide, Mitya had answered grinning: \'93You\'92ll be\
too late.\'94 So they must make haste to Mokroe to find the criminal, before\
he really did shoot himself.\
\
\'93That\'92s clear, that\'92s clear!\'94 repeated the prosecutor in great excitement.\
\'93That\'92s just the way with mad fellows like that: \'91I shall kill myself to\uc0\u8208 \
morrow, so I\'92ll make merry till I die!\'92 \'94\
\
The story of how he had bought the wine and provisions excited the\
prosecutor more than ever.\
\
\'93Do you remember the fellow that murdered a merchant called Olsufyev,\
gentlemen? He stole fifteen hundred, went at once to have his hair curled,\
and then, without even hiding the money, carrying it almost in his hand in\
the same way, he went off to the girls.\'94\
\
All were delayed, however, by the inquiry, the search, and the\
formalities, etc., in the house of Fyodor Pavlovitch. It all took time and\
so, two hours before starting, they sent on ahead to Mokroe the officer of\
the rural police, Mavriky Mavrikyevitch Schmertsov, who had arrived in the\
town the morning before to get his pay. He was instructed to avoid raising\
the alarm when he reached Mokroe, but to keep constant watch over the\
\'93criminal\'94 till the arrival of the proper authorities, to procure also\
witnesses for the arrest, police constables, and so on. Mavriky\
Mavrikyevitch did as he was told, preserving his incognito, and giving no\
one but his old acquaintance, Trifon Borissovitch, the slightest hint of\
his secret business. He had spoken to him just before Mitya met the\
