stopped him, and opening the big portfolio that lay on the sofa beside him\
he brought out the brass pestle.\
\
\'93Do you recognize this object?\'94 he asked, showing it to Mitya.\
\
\'93Oh, yes,\'94 he laughed gloomily. \'93Of course I recognize it. Let me have a\
look at it.... Damn it, never mind!\'94\
\
\'93You have forgotten to mention it,\'94 observed the investigating lawyer.\
\
\'93Hang it all, I shouldn\'92t have concealed it from you. Do you suppose I\
could have managed without it? It simply escaped my memory.\'94\
\
\'93Be so good as to tell us precisely how you came to arm yourself with it.\'94\
\
\'93Certainly I will be so good, gentlemen.\'94\
\
And Mitya described how he took the pestle and ran.\
\
\'93But what object had you in view in arming yourself with such a weapon?\'94\
\
\'93What object? No object. I just picked it up and ran off.\'94\
\
\'93What for, if you had no object?\'94\
\
Mitya\'92s wrath flared up. He looked intently at \'93the boy\'94 and smiled\
gloomily and malignantly. He was feeling more and more ashamed at having\
told \'93such people\'94 the story of his jealousy so sincerely and\
spontaneously.\
\
\'93Bother the pestle!\'94 broke from him suddenly.\
\
\'93But still\'97\'94\
\
\'93Oh, to keep off dogs.... Oh, because it was dark.... In case anything\
turned up.\'94\
\
\'93But have you ever on previous occasions taken a weapon with you when you\
went out, since you\'92re afraid of the dark?\'94\
\
\'93Ugh! damn it all, gentlemen! There\'92s positively no talking to you!\'94 cried\
Mitya, exasperated beyond endurance, and turning to the secretary, crimson\
with anger, he said quickly, with a note of fury in his voice:\
\
\'93Write down at once ... at once ... \'91that I snatched up the pestle to go\
and kill my father ... Fyodor Pavlovitch ... by hitting him on the head\
with it!\'92 Well, now are you satisfied, gentlemen? Are your minds\
relieved?\'94 he said, glaring defiantly at the lawyers.\
\
\'93We quite understand that you made that statement just now through\
exasperation with us and the questions we put to you, which you consider\
trivial, though they are, in fact, essential,\'94 the prosecutor remarked\
