humored at every word. \'93You may not trust a criminal or a man on trial\
tortured by your questions, but an honorable man, the honorable impulses\
of the heart (I say that boldly!)\'97no! That you must believe you have no\
right indeed ... but\'97\
\
\
    Be silent, heart,\
    Be patient, humble, hold thy peace.\
\
\
Well, shall I go on?\'94 he broke off gloomily.\
\
\'93If you\'92ll be so kind,\'94 answered Nikolay Parfenovitch.\
\
\
\
Chapter V. The Third Ordeal\
\
\
Though Mitya spoke sullenly, it was evident that he was trying more than\
ever not to forget or miss a single detail of his story. He told them how\
he had leapt over the fence into his father\'92s garden; how he had gone up\
to the window; told them all that had passed under the window. Clearly,\
precisely, distinctly, he described the feelings that troubled him during\
those moments in the garden when he longed so terribly to know whether\
Grushenka was with his father or not. But, strange to say, both the\
lawyers listened now with a sort of awful reserve, looked coldly at him,\
asked few questions. Mitya could gather nothing from their faces.\
\
\'93They\'92re angry and offended,\'94 he thought. \'93Well, bother them!\'94\
\
When he described how he made up his mind at last to make the \'93signal\'94 to\
his father that Grushenka had come, so that he should open the window, the\
lawyers paid no attention to the word \'93signal,\'94 as though they entirely\
failed to grasp the meaning of the word in this connection: so much so,\
that Mitya noticed it. Coming at last to the moment when, seeing his\
father peering out of the window, his hatred flared up and he pulled the\
pestle out of his pocket, he suddenly, as though of design, stopped short.\
He sat gazing at the wall and was aware that their eyes were fixed upon\
him.\
\
\'93Well?\'94 said the investigating lawyer. \'93You pulled out the weapon and ...\
and what happened then?\'94\
\
\'93Then? Why, then I murdered him ... hit him on the head and cracked his\
skull.... I suppose that\'92s your story. That\'92s it!\'94\
\
His eyes suddenly flashed. All his smothered wrath suddenly flamed up with\
extraordinary violence in his soul.\
\
\'93Our story?\'94 repeated Nikolay Parfenovitch. \'93Well\'97and yours?\'94\
\
Mitya dropped his eyes and was a long time silent.\
\
\'93My story, gentlemen? Well, it was like this,\'94 he began softly. \'93Whether\
it was some one\'92s tears, or my mother prayed to God, or a good angel\
kissed me at that instant, I don\'92t know. But the devil was conquered. I\
rushed from the window and ran to the fence. My father was alarmed and,\
for the first time, he saw me then, cried out, and sprang back from the\
window. I remember that very well. I ran across the garden to the fence\
... and there Grigory caught me, when I was sitting on the fence.\'94\
\
At that point he raised his eyes at last and looked at his listeners. They\
seemed to be staring at him with perfectly unruffled attention. A sort of\
paroxysm of indignation seized on Mitya\'92s soul.\
\
\'93Why, you\'92re laughing at me at this moment, gentlemen!\'94 he broke off\
suddenly.\
\
\'93What makes you think that?\'94 observed Nikolay Parfenovitch.\
\
\'93You don\'92t believe one word\'97that\'92s why! I understand, of course, that I\
have come to the vital point. The old man\'92s lying there now with his skull\
broken, while I\'97after dramatically describing how I wanted to kill him,\
and how I snatched up the pestle\'97I suddenly run away from the window. A\
romance! Poetry! As though one could believe a fellow on his word. Ha ha!\
You are scoffers, gentlemen!\'94\
\
And he swung round on his chair so that it creaked.\
\
\'93And did you notice,\'94 asked the prosecutor suddenly, as though not\
observing Mitya\'92s excitement, \'93did you notice when you ran away from the\
window, whether the door into the garden was open?\'94\
\
\'93No, it was not open.\'94\
\
\'93It was not?\'94\
\
\'93It was shut. And who could open it? Bah! the door. Wait a bit!\'94 he seemed\
suddenly to bethink himself, and almost with a start:\
\
\'93Why, did you find the door open?\'94\
\
\'93Yes, it was open.\'94\
\
\'93Why, who could have opened it if you did not open it yourselves?\'94 cried\
Mitya, greatly astonished.\
\
\'93The door stood open, and your father\'92s murderer undoubtedly went in at\
that door, and, having accomplished the crime, went out again by the same\
door,\'94 the prosecutor pronounced deliberately, as though chiseling out\
each word separately. \'93That is perfectly clear. The murder was committed\
in the room and _not through the __ window_; that is absolutely certain\
from the examination that has been made, from the position of the body and\
everything. There can be no doubt of that circumstance.\'94\
\
Mitya was absolutely dumbfounded.\
\
\'93But that\'92s utterly impossible!\'94 he cried, completely at a loss. \'93I ... I\
didn\'92t go in.... I tell you positively, definitely, the door was shut the\
whole time I was in the garden, and when I ran out of the garden. I only\
stood at the window and saw him through the window. That\'92s all, that\'92s\
all.... I remember to the last minute. And if I didn\'92t remember, it would\
be just the same. I know it, for no one knew the signals except\
Smerdyakov, and me, and the dead man. And he wouldn\'92t have opened the door\
to any one in the world without the signals.\'94\
\
\'93Signals? What signals?\'94 asked the prosecutor, with greedy, almost\
hysterical, curiosity. He instantly lost all trace of his reserve and\
dignity. He asked the question with a sort of cringing timidity. He\
scented an important fact of which he had known nothing, and was already\
filled with dread that Mitya might be unwilling to disclose it.\
\
\'93So you didn\'92t know!\'94 Mitya winked at him with a malicious and mocking\
smile. \'93What if I won\'92t tell you? From whom could you find out? No one\
knew about the signals except my father, Smerdyakov, and me: that was all.\
Heaven knew, too, but it won\'92t tell you. But it\'92s an interesting fact.\
There\'92s no knowing what you might build on it. Ha ha! Take comfort,\
gentlemen, I\'92ll reveal it. You\'92ve some foolish idea in your hearts. You\
don\'92t know the man you have to deal with! You have to do with a prisoner\
who gives evidence against himself, to his own damage! Yes, for I\'92m a man\
of honor and you\'97are not.\'94\
\
The prosecutor swallowed this without a murmur. He was trembling with\
impatience to hear the new fact. Minutely and diffusely Mitya told them\
everything about the signals invented by Fyodor Pavlovitch for Smerdyakov.\
He told them exactly what every tap on the window meant, tapped the\
signals on the table, and when Nikolay Parfenovitch said that he supposed\
he, Mitya, had tapped the signal \'93Grushenka has come,\'94 when he tapped to\
his father, he answered precisely that he had tapped that signal, that\
\'93Grushenka had come.\'94\
\
\'93So now you can build up your tower,\'94 Mitya broke off, and again turned\
away from them contemptuously.\
\
\'93So no one knew of the signals but your dead father, you, and the valet\
Smerdyakov? And no one else?\'94 Nikolay Parfenovitch inquired once more.\
\
\'93Yes. The valet Smerdyakov, and Heaven. Write down about Heaven. That may\
be of use. Besides, you will need God yourselves.\'94\
\
And they had already, of course, begun writing it down. But while they\
wrote, the prosecutor said suddenly, as though pitching on a new idea:\
\
\'93But if Smerdyakov also knew of these signals and you absolutely deny all\
responsibility for the death of your father, was it not he, perhaps, who\
knocked the signal agreed upon, induced your father to open to him, and\
then ... committed the crime?\'94\
\
Mitya turned upon him a look of profound irony and intense hatred. His\
silent stare lasted so long that it made the prosecutor blink.\
\
\'93You\'92ve caught the fox again,\'94 commented Mitya at last; \'93you\'92ve got the\
beast by the tail. Ha ha! I see through you, Mr. Prosecutor. You thought,\
of course, that I should jump at that, catch at your prompting, and shout\
with all my might, \'91Aie! it\'92s Smerdyakov; he\'92s the murderer.\'92 Confess\
that\'92s what you thought. Confess, and I\'92ll go on.\'94\
\
But the prosecutor did not confess. He held his tongue and waited.\
\
\'93You\'92re mistaken. I\'92m not going to shout \'91It\'92s Smerdyakov,\'92 \'94 said Mitya.\
\
\'93And you don\'92t even suspect him?\'94\
\
\'93Why, do you suspect him?\'94\
\
\'93He is suspected, too.\'94\
\
Mitya fixed his eyes on the floor.\
\
\'93Joking apart,\'94 he brought out gloomily. \'93Listen. From the very beginning,\
almost from the moment when I ran out to you from behind the curtain, I\'92ve\
had the thought of Smerdyakov in my mind. I\'92ve been sitting here, shouting\
that I\'92m innocent and thinking all the time \'91Smerdyakov!\'92 I can\'92t get\
Smerdyakov out of my head. In fact, I, too, thought of Smerdyakov just\
now; but only for a second. Almost at once I thought, \'91No, it\'92s not\
Smerdyakov.\'92 It\'92s not his doing, gentlemen.\'94\
\
\'93In that case is there anybody else you suspect?\'94 Nikolay Parfenovitch\
inquired cautiously.\
\
\'93I don\'92t know any one it could be, whether it\'92s the hand of Heaven or\
Satan, but ... not Smerdyakov,\'94 Mitya jerked out with decision.\
\
\'93But what makes you affirm so confidently and emphatically that it\'92s not\
he?\'94\
\
\'93From my conviction\'97my impression. Because Smerdyakov is a man of the most\
abject character and a coward. He\'92s not a coward, he\'92s the epitome of all\
the cowardice in the world walking on two legs. He has the heart of a\
chicken. When he talked to me, he was always trembling for fear I should\
kill him, though I never raised my hand against him. He fell at my feet\
and blubbered; he has kissed these very boots, literally, beseeching me\
\'91not to frighten him.\'92 Do you hear? \'91Not to frighten him.\'92 What a thing to\
say! Why, I offered him money. He\'92s a puling chicken\'97sickly, epileptic,\
weak\uc0\u8208 minded\'97a child of eight could thrash him. He has no character worth\
talking about. It\'92s not Smerdyakov, gentlemen. He doesn\'92t care for money;\
he wouldn\'92t take my presents. Besides, what motive had he for murdering\
the old man? Why, he\'92s very likely his son, you know\'97his natural son. Do\
you know that?\'94\
\
\'93We have heard that legend. But you are your father\'92s son, too, you know;\
yet you yourself told every one you meant to murder him.\'94\
\
\'93That\'92s a thrust! And a nasty, mean one, too! I\'92m not afraid! Oh,\
gentlemen, isn\'92t it too base of you to say that to my face? It\'92s base,\
because I told you that myself. I not only wanted to murder him, but I\
might have done it. And, what\'92s more, I went out of my way to tell you of\
my own accord that I nearly murdered him. But, you see, I didn\'92t murder\
him; you see, my guardian angel saved me\'97that\'92s what you\'92ve not taken into\
account. And that\'92s why it\'92s so base of you. For I didn\'92t kill him, I\
didn\'92t kill him! Do you hear, I did not kill him.\'94\
\
He was almost choking. He had not been so moved before during the whole\
interrogation.\
\
\'93And what has he told you, gentlemen\'97Smerdyakov, I mean?\'94 he added\
suddenly, after a pause. \'93May I ask that question?\'94\
\
\'93You may ask any question,\'94 the prosecutor replied with frigid severity,\
\'93any question relating to the facts of the case, and we are, I repeat,\
bound to answer every inquiry you make. We found the servant Smerdyakov,\
concerning whom you inquire, lying unconscious in his bed, in an epileptic\
fit of extreme severity, that had recurred, possibly, ten times. The\
doctor who was with us told us, after seeing him, that he may possibly not\
outlive the night.\'94\
\
\'93Well, if that\'92s so, the devil must have killed him,\'94 broke suddenly from\
Mitya, as though until that moment he had been asking himself: \'93Was it\
Smerdyakov or not?\'94\
\
\'93We will come back to this later,\'94 Nikolay Parfenovitch decided. \'93Now,\
wouldn\'92t you like to continue your statement?\'94\
\
Mitya asked for a rest. His request was courteously granted. After\
resting, he went on with his story. But he was evidently depressed. He was\
exhausted, mortified and morally shaken. To make things worse the\
prosecutor exasperated him, as though intentionally, by vexatious\
interruptions about \'93trifling points.\'94 Scarcely had Mitya described how,\
sitting on the wall, he had struck Grigory on the head with the pestle,\
while the old man had hold of his left leg, and how he had then jumped\
down to look at him, when the prosecutor stopped him to ask him to\
describe exactly how he was sitting on the wall. Mitya was surprised.\
\
\'93Oh, I was sitting like this, astride, one leg on one side of the wall and\
one on the other.\'94\
\
\'93And the pestle?\'94\
\
\'93The pestle was in my hand.\'94\
\
\'93Not in your pocket? Do you remember that precisely? Was it a violent blow\
you gave him?\'94\
\
\'93It must have been a violent one. But why do you ask?\'94\
\
\'93Would you mind sitting on the chair just as you sat on the wall then and\
showing us just how you moved your arm, and in what direction?\'94\
\
\'93You\'92re making fun of me, aren\'92t you?\'94 asked Mitya, looking haughtily at\
the speaker; but the latter did not flinch.\
\
Mitya turned abruptly, sat astride on his chair, and swung his arm.\
\
\'93This was how I struck him! That\'92s how I knocked him down! What more do\
you want?\'94\
\
\'93Thank you. May I trouble you now to explain why you jumped down, with\
what object, and what you had in view?\'94\
\
\'93Oh, hang it!... I jumped down to look at the man I\'92d hurt ... I don\'92t\
know what for!\'94\
\
\'93Though you were so excited and were running away?\'94\
\
\'93Yes, though I was excited and running away.\'94\
\
\'93You wanted to help him?\'94\
\
\'93Help!... Yes, perhaps I did want to help him.... I don\'92t remember.\'94\
\
\'93You don\'92t remember? Then you didn\'92t quite know what you were doing?\'94\
\
\'93Not at all. I remember everything\'97every detail. I jumped down to look at\
him, and wiped his face with my handkerchief.\'94\
\
\'93We have seen your handkerchief. Did you hope to restore him to\
consciousness?\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t know whether I hoped it. I simply wanted to make sure whether he\
was alive or not.\'94\
\
\'93Ah! You wanted to be sure? Well, what then?\'94\
\
\'93I\'92m not a doctor. I couldn\'92t decide. I ran away thinking I\'92d killed him.\
And now he\'92s recovered.\'94\
\
\'93Excellent,\'94 commented the prosecutor. \'93Thank you. That\'92s all I wanted.\
Kindly proceed.\'94\
\
Alas! it never entered Mitya\'92s head to tell them, though he remembered it,\
that he had jumped back from pity, and standing over the prostrate figure\
had even uttered some words of regret: \'93You\'92ve come to grief, old\
man\'97there\'92s no help for it. Well, there you must lie.\'94\
\
The prosecutor could only draw one conclusion: that the man had jumped\
back \'93at such a moment and in such excitement simply with the object of\
ascertaining whether the _only_ witness of his crime were dead; that he\
must therefore have been a man of great strength, coolness, decision and\
foresight even at such a moment,\'94 ... and so on. The prosecutor was\
satisfied: \'93I\'92ve provoked the nervous fellow by \'91trifles\'92 and he has said\
more than he meant to.\'94\
\
With painful effort Mitya went on. But this time he was pulled up\
immediately by Nikolay Parfenovitch.\
\
\'93How came you to run to the servant, Fedosya Markovna, with your hands so\
covered with blood, and, as it appears, your face, too?\'94\
\
\'93Why, I didn\'92t notice the blood at all at the time,\'94 answered Mitya.\
\
\'93That\'92s quite likely. It does happen sometimes.\'94 The prosecutor exchanged\
glances with Nikolay Parfenovitch.\
\
\'93I simply didn\'92t notice. You\'92re quite right there, prosecutor,\'94 Mitya\
assented suddenly.\
\
Next came the account of Mitya\'92s sudden determination to \'93step aside\'94 and\
make way for their happiness. But he could not make up his mind to open\
his heart to them as before, and tell them about \'93the queen of his soul.\'94\
He disliked speaking of her before these chilly persons \'93who were\
fastening on him like bugs.\'94 And so in response to their reiterated\
questions he answered briefly and abruptly:\
\
\'93Well, I made up my mind to kill myself. What had I left to live for? That\
question stared me in the face. Her first rightful lover had come back,\
the man who wronged her but who\'92d hurried back to offer his love, after\
five years, and atone for the wrong with marriage.... So I knew it was all\
over for me.... And behind me disgrace, and that blood\'97Grigory\'92s.... What\
had I to live for? So I went to redeem the pistols I had pledged, to load\
them and put a bullet in my brain to\uc0\u8208 morrow.\'94\
\
\'93And a grand feast the night before?\'94\
\
\'93Yes, a grand feast the night before. Damn it all, gentlemen! Do make\
haste and finish it. I meant to shoot myself not far from here, beyond the\
village, and I\'92d planned to do it at five o\'92clock in the morning. And I\
had a note in my pocket already. I wrote it at Perhotin\'92s when I loaded my\
pistols. Here\'92s the letter. Read it! It\'92s not for you I tell it,\'94 he added\
contemptuously. He took it from his waistcoat pocket and flung it on the\
table. The lawyers read it with curiosity, and, as is usual, added it to\
the papers connected with the case.\
\
\'93And you didn\'92t even think of washing your hands at Perhotin\'92s? You were\
not afraid then of arousing suspicion?\'94\
\
\'93What suspicion? Suspicion or not, I should have galloped here just the\
same, and shot myself at five o\'92clock, and you wouldn\'92t have been in time\
to do anything. If it hadn\'92t been for what\'92s happened to my father, you\
would have known nothing about it, and wouldn\'92t have come here. Oh, it\'92s\
the devil\'92s doing. It was the devil murdered father, it was through the\
devil that you found it out so soon. How did you manage to get here so\
quick? It\'92s marvelous, a dream!\'94\
\
\'93Mr. Perhotin informed us that when you came to him, you held in your\
hands ... your blood\uc0\u8208 stained hands ... your money ... a lot of money ... a\
bundle of hundred\uc0\u8208 rouble notes, and that his servant\u8208 boy saw it too.\'94\
\
\'93That\'92s true, gentlemen. I remember it was so.\'94\
\
\'93Now, there\'92s one little point presents itself. Can you inform us,\'94\
Nikolay Parfenovitch began, with extreme gentleness, \'93where did you get so\
much money all of a sudden, when it appears from the facts, from the\
reckoning of time, that you had not been home?\'94\
\
The prosecutor\'92s brows contracted at the question being asked so plainly,\
but he did not interrupt Nikolay Parfenovitch.\
\
\'93No, I didn\'92t go home,\'94 answered Mitya, apparently perfectly composed, but\
looking at the floor.\
\
\'93Allow me then to repeat my question,\'94 Nikolay Parfenovitch went on as\
though creeping up to the subject. \'93Where were you able to procure such a\
sum all at once, when by your own confession, at five o\'92clock the same day\
you\'97\'94\
\
\'93I was in want of ten roubles and pledged my pistols with Perhotin, and\
then went to Madame Hohlakov to borrow three thousand which she wouldn\'92t\
give me, and so on, and all the rest of it,\'94 Mitya interrupted sharply.\
\'93Yes, gentlemen, I was in want of it, and suddenly thousands turned up,\
eh? Do you know, gentlemen, you\'92re both afraid now \'91what if he won\'92t tell\
us where he got it?\'92 That\'92s just how it is. I\'92m not going to tell you,\
gentlemen. You\'92ve guessed right. You\'92ll never know,\'94 said Mitya, chipping\
out each word with extraordinary determination. The lawyers were silent\
for a moment.\
\
\'93You must understand, Mr. Karamazov, that it is of vital importance for us\
to know,\'94 said Nikolay Parfenovitch, softly and suavely.\
\
\'93I understand; but still I won\'92t tell you.\'94\
\
The prosecutor, too, intervened, and again reminded the prisoner that he\
was at liberty to refuse to answer questions, if he thought it to his\
interest, and so on. But in view of the damage he might do himself by his\
silence, especially in a case of such importance as\'97\
\
\'93And so on, gentlemen, and so on. Enough! I\'92ve heard that rigmarole\
before,\'94 Mitya interrupted again. \'93I can see for myself how important it\
is, and that this is the vital point, and still I won\'92t say.\'94\
\
\'93What is it to us? It\'92s not our business, but yours. You are doing\
yourself harm,\'94 observed Nikolay Parfenovitch nervously.\
\
\'93You see, gentlemen, joking apart\'94\'97Mitya lifted his eyes and looked firmly\
at them both\'97\'93I had an inkling from the first that we should come to\
loggerheads at this point. But at first when I began to give my evidence,\
it was all still far away and misty; it was all floating, and I was so\
simple that I began with the supposition of mutual confidence existing\
between us. Now I can see for myself that such confidence is out of the\
question, for in any case we were bound to come to this cursed stumbling\uc0\u8208 \
block. And now we\'92ve come to it! It\'92s impossible and there\'92s an end of it!\
But I don\'92t blame you. You can\'92t believe it all simply on my word. I\
understand that, of course.\'94\
\
He relapsed into gloomy silence.\
\
\'93Couldn\'92t you, without abandoning your resolution to be silent about the\
chief point, could you not, at the same time, give us some slight hint as\
to the nature of the motives which are strong enough to induce you to\
refuse to answer, at a crisis so full of danger to you?\'94\
\
Mitya smiled mournfully, almost dreamily.\
\
\'93I\'92m much more good\uc0\u8208 natured than you think, gentlemen. I\'92ll tell you the\
reason why and give you that hint, though you don\'92t deserve it. I won\'92t\
speak of that, gentlemen, because it would be a stain on my honor. The\
answer to the question where I got the money would expose me to far\
greater disgrace than the murder and robbing of my father, if I had\
murdered and robbed him. That\'92s why I can\'92t tell you. I can\'92t for fear of\
disgrace. What, gentlemen, are you going to write that down?\'94\
\
\'93Yes, we\'92ll write it down,\'94 lisped Nikolay Parfenovitch.\
\
\'93You ought not to write that down about \'91disgrace.\'92 I only told you that\
in the goodness of my heart. I needn\'92t have told you. I made you a present\
of it, so to speak, and you pounce upon it at once. Oh, well, write\'97write\
what you like,\'94 he concluded, with scornful disgust. \'93I\'92m not afraid of\
you and I can still hold up my head before you.\'94\
\
\'93And can\'92t you tell us the nature of that disgrace?\'94 Nikolay Parfenovitch\
hazarded.\
\
The prosecutor frowned darkly.\
\
\'93No, no, _c\'92est fini_, don\'92t trouble yourselves. It\'92s not worth while\
soiling one\'92s hands. I have soiled myself enough through you as it is.\
You\'92re not worth it\'97no one is ... Enough, gentlemen. I\'92m not going on.\'94\
\
This was said too peremptorily. Nikolay Parfenovitch did not insist\
further, but from Ippolit Kirillovitch\'92s eyes he saw that he had not given\
up hope.\
\
\'93Can you not, at least, tell us what sum you had in your hands when you\
went into Mr. Perhotin\'92s\'97how many roubles exactly?\'94\
\
\'93I can\'92t tell you that.\'94\
\
\'93You spoke to Mr. Perhotin, I believe, of having received three thousand\
from Madame Hohlakov.\'94\
\
\'93Perhaps I did. Enough, gentlemen. I won\'92t say how much I had.\'94\
\
\'93Will you be so good then as to tell us how you came here and what you\
have done since you arrived?\'94\
\
\'93Oh! you might ask the people here about that. But I\'92ll tell you if you\
like.\'94\
\
He proceeded to do so, but we won\'92t repeat his story. He told it dryly and\
curtly. Of the raptures of his love he said nothing, but told them that he\
abandoned his determination to shoot himself, owing to \'93new factors in the\
case.\'94 He told the story without going into motives or details. And this\
time the lawyers did not worry him much. It was obvious that there was no\
essential point of interest to them here.\
\
\'93We shall verify all that. We will come back to it during the examination\
of the witnesses, which will, of course, take place in your presence,\'94\
said Nikolay Parfenovitch in conclusion. \'93And now allow me to request you\
to lay on the table everything in your possession, especially all the\
money you still have about you.\'94\
\
\'93My money, gentlemen? Certainly. I understand that that is necessary. I\'92m\
surprised, indeed, that you haven\'92t inquired about it before. It\'92s true I\
couldn\'92t get away anywhere. I\'92m sitting here where I can be seen. But\
here\'92s my money\'97count it\'97take it. That\'92s all, I think.\'94\
\
He turned it all out of his pockets; even the small change\'97two pieces of\
twenty copecks\'97he pulled out of his waistcoat pocket. They counted the\
money, which amounted to eight hundred and thirty\uc0\u8208 six roubles, and forty\
copecks.\
\
\'93And is that all?\'94 asked the investigating lawyer.\
\
\'93Yes.\'94\
\
\'93You stated just now in your evidence that you spent three hundred roubles\
at Plotnikovs\'92. You gave Perhotin ten, your driver twenty, here you lost\
two hundred, then....\'94\
\
Nikolay Parfenovitch reckoned it all up. Mitya helped him readily. They\
recollected every farthing and included it in the reckoning. Nikolay\
Parfenovitch hurriedly added up the total.\
\
\'93With this eight hundred you must have had about fifteen hundred at\
first?\'94\
\
\'93I suppose so,\'94 snapped Mitya.\
\
\'93How is it they all assert there was much more?\'94\
\
\'93Let them assert it.\'94\
\
\'93But you asserted it yourself.\'94\
\
\'93Yes, I did, too.\'94\
\
\'93We will compare all this with the evidence of other persons not yet\
examined. Don\'92t be anxious about your money. It will be properly taken\
care of and be at your disposal at the conclusion of ... what is beginning\
... if it appears, or, so to speak, is proved that you have undisputed\
right to it. Well, and now....\'94\
\
Nikolay Parfenovitch suddenly got up, and informed Mitya firmly that it\
was his duty and obligation to conduct a minute and thorough search \'93of\
your clothes and everything else....\'94\
\
\'93By all means, gentlemen. I\'92ll turn out all my pockets, if you like.\'94\
\
And he did, in fact, begin turning out his pockets.\
\
\'93It will be necessary to take off your clothes, too.\'94\
\
\'93What! Undress? Ugh! Damn it! Won\'92t you search me as I am! Can\'92t you?\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s utterly impossible, Dmitri Fyodorovitch. You must take off your\
clothes.\'94\
\
\'93As you like,\'94 Mitya submitted gloomily; \'93only, please, not here, but\
behind the curtains. Who will search them?\'94\
\
\'93Behind the curtains, of course.\'94\
\
Nikolay Parfenovitch bent his head in assent. His small face wore an\
expression of peculiar solemnity.\
\
\
\
Chapter VI. The Prosecutor Catches Mitya\
\
\
Something utterly unexpected and amazing to Mitya followed. He could\
never, even a minute before, have conceived that any one could behave like\
that to him, Mitya Karamazov. What was worst of all, there was something\
humiliating in it, and on their side something \'93supercilious and\
scornful.\'94 It was nothing to take off his coat, but he was asked to\
undress further, or rather not asked but \'93commanded,\'94 he quite understood\
that. From pride and contempt he submitted without a word. Several\
peasants accompanied the lawyers and remained on the same side of the\
curtain. \'93To be ready if force is required,\'94 thought Mitya, \'93and perhaps\
for some other reason, too.\'94\
\
\'93Well, must I take off my shirt, too?\'94 he asked sharply, but Nikolay\
Parfenovitch did not answer. He was busily engaged with the prosecutor in\
examining the coat, the trousers, the waistcoat and the cap; and it was\
evident that they were both much interested in the scrutiny. \'93They make no\
bones about it,\'94 thought Mitya, \'93they don\'92t keep up the most elementary\
politeness.\'94\
\
\'93I ask you for the second time\'97need I take off my shirt or not?\'94 he said,\
still more sharply and irritably.\
\
\'93Don\'92t trouble yourself. We will tell you what to do,\'94 Nikolay\
Parfenovitch said, and his voice was positively peremptory, or so it\
seemed to Mitya.\
\
Meantime a consultation was going on in undertones between the lawyers.\
There turned out to be on the coat, especially on the left side at the\
back, a huge patch of blood, dry, and still stiff. There were bloodstains\
on the trousers, too. Nikolay Parfenovitch, moreover, in the presence of\
the peasant witnesses, passed his fingers along the collar, the cuffs, and\
all the seams of the coat and trousers, obviously looking for\
something\'97money, of course. He didn\'92t even hide from Mitya his suspicion\
that he was capable of sewing money up in his clothes.\
\
\'93He treats me not as an officer but as a thief,\'94 Mitya muttered to\
himself. They communicated their ideas to one another with amazing\
frankness. The secretary, for instance, who was also behind the curtain,\
fussing about and listening, called Nikolay Parfenovitch\'92s attention to\
the cap, which they were also fingering.\
\
\'93You remember Gridyenko, the copying\uc0\u8208 clerk,\'94 observed the secretary. \'93Last\
summer he received the wages of the whole office, and pretended to have\
lost the money when he was drunk. And where was it found? Why, in just\
such pipings in his cap. The hundred\uc0\u8208 rouble notes were screwed up in\
little rolls and sewed in the piping.\'94\
\
Both the lawyers remembered Gridyenko\'92s case perfectly, and so laid aside\
Mitya\'92s cap, and decided that all his clothes must be more thoroughly\
examined later.\
\
\'93Excuse me,\'94 cried Nikolay Parfenovitch, suddenly, noticing that the right\
cuff of Mitya\'92s shirt was turned in, and covered with blood, \'93excuse me,\
what\'92s that, blood?\'94\
\
\'93Yes,\'94 Mitya jerked out.\
\
\'93That is, what blood? ... and why is the cuff turned in?\'94\
\
Mitya told him how he had got the sleeve stained with blood looking after\
Grigory, and had turned it inside when he was washing his hands at\
Perhotin\'92s.\
\
\'93You must take off your shirt, too. That\'92s very important as material\
evidence.\'94\
\
Mitya flushed red and flew into a rage.\
\
\'93What, am I to stay naked?\'94 he shouted.\
\
\'93Don\'92t disturb yourself. We will arrange something. And meanwhile take off\
your socks.\'94\
\
\'93You\'92re not joking? Is that really necessary?\'94 Mitya\'92s eyes flashed.\
\
\'93We are in no mood for joking,\'94 answered Nikolay Parfenovitch sternly.\
\
\'93Well, if I must\'97\'94 muttered Mitya, and sitting down on the bed, he took\
off his socks. He felt unbearably awkward. All were clothed, while he was\
naked, and strange to say, when he was undressed he felt somehow guilty in\
their presence, and was almost ready to believe himself that he was\
inferior to them, and that now they had a perfect right to despise him.\
\
\'93When all are undressed, one is somehow not ashamed, but when one\'92s the\
only one undressed and everybody is looking, it\'92s degrading,\'94 he kept\
repeating to himself, again and again. \'93It\'92s like a dream, I\'92ve sometimes\
dreamed of being in such degrading positions.\'94 It was a misery to him to\
take off his socks. They were very dirty, and so were his underclothes,\
and now every one could see it. And what was worse, he disliked his feet.\
All his life he had thought both his big toes hideous. He particularly\
loathed the coarse, flat, crooked nail on the right one, and now they\
would all see it. Feeling intolerably ashamed made him, at once and\
intentionally, rougher. He pulled off his shirt, himself.\
\
\'93Would you like to look anywhere else if you\'92re not ashamed to?\'94\
\
\'93No, there\'92s no need to, at present.\'94\
\
\'93Well, am I to stay naked like this?\'94 he added savagely.\
\
\'93Yes, that can\'92t be helped for the time.... Kindly sit down here for a\
while. You can wrap yourself in a quilt from the bed, and I ... I\'92ll see\
to all this.\'94\
\
All the things were shown to the witnesses. The report of the search was\
drawn up, and at last Nikolay Parfenovitch went out, and the clothes were\
carried out after him. Ippolit Kirillovitch went out, too. Mitya was left\
alone with the peasants, who stood in silence, never taking their eyes off\
him. Mitya wrapped himself up in the quilt. He felt cold. His bare feet\
stuck out, and he couldn\'92t pull the quilt over so as to cover them.\
Nikolay Parfenovitch seemed to be gone a long time, \'93an insufferable\
time.\'94 \'93He thinks of me as a puppy,\'94 thought Mitya, gnashing his teeth.\
\'93That rotten prosecutor has gone, too, contemptuous no doubt, it disgusts\
him to see me naked!\'94\
\
Mitya imagined, however, that his clothes would be examined and returned\
to him. But what was his indignation when Nikolay Parfenovitch came back\
with quite different clothes, brought in behind him by a peasant.\
\
\'93Here are clothes for you,\'94 he observed airily, seeming well satisfied\
with the success of his mission. \'93Mr. Kalganov has kindly provided these\
for this unusual emergency, as well as a clean shirt. Luckily he had them\
all in his trunk. You can keep your own socks and underclothes.\'94\
\
Mitya flew into a passion.\
\
\'93I won\'92t have other people\'92s clothes!\'94 he shouted menacingly, \'93give me my\
own!\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s impossible!\'94\
\
\'93Give me my own. Damn Kalganov and his clothes, too!\'94\
\
It was a long time before they could persuade him. But they succeeded\
somehow in quieting him down. They impressed upon him that his clothes,\
being stained with blood, must be \'93included with the other material\
evidence,\'94 and that they \'93had not even the right to let him have them now\
... taking into consideration the possible outcome of the case.\'94 Mitya at\
last understood this. He subsided into gloomy silence and hurriedly\
dressed himself. He merely observed, as he put them on, that the clothes\
were much better than his old ones, and that he disliked \'93gaining by the\
change.\'94 The coat was, besides, \'93ridiculously tight. Am I to be dressed up\
like a fool ... for your amusement?\'94\
\
They urged upon him again that he was exaggerating, that Kalganov was only\
a little taller, so that only the trousers might be a little too long. But\
the coat turned out to be really tight in the shoulders.\
\
\'93Damn it all! I can hardly button it,\'94 Mitya grumbled. \'93Be so good as to\
tell Mr. Kalganov from me that I didn\'92t ask for his clothes, and it\'92s not\
my doing that they\'92ve dressed me up like a clown.\'94\
\
\'93He understands that, and is sorry ... I mean, not sorry to lend you his\
clothes, but sorry about all this business,\'94 mumbled Nikolay Parfenovitch.\
\
\'93Confound his sorrow! Well, where now? Am I to go on sitting here?\'94\
\
He was asked to go back to the \'93other room.\'94 Mitya went in, scowling with\
anger, and trying to avoid looking at any one. Dressed in another man\'92s\
clothes he felt himself disgraced, even in the eyes of the peasants, and\
of Trifon Borissovitch, whose face appeared, for some reason, in the\
doorway, and vanished immediately. \'93He\'92s come to look at me dressed up,\'94\
thought Mitya. He sat down on the same chair as before. He had an absurd\
nightmarish feeling, as though he were out of his mind.\
\
\'93Well, what now? Are you going to flog me? That\'92s all that\'92s left for\
you,\'94 he said, clenching his teeth and addressing the prosecutor. He would\
not turn to Nikolay Parfenovitch, as though he disdained to speak to him.\
\
\'93He looked too closely at my socks, and turned them inside out on purpose\
to show every one how dirty they were\'97the scoundrel!\'94\
\
\'93Well, now we must proceed to the examination of witnesses,\'94 observed\
Nikolay Parfenovitch, as though in reply to Mitya\'92s question.\
\
\'93Yes,\'94 said the prosecutor thoughtfully, as though reflecting on\
something.\
\
\'93We\'92ve done what we could in your interest, Dmitri Fyodorovitch,\'94 Nikolay\
Parfenovitch went on, \'93but having received from you such an uncompromising\
refusal to explain to us the source from which you obtained the money\
found upon you, we are, at the present moment\'97\'94\
\
\'93What is the stone in your ring?\'94 Mitya interrupted suddenly, as though\
awakening from a reverie. He pointed to one of the three large rings\
adorning Nikolay Parfenovitch\'92s right hand.\
\
\'93Ring?\'94 repeated Nikolay Parfenovitch with surprise.\
\
\'93Yes, that one ... on your middle finger, with the little veins in it,\
what stone is that?\'94 Mitya persisted, like a peevish child.\
\
\'93That\'92s a smoky topaz,\'94 said Nikolay Parfenovitch, smiling. \'93Would you\
like to look at it? I\'92ll take it off ...\'94\
\
\'93No, don\'92t take it off,\'94 cried Mitya furiously, suddenly waking up, and\
angry with himself. \'93Don\'92t take it off ... there\'92s no need.... Damn it!...\
Gentlemen, you\'92ve sullied my heart! Can you suppose that I would conceal\
it from you, if I had really killed my father, that I would shuffle, lie,\
and hide myself? No, that\'92s not like Dmitri Karamazov, that he couldn\'92t\
do, and if I were guilty, I swear I shouldn\'92t have waited for your coming,\
or for the sunrise as I meant at first, but should have killed myself\
before this, without waiting for the dawn! I know that about myself now. I\
couldn\'92t have learnt so much in twenty years as I\'92ve found out in this\
accursed night!... And should I have been like this on this night, and at\
this moment, sitting with you, could I have talked like this, could I have\
moved like this, could I have looked at you and at the world like this, if\
I had really been the murderer of my father, when the very thought of\
having accidentally killed Grigory gave me no peace all night\'97not from\
fear\'97oh, not simply from fear of your punishment! The disgrace of it! And\
you expect me to be open with such scoffers as you, who see nothing and\
believe in nothing, blind moles and scoffers, and to tell you another\
