\
\
Chapter VII. Mitya\'92s Great Secret. Received With Hisses\
\
\
\'93Gentlemen,\'94 he began, still in the same agitation, \'93I want to make a full\
confession: that money was _my own_.\'94 The lawyers\'92 faces lengthened. That\
was not at all what they expected.\
\
\'93How do you mean?\'94 faltered Nikolay Parfenovitch, \'93when at five o\'92clock on\
the same day, from your own confession\'97\'94\
\
\'93Damn five o\'92clock on the same day and my own confession! That\'92s nothing\
to do with it now! That money was my own, my own, that is, stolen by me\
... not mine, I mean, but stolen by me, and it was fifteen hundred\
roubles, and I had it on me all the time, all the time ...\'94\
\
\'93But where did you get it?\'94\
\
\'93I took it off my neck, gentlemen, off this very neck ... it was here,\
round my neck, sewn up in a rag, and I\'92d had it round my neck a long time,\
it\'92s a month since I put it round my neck ... to my shame and disgrace!\'94\
\
\'93And from whom did you ... appropriate it?\'94\
\
\'93You mean, \'91steal it\'92? Speak out plainly now. Yes, I consider that I\
practically stole it, but, if you prefer, I \'91appropriated it.\'92 I consider\
I stole it. And last night I stole it finally.\'94\
\
\'93Last night? But you said that it\'92s a month since you ... obtained it?...\'94\
\
\'93Yes. But not from my father. Not from my father, don\'92t be uneasy. I\
didn\'92t steal it from my father, but from her. Let me tell you without\
