asked Mitya to get into the cart with somewhat excessive surliness.\
\
\'93When I stood him drinks in the tavern, the man had quite a different\
face,\'94 thought Mitya, as he got in. At the gates there was a crowd of\
people, peasants, women and drivers. Trifon Borissovitch came down the\
steps too. All stared at Mitya.\
\
\'93Forgive me at parting, good people!\'94 Mitya shouted suddenly from the\
cart.\
\
\'93Forgive us too!\'94 he heard two or three voices.\
\
\'93Good\uc0\u8208 by to you, too, Trifon Borissovitch!\'94\
\
But Trifon Borissovitch did not even turn round. He was, perhaps, too\
busy. He, too, was shouting and fussing about something. It appeared that\
