\
\'93I know you!\'94 he cried angrily, \'93I know you!\'94\
\
Kolya stared at him. He could not recall when he could have had a row with\
the man. But he had been in so many rows in the street that he could\
hardly remember them all.\
\
\'93Do you?\'94 he asked sarcastically.\
\
\'93I know you! I know you!\'94 the man repeated idiotically.\
\
\'93So much the better for you. Well, it\'92s time I was going. Good\uc0\u8208 by!\'94\
\
\'93You are at your saucy pranks again?\'94 cried the man. \'93You are at your\
saucy pranks again? I know, you are at it again!\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s not your business, brother, if I am at my saucy pranks again,\'94 said\
Kolya, standing still and scanning him.\
\
\'93Not my business?\'94\
\
\'93No; it\'92s not your business.\'94\
\
\'93Whose then? Whose then? Whose then?\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s Trifon Nikititch\'92s business, not yours.\'94\
\
\'93What Trifon Nikititch?\'94 asked the youth, staring with loutish amazement\
at Kolya, but still as angry as ever.\
\
Kolya scanned him gravely.\
\
\'93Have you been to the Church of the Ascension?\'94 he suddenly asked him,\
with stern emphasis.\
\
\'93What Church of Ascension? What for? No, I haven\'92t,\'94 said the young man,\
somewhat taken aback.\
\
\'93Do you know Sabaneyev?\'94 Kolya went on even more emphatically and even\
more severely.\
\
\'93What Sabaneyev? No, I don\'92t know him.\'94\
\
\'93Well then you can go to the devil,\'94 said Kolya, cutting short the\
