\
\
\
Chapter IV. The Lost Dog\
\
\
Kolya leaned against the fence with an air of dignity, waiting for Alyosha\
to appear. Yes, he had long wanted to meet him. He had heard a great deal\
about him from the boys, but hitherto he had always maintained an\
appearance of disdainful indifference when he was mentioned, and he had\
even \'93criticized\'94 what he heard about Alyosha. But secretly he had a great\
longing to make his acquaintance; there was something sympathetic and\
attractive in all he was told about Alyosha. So the present moment was\
important: to begin with, he had to show himself at his best, to show his\
independence, \'93Or he\'92ll think of me as thirteen and take me for a boy,\
like the rest of them. And what are these boys to him? I shall ask him\
when I get to know him. It\'92s a pity I am so short, though. Tuzikov is\
younger than I am, yet he is half a head taller. But I have a clever face.\
I am not good\uc0\u8208 looking. I know I\'92m hideous, but I\'92ve a clever face. I\
mustn\'92t talk too freely; if I fall into his arms all at once, he may\
think\'97Tfoo! how horrible if he should think\'97!\'94\
\
Such were the thoughts that excited Kolya while he was doing his utmost to\
assume the most independent air. What distressed him most was his being so\
short; he did not mind so much his \'93hideous\'94 face, as being so short. On\
the wall in a corner at home he had the year before made a pencil\uc0\u8208 mark to\
show his height, and every two months since he anxiously measured himself\
against it to see how much he had gained. But alas! he grew very slowly,\
and this sometimes reduced him almost to despair. His face was in reality\
by no means \'93hideous\'94; on the contrary, it was rather attractive, with a\
fair, pale skin, freckled. His small, lively gray eyes had a fearless\
look, and often glowed with feeling. He had rather high cheekbones; small,\
very red, but not very thick, lips; his nose was small and unmistakably\
turned up. \'93I\'92ve a regular pug nose, a regular pug nose,\'94 Kolya used to\
mutter to himself when he looked in the looking\uc0\u8208 glass, and he always left\
it with indignation. \'93But perhaps I haven\'92t got a clever face?\'94 he\
sometimes thought, doubtful even of that. But it must not be supposed that\
his mind was preoccupied with his face and his height. On the contrary,\
however bitter the moments before the looking\uc0\u8208 glass were to him, he\
quickly forgot them, and forgot them for a long time, \'93abandoning himself\
entirely to ideas and to real life,\'94 as he formulated it to himself.\
\
Alyosha came out quickly and hastened up to Kolya. Before he reached him,\
Kolya could see that he looked delighted. \'93Can he be so glad to see me?\'94\
Kolya wondered, feeling pleased. We may note here, in passing, that\
Alyosha\'92s appearance had undergone a complete change since we saw him\
last. He had abandoned his cassock and was wearing now a well\uc0\u8208 cut coat, a\
soft, round hat, and his hair had been cropped short. All this was very\
becoming to him, and he looked quite handsome. His charming face always\
had a good\uc0\u8208 humored expression; but there was a gentleness and serenity in\
his good\uc0\u8208 humor. To Kolya\'92s surprise, Alyosha came out to him just as he\
was, without an overcoat. He had evidently come in haste. He held out his\
hand to Kolya at once.\
\
\'93Here you are at last! How anxious we\'92ve been to see you!\'94\
\
\'93There were reasons which you shall know directly. Anyway, I am glad to\
make your acquaintance. I\'92ve long been hoping for an opportunity, and have\
heard a great deal about you,\'94 Kolya muttered, a little breathless.\
\
\'93We should have met anyway. I\'92ve heard a great deal about you, too; but\
you\'92ve been a long time coming here.\'94\
\
\'93Tell me, how are things going?\'94\
\
\'93Ilusha is very ill. He is certainly dying.\'94\
\
\'93How awful! You must admit that medicine is a fraud, Karamazov,\'94 cried\
Kolya warmly.\
\
\'93Ilusha has mentioned you often, very often, even in his sleep, in\
delirium, you know. One can see that you used to be very, very dear to him\
... before the incident ... with the knife.... Then there\'92s another\
reason.... Tell me, is that your dog?\'94\
\
\'93Yes, Perezvon.\'94\
\
\'93Not Zhutchka?\'94 Alyosha looked at Kolya with eyes full of pity. \'93Is she\
lost for ever?\'94\
\
\'93I know you would all like it to be Zhutchka. I\'92ve heard all about it.\'94\
Kolya smiled mysteriously. \'93Listen, Karamazov, I\'92ll tell you all about it.\
That\'92s what I came for; that\'92s what I asked you to come out here for, to\
explain the whole episode to you before we go in,\'94 he began with\
animation. \'93You see, Karamazov, Ilusha came into the preparatory class\
last spring. Well, you know what our preparatory class is\'97a lot of small\
boys. They began teasing Ilusha at once. I am two classes higher up, and,\
of course, I only look on at them from a distance. I saw the boy was weak\
and small, but he wouldn\'92t give in to them; he fought with them. I saw he\
was proud, and his eyes were full of fire. I like children like that. And\
they teased him all the more. The worst of it was he was horribly dressed\
at the time, his breeches were too small for him, and there were holes in\
his boots. They worried him about it; they jeered at him. That I can\'92t\
stand. I stood up for him at once, and gave it to them hot. I beat them,\
but they adore me, do you know, Karamazov?\'94 Kolya boasted impulsively;\
\'93but I am always fond of children. I\'92ve two chickens in my hands at home\
now\'97that\'92s what detained me to\uc0\u8208 day. So they left off beating Ilusha and I\
took him under my protection. I saw the boy was proud. I tell you that,\
the boy was proud; but in the end he became slavishly devoted to me: he\
did my slightest bidding, obeyed me as though I were God, tried to copy\
me. In the intervals between the classes he used to run to me at once, and\
I\'92d go about with him. On Sundays, too. They always laugh when an older\
boy makes friends with a younger one like that; but that\'92s a prejudice. If\
it\'92s my fancy, that\'92s enough. I am teaching him, developing him. Why\
shouldn\'92t I develop him if I like him? Here you, Karamazov, have taken up\
with all these nestlings. I see you want to influence the younger\
generation\'97to develop them, to be of use to them, and I assure you this\
trait in your character, which I knew by hearsay, attracted me more than\
anything. Let us get to the point, though. I noticed that there was a sort\
of softness and sentimentality coming over the boy, and you know I have a\
positive hatred of this sheepish sentimentality, and I have had it from a\
baby. There were contradictions in him, too: he was proud, but he was\
slavishly devoted to me, and yet all at once his eyes would flash and he\'92d\
refuse to agree with me; he\'92d argue, fly into a rage. I used sometimes to\
propound certain ideas; I could see that it was not so much that he\
disagreed with the ideas, but that he was simply rebelling against me,\
because I was cool in responding to his endearments. And so, in order to\
train him properly, the tenderer he was, the colder I became. I did it on\
purpose: that was my idea. My object was to form his character, to lick\
him into shape, to make a man of him ... and besides ... no doubt, you\
understand me at a word. Suddenly I noticed for three days in succession\
he was downcast and dejected, not because of my coldness, but for\
something else, something more important. I wondered what the tragedy was.\
I have pumped him and found out that he had somehow got to know\
Smerdyakov, who was footman to your late father\'97it was before his death,\
of course\'97and he taught the little fool a silly trick\'97that is, a brutal,\
nasty trick. He told him to take a piece of bread, to stick a pin in it,\
and throw it to one of those hungry dogs who snap up anything without\
biting it, and then to watch and see what would happen. So they prepared a\
piece of bread like that and threw it to Zhutchka, that shaggy dog there\'92s\
been such a fuss about. The people of the house it belonged to never fed\
it at all, though it barked all day. (Do you like that stupid barking,\
Karamazov? I can\'92t stand it.) So it rushed at the bread, swallowed it, and\
began to squeal; it turned round and round and ran away, squealing as it\
ran out of sight. That was Ilusha\'92s own account of it. He confessed it to\
me, and cried bitterly. He hugged me, shaking all over. He kept on\
repeating \'91He ran away squealing\'92: the sight of that haunted him. He was\
tormented by remorse, I could see that. I took it seriously. I determined\
to give him a lesson for other things as well. So I must confess I wasn\'92t\
quite straightforward, and pretended to be more indignant perhaps than I\
was. \'91You\'92ve done a nasty thing,\'92 I said, \'91you are a scoundrel. I won\'92t\
tell of it, of course, but I shall have nothing more to do with you for a\
time. I\'92ll think it over and let you know through Smurov\'92\'97that\'92s the boy\
who\'92s just come with me; he\'92s always ready to do anything for me\'97\'91whether\
I will have anything to do with you in the future or whether I give you up\
for good as a scoundrel.\'92 He was tremendously upset. I must own I felt I\'92d\
gone too far as I spoke, but there was no help for it. I did what I\
thought best at the time. A day or two after, I sent Smurov to tell him\
that I would not speak to him again. That\'92s what we call it when two\
schoolfellows refuse to have anything more to do with one another.\
Secretly I only meant to send him to Coventry for a few days and then, if\
I saw signs of repentance, to hold out my hand to him again. That was my\
intention. But what do you think happened? He heard Smurov\'92s message, his\
eyes flashed. \'91Tell Krassotkin from me,\'92 he cried, \'91that I will throw\
bread with pins to all the dogs\'97all\'97all of them!\'92 \'91So he\'92s going in for a\
little temper. We must smoke it out of him.\'92 And I began to treat him with\
contempt; whenever I met him I turned away or smiled sarcastically. And\
just then that affair with his father happened. You remember? You must\
realize that he was fearfully worked up by what had happened already. The\
boys, seeing I\'92d given him up, set on him and taunted him, shouting, \'91Wisp\
of tow, wisp of tow!\'92 And he had soon regular skirmishes with them, which\
I am very sorry for. They seem to have given him one very bad beating. One\
day he flew at them all as they were coming out of school. I stood a few\
yards off, looking on. And, I swear, I don\'92t remember that I laughed; it\
was quite the other way, I felt awfully sorry for him, in another minute I\
would have run up to take his part. But he suddenly met my eyes. I don\'92t\
know what he fancied; but he pulled out a penknife, rushed at me, and\
struck at my thigh, here in my right leg. I didn\'92t move. I don\'92t mind\
owning I am plucky sometimes, Karamazov. I simply looked at him\
contemptuously, as though to say, \'91This is how you repay all my kindness!\
Do it again, if you like, I\'92m at your service.\'92 But he didn\'92t stab me\
again; he broke down, he was frightened at what he had done, he threw away\
the knife, burst out crying, and ran away. I did not sneak on him, of\
course, and I made them all keep quiet, so it shouldn\'92t come to the ears\
of the masters. I didn\'92t even tell my mother till it had healed up. And\
the wound was a mere scratch. And then I heard that the same day he\'92d been\
throwing stones and had bitten your finger\'97but you understand now what a\
state he was in! Well, it can\'92t be helped: it was stupid of me not to come\
and forgive him\'97that is, to make it up with him\'97when he was taken ill. I\
am sorry for it now. But I had a special reason. So now I\'92ve told you all\
about it ... but I\'92m afraid it was stupid of me.\'94\
\
\'93Oh, what a pity,\'94 exclaimed Alyosha, with feeling, \'93that I didn\'92t know\
before what terms you were on with him, or I\'92d have come to you long ago\
to beg you to go to him with me. Would you believe it, when he was\
feverish he talked about you in delirium. I didn\'92t know how much you were\
to him! And you\'92ve really not succeeded in finding that dog? His father\
and the boys have been hunting all over the town for it. Would you believe\
it, since he\'92s been ill, I\'92ve three times heard him repeat with tears,\
\'91It\'92s because I killed Zhutchka, father, that I am ill now. God is\
punishing me for it.\'92 He can\'92t get that idea out of his head. And if the\
dog were found and proved to be alive, one might almost fancy the joy\
would cure him. We have all rested our hopes on you.\'94\
\
\'93Tell me, what made you hope that I should be the one to find him?\'94 Kolya\
asked, with great curiosity. \'93Why did you reckon on me rather than any one\
else?\'94\
\
\'93There was a report that you were looking for the dog, and that you would\
bring it when you\'92d found it. Smurov said something of the sort. We\'92ve all\
been trying to persuade Ilusha that the dog is alive, that it\'92s been seen.\
The boys brought him a live hare; he just looked at it, with a faint\
smile, and asked them to set it free in the fields. And so we did. His\
father has just this moment come back, bringing him a mastiff pup, hoping\
to comfort him with that; but I think it only makes it worse.\'94\
\
\'93Tell me, Karamazov, what sort of man is the father? I know him, but what\
do you make of him\'97a mountebank, a buffoon?\'94\
\
\'93Oh, no; there are people of deep feeling who have been somehow crushed.\
Buffoonery in them is a form of resentful irony against those to whom they\
daren\'92t speak the truth, from having been for years humiliated and\
intimidated by them. Believe me, Krassotkin, that sort of buffoonery is\
sometimes tragic in the extreme. His whole life now is centered in Ilusha,\
and if Ilusha dies, he will either go mad with grief or kill himself. I\
feel almost certain of that when I look at him now.\'94\
\
\'93I understand you, Karamazov. I see you understand human nature,\'94 Kolya\
added, with feeling.\
\
\'93And as soon as I saw you with a dog, I thought it was Zhutchka you were\
bringing.\'94\
\
\'93Wait a bit, Karamazov, perhaps we shall find it yet; but this is\
Perezvon. I\'92ll let him go in now and perhaps it will amuse Ilusha more\
than the mastiff pup. Wait a bit, Karamazov, you will know something in a\
minute. But, I say, I am keeping you here!\'94 Kolya cried suddenly. \'93You\'92ve\
no overcoat on in this bitter cold. You see what an egoist I am. Oh, we\
are all egoists, Karamazov!\'94\
\
\'93Don\'92t trouble; it is cold, but I don\'92t often catch cold. Let us go in,\
though, and, by the way, what is your name? I know you are called Kolya,\
but what else?\'94\
\
\'93Nikolay\'97Nikolay Ivanovitch Krassotkin, or, as they say in official\
documents, \'91Krassotkin son.\'92 \'94 Kolya laughed for some reason, but added\
suddenly, \'93Of course I hate my name Nikolay.\'94\
\
\'93Why so?\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s so trivial, so ordinary.\'94\
\
\'93You are thirteen?\'94 asked Alyosha.\
\
\'93No, fourteen\'97that is, I shall be fourteen very soon, in a fortnight. I\'92ll\
confess one weakness of mine, Karamazov, just to you, since it\'92s our first\
meeting, so that you may understand my character at once. I hate being\
asked my age, more than that ... and in fact ... there\'92s a libelous story\
going about me, that last week I played robbers with the preparatory boys.\
It\'92s a fact that I did play with them, but it\'92s a perfect libel to say I\
did it for my own amusement. I have reasons for believing that you\'92ve\
heard the story; but I wasn\'92t playing for my own amusement, it was for the\
sake of the children, because they couldn\'92t think of anything to do by\
themselves. But they\'92ve always got some silly tale. This is an awful town\
for gossip, I can tell you.\'94\
\
\'93But what if you had been playing for your own amusement, what\'92s the\
harm?\'94\
\
\'93Come, I say, for my own amusement! You don\'92t play horses, do you?\'94\
\
\'93But you must look at it like this,\'94 said Alyosha, smiling. \'93Grown\uc0\u8208 up\
people go to the theater and there the adventures of all sorts of heroes\
are represented\'97sometimes there are robbers and battles, too\'97and isn\'92t\
that just the same thing, in a different form, of course? And young\
people\'92s games of soldiers or robbers in their playtime are also art in\
its first stage. You know, they spring from the growing artistic instincts\
of the young. And sometimes these games are much better than performances\
in the theater, the only difference is that people go there to look at the\
actors, while in these games the young people are the actors themselves.\
But that\'92s only natural.\'94\
\
\'93You think so? Is that your idea?\'94 Kolya looked at him intently. \'93Oh, you\
know, that\'92s rather an interesting view. When I go home, I\'92ll think it\
over. I\'92ll admit I thought I might learn something from you. I\'92ve come to\
learn of you, Karamazov,\'94 Kolya concluded, in a voice full of spontaneous\
feeling.\
\
\'93And I of you,\'94 said Alyosha, smiling and pressing his hand.\
\
Kolya was much pleased with Alyosha. What struck him most was that he\
treated him exactly like an equal and that he talked to him just as if he\
were \'93quite grown up.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92ll show you something directly, Karamazov; it\'92s a theatrical\
performance, too,\'94 he said, laughing nervously. \'93That\'92s why I\'92ve come.\'94\
\
\'93Let us go first to the people of the house, on the left. All the boys\
leave their coats in there, because the room is small and hot.\'94\
\
\'93Oh, I\'92m only coming in for a minute. I\'92ll keep on my overcoat. Perezvon\
will stay here in the passage and be dead. _Ici_, Perezvon, lie down and\
be dead! You see how he\'92s dead. I\'92ll go in first and explore, then I\'92ll\
whistle to him when I think fit, and you\'92ll see, he\'92ll dash in like mad.\
Only Smurov must not forget to open the door at the moment. I\'92ll arrange\
it all and you\'92ll see something.\'94\
\
\
\
Chapter V. By Ilusha\'92s Bedside\
\
\
The room inhabited by the family of the retired captain Snegiryov is\
already familiar to the reader. It was close and crowded at that moment\
with a number of visitors. Several boys were sitting with Ilusha, and\
though all of them, like Smurov, were prepared to deny that it was Alyosha\
who had brought them and reconciled them with Ilusha, it was really the\
fact. All the art he had used had been to take them, one by one, to\
Ilusha, without \'93sheepish sentimentality,\'94 appearing to do so casually and\
without design. It was a great consolation to Ilusha in his suffering. He\
was greatly touched by seeing the almost tender affection and sympathy\
shown him by these boys, who had been his enemies. Krassotkin was the only\
one missing and his absence was a heavy load on Ilusha\'92s heart. Perhaps\
the bitterest of all his bitter memories was his stabbing Krassotkin, who\
had been his one friend and protector. Clever little Smurov, who was the\
first to make it up with Ilusha, thought it was so. But when Smurov hinted\
to Krassotkin that Alyosha wanted to come and see him about something, the\
latter cut him short, bidding Smurov tell \'93Karamazov\'94 at once that he knew\
best what to do, that he wanted no one\'92s advice, and that, if he went to\
see Ilusha, he would choose his own time for he had \'93his own reasons.\'94\
\
That was a fortnight before this Sunday. That was why Alyosha had not been\
to see him, as he had meant to. But though he waited, he sent Smurov to\
him twice again. Both times Krassotkin met him with a curt, impatient\
refusal, sending Alyosha a message not to bother him any more, that if he\
came himself, he, Krassotkin, would not go to Ilusha at all. Up to the\
very last day, Smurov did not know that Kolya meant to go to Ilusha that\
morning, and only the evening before, as he parted from Smurov, Kolya\
abruptly told him to wait at home for him next morning, for he would go\
with him to the Snegiryovs\'92, but warned him on no account to say he was\
coming, as he wanted to drop in casually. Smurov obeyed. Smurov\'92s fancy\
that Kolya would bring back the lost dog was based on the words Kolya had\
dropped that \'93they must be asses not to find the dog, if it was alive.\'94\
When Smurov, waiting for an opportunity, timidly hinted at his guess about\
the dog, Krassotkin flew into a violent rage. \'93I\'92m not such an ass as to\
go hunting about the town for other people\'92s dogs when I\'92ve got a dog of\
my own! And how can you imagine a dog could be alive after swallowing a\
pin? Sheepish sentimentality, that\'92s what it is!\'94\
\
For the last fortnight Ilusha had not left his little bed under the ikons\
in the corner. He had not been to school since the day he met Alyosha and\
bit his finger. He was taken ill the same day, though for a month\
afterwards he was sometimes able to get up and walk about the room and\
passage. But latterly he had become so weak that he could not move without\
help from his father. His father was terribly concerned about him. He even\
gave up drinking and was almost crazy with terror that his boy would die.\
And often, especially after leading him round the room on his arm and\
putting him back to bed, he would run to a dark corner in the passage and,\
leaning his head against the wall, he would break into paroxysms of\
violent weeping, stifling his sobs that they might not be heard by Ilusha.\
\
Returning to the room, he would usually begin doing something to amuse and\
comfort his precious boy; he would tell him stories, funny anecdotes, or\
would mimic comic people he had happened to meet, even imitate the howls\
and cries of animals. But Ilusha could not bear to see his father fooling\
and playing the buffoon. Though the boy tried not to show how he disliked\
it, he saw with an aching heart that his father was an object of contempt,\
and he was continually haunted by the memory of the \'93wisp of tow\'94 and that\
\'93terrible day.\'94\
\
Nina, Ilusha\'92s gentle, crippled sister, did not like her father\'92s\
buffoonery either (Varvara had been gone for some time past to Petersburg\
to study at the university). But the half\uc0\u8208 imbecile mother was greatly\
diverted and laughed heartily when her husband began capering about or\
performing something. It was the only way she could be amused; all the\
rest of the time she was grumbling and complaining that now every one had\
forgotten her, that no one treated her with respect, that she was\
slighted, and so on. But during the last few days she had completely\
changed. She began looking constantly at Ilusha\'92s bed in the corner and\
seemed lost in thought. She was more silent, quieter, and, if she cried,\
she cried quietly so as not to be heard. The captain noticed the change in\
her with mournful perplexity. The boys\'92 visits at first only angered her,\
but later on their merry shouts and stories began to divert her, and at\
last she liked them so much that, if the boys had given up coming, she\
would have felt dreary without them. When the children told some story or\
played a game, she laughed and clapped her hands. She called some of them\
to her and kissed them. She was particularly fond of Smurov.\
\
As for the captain, the presence in his room of the children, who came to\
cheer up Ilusha, filled his heart from the first with ecstatic joy. He\
even hoped that Ilusha would now get over his depression, and that that\
would hasten his recovery. In spite of his alarm about Ilusha, he had not,\
till lately, felt one minute\'92s doubt of his boy\'92s ultimate recovery.\
\
He met his little visitors with homage, waited upon them hand and foot; he\
was ready to be their horse and even began letting them ride on his back,\
but Ilusha did not like the game and it was given up. He began buying\
little things for them, gingerbread and nuts, gave them tea and cut them\
sandwiches. It must be noted that all this time he had plenty of money. He\
had taken the two hundred roubles from Katerina Ivanovna just as Alyosha\
had predicted he would. And afterwards Katerina Ivanovna, learning more\
about their circumstances and Ilusha\'92s illness, visited them herself, made\
the acquaintance of the family, and succeeded in fascinating the half\uc0\u8208 \
imbecile mother. Since then she had been lavish in helping them, and the\
captain, terror\uc0\u8208 stricken at the thought that his boy might be dying,\
forgot his pride and humbly accepted her assistance.\
\
All this time Doctor Herzenstube, who was called in by Katerina Ivanovna,\
came punctually every other day, but little was gained by his visits and\
he dosed the invalid mercilessly. But on that Sunday morning a new doctor\
was expected, who had come from Moscow, where he had a great reputation.\
Katerina Ivanovna had sent for him from Moscow at great expense, not\
expressly for Ilusha, but for another object of which more will be said in\
its place hereafter. But, as he had come, she had asked him to see Ilusha\
as well, and the captain had been told to expect him. He hadn\'92t the\
slightest idea that Kolya Krassotkin was coming, though he had long wished\
for a visit from the boy for whom Ilusha was fretting.\
\
At the moment when Krassotkin opened the door and came into the room, the\
captain and all the boys were round Ilusha\'92s bed, looking at a tiny\
mastiff pup, which had only been born the day before, though the captain\
had bespoken it a week ago to comfort and amuse Ilusha, who was still\
fretting over the lost and probably dead Zhutchka. Ilusha, who had heard\
three days before that he was to be presented with a puppy, not an\
ordinary puppy, but a pedigree mastiff (a very important point, of\
course), tried from delicacy of feeling to pretend that he was pleased.\
But his father and the boys could not help seeing that the puppy only\
served to recall to his little heart the thought of the unhappy dog he had\
killed. The puppy lay beside him feebly moving and he, smiling sadly,\
stroked it with his thin, pale, wasted hand. Clearly he liked the puppy,\
but ... it wasn\'92t Zhutchka; if he could have had Zhutchka and the puppy,\
too, then he would have been completely happy.\
\
\'93Krassotkin!\'94 cried one of the boys suddenly. He was the first to see him\
come in.\
\
Krassotkin\'92s entrance made a general sensation; the boys moved away and\
stood on each side of the bed, so that he could get a full view of Ilusha.\
The captain ran eagerly to meet Kolya.\
\
\'93Please come in ... you are welcome!\'94 he said hurriedly. \'93Ilusha, Mr.\
Krassotkin has come to see you!\'94\
\
But Krassotkin, shaking hands with him hurriedly, instantly showed his\
complete knowledge of the manners of good society. He turned first to the\
captain\'92s wife sitting in her arm\uc0\u8208 chair, who was very ill\u8208 humored at the\
moment, and was grumbling that the boys stood between her and Ilusha\'92s bed\
and did not let her see the new puppy. With the greatest courtesy he made\
her a bow, scraping his foot, and turning to Nina, he made her, as the\
only other lady present, a similar bow. This polite behavior made an\
extremely favorable impression on the deranged lady.\
\
\'93There, you can see at once he is a young man that has been well brought\
up,\'94 she commented aloud, throwing up her hands; \'93but as for our other\
visitors they come in one on the top of another.\'94\
\
\'93How do you mean, mamma, one on the top of another, how is that?\'94 muttered\
the captain affectionately, though a little anxious on her account.\
\
\'93That\'92s how they ride in. They get on each other\'92s shoulders in the\
passage and prance in like that on a respectable family. Strange sort of\
visitors!\'94\
\
\'93But who\'92s come in like that, mamma?\'94\
\
\'93Why, that boy came in riding on that one\'92s back and this one on that\
one\'92s.\'94\
\
Kolya was already by Ilusha\'92s bedside. The sick boy turned visibly paler.\
He raised himself in the bed and looked intently at Kolya. Kolya had not\
seen his little friend for two months, and he was overwhelmed at the sight\
of him. He had never imagined that he would see such a wasted, yellow\
face, such enormous, feverishly glowing eyes and such thin little hands.\
He saw, with grieved surprise, Ilusha\'92s rapid, hard breathing and dry\
lips. He stepped close to him, held out his hand, and almost overwhelmed,\
he said:\
\
\'93Well, old man ... how are you?\'94 But his voice failed him, he couldn\'92t\
achieve an appearance of ease; his face suddenly twitched and the corners\
of his mouth quivered. Ilusha smiled a pitiful little smile, still unable\
to utter a word. Something moved Kolya to raise his hand and pass it over\
Ilusha\'92s hair.\
\
\'93Never mind!\'94 he murmured softly to him to cheer him up, or perhaps not\
knowing why he said it. For a minute they were silent again.\
\
\'93Hallo, so you\'92ve got a new puppy?\'94 Kolya said suddenly, in a most callous\
voice.\
\
\'93Ye\'97es,\'94 answered Ilusha in a long whisper, gasping for breath.\
\
\'93A black nose, that means he\'92ll be fierce, a good house\uc0\u8208 dog,\'94 Kolya\
observed gravely and stolidly, as if the only thing he cared about was the\
puppy and its black nose. But in reality he still had to do his utmost to\
control his feelings not to burst out crying like a child, and do what he\
would he could not control it. \'93When it grows up, you\'92ll have to keep it\
on the chain, I\'92m sure.\'94\
\
\'93He\'92ll be a huge dog!\'94 cried one of the boys.\
\
\'93Of course he will,\'94 \'93a mastiff,\'94 \'93large,\'94 \'93like this,\'94 \'93as big as a\
calf,\'94 shouted several voices.\
\
\'93As big as a calf, as a real calf,\'94 chimed in the captain. \'93I got one like\
that on purpose, one of the fiercest breed, and his parents are huge and\
very fierce, they stand as high as this from the floor.... Sit down here,\
on Ilusha\'92s bed, or here on the bench. You are welcome, we\'92ve been hoping\
to see you a long time.... You were so kind as to come with Alexey\
Fyodorovitch?\'94\
\
Krassotkin sat on the edge of the bed, at Ilusha\'92s feet. Though he had\
perhaps prepared a free\uc0\u8208 and\u8208 easy opening for the conversation on his way,\
now he completely lost the thread of it.\
\
\'93No ... I came with Perezvon. I\'92ve got a dog now, called Perezvon. A\
Slavonic name. He\'92s out there ... if I whistle, he\'92ll run in. I\'92ve brought\
a dog, too,\'94 he said, addressing Ilusha all at once. \'93Do you remember\
Zhutchka, old man?\'94 he suddenly fired the question at him.\
\
Ilusha\'92s little face quivered. He looked with an agonized expression at\
Kolya. Alyosha, standing at the door, frowned and signed to Kolya not to\
speak of Zhutchka, but he did not or would not notice.\
\
\'93Where ... is Zhutchka?\'94 Ilusha asked in a broken voice.\
\
\'93Oh, well, my boy, your Zhutchka\'92s lost and done for!\'94\
\
Ilusha did not speak, but he fixed an intent gaze once more on Kolya.\
Alyosha, catching Kolya\'92s eye, signed to him vigorously again, but he\
turned away his eyes pretending not to have noticed.\
\
\'93It must have run away and died somewhere. It must have died after a meal\
like that,\'94 Kolya pronounced pitilessly, though he seemed a little\
breathless. \'93But I\'92ve got a dog, Perezvon ... A Slavonic name.... I\'92ve\
brought him to show you.\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t want him!\'94 said Ilusha suddenly.\
\
\'93No, no, you really must see him ... it will amuse you. I brought him on\
purpose.... He\'92s the same sort of shaggy dog.... You allow me to call in\
my dog, madam?\'94 He suddenly addressed Madame Snegiryov, with inexplicable\
excitement in his manner.\
\
\'93I don\'92t want him, I don\'92t want him!\'94 cried Ilusha, with a mournful break\
in his voice. There was a reproachful light in his eyes.\
\
\'93You\'92d better,\'94 the captain started up from the chest by the wall on which\
he had just sat down, \'93you\'92d better ... another time,\'94 he muttered, but\
Kolya could not be restrained. He hurriedly shouted to Smurov, \'93Open the\
door,\'94 and as soon as it was open, he blew his whistle. Perezvon dashed\
headlong into the room.\
\
\'93Jump, Perezvon, beg! Beg!\'94 shouted Kolya, jumping up, and the dog stood\
erect on its hind\uc0\u8208 legs by Ilusha\'92s bedside. What followed was a surprise\
to every one: Ilusha started, lurched violently forward, bent over\
Perezvon and gazed at him, faint with suspense.\
\
\'93It\'92s ... Zhutchka!\'94 he cried suddenly, in a voice breaking with joy and\
suffering.\
\
\'93And who did you think it was?\'94 Krassotkin shouted with all his might, in\
a ringing, happy voice, and bending down he seized the dog and lifted him\
up to Ilusha.\
\
\'93Look, old man, you see, blind of one eye and the left ear is torn, just\
the marks you described to me. It was by that I found him. I found him\
directly. He did not belong to any one!\'94 he explained, turning quickly to\
the captain, to his wife, to Alyosha and then again to Ilusha. \'93He used to\
live in the Fedotovs\'92 back\uc0\u8208 yard. Though he made his home there, they did\
not feed him. He was a stray dog that had run away from the village ... I\
found him.... You see, old man, he couldn\'92t have swallowed what you gave\
him. If he had, he must have died, he must have! So he must have spat it\
out, since he is alive. You did not see him do it. But the pin pricked his\
tongue, that is why he squealed. He ran away squealing and you thought\
he\'92d swallowed it. He might well squeal, because the skin of dogs\'92 mouths\
is so tender ... tenderer than in men, much tenderer!\'94 Kolya cried\
impetuously, his face glowing and radiant with delight. Ilusha could not\
speak. White as a sheet, he gazed open\uc0\u8208 mouthed at Kolya, with his great\
eyes almost starting out of his head. And if Krassotkin, who had no\
suspicion of it, had known what a disastrous and fatal effect such a\
moment might have on the sick child\'92s health, nothing would have induced\
him to play such a trick on him. But Alyosha was perhaps the only person\
in the room who realized it. As for the captain he behaved like a small\
child.\
\
\'93Zhutchka! It\'92s Zhutchka!\'94 he cried in a blissful voice, \'93Ilusha, this is\
Zhutchka, your Zhutchka! Mamma, this is Zhutchka!\'94 He was almost weeping.\
\
\'93And I never guessed!\'94 cried Smurov regretfully. \'93Bravo, Krassotkin! I\
said he\'92d find the dog and here he\'92s found him.\'94\
\
\'93Here he\'92s found him!\'94 another boy repeated gleefully.\
\
\'93Krassotkin\'92s a brick!\'94 cried a third voice.\
\
\'93He\'92s a brick, he\'92s a brick!\'94 cried the other boys, and they began\
clapping.\
\
\'93Wait, wait,\'94 Krassotkin did his utmost to shout above them all. \'93I\'92ll\
tell you how it happened, that\'92s the whole point. I found him, I took him\
home and hid him at once. I kept him locked up at home and did not show\
him to any one till to\uc0\u8208 day. Only Smurov has known for the last fortnight,\
but I assured him this dog was called Perezvon and he did not guess. And\
meanwhile I taught the dog all sorts of tricks. You should only see all\
the things he can do! I trained him so as to bring you a well\uc0\u8208 trained dog,\
in good condition, old man, so as to be able to say to you, \'91See, old man,\
what a fine dog your Zhutchka is now!\'92 Haven\'92t you a bit of meat? He\'92ll\
show you a trick that will make you die with laughing. A piece of meat,\
haven\'92t you got any?\'94\
\
The captain ran across the passage to the landlady, where their cooking\
was done. Not to lose precious time, Kolya, in desperate haste, shouted to\
Perezvon, \'93Dead!\'94 And the dog immediately turned round and lay on his back\
with its four paws in the air. The boys laughed. Ilusha looked on with the\
same suffering smile, but the person most delighted with the dog\'92s\
performance was \'93mamma.\'94 She laughed at the dog and began snapping her\
fingers and calling it, \'93Perezvon, Perezvon!\'94\
\
\'93Nothing will make him get up, nothing!\'94 Kolya cried triumphantly, proud\
of his success. \'93He won\'92t move for all the shouting in the world, but if I\
call to him, he\'92ll jump up in a minute. Ici, Perezvon!\'94 The dog leapt up\
and bounded about, whining with delight. The captain ran back with a piece\
of cooked beef.\
\
\'93Is it hot?\'94 Kolya inquired hurriedly, with a business\uc0\u8208 like air, taking\
the meat. \'93Dogs don\'92t like hot things. No, it\'92s all right. Look,\
everybody, look, Ilusha, look, old man; why aren\'92t you looking? He does\
not look at him, now I\'92ve brought him.\'94\
\
The new trick consisted in making the dog stand motionless with his nose\
out and putting a tempting morsel of meat just on his nose. The luckless\
dog had to stand without moving, with the meat on his nose, as long as his\
master chose to keep him, without a movement, perhaps for half an hour.\
But he kept Perezvon only for a brief moment.\
\
\'93Paid for!\'94 cried Kolya, and the meat passed in a flash from the dog\'92s\
nose to his mouth. The audience, of course, expressed enthusiasm and\
surprise.\
\
\'93Can you really have put off coming all this time simply to train the\
dog?\'94 exclaimed Alyosha, with an involuntary note of reproach in his\
voice.\
\
\'93Simply for that!\'94 answered Kolya, with perfect simplicity. \'93I wanted to\
show him in all his glory.\'94\
\
\'93Perezvon! Perezvon,\'94 called Ilusha suddenly, snapping his thin fingers\
and beckoning to the dog.\
\
\'93What is it? Let him jump up on the bed! _Ici_, Perezvon!\'94 Kolya slapped\
the bed and Perezvon darted up by Ilusha. The boy threw both arms round\
his head and Perezvon instantly licked his cheek. Ilusha crept close to\
him, stretched himself out in bed and hid his face in the dog\'92s shaggy\
coat.\
\
\'93Dear, dear!\'94 kept exclaiming the captain. Kolya sat down again on the\
edge of the bed.\
\
\'93Ilusha, I can show you another trick. I\'92ve brought you a little cannon.\
You remember, I told you about it before and you said how much you\'92d like\
to see it. Well, here, I\'92ve brought it to you.\'94\
\
And Kolya hurriedly pulled out of his satchel the little bronze cannon. He\
hurried, because he was happy himself. Another time he would have waited\
till the sensation made by Perezvon had passed off, now he hurried on\
regardless of all consideration. \'93You are all happy now,\'94 he felt, \'93so\
here\'92s something to make you happier!\'94 He was perfectly enchanted himself.\
\
\'93I\'92ve been coveting this thing for a long while; it\'92s for you, old man,\
it\'92s for you. It belonged to Morozov, it was no use to him, he had it from\
his brother. I swopped a book from father\'92s book\uc0\u8208 case for it, _A Kinsman\
of Mahomet or Salutary Folly_, a scandalous book published in Moscow a\
hundred years ago, before they had any censorship. And Morozov has a taste\
for such things. He was grateful to me, too....\'94\
\
Kolya held the cannon in his hand so that all could see and admire it.\
Ilusha raised himself, and, with his right arm still round the dog, he\
gazed enchanted at the toy. The sensation was even greater when Kolya\
announced that he had gunpowder too, and that it could be fired off at\
once \'93if it won\'92t alarm the ladies.\'94 \'93Mamma\'94 immediately asked to look at\
the toy closer and her request was granted. She was much pleased with the\
little bronze cannon on wheels and began rolling it to and fro on her lap.\
She readily gave permission for the cannon to be fired, without any idea\
of what she had been asked. Kolya showed the powder and the shot. The\
captain, as a military man, undertook to load it, putting in a minute\
quantity of powder. He asked that the shot might be put off till another\
time. The cannon was put on the floor, aiming towards an empty part of the\
room, three grains of powder were thrust into the touch\uc0\u8208 hole and a match\
was put to it. A magnificent explosion followed. Mamma was startled, but\
at once laughed with delight. The boys gazed in speechless triumph. But\
the captain, looking at Ilusha, was more enchanted than any of them. Kolya\
picked up the cannon and immediately presented it to Ilusha, together with\
the powder and the shot.\
\
\'93I got it for you, for you! I\'92ve been keeping it for you a long time,\'94 he\
repeated once more in his delight.\
\
\'93Oh, give it to me! No, give me the cannon!\'94 mamma began begging like a\
little child. Her face showed a piteous fear that she would not get it.\
Kolya was disconcerted. The captain fidgeted uneasily.\
\
\'93Mamma, mamma,\'94 he ran to her, \'93the cannon\'92s yours, of course, but let\
Ilusha have it, because it\'92s a present to him, but it\'92s just as good as\
yours. Ilusha will always let you play with it; it shall belong to both of\
you, both of you.\'94\
\
\'93No, I don\'92t want it to belong to both of us, I want it to be mine\
altogether, not Ilusha\'92s,\'94 persisted mamma, on the point of tears.\
\
\'93Take it, mother, here, keep it!\'94 Ilusha cried. \'93Krassotkin, may I give it\
to my mother?\'94 he turned to Krassotkin with an imploring face, as though\
he were afraid he might be offended at his giving his present to some one\
else.\
\
\'93Of course you may,\'94 Krassotkin assented heartily, and, taking the cannon\
from Ilusha, he handed it himself to mamma with a polite bow. She was so\
touched that she cried.\
\
\'93Ilusha, darling, he\'92s the one who loves his mamma!\'94 she said tenderly,\
and at once began wheeling the cannon to and fro on her lap again.\
\
\'93Mamma, let me kiss your hand.\'94 The captain darted up to her at once and\
did so.\
\
\'93And I never saw such a charming fellow as this nice boy,\'94 said the\
grateful lady, pointing to Krassotkin.\
\
\'93And I\'92ll bring you as much powder as you like, Ilusha. We make the powder\
ourselves now. Borovikov found out how it\'92s made\'97twenty\uc0\u8208 four parts of\
saltpeter, ten of sulphur and six of birchwood charcoal. It\'92s all pounded\
together, mixed into a paste with water and rubbed through a tammy\
sieve\'97that\'92s how it\'92s done.\'94\
\
\'93Smurov told me about your powder, only father says it\'92s not real\
