the room, the washing hanging on a line in the corner, puzzled him. The\
captain, bent double, was bowing low before him.\
\
\'93It\'92s here, sir, here, sir,\'94 he muttered cringingly; \'93it\'92s here, you\'92ve\
come right, you were coming to us...\'94\
\
\'93Sne\uc0\u8208 gi\u8208 ryov?\'94 the doctor said loudly and pompously. \'93Mr. Snegiryov\'97is\
that you?\'94\
\
\'93That\'92s me, sir!\'94\
\
\'93Ah!\'94\
\
The doctor looked round the room with a squeamish air once more and threw\
off his coat, displaying to all eyes the grand decoration at his neck. The\
captain caught the fur coat in the air, and the doctor took off his cap.\
\
\'93Where is the patient?\'94 he asked emphatically.\
\
\
\
Chapter VI. Precocity\
\
\
\'93What do you think the doctor will say to him?\'94 Kolya asked quickly. \'93What\
a repulsive mug, though, hasn\'92t he? I can\'92t endure medicine!\'94\
\
\'93Ilusha is dying. I think that\'92s certain,\'94 answered Alyosha, mournfully.\
\
\'93They are rogues! Medicine\'92s a fraud! I am glad to have made your\
acquaintance, though, Karamazov. I wanted to know you for a long time. I\
am only sorry we meet in such sad circumstances.\'94\
