\
\'93He loves you, that\'92s what it is: he loves you so much. And now he is\
particularly worried.\'94\
\
\'93I should think he might be, with the trial to\uc0\u8208 morrow. And I went to him\
to say something about to\uc0\u8208 morrow, for I dread to think what\'92s going to\
happen then. You say that he is worried, but how worried I am! And he\
talks about the Pole! He\'92s too silly! He is not jealous of Maximushka yet,\
anyway.\'94\
\
\'93My wife was dreadfully jealous over me, too,\'94 Maximov put in his word.\
\
\'93Jealous of you?\'94 Grushenka laughed in spite of herself. \'93Of whom could\
she have been jealous?\'94\
\
\'93Of the servant girls.\'94\
\
\'93Hold your tongue, Maximushka, I am in no laughing mood now; I feel angry.\
Don\'92t ogle the pies. I shan\'92t give you any; they are not good for you, and\
I won\'92t give you any vodka either. I have to look after him, too, just as\
though I kept an almshouse,\'94 she laughed.\
\
\'93I don\'92t deserve your kindness. I am a worthless creature,\'94 said Maximov,\
with tears in his voice. \'93You would do better to spend your kindness on\
people of more use than me.\'94\
\
\'93Ech, every one is of use, Maximushka, and how can we tell who\'92s of most\
use? If only that Pole didn\'92t exist, Alyosha. He\'92s taken it into his head\
to fall ill, too, to\uc0\u8208 day. I\'92ve been to see him also. And I shall send him\
some pies, too, on purpose. I hadn\'92t sent him any, but Mitya accused me of\
it, so now I shall send some! Ah, here\'92s Fenya with a letter! Yes, it\'92s\
from the Poles\'97begging again!\'94\
\
Pan Mussyalovitch had indeed sent an extremely long and characteristically\
eloquent letter in which he begged her to lend him three roubles. In the\
letter was enclosed a receipt for the sum, with a promise to repay it\
within three months, signed by Pan Vrublevsky as well. Grushenka had\
received many such letters, accompanied by such receipts, from her former\
lover during the fortnight of her convalescence. But she knew that the two\
Poles had been to ask after her health during her illness. The first\
letter Grushenka got from them was a long one, written on large notepaper\
and with a big family crest on the seal. It was so obscure and rhetorical\
that Grushenka put it down before she had read half, unable to make head\
or tail of it. She could not attend to letters then. The first letter was\
followed next day by another in which Pan Mussyalovitch begged her for a\
