\
\'93And Grigory\'97Grigory Vassilyevitch\'97sticks to his story that the door was\
open, persists that he saw it\'97there\'92s no shaking him. I went and talked to\
him myself. He\'92s rude about it, too.\'94\
\
\'93Yes, that\'92s perhaps the strongest evidence against him,\'94 said Alyosha.\
\
\'93And as for Mitya\'92s being mad, he certainly seems like it now,\'94 Grushenka\
began with a peculiarly anxious and mysterious air. \'93Do you know, Alyosha,\
I\'92ve been wanting to talk to you about it for a long time. I go to him\
every day and simply wonder at him. Tell me, now, what do you suppose he\'92s\
always talking about? He talks and talks and I can make nothing of it. I\
fancied he was talking of something intellectual that I couldn\'92t\
