\
Alyosha sat plunged in thought, considering something. The news evidently\
impressed him.\
\
\'93Ivan doesn\'92t talk to me of Mitya\'92s case,\'94 he said slowly. \'93He\'92s said very\
little to me these last two months. And whenever I go to see him, he seems\
vexed at my coming, so I\'92ve not been to him for the last three weeks.\
H\'92m!... if he was there a week ago ... there certainly has been a change\
in Mitya this week.\'94\
\
\'93There has been a change,\'94 Grushenka assented quickly. \'93They have a\
secret, they have a secret! Mitya told me himself there was a secret, and\
such a secret that Mitya can\'92t rest. Before then, he was cheerful\'97and,\
indeed, he is cheerful now\'97but when he shakes his head like that, you\
know, and strides about the room and keeps pulling at the hair on his\
right temple with his right hand, I know there is something on his mind\
worrying him.... I know! He was cheerful before, though, indeed, he is\
cheerful to\uc0\u8208 day.\'94\
\
\'93But you said he was worried.\'94\
\
\'93Yes, he is worried and yet cheerful. He keeps on being irritable for a\
minute and then cheerful and then irritable again. And you know, Alyosha,\
I am constantly wondering at him\'97with this awful thing hanging over him,\
he sometimes laughs at such trifles as though he were a baby himself.\'94\
\
\'93And did he really tell you not to tell me about Ivan? Did he say, \'91Don\'92t\
tell him\'92?\'94\
\
\'93Yes, he told me, \'91Don\'92t tell him.\'92 It\'92s you that Mitya\'92s most afraid of.\
Because it\'92s a secret: he said himself it was a secret. Alyosha, darling,\
go to him and find out what their secret is and come and tell me,\'94\
Grushenka besought him with sudden eagerness. \'93Set my mind at rest that I\
may know the worst that\'92s in store for me. That\'92s why I sent for you.\'94\
\
\'93You think it\'92s something to do with you? If it were, he wouldn\'92t have\
told you there was a secret.\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t know. Perhaps he wants to tell me, but doesn\'92t dare to. He warns\
me. There is a secret, he tells me, but he won\'92t tell me what it is.\'94\
\
\'93What do you think yourself?\'94\
\
\'93What do I think? It\'92s the end for me, that\'92s what I think. They all three\
have been plotting my end, for Katerina\'92s in it. It\'92s all Katerina, it all\
comes from her. She is this and that, and that means that I am not. He\
tells me that beforehand\'97warns me. He is planning to throw me over, that\'92s\
the whole secret. They\'92ve planned it together, the three of them\'97Mitya,\
Katerina, and Ivan Fyodorovitch. Alyosha, I\'92ve been wanting to ask you a\
long time. A week ago he suddenly told me that Ivan was in love with\
Katerina, because he often goes to see her. Did he tell me the truth or\
not? Tell me, on your conscience, tell me the worst.\'94\
\
\'93I won\'92t tell you a lie. Ivan is not in love with Katerina Ivanovna, I\
think.\'94\
\
\'93Oh, that\'92s what I thought! He is lying to me, shameless deceiver, that\'92s\
what it is! And he was jealous of me just now, so as to put the blame on\
me afterwards. He is stupid, he can\'92t disguise what he is doing; he is so\
open, you know.... But I\'92ll give it to him, I\'92ll give it to him! \'91You\
believe I did it,\'92 he said. He said that to me, to me. He reproached me\
with that! God forgive him! You wait, I\'92ll make it hot for Katerina at the\
trial! I\'92ll just say a word then ... I\'92ll tell everything then!\'94\
\
And again she cried bitterly.\
\
\'93This I can tell you for certain, Grushenka,\'94 Alyosha said, getting up.\
\'93First, that he loves you, loves you more than any one in the world, and\
you only, believe me. I know. I do know. The second thing is that I don\'92t\
want to worm his secret out of him, but if he\'92ll tell me of himself to\uc0\u8208 \
day, I shall tell him straight out that I have promised to tell you. Then\
I\'92ll come to you to\uc0\u8208 day, and tell you. Only ... I fancy ... Katerina\
Ivanovna has nothing to do with it, and that the secret is about something\
else. That\'92s certain. It isn\'92t likely it\'92s about Katerina Ivanovna, it\
seems to me. Good\uc0\u8208 by for now.\'94\
\
Alyosha shook hands with her. Grushenka was still crying. He saw that she\
put little faith in his consolation, but she was better for having had her\
sorrow out, for having spoken of it. He was sorry to leave her in such a\
state of mind, but he was in haste. He had a great many things to do\
still.\
\
\
\
Chapter II. The Injured Foot\
\
\
The first of these things was at the house of Madame Hohlakov, and he\
hurried there to get it over as quickly as possible and not be too late\
for Mitya. Madame Hohlakov had been slightly ailing for the last three\
weeks: her foot had for some reason swollen up, and though she was not in\
bed, she lay all day half\uc0\u8208 reclining on the couch in her boudoir, in a\
fascinating but decorous _d\'e9shabill\'e9_. Alyosha had once noted with\
innocent amusement that, in spite of her illness, Madame Hohlakov had\
begun to be rather dressy\'97top\uc0\u8208 knots, ribbons, loose wrappers, had made\
their appearance, and he had an inkling of the reason, though he dismissed\
such ideas from his mind as frivolous. During the last two months the\
young official, Perhotin, had become a regular visitor at the house.\
\
Alyosha had not called for four days and he was in haste to go straight to\
Lise, as it was with her he had to speak, for Lise had sent a maid to him\
the previous day, specially asking him to come to her \'93about something\
very important,\'94 a request which, for certain reasons, had interest for\
Alyosha. But while the maid went to take his name in to Lise, Madame\
Hohlakov heard of his arrival from some one, and immediately sent to beg\
him to come to her \'93just for one minute.\'94 Alyosha reflected that it was\
better to accede to the mamma\'92s request, or else she would be sending down\
to Lise\'92s room every minute that he was there. Madame Hohlakov was lying\
on a couch. She was particularly smartly dressed and was evidently in a\
state of extreme nervous excitement. She greeted Alyosha with cries of\
rapture.\
\
\'93It\'92s ages, ages, perfect ages since I\'92ve seen you! It\'92s a whole week\'97only\
think of it! Ah, but you were here only four days ago, on Wednesday. You\
have come to see Lise. I\'92m sure you meant to slip into her room on tiptoe,\
without my hearing you. My dear, dear Alexey Fyodorovitch, if you only\
knew how worried I am about her! But of that later, though that\'92s the most\
important thing, of that later. Dear Alexey Fyodorovitch, I trust you\
implicitly with my Lise. Since the death of Father Zossima\'97God rest his\
soul!\'94 (she crossed herself)\'97\'93I look upon you as a monk, though you look\
charming in your new suit. Where did you find such a tailor in these\
parts? No, no, that\'92s not the chief thing\'97of that later. Forgive me for\
sometimes calling you Alyosha; an old woman like me may take liberties,\'94\
she smiled coquettishly; \'93but that will do later, too. The important thing\
is that I shouldn\'92t forget what is important. Please remind me of it\
yourself. As soon as my tongue runs away with me, you just say \'91the\
important thing?\'92 Ach! how do I know now what is of most importance? Ever\
since Lise took back her promise\'97her childish promise, Alexey\
Fyodorovitch\'97to marry you, you\'92ve realized, of course, that it was only\
the playful fancy of a sick child who had been so long confined to her\
chair\'97thank God, she can walk now!... that new doctor Katya sent for from\
Moscow for your unhappy brother, who will to\uc0\u8208 morrow\'97But why speak of to\u8208 \
morrow? I am ready to die at the very thought of to\uc0\u8208 morrow. Ready to die\
of curiosity.... That doctor was with us yesterday and saw Lise.... I paid\
him fifty roubles for the visit. But that\'92s not the point, that\'92s not the\
point again. You see, I\'92m mixing everything up. I am in such a hurry. Why\
am I in a hurry? I don\'92t understand. It\'92s awful how I seem growing unable\
to understand anything. Everything seems mixed up in a sort of tangle. I\
am afraid you are so bored you will jump up and run away, and that will be\
all I shall see of you. Goodness! Why are we sitting here and no coffee?\
Yulia, Glafira, coffee!\'94\
\
Alyosha made haste to thank her, and said that he had only just had\
coffee.\
\
\'93Where?\'94\
\
\'93At Agrafena Alexandrovna\'92s.\'94\
\
\'93At ... at that woman\'92s? Ah, it\'92s she has brought ruin on every one. I\
know nothing about it though. They say she has become a saint, though it\'92s\
rather late in the day. She had better have done it before. What use is it\
now? Hush, hush, Alexey Fyodorovitch, for I have so much to say to you\
that I am afraid I shall tell you nothing. This awful trial ... I shall\
certainly go, I am making arrangements. I shall be carried there in my\
chair; besides I can sit up. I shall have people with me. And, you know, I\
am a witness. How shall I speak, how shall I speak? I don\'92t know what I\
shall say. One has to take an oath, hasn\'92t one?\'94\
\
\'93Yes; but I don\'92t think you will be able to go.\'94\
\
\'93I can sit up. Ah, you put me out! Ah! this trial, this savage act, and\
then they are all going to Siberia, some are getting married, and all this\
so quickly, so quickly, everything\'92s changing, and at last\'97nothing. All\
grow old and have death to look forward to. Well, so be it! I am weary.\
This Katya, _cette charmante personne_, has disappointed all my hopes. Now\
she is going to follow one of your brothers to Siberia, and your other\
brother is going to follow her, and will live in the nearest town, and\
they will all torment one another. It drives me out of my mind. Worst of\
all\'97the publicity. The story has been told a million times over in all the\
papers in Moscow and Petersburg. Ah! yes, would you believe it, there\'92s a\
paragraph that I was \'91a dear friend\'92 of your brother\'92s \'97\'97, I can\'92t repeat\
the horrid word. Just fancy, just fancy!\'94\
\
\'93Impossible! Where was the paragraph? What did it say?\'94\
\
\'93I\'92ll show you directly. I got the paper and read it yesterday. Here, in\
the Petersburg paper _Gossip_. The paper began coming out this year. I am\
awfully fond of gossip, and I take it in, and now it pays me out\'97this is\
what gossip comes to! Here it is, here, this passage. Read it.\'94\
\
And she handed Alyosha a sheet of newspaper which had been under her\
pillow.\
\
It was not exactly that she was upset, she seemed overwhelmed and perhaps\
everything really was mixed up in a tangle in her head. The paragraph was\
very typical, and must have been a great shock to her, but, fortunately\
perhaps, she was unable to keep her mind fixed on any one subject at that\
moment, and so might race off in a minute to something else and quite\
forget the newspaper.\
\
Alyosha was well aware that the story of the terrible case had spread all\
over Russia. And, good heavens! what wild rumors about his brother, about\
the Karamazovs, and about himself he had read in the course of those two\
months, among other equally credible items! One paper had even stated that\
he had gone into a monastery and become a monk, in horror at his brother\'92s\
crime. Another contradicted this, and stated that he and his elder, Father\
Zossima, had broken into the monastery chest and \'93made tracks from the\
monastery.\'94 The present paragraph in the paper _Gossip_ was under the\
heading, \'93The Karamazov Case at Skotoprigonyevsk.\'94 (That, alas! was the\
name of our little town. I had hitherto kept it concealed.) It was brief,\
and Madame Hohlakov was not directly mentioned in it. No names appeared,\
in fact. It was merely stated that the criminal, whose approaching trial\
was making such a sensation\'97retired army captain, an idle swaggerer, and\
reactionary bully\'97was continually involved in amorous intrigues, and\
particularly popular with certain ladies \'93who were pining in solitude.\'94\
One such lady, a pining widow, who tried to seem young though she had a\
grown\uc0\u8208 up daughter, was so fascinated by him that only two hours before the\
crime she offered him three thousand roubles, on condition that he would\
elope with her to the gold mines. But the criminal, counting on escaping\
punishment, had preferred to murder his father to get the three thousand\
rather than go off to Siberia with the middle\uc0\u8208 aged charms of his pining\
lady. This playful paragraph finished, of course, with an outburst of\
generous indignation at the wickedness of parricide and at the lately\
abolished institution of serfdom. Reading it with curiosity, Alyosha\
folded up the paper and handed it back to Madame Hohlakov.\
\
\'93Well, that must be me,\'94 she hurried on again. \'93Of course I am meant.\
Scarcely more than an hour before, I suggested gold mines to him, and here\
they talk of \'91middle\uc0\u8208 aged charms\'92 as though that were my motive! He writes\
that out of spite! God Almighty forgive him for the middle\uc0\u8208 aged charms, as\
I forgive him! You know it\'92s\'97 Do you know who it is? It\'92s your friend\
Rakitin.\'94\
\
\'93Perhaps,\'94 said Alyosha, \'93though I\'92ve heard nothing about it.\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s he, it\'92s he! No \'91perhaps\'92 about it. You know I turned him out of the\
house.... You know all that story, don\'92t you?\'94\
\
\'93I know that you asked him not to visit you for the future, but why it\
was, I haven\'92t heard ... from you, at least.\'94\
\
\'93Ah, then you\'92ve heard it from him! He abuses me, I suppose, abuses me\
dreadfully?\'94\
\
\'93Yes, he does; but then he abuses every one. But why you\'92ve given him up I\
haven\'92t heard from him either. I meet him very seldom now, indeed. We are\
not friends.\'94\
\
\'93Well, then, I\'92ll tell you all about it. There\'92s no help for it, I\'92ll\
confess, for there is one point in which I was perhaps to blame. Only a\
little, little point, so little that perhaps it doesn\'92t count. You see, my\
dear boy\'94\'97Madame Hohlakov suddenly looked arch and a charming, though\
enigmatic, smile played about her lips\'97\'93you see, I suspect ... You must\
forgive me, Alyosha. I am like a mother to you.... No, no; quite the\
contrary. I speak to you now as though you were my father\'97mother\'92s quite\
out of place. Well, it\'92s as though I were confessing to Father Zossima,\
that\'92s just it. I called you a monk just now. Well, that poor young man,\
your friend, Rakitin (Mercy on us! I can\'92t be angry with him. I feel\
cross, but not very), that frivolous young man, would you believe it,\
seems to have taken it into his head to fall in love with me. I only\
noticed it later. At first\'97a month ago\'97he only began to come oftener to\
see me, almost every day; though, of course, we were acquainted before. I\
knew nothing about it ... and suddenly it dawned upon me, and I began to\
notice things with surprise. You know, two months ago, that modest,\
charming, excellent young man, Pyotr Ilyitch Perhotin, who\'92s in the\
service here, began to be a regular visitor at the house. You met him here\
ever so many times yourself. And he is an excellent, earnest young man,\
isn\'92t he? He comes once every three days, not every day (though I should\
be glad to see him every day), and always so well dressed. Altogether, I\
love young people, Alyosha, talented, modest, like you, and he has almost\
the mind of a statesman, he talks so charmingly, and I shall certainly,\
certainly try and get promotion for him. He is a future diplomat. On that\
awful day he almost saved me from death by coming in the night. And your\
friend Rakitin comes in such boots, and always stretches them out on the\
carpet.... He began hinting at his feelings, in fact, and one day, as he\
was going, he squeezed my hand terribly hard. My foot began to swell\
directly after he pressed my hand like that. He had met Pyotr Ilyitch here\
before, and would you believe it, he is always gibing at him, growling at\
him, for some reason. I simply looked at the way they went on together and\
laughed inwardly. So I was sitting here alone\'97no, I was laid up then.\
Well, I was lying here alone and suddenly Rakitin comes in, and only\
fancy! brought me some verses of his own composition\'97a short poem, on my\
bad foot: that is, he described my foot in a poem. Wait a minute\'97how did\
it go?\
\
\
    A captivating little foot.\
\
\
It began somehow like that. I can never remember poetry. I\'92ve got it here.\
I\'92ll show it to you later. But it\'92s a charming thing\'97charming; and, you\
know, it\'92s not only about the foot, it had a good moral, too, a charming\
idea, only I\'92ve forgotten it; in fact, it was just the thing for an album.\
So, of course, I thanked him, and he was evidently flattered. I\'92d hardly\
had time to thank him when in comes Pyotr Ilyitch, and Rakitin suddenly\
looked as black as night. I could see that Pyotr Ilyitch was in the way,\
for Rakitin certainly wanted to say something after giving me the verses.\
I had a presentiment of it; but Pyotr Ilyitch came in. I showed Pyotr\
Ilyitch the verses and didn\'92t say who was the author. But I am convinced\
that he guessed, though he won\'92t own it to this day, and declares he had\
no idea. But he says that on purpose. Pyotr Ilyitch began to laugh at\
once, and fell to criticizing it. \'91Wretched doggerel,\'92 he said they were,\
\'91some divinity student must have written them,\'92 and with such vehemence,\
such vehemence! Then, instead of laughing, your friend flew into a rage.\
\'91Good gracious!\'92 I thought, \'91they\'92ll fly at each other.\'92 \'91It was I who\
wrote them,\'92 said he. \'91I wrote them as a joke,\'92 he said, \'91for I think it\
degrading to write verses.... But they are good poetry. They want to put a\
monument to your Pushkin for writing about women\'92s feet, while I wrote\
with a moral purpose, and you,\'92 said he, \'91are an advocate of serfdom.\
You\'92ve no humane ideas,\'92 said he. \'91You have no modern enlightened\
feelings, you are uninfluenced by progress, you are a mere official,\'92 he\
said, \'91and you take bribes.\'92 Then I began screaming and imploring them.\
And, you know, Pyotr Ilyitch is anything but a coward. He at once took up\
the most gentlemanly tone, looked at him sarcastically, listened, and\
apologized. \'91I\'92d no idea,\'92 said he. \'91I shouldn\'92t have said it, if I had\
known. I should have praised it. Poets are all so irritable,\'92 he said. In\
short, he laughed at him under cover of the most gentlemanly tone. He\
explained to me afterwards that it was all sarcastic. I thought he was in\
earnest. Only as I lay there, just as before you now, I thought, \'91Would\
it, or would it not, be the proper thing for me to turn Rakitin out for\
shouting so rudely at a visitor in my house?\'92 And, would you believe it, I\
lay here, shut my eyes, and wondered, would it be the proper thing or not.\
I kept worrying and worrying, and my heart began to beat, and I couldn\'92t\
make up my mind whether to make an outcry or not. One voice seemed to be\
telling me, \'91Speak,\'92 and the other \'91No, don\'92t speak.\'92 And no sooner had\
the second voice said that than I cried out, and fainted. Of course, there\
was a fuss. I got up suddenly and said to Rakitin, \'91It\'92s painful for me to\
say it, but I don\'92t wish to see you in my house again.\'92 So I turned him\
out. Ah! Alexey Fyodorovitch, I know myself I did wrong. I was putting it\
on. I wasn\'92t angry with him at all, really; but I suddenly fancied\'97that\
was what did it\'97that it would be such a fine scene.... And yet, believe\
me, it was quite natural, for I really shed tears and cried for several\
days afterwards, and then suddenly, one afternoon, I forgot all about it.\
So it\'92s a fortnight since he\'92s been here, and I kept wondering whether he\
would come again. I wondered even yesterday, then suddenly last night came\
this _Gossip_. I read it and gasped. Who could have written it? He must\
have written it. He went home, sat down, wrote it on the spot, sent it,\
and they put it in. It was a fortnight ago, you see. But, Alyosha, it\'92s\
awful how I keep talking and don\'92t say what I want to say. Ah! the words\
