\
\'93It\'92s very important for me to be in time to see my brother to\uc0\u8208 day,\'94\
Alyosha faltered.\
\
\'93To be sure, to be sure! You bring it all back to me. Listen, what is an\
aberration?\'94\
\
\'93What aberration?\'94 asked Alyosha, wondering.\
\
\'93In the legal sense. An aberration in which everything is pardonable.\
Whatever you do, you will be acquitted at once.\'94\
\
\'93What do you mean?\'94\
\
\'93I\'92ll tell you. This Katya ... Ah! she is a charming, charming creature,\
only I never can make out who it is she is in love with. She was with me\
some time ago and I couldn\'92t get anything out of her. Especially as she\
won\'92t talk to me except on the surface now. She is always talking about my\
health and nothing else, and she takes up such a tone with me, too. I\
simply said to myself, \'91Well, so be it. I don\'92t care\'92... Oh, yes. I was\
talking of aberration. This doctor has come. You know a doctor has come?\
Of course, you know it\'97the one who discovers madmen. You wrote for him.\
No, it wasn\'92t you, but Katya. It\'92s all Katya\'92s doing. Well, you see, a man\
may be sitting perfectly sane and suddenly have an aberration. He may be\
conscious and know what he is doing and yet be in a state of aberration.\
And there\'92s no doubt that Dmitri Fyodorovitch was suffering from\
aberration. They found out about aberration as soon as the law courts were\
reformed. It\'92s all the good effect of the reformed law courts. The doctor\
has been here and questioned me about that evening, about the gold mines.\
\'91How did he seem then?\'92 he asked me. He must have been in a state of\
aberration. He came in shouting, \'91Money, money, three thousand! Give me\
three thousand!\'92 and then went away and immediately did the murder. \'91I\
don\'92t want to murder him,\'92 he said, and he suddenly went and murdered him.\
That\'92s why they\'92ll acquit him, because he struggled against it and yet he\
murdered him.\'94\
\
\'93But he didn\'92t murder him,\'94 Alyosha interrupted rather sharply. He felt\
more and more sick with anxiety and impatience.\
\
\'93Yes, I know it was that old man Grigory murdered him.\'94\
\
\'93Grigory?\'94 cried Alyosha.\
\
\'93Yes, yes; it was Grigory. He lay as Dmitri Fyodorovitch struck him down,\
and then got up, saw the door open, went in and killed Fyodor Pavlovitch.\'94\
\
\'93But why, why?\'94\
\
\'93Suffering from aberration. When he recovered from the blow Dmitri\
Fyodorovitch gave him on the head, he was suffering from aberration; he\
went and committed the murder. As for his saying he didn\'92t, he very likely\
doesn\'92t remember. Only, you know, it\'92ll be better, ever so much better, if\
Dmitri Fyodorovitch murdered him. And that\'92s how it must have been, though\
I say it was Grigory. It certainly was Dmitri Fyodorovitch, and that\'92s\
better, ever so much better! Oh! not better that a son should have killed\
his father, I don\'92t defend that. Children ought to honor their parents,\
and yet it would be better if it were he, as you\'92d have nothing to cry\
over then, for he did it when he was unconscious or rather when he was\
conscious, but did not know what he was doing. Let them acquit him\'97that\'92s\
so humane, and would show what a blessing reformed law courts are. I knew\
nothing about it, but they say they have been so a long time. And when I\
heard it yesterday, I was so struck by it that I wanted to send for you at\
once. And if he is acquitted, make him come straight from the law courts\
to dinner with me, and I\'92ll have a party of friends, and we\'92ll drink to\
the reformed law courts. I don\'92t believe he\'92d be dangerous; besides, I\'92ll\
invite a great many friends, so that he could always be led out if he did\
anything. And then he might be made a justice of the peace or something in\
another town, for those who have been in trouble themselves make the best\
judges. And, besides, who isn\'92t suffering from aberration nowadays?\'97you,\
I, all of us are in a state of aberration, and there are ever so many\
examples of it: a man sits singing a song, suddenly something annoys him,\
he takes a pistol and shoots the first person he comes across, and no one\
blames him for it. I read that lately, and all the doctors confirm it. The\
doctors are always confirming; they confirm anything. Why, my Lise is in a\
state of aberration. She made me cry again yesterday, and the day before,\
too, and to\uc0\u8208 day I suddenly realized that it\'92s all due to aberration. Oh,\
Lise grieves me so! I believe she\'92s quite mad. Why did she send for you?\
Did she send for you or did you come of yourself?\'94\
\
\'93Yes, she sent for me, and I am just going to her.\'94 Alyosha got up\
resolutely.\
\
\'93Oh, my dear, dear Alexey Fyodorovitch, perhaps that\'92s what\'92s most\
important,\'94 Madame Hohlakov cried, suddenly bursting into tears. \'93God\
knows I trust Lise to you with all my heart, and it\'92s no matter her\
sending for you on the sly, without telling her mother. But forgive me, I\
can\'92t trust my daughter so easily to your brother Ivan Fyodorovitch,\
though I still consider him the most chivalrous young man. But only fancy,\
he\'92s been to see Lise and I knew nothing about it!\'94\
\
\'93How? What? When?\'94 Alyosha was exceedingly surprised. He had not sat down\
again and listened standing.\
\
\'93I will tell you; that\'92s perhaps why I asked you to come, for I don\'92t know\
now why I did ask you to come. Well, Ivan Fyodorovitch has been to see me\
twice, since he came back from Moscow. First time he came as a friend to\
call on me, and the second time Katya was here and he came because he\
heard she was here. I didn\'92t, of course, expect him to come often, knowing\
what a lot he has to do as it is, _vous comprenez, cette affaire et la\
mort terrible de votre papa_. But I suddenly heard he\'92d been here again,\
not to see me but to see Lise. That\'92s six days ago now. He came, stayed\
five minutes, and went away. And I didn\'92t hear of it till three days\
afterwards, from Glafira, so it was a great shock to me. I sent for Lise\
directly. She laughed. \'91He thought you were asleep,\'92 she said, \'91and came\
in to me to ask after your health.\'92 Of course, that\'92s how it happened. But\
Lise, Lise, mercy on us, how she distresses me! Would you believe it, one\
night, four days ago, just after you saw her last time, and had gone away,\
she suddenly had a fit, screaming, shrieking, hysterics! Why is it I never\
have hysterics? Then, next day another fit, and the same thing on the\
third, and yesterday too, and then yesterday that aberration. She suddenly\
screamed out, \'91I hate Ivan Fyodorovitch. I insist on your never letting\
him come to the house again.\'92 I was struck dumb at these amazing words,\
and answered, \'91On what grounds could I refuse to see such an excellent\
young man, a young man of such learning too, and so unfortunate?\'92\'97for all\
this business is a misfortune, isn\'92t it? She suddenly burst out laughing\
at my words, and so rudely, you know. Well, I was pleased; I thought I had\
amused her and the fits would pass off, especially as I wanted to refuse\
to see Ivan Fyodorovitch anyway on account of his strange visits without\
my knowledge, and meant to ask him for an explanation. But early this\
morning Lise waked up and flew into a passion with Yulia and, would you\
believe it, slapped her in the face. That\'92s monstrous; I am always polite\
to my servants. And an hour later she was hugging Yulia\'92s feet and kissing\
them. She sent a message to me that she wasn\'92t coming to me at all, and\
would never come and see me again, and when I dragged myself down to her,\
she rushed to kiss me, crying, and as she kissed me, she pushed me out of\
the room without saying a word, so I couldn\'92t find out what was the\
matter. Now, dear Alexey Fyodorovitch, I rest all my hopes on you, and, of\
course, my whole life is in your hands. I simply beg you to go to Lise and\
find out everything from her, as you alone can, and come back and tell\
me\'97me, her mother, for you understand it will be the death of me, simply\
the death of me, if this goes on, or else I shall run away. I can stand no\
more. I have patience; but I may lose patience, and then ... then\
something awful will happen. Ah, dear me! At last, Pyotr Ilyitch!\'94 cried\
Madame Hohlakov, beaming all over as she saw Perhotin enter the room. \'93You\
are late, you are late! Well, sit down, speak, put us out of suspense.\
What does the counsel say. Where are you off to, Alexey Fyodorovitch?\'94\
\
\'93To Lise.\'94\
\
\'93Oh, yes. You won\'92t forget, you won\'92t forget what I asked you? It\'92s a\
question of life and death!\'94\
\
\'93Of course, I won\'92t forget, if I can ... but I am so late,\'94 muttered\
Alyosha, beating a hasty retreat.\
\
\'93No, be sure, be sure to come in; don\'92t say \'91If you can.\'92 I shall die if\
you don\'92t,\'94 Madame Hohlakov called after him, but Alyosha had already left\
the room.\
\
\
\
Chapter III. A Little Demon\
\
\
Going in to Lise, he found her half reclining in the invalid\uc0\u8208 chair, in\
which she had been wheeled when she was unable to walk. She did not move\
to meet him, but her sharp, keen eyes were simply riveted on his face.\
There was a feverish look in her eyes, her face was pale and yellow.\
Alyosha was amazed at the change that had taken place in her in three\
days. She was positively thinner. She did not hold out her hand to him. He\
touched the thin, long fingers which lay motionless on her dress, then he\
sat down facing her, without a word.\
\
\'93I know you are in a hurry to get to the prison,\'94 Lise said curtly, \'93and\
mamma\'92s kept you there for hours; she\'92s just been telling you about me and\
Yulia.\'94\
\
\'93How do you know?\'94 asked Alyosha.\
\
\'93I\'92ve been listening. Why do you stare at me? I want to listen and I do\
listen, there\'92s no harm in that. I don\'92t apologize.\'94\
\
\'93You are upset about something?\'94\
\
\'93On the contrary, I am very happy. I\'92ve only just been reflecting for the\
thirtieth time what a good thing it is I refused you and shall not be your\
wife. You are not fit to be a husband. If I were to marry you and give you\
a note to take to the man I loved after you, you\'92d take it and be sure to\
give it to him and bring an answer back, too. If you were forty, you would\
still go on taking my love\uc0\u8208 letters for me.\'94\
\
She suddenly laughed.\
\
\'93There is something spiteful and yet open\uc0\u8208 hearted about you,\'94 Alyosha\
smiled to her.\
\
\'93The open\uc0\u8208 heartedness consists in my not being ashamed of myself with you.\
What\'92s more, I don\'92t want to feel ashamed with you, just with you.\
Alyosha, why is it I don\'92t respect you? I am very fond of you, but I don\'92t\
respect you. If I respected you, I shouldn\'92t talk to you without shame,\
should I?\'94\
\
\'93No.\'94\
\
\'93But do you believe that I am not ashamed with you?\'94\
\
\'93No, I don\'92t believe it.\'94\
\
Lise laughed nervously again; she spoke rapidly.\
\
\'93I sent your brother, Dmitri Fyodorovitch, some sweets in prison. Alyosha,\
you know, you are quite pretty! I shall love you awfully for having so\
quickly allowed me not to love you.\'94\
\
\'93Why did you send for me to\uc0\u8208 day, Lise?\'94\
\
\'93I wanted to tell you of a longing I have. I should like some one to\
torture me, marry me and then torture me, deceive me and go away. I don\'92t\
want to be happy.\'94\
\
\'93You are in love with disorder?\'94\
\
\'93Yes, I want disorder. I keep wanting to set fire to the house. I keep\
imagining how I\'92ll creep up and set fire to the house on the sly; it must\
be on the sly. They\'92ll try to put it out, but it\'92ll go on burning. And I\
shall know and say nothing. Ah, what silliness! And how bored I am!\'94\
\
She waved her hand with a look of repulsion.\
\
\'93It\'92s your luxurious life,\'94 said Alyosha, softly.\
\
\'93Is it better, then, to be poor?\'94\
\
\'93Yes, it is better.\'94\
\
\'93That\'92s what your monk taught you. That\'92s not true. Let me be rich and all\
the rest poor, I\'92ll eat sweets and drink cream and not give any to any one\
else. Ach, don\'92t speak, don\'92t say anything,\'94 she shook her hand at him,\
though Alyosha had not opened his mouth. \'93You\'92ve told me all that before,\
I know it all by heart. It bores me. If I am ever poor, I shall murder\
somebody, and even if I am rich, I may murder some one, perhaps\'97why do\
nothing! But do you know, I should like to reap, cut the rye? I\'92ll marry\
you, and you shall become a peasant, a real peasant; we\'92ll keep a colt,\
shall we? Do you know Kalganov?\'94\
\
\'93Yes.\'94\
\
\'93He is always wandering about, dreaming. He says, \'91Why live in real life?\
It\'92s better to dream. One can dream the most delightful things, but real\
life is a bore.\'92 But he\'92ll be married soon for all that; he\'92s been making\
love to me already. Can you spin tops?\'94\
\
\'93Yes.\'94\
\
\'93Well, he\'92s just like a top: he wants to be wound up and set spinning and\
then to be lashed, lashed, lashed with a whip. If I marry him, I\'92ll keep\
him spinning all his life. You are not ashamed to be with me?\'94\
\
\'93No.\'94\
\
\'93You are awfully cross, because I don\'92t talk about holy things. I don\'92t\
want to be holy. What will they do to one in the next world for the\
greatest sin? You must know all about that.\'94\
\
\'93God will censure you.\'94 Alyosha was watching her steadily.\
\
\'93That\'92s just what I should like. I would go up and they would censure me,\
and I would burst out laughing in their faces. I should dreadfully like to\
set fire to the house, Alyosha, to our house; you still don\'92t believe me?\'94\
\
\'93Why? There are children of twelve years old, who have a longing to set\
fire to something and they do set things on fire, too. It\'92s a sort of\
disease.\'94\
\
\'93That\'92s not true, that\'92s not true; there may be children, but that\'92s not\
what I mean.\'94\
\
\'93You take evil for good; it\'92s a passing crisis, it\'92s the result of your\
illness, perhaps.\'94\
\
\'93You do despise me, though! It\'92s simply that I don\'92t want to do good, I\
want to do evil, and it has nothing to do with illness.\'94\
\
\'93Why do evil?\'94\
\
\'93So that everything might be destroyed. Ah, how nice it would be if\
everything were destroyed! You know, Alyosha, I sometimes think of doing a\
fearful lot of harm and everything bad, and I should do it for a long\
while on the sly and suddenly every one would find it out. Every one will\
stand round and point their fingers at me and I would look at them all.\
That would be awfully nice. Why would it be so nice, Alyosha?\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t know. It\'92s a craving to destroy something good or, as you say, to\
set fire to something. It happens sometimes.\'94\
\
\'93I not only say it, I shall do it.\'94\
\
\'93I believe you.\'94\
\
\'93Ah, how I love you for saying you believe me. And you are not lying one\
little bit. But perhaps you think that I am saying all this on purpose to\
annoy you?\'94\
\
\'93No, I don\'92t think that ... though perhaps there is a little desire to do\
that in it, too.\'94\
\
\'93There is a little. I never can tell lies to you,\'94 she declared, with a\
strange fire in her eyes.\
\
What struck Alyosha above everything was her earnestness. There was not a\
trace of humor or jesting in her face now, though, in old days, fun and\
gayety never deserted her even at her most \'93earnest\'94 moments.\
\
\'93There are moments when people love crime,\'94 said Alyosha thoughtfully.\
\
\'93Yes, yes! You have uttered my thought; they love crime, every one loves\
crime, they love it always, not at some \'91moments.\'92 You know, it\'92s as\
though people have made an agreement to lie about it and have lied about\
it ever since. They all declare that they hate evil, but secretly they all\
love it.\'94\
\
\'93And are you still reading nasty books?\'94\
\
\'93Yes, I am. Mamma reads them and hides them under her pillow and I steal\
them.\'94\
\
\'93Aren\'92t you ashamed to destroy yourself?\'94\
\
\'93I want to destroy myself. There\'92s a boy here, who lay down between the\
railway lines when the train was passing. Lucky fellow! Listen, your\
brother is being tried now for murdering his father and every one loves\
his having killed his father.\'94\
\
\'93Loves his having killed his father?\'94\
\
\'93Yes, loves it; every one loves it! Everybody says it\'92s so awful, but\
secretly they simply love it. I for one love it.\'94\
\
\'93There is some truth in what you say about every one,\'94 said Alyosha\
softly.\
\
\'93Oh, what ideas you have!\'94 Lise shrieked in delight. \'93And you a monk, too!\
You wouldn\'92t believe how I respect you, Alyosha, for never telling lies.\
Oh, I must tell you a funny dream of mine. I sometimes dream of devils.\
It\'92s night; I am in my room with a candle and suddenly there are devils\
all over the place, in all the corners, under the table, and they open the\
doors; there\'92s a crowd of them behind the doors and they want to come and\
seize me. And they are just coming, just seizing me. But I suddenly cross\
myself and they all draw back, though they don\'92t go away altogether, they\
stand at the doors and in the corners, waiting. And suddenly I have a\
frightful longing to revile God aloud, and so I begin, and then they come\
crowding back to me, delighted, and seize me again and I cross myself\
again and they all draw back. It\'92s awful fun. it takes one\'92s breath away.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92ve had the same dream, too,\'94 said Alyosha suddenly.\
\
\'93Really?\'94 cried Lise, surprised. \'93I say, Alyosha, don\'92t laugh, that\'92s\
awfully important. Could two different people have the same dream?\'94\
\
\'93It seems they can.\'94\
\
\'93Alyosha, I tell you, it\'92s awfully important,\'94 Lise went on, with really\
excessive amazement. \'93It\'92s not the dream that\'92s important, but your having\
the same dream as me. You never lie to me, don\'92t lie now: is it true? You\
are not laughing?\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s true.\'94\
\
Lise seemed extraordinarily impressed and for half a minute she was\
silent.\
\
\'93Alyosha, come and see me, come and see me more often,\'94 she said suddenly,\
in a supplicating voice.\
\
\'93I\'92ll always come to see you, all my life,\'94 answered Alyosha firmly.\
\
\'93You are the only person I can talk to, you know,\'94 Lise began again. \'93I\
talk to no one but myself and you. Only you in the whole world. And to you\
more readily than to myself. And I am not a bit ashamed with you, not a\
bit. Alyosha, why am I not ashamed with you, not a bit? Alyosha, is it\
true that at Easter the Jews steal a child and kill it?\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t know.\'94\
\
\'93There\'92s a book here in which I read about the trial of a Jew, who took a\
child of four years old and cut off the fingers from both hands, and then\
crucified him on the wall, hammered nails into him and crucified him, and\
afterwards, when he was tried, he said that the child died soon, within\
four hours. That was \'91soon\'92! He said the child moaned, kept on moaning and\
he stood admiring it. That\'92s nice!\'94\
\
\'93Nice?\'94\
\
\'93Nice; I sometimes imagine that it was I who crucified him. He would hang\
there moaning and I would sit opposite him eating pineapple _compote_. I\
am awfully fond of pineapple _compote_. Do you like it?\'94\
\
Alyosha looked at her in silence. Her pale, sallow face was suddenly\
contorted, her eyes burned.\
\
\'93You know, when I read about that Jew I shook with sobs all night. I kept\
fancying how the little thing cried and moaned (a child of four years old\
understands, you know), and all the while the thought of pineapple\
_compote_ haunted me. In the morning I wrote a letter to a certain person,\
begging him _particularly_ to come and see me. He came and I suddenly told\
him all about the child and the pineapple _compote_. _All_ about it,\
_all_, and said that it was nice. He laughed and said it really was nice.\
Then he got up and went away. He was only here five minutes. Did he\
despise me? Did he despise me? Tell me, tell me, Alyosha, did he despise\
me or not?\'94 She sat up on the couch, with flashing eyes.\
\
\'93Tell me,\'94 Alyosha asked anxiously, \'93did you send for that person?\'94\
\
\'93Yes, I did.\'94\
\
\'93Did you send him a letter?\'94\
\
\'93Yes.\'94\
\
\'93Simply to ask about that, about that child?\'94\
\
\'93No, not about that at all. But when he came, I asked him about that at\
once. He answered, laughed, got up and went away.\'94\
\
\'93That person behaved honorably,\'94 Alyosha murmured.\
\
\'93And did he despise me? Did he laugh at me?\'94\
\
\'93No, for perhaps he believes in the pineapple _compote_ himself. He is\
very ill now, too, Lise.\'94\
\
\'93Yes, he does believe in it,\'94 said Lise, with flashing eyes.\
\
\'93He doesn\'92t despise any one,\'94 Alyosha went on. \'93Only he does not believe\
any one. If he doesn\'92t believe in people, of course, he does despise\
them.\'94\
\
\'93Then he despises me, me?\'94\
\
\'93You, too.\'94\
\
\'93Good,\'94 Lise seemed to grind her teeth. \'93When he went out laughing, I felt\
that it was nice to be despised. The child with fingers cut off is nice,\
and to be despised is nice....\'94\
\
And she laughed in Alyosha\'92s face, a feverish malicious laugh.\
\
\'93Do you know, Alyosha, do you know, I should like\'97Alyosha, save me!\'94 She\
suddenly jumped from the couch, rushed to him and seized him with both\
hands. \'93Save me!\'94 she almost groaned. \'93Is there any one in the world I\
could tell what I\'92ve told you? I\'92ve told you the truth, the truth. I shall\
kill myself, because I loathe everything! I don\'92t want to live, because I\
loathe everything! I loathe everything, everything. Alyosha, why don\'92t you\
love me in the least?\'94 she finished in a frenzy.\
\
\'93But I do love you!\'94 answered Alyosha warmly.\
\
\'93And will you weep over me, will you?\'94\
\
\'93Yes.\'94\
\
\'93Not because I won\'92t be your wife, but simply weep for me?\'94\
\
\'93Yes.\'94\
\
\'93Thank you! It\'92s only your tears I want. Every one else may punish me and\
trample me under foot, every one, every one, not excepting _any one_. For\
I don\'92t love any one. Do you hear, not any one! On the contrary, I hate\
him! Go, Alyosha; it\'92s time you went to your brother\'94; she tore herself\
away from him suddenly.\
\
\'93How can I leave you like this?\'94 said Alyosha, almost in alarm.\
\
\'93Go to your brother, the prison will be shut; go, here\'92s your hat. Give my\
love to Mitya, go, go!\'94\
\
And she almost forcibly pushed Alyosha out of the door. He looked at her\
with pained surprise, when he was suddenly aware of a letter in his right\
hand, a tiny letter folded up tight and sealed. He glanced at it and\
instantly read the address, \'93To Ivan Fyodorovitch Karamazov.\'94 He looked\
quickly at Lise. Her face had become almost menacing.\
\
\'93Give it to him, you must give it to him!\'94 she ordered him, trembling and\
beside herself. \'93To\uc0\u8208 day, at once, or I\'92ll poison myself! That\'92s why I sent\
for you.\'94\
\
And she slammed the door quickly. The bolt clicked. Alyosha put the note\
in his pocket and went straight downstairs, without going back to Madame\
Hohlakov; forgetting her, in fact. As soon as Alyosha had gone, Lise\
unbolted the door, opened it a little, put her finger in the crack and\
slammed the door with all her might, pinching her finger. Ten seconds\
after, releasing her finger, she walked softly, slowly to her chair, sat\
up straight in it and looked intently at her blackened finger and at the\
blood that oozed from under the nail. Her lips were quivering and she kept\
whispering rapidly to herself:\
\
\'93I am a wretch, wretch, wretch, wretch!\'94\
\
\
\
Chapter IV. A Hymn And A Secret\
\
\
It was quite late (days are short in November) when Alyosha rang at the\
prison gate. It was beginning to get dusk. But Alyosha knew that he would\
be admitted without difficulty. Things were managed in our little town, as\
everywhere else. At first, of course, on the conclusion of the preliminary\
inquiry, relations and a few other persons could only obtain interviews\
with Mitya by going through certain inevitable formalities. But later,\
though the formalities were not relaxed, exceptions were made for some, at\
least, of Mitya\'92s visitors. So much so, that sometimes the interviews with\
the prisoner in the room set aside for the purpose were practically\
_t\'eate\uc0\u8208 \'e0\u8208 t\'eate_.\
\
These exceptions, however, were few in number; only Grushenka, Alyosha and\
Rakitin were treated like this. But the captain of the police, Mihail\
Mihailovitch, was very favorably disposed to Grushenka. His abuse of her\
at Mokroe weighed on the old man\'92s conscience, and when he learned the\
whole story, he completely changed his view of her. And strange to say,\
though he was firmly persuaded of his guilt, yet after Mitya was once in\
prison, the old man came to take a more and more lenient view of him. \'93He\
was a man of good heart, perhaps,\'94 he thought, \'93who had come to grief from\
drinking and dissipation.\'94 His first horror had been succeeded by pity. As\
for Alyosha, the police captain was very fond of him and had known him for\
a long time. Rakitin, who had of late taken to coming very often to see\
the prisoner, was one of the most intimate acquaintances of the \'93police\
captain\'92s young ladies,\'94 as he called them, and was always hanging about\
their house. He gave lessons in the house of the prison superintendent,\
too, who, though scrupulous in the performance of his duties, was a kind\uc0\u8208 \
hearted old man. Alyosha, again, had an intimate acquaintance of long\
standing with the superintendent, who was fond of talking to him,\
generally on sacred subjects. He respected Ivan Fyodorovitch, and stood in\
awe of his opinion, though he was a great philosopher himself; \'93self\uc0\u8208 \
taught,\'94 of course. But Alyosha had an irresistible attraction for him.\
During the last year the old man had taken to studying the Apocryphal\
Gospels, and constantly talked over his impressions with his young friend.\
He used to come and see him in the monastery and discussed for hours\
together with him and with the monks. So even if Alyosha were late at the\
prison, he had only to go to the superintendent and everything was made\
easy. Besides, every one in the prison, down to the humblest warder, had\
grown used to Alyosha. The sentry, of course, did not trouble him so long\
as the authorities were satisfied.\
\
When Mitya was summoned from his cell, he always went downstairs, to the\
place set aside for interviews. As Alyosha entered the room he came upon\
Rakitin, who was just taking leave of Mitya. They were both talking\
loudly. Mitya was laughing heartily as he saw him out, while Rakitin\
seemed grumbling. Rakitin did not like meeting Alyosha, especially of\
late. He scarcely spoke to him, and bowed to him stiffly. Seeing Alyosha\
enter now, he frowned and looked away, as though he were entirely absorbed\
in buttoning his big, warm, fur\uc0\u8208 trimmed overcoat. Then he began looking at\
once for his umbrella.\
\
\'93I must mind not to forget my belongings,\'94 he muttered, simply to say\
something.\
\
\'93Mind you don\'92t forget other people\'92s belongings,\'94 said Mitya, as a joke,\
and laughed at once at his own wit. Rakitin fired up instantly.\
\
\'93You\'92d better give that advice to your own family, who\'92ve always been a\
slave\uc0\u8208 driving lot, and not to Rakitin,\'94 he cried, suddenly trembling with\
anger.\
\
\'93What\'92s the matter? I was joking,\'94 cried Mitya. \'93Damn it all! They are all\
like that,\'94 he turned to Alyosha, nodding towards Rakitin\'92s hurriedly\
retreating figure. \'93He was sitting here, laughing and cheerful, and all at\
once he boils up like that. He didn\'92t even nod to you. Have you broken\
with him completely? Why are you so late? I\'92ve not been simply waiting,\
but thirsting for you the whole morning. But never mind. We\'92ll make up for\
it now.\'94\
\
\'93Why does he come here so often? Surely you are not such great friends?\'94\
asked Alyosha. He, too, nodded at the door through which Rakitin had\
disappeared.\
\
\'93Great friends with Rakitin? No, not as much as that. Is it likely\'97a pig\
like that? He considers I am ... a blackguard. They can\'92t understand a\
joke either, that\'92s the worst of such people. They never understand a\
joke, and their souls are dry, dry and flat; they remind me of prison\
walls when I was first brought here. But he is a clever fellow, very\
clever. Well, Alexey, it\'92s all over with me now.\'94\
\
He sat down on the bench and made Alyosha sit down beside him.\
\
\'93Yes, the trial\'92s to\uc0\u8208 morrow. Are you so hopeless, brother?\'94 Alyosha said,\
with an apprehensive feeling.\
\
\'93What are you talking about?\'94 said Mitya, looking at him rather\
uncertainly. \'93Oh, you mean the trial! Damn it all! Till now we\'92ve been\
talking of things that don\'92t matter, about this trial, but I haven\'92t said\
a word to you about the chief thing. Yes, the trial is to\uc0\u8208 morrow; but it\
wasn\'92t the trial I meant, when I said it was all over with me. Why do you\
look at me so critically?\'94\
\
\'93What do you mean, Mitya?\'94\
\
\'93Ideas, ideas, that\'92s all! Ethics! What is ethics?\'94\
\
\'93Ethics?\'94 asked Alyosha, wondering.\
\
\'93Yes; is it a science?\'94\
\
\'93Yes, there is such a science ... but ... I confess I can\'92t explain to you\
what sort of science it is.\'94\
\
\'93Rakitin knows. Rakitin knows a lot, damn him! He\'92s not going to be a\
monk. He means to go to Petersburg. There he\'92ll go in for criticism of an\
elevating tendency. Who knows, he may be of use and make his own career,\
too. Ough! they are first\uc0\u8208 rate, these people, at making a career! Damn\
ethics, I am done for, Alexey, I am, you man of God! I love you more than\
any one. It makes my heart yearn to look at you. Who was Karl Bernard?\'94\
\
\'93Karl Bernard?\'94 Alyosha was surprised again.\
\
\'93No, not Karl. Stay, I made a mistake. Claude Bernard. What was he?\
Chemist or what?\'94\
\
\'93He must be a savant,\'94 answered Alyosha; \'93but I confess I can\'92t tell you\
much about him, either. I\'92ve heard of him as a savant, but what sort I\
don\'92t know.\'94\
\
\'93Well, damn him, then! I don\'92t know either,\'94 swore Mitya. \'93A scoundrel of\
some sort, most likely. They are all scoundrels. And Rakitin will make his\
way. Rakitin will get on anywhere; he is another Bernard. Ugh, these\
Bernards! They are all over the place.\'94\
\
\'93But what is the matter?\'94 Alyosha asked insistently.\
\
\'93He wants to write an article about me, about my case, and so begin his\
literary career. That\'92s what he comes for; he said so himself. He wants to\
prove some theory. He wants to say \'91he couldn\'92t help murdering his father,\
he was corrupted by his environment,\'92 and so on. He explained it all to\
me. He is going to put in a tinge of Socialism, he says. But there, damn\
the fellow, he can put in a tinge if he likes, I don\'92t care. He can\'92t bear\
Ivan, he hates him. He\'92s not fond of you, either. But I don\'92t turn him\
out, for he is a clever fellow. Awfully conceited, though. I said to him\
just now, \'91The Karamazovs are not blackguards, but philosophers; for all\
true Russians are philosophers, and though you\'92ve studied, you are not a\
philosopher\'97you are a low fellow.\'92 He laughed, so maliciously. And I said\
to him, \'91_De ideabus non est disputandum_.\'92 Isn\'92t that rather good? I can\
set up for being a classic, you see!\'94 Mitya laughed suddenly.\
\
\'93Why is it all over with you? You said so just now,\'94 Alyosha interposed.\
\
\'93Why is it all over with me? H\'92m!... The fact of it is ... if you take it\
as a whole, I am sorry to lose God\'97that\'92s why it is.\'94\
\
\'93What do you mean by \'91sorry to lose God\'92?\'94\
\
\'93Imagine: inside, in the nerves, in the head\'97that is, these nerves are\
there in the brain ... (damn them!) there are sort of little tails, the\
little tails of those nerves, and as soon as they begin quivering ... that\
is, you see, I look at something with my eyes and then they begin\
quivering, those little tails ... and when they quiver, then an image\
appears ... it doesn\'92t appear at once, but an instant, a second, passes\
... and then something like a moment appears; that is, not a moment\'97devil\
take the moment!\'97but an image; that is, an object, or an action, damn it!\
That\'92s why I see and then think, because of those tails, not at all\
because I\'92ve got a soul, and that I am some sort of image and likeness.\
All that is nonsense! Rakitin explained it all to me yesterday, brother,\
and it simply bowled me over. It\'92s magnificent, Alyosha, this science! A\
new man\'92s arising\'97that I understand.... And yet I am sorry to lose God!\'94\
\
\'93Well, that\'92s a good thing, anyway,\'94 said Alyosha.\
\
\'93That I am sorry to lose God? It\'92s chemistry, brother, chemistry! There\'92s\
no help for it, your reverence, you must make way for chemistry. And\
Rakitin does dislike God. Ough! doesn\'92t he dislike Him! That\'92s the sore\
point with all of them. But they conceal it. They tell lies. They pretend.\
\'91Will you preach this in your reviews?\'92 I asked him. \'91Oh, well, if I did\
it openly, they won\'92t let it through,\'92 he said. He laughed. \'91But what will\
become of men then?\'92 I asked him, \'91without God and immortal life? All\
things are lawful then, they can do what they like?\'92 \'91Didn\'92t you know?\'92 he\
said laughing, \'91a clever man can do what he likes,\'92 he said. \'91A clever man\
knows his way about, but you\'92ve put your foot in it, committing a murder,\
and now you are rotting in prison.\'92 He says that to my face! A regular\
pig! I used to kick such people out, but now I listen to them. He talks a\
lot of sense, too. Writes well. He began reading me an article last week.\
I copied out three lines of it. Wait a minute. Here it is.\'94\
\
Mitya hurriedly pulled out a piece of paper from his pocket and read:\
\
\'93 \'91In order to determine this question, it is above all essential to put\
one\'92s personality in contradiction to one\'92s reality.\'92 Do you understand\
that?\'94\
\
\'93No, I don\'92t,\'94 said Alyosha. He looked at Mitya and listened to him with\
curiosity.\
\
\'93I don\'92t understand either. It\'92s dark and obscure, but intellectual.\
\'91Every one writes like that now,\'92 he says, \'91it\'92s the effect of their\
environment.\'92 They are afraid of the environment. He writes poetry, too,\
the rascal. He\'92s written in honor of Madame Hohlakov\'92s foot. Ha ha ha!\'94\
\
\'93I\'92ve heard about it,\'94 said Alyosha.\
\
\'93Have you? And have you heard the poem?\'94\
\
\'93No.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92ve got it. Here it is. I\'92ll read it to you. You don\'92t know\'97I haven\'92t\
told you\'97there\'92s quite a story about it. He\'92s a rascal! Three weeks ago he\
began to tease me. \'91You\'92ve got yourself into a mess, like a fool, for the\
sake of three thousand, but I\'92m going to collar a hundred and fifty\
thousand. I am going to marry a widow and buy a house in Petersburg.\'92 And\
he told me he was courting Madame Hohlakov. She hadn\'92t much brains in her\
youth, and now at forty she has lost what she had. \'91But she\'92s awfully\
sentimental,\'92 he says; \'91that\'92s how I shall get hold of her. When I marry\
her, I shall take her to Petersburg and there I shall start a newspaper.\'92\
And his mouth was simply watering, the beast, not for the widow, but for\
the hundred and fifty thousand. And he made me believe it. He came to see\
me every day. \'91She is coming round,\'92 he declared. He was beaming with\
delight. And then, all of a sudden, he was turned out of the house.\
Perhotin\'92s carrying everything before him, bravo! I could kiss the silly\
old noodle for turning him out of the house. And he had written this\
doggerel. \'91It\'92s the first time I\'92ve soiled my hands with writing poetry,\'92\
he said. \'91It\'92s to win her heart, so it\'92s in a good cause. When I get hold\
of the silly woman\'92s fortune, I can be of great social utility.\'92 They have\
this social justification for every nasty thing they do! \'91Anyway it\'92s\
better than your Pushkin\'92s poetry,\'92 he said, \'91for I\'92ve managed to advocate\
enlightenment even in that.\'92 I understand what he means about Pushkin, I\
quite see that, if he really was a man of talent and only wrote about\
women\'92s feet. But wasn\'92t Rakitin stuck up about his doggerel! The vanity\
of these fellows! \'91On the convalescence of the swollen foot of the object\
of my affections\'92\'97he thought of that for a title. He\'92s a waggish fellow.\
\
\
    A captivating little foot,\
    Though swollen and red and tender!\
    The doctors come and plasters put,\
    But still they cannot mend her.\
\
    Yet, \'92tis not for her foot I dread\'97\
    A theme for Pushkin\'92s muse more fit\'97\
    It\'92s not her foot, it is her head:\
    I tremble for her loss of wit!\
\
    For as her foot swells, strange to say,\
    Her intellect is on the wane\'97\
    Oh, for some remedy I pray\
    That may restore both foot and brain!\
\
\
He is a pig, a regular pig, but he\'92s very arch, the rascal! And he really\
has put in a progressive idea. And wasn\'92t he angry when she kicked him\
out! He was gnashing his teeth!\'94\
\
\'93He\'92s taken his revenge already,\'94 said Alyosha. \'93He\'92s written a paragraph\
about Madame Hohlakov.\'94\
\
And Alyosha told him briefly about the paragraph in _Gossip_.\
\
\'93That\'92s his doing, that\'92s his doing!\'94 Mitya assented, frowning. \'93That\'92s\
him! These paragraphs ... I know ... the insulting things that have been\
written about Grushenka, for instance.... And about Katya, too.... H\'92m!\'94\
\
He walked across the room with a harassed air.\
\
\'93Brother, I cannot stay long,\'94 Alyosha said, after a pause. \'93To\uc0\u8208 morrow\
will be a great and awful day for you, the judgment of God will be\
accomplished ... I am amazed at you, you walk about here, talking of I\
don\'92t know what ...\'94\
\
\'93No, don\'92t be amazed at me,\'94 Mitya broke in warmly. \'93Am I to talk of that\
stinking dog? Of the murderer? We\'92ve talked enough of him. I don\'92t want to\
say more of the stinking son of Stinking Lizaveta! God will kill him, you\
will see. Hush!\'94\
\
He went up to Alyosha excitedly and kissed him. His eyes glowed.\
\
\'93Rakitin wouldn\'92t understand it,\'94 he began in a sort of exaltation; \'93but\
you, you\'92ll understand it all. That\'92s why I was thirsting for you. You\
see, there\'92s so much I\'92ve been wanting to tell you for ever so long, here,\
within these peeling walls, but I haven\'92t said a word about what matters\
most; the moment never seems to have come. Now I can wait no longer. I\
must pour out my heart to you. Brother, these last two months I\'92ve found\
in myself a new man. A new man has risen up in me. He was hidden in me,\
but would never have come to the surface, if it hadn\'92t been for this blow\
from heaven. I am afraid! And what do I care if I spend twenty years in\
the mines, breaking ore with a hammer? I am not a bit afraid of that\'97it\'92s\
something else I am afraid of now: that that new man may leave me. Even\
there, in the mines, under\uc0\u8208 ground, I may find a human heart in another\
convict and murderer by my side, and I may make friends with him, for even\
there one may live and love and suffer. One may thaw and revive a frozen\
heart in that convict, one may wait upon him for years, and at last bring\
up from the dark depths a lofty soul, a feeling, suffering creature; one\
may bring forth an angel, create a hero! There are so many of them,\
hundreds of them, and we are all to blame for them. Why was it I dreamed\
of that \'91babe\'92 at such a moment? \'91Why is the babe so poor?\'92 That was a\
sign to me at that moment. It\'92s for the babe I\'92m going. Because we are all\
responsible for all. For all the \'91babes,\'92 for there are big children as\
well as little children. All are \'91babes.\'92 I go for all, because some one\
must go for all. I didn\'92t kill father, but I\'92ve got to go. I accept it.\
It\'92s all come to me here, here, within these peeling walls. There are\
numbers of them there, hundreds of them underground, with hammers in their\
hands. Oh, yes, we shall be in chains and there will be no freedom, but\
then, in our great sorrow, we shall rise again to joy, without which man\
cannot live nor God exist, for God gives joy: it\'92s His privilege\'97a grand\
one. Ah, man should be dissolved in prayer! What should I be underground\
there without God? Rakitin\'92s laughing! If they drive God from the earth,\
we shall shelter Him underground. One cannot exist in prison without God;\
it\'92s even more impossible than out of prison. And then we men underground\
will sing from the bowels of the earth a glorious hymn to God, with Whom\
is joy. Hail to God and His joy! I love Him!\'94\
\
Mitya was almost gasping for breath as he uttered his wild speech. He\
turned pale, his lips quivered, and tears rolled down his cheeks.\
\
\'93Yes, life is full, there is life even underground,\'94 he began again. \'93You\
wouldn\'92t believe, Alexey, how I want to live now, what a thirst for\
existence and consciousness has sprung up in me within these peeling\
walls. Rakitin doesn\'92t understand that; all he cares about is building a\
house and letting flats. But I\'92ve been longing for you. And what is\
suffering? I am not afraid of it, even if it were beyond reckoning. I am\
not afraid of it now. I was afraid of it before. Do you know, perhaps I\
won\'92t answer at the trial at all.... And I seem to have such strength in\
me now, that I think I could stand anything, any suffering, only to be\
able to say and to repeat to myself every moment, \'91I exist.\'92 In thousands\
of agonies\'97I exist. I\'92m tormented on the rack\'97but I exist! Though I sit\
alone on a pillar\'97I exist! I see the sun, and if I don\'92t see the sun, I\
know it\'92s there. And there\'92s a whole life in that, in knowing that the sun\
is there. Alyosha, my angel, all these philosophies are the death of me.\
Damn them! Brother Ivan\'97\'94\
\
\'93What of brother Ivan?\'94 interrupted Alyosha, but Mitya did not hear.\
\
\'93You see, I never had any of these doubts before, but it was all hidden\
away in me. It was perhaps just because ideas I did not understand were\
surging up in me, that I used to drink and fight and rage. It was to\
stifle them in myself, to still them, to smother them. Ivan is not\
Rakitin, there is an idea in him. Ivan is a sphinx and is silent; he is\
always silent. It\'92s God that\'92s worrying me. That\'92s the only thing that\'92s\
worrying me. What if He doesn\'92t exist? What if Rakitin\'92s right\'97that it\'92s\
an idea made up by men? Then if He doesn\'92t exist, man is the chief of the\
earth, of the universe. Magnificent! Only how is he going to be good\
without God? That\'92s the question. I always come back to that. For whom is\
man going to love then? To whom will he be thankful? To whom will he sing\
the hymn? Rakitin laughs. Rakitin says that one can love humanity without\
God. Well, only a sniveling idiot can maintain that. I can\'92t understand\
it. Life\'92s easy for Rakitin. \'91You\'92d better think about the extension of\
civic rights, or even of keeping down the price of meat. You will show\
your love for humanity more simply and directly by that, than by\
philosophy.\'92 I answered him, \'91Well, but you, without a God, are more\
likely to raise the price of meat, if it suits you, and make a rouble on\
every copeck.\'92 He lost his temper. But after all, what is goodness? Answer\
me that, Alexey. Goodness is one thing with me and another with a\
Chinaman, so it\'92s a relative thing. Or isn\'92t it? Is it not relative? A\
treacherous question! You won\'92t laugh if I tell you it\'92s kept me awake two\
nights. I only wonder now how people can live and think nothing about it.\
Vanity! Ivan has no God. He has an idea. It\'92s beyond me. But he is silent.\
I believe he is a free\uc0\u8208 mason. I asked him, but he is silent. I wanted to\
drink from the springs of his soul\'97he was silent. But once he did drop a\
word.\'94\
\
\'93What did he say?\'94 Alyosha took it up quickly.\
\
\'93I said to him, \'91Then everything is lawful, if it is so?\'92 He frowned.\
\'91Fyodor Pavlovitch, our papa,\'92 he said, \'91was a pig, but his ideas were\
right enough.\'92 That was what he dropped. That was all he said. That was\
going one better than Rakitin.\'94\
\
\'93Yes,\'94 Alyosha assented bitterly. \'93When was he with you?\'94\
\
\'93Of that later; now I must speak of something else. I have said nothing\
about Ivan to you before. I put it off to the last. When my business here\
is over and the verdict has been given, then I\'92ll tell you something. I\'92ll\
tell you everything. We\'92ve something tremendous on hand.... And you shall\
be my judge in it. But don\'92t begin about that now; be silent. You talk of\
to\uc0\u8208 morrow, of the trial; but, would you believe it, I know nothing about\
it.\'94\
\
\'93Have you talked to the counsel?\'94\
\
\'93What\'92s the use of the counsel? I told him all about it. He\'92s a soft,\
city\uc0\u8208 bred rogue\'97a Bernard! But he doesn\'92t believe me\'97not a bit of it. Only\
imagine, he believes I did it. I see it. \'91In that case,\'92 I asked him, \'91why\
have you come to defend me?\'92 Hang them all! They\'92ve got a doctor down,\
too, want to prove I\'92m mad. I won\'92t have that! Katerina Ivanovna wants to\
do her \'91duty\'92 to the end, whatever the strain!\'94 Mitya smiled bitterly.\
\'93The cat! Hard\uc0\u8208 hearted creature! She knows that I said of her at Mokroe\
that she was a woman of \'91great wrath.\'92 They repeated it. Yes, the facts\
against me have grown numerous as the sands of the sea. Grigory sticks to\
his point. Grigory\'92s honest, but a fool. Many people are honest because\
they are fools: that\'92s Rakitin\'92s idea. Grigory\'92s my enemy. And there are\
some people who are better as foes than friends. I mean Katerina Ivanovna.\
I am afraid, oh, I am afraid she will tell how she bowed to the ground\
after that four thousand. She\'92ll pay it back to the last farthing. I don\'92t\
want her sacrifice; they\'92ll put me to shame at the trial. I wonder how I\
can stand it. Go to her, Alyosha, ask her not to speak of that in the\
court, can\'92t you? But damn it all, it doesn\'92t matter! I shall get through\
somehow. I don\'92t pity her. It\'92s her own doing. She deserves what she gets.\
I shall have my own story to tell, Alexey.\'94 He smiled bitterly again.\
\'93Only ... only Grusha, Grusha! Good Lord! Why should she have such\
suffering to bear?\'94 he exclaimed suddenly, with tears. \'93Grusha\'92s killing\
me; the thought of her\'92s killing me, killing me. She was with me just\
now....\'94\
\
\'93She told me she was very much grieved by you to\uc0\u8208 day.\'94\
\
\'93I know. Confound my temper! It was jealousy. I was sorry, I kissed her as\
she was going. I didn\'92t ask her forgiveness.\'94\
\
\'93Why didn\'92t you?\'94 exclaimed Alyosha.\
\
Suddenly Mitya laughed almost mirthfully.\
\
\'93God preserve you, my dear boy, from ever asking forgiveness for a fault\
from a woman you love. From one you love especially, however greatly you\
may have been in fault. For a woman\'97devil only knows what to make of a\
woman! I know something about them, anyway. But try acknowledging you are\
in fault to a woman. Say, \'91I am sorry, forgive me,\'92 and a shower of\
reproaches will follow! Nothing will make her forgive you simply and\
directly, she\'92ll humble you to the dust, bring forward things that have\
never happened, recall everything, forget nothing, add something of her\
own, and only then forgive you. And even the best, the best of them do it.\
She\'92ll scrape up all the scrapings and load them on your head. They are\
ready to flay you alive, I tell you, every one of them, all these angels\
without whom we cannot live! I tell you plainly and openly, dear boy,\
every decent man ought to be under some woman\'92s thumb. That\'92s my\
conviction\'97not conviction, but feeling. A man ought to be magnanimous, and\
it\'92s no disgrace to a man! No disgrace to a hero, not even a C\'e6sar! But\
don\'92t ever beg her pardon all the same for anything. Remember that rule\
given you by your brother Mitya, who\'92s come to ruin through women. No, I\'92d\
better make it up to Grusha somehow, without begging pardon. I worship\
her, Alexey, worship her. Only she doesn\'92t see it. No, she still thinks I\
don\'92t love her enough. And she tortures me, tortures me with her love. The\
past was nothing! In the past it was only those infernal curves of hers\
that tortured me, but now I\'92ve taken all her soul into my soul and through\
her I\'92ve become a man myself. Will they marry us? If they don\'92t, I shall\
