till after the trial!\'94\
\
Mitya ended beside himself. He held Alyosha with both hands on his\
shoulders, and his yearning, feverish eyes were fixed on his brother\'92s.\
\
\'93They don\'92t let convicts marry, do they?\'94 he repeated for the third time\
in a supplicating voice.\
\
Alyosha listened with extreme surprise and was deeply moved.\
\
\'93Tell me one thing,\'94 he said. \'93Is Ivan very keen on it, and whose idea was\
it?\'94\
\
\'93His, his, and he is very keen on it. He didn\'92t come to see me at first,\
then he suddenly came a week ago and he began about it straight away. He\
is awfully keen on it. He doesn\'92t ask me, but orders me to escape. He\
doesn\'92t doubt of my obeying him, though I showed him all my heart as I\
have to you, and told him about the hymn, too. He told me he\'92d arrange it;\
