It\'92s all a matter of money: he\'92ll pay ten thousand for escape and give me\
twenty thousand for America. And he says we can arrange a magnificent\
escape for ten thousand.\'94\
\
\'93And he told you on no account to tell me?\'94 Alyosha asked again.\
\
\'93To tell no one, and especially not you; on no account to tell you. He is\
afraid, no doubt, that you\'92ll stand before me as my conscience. Don\'92t tell\
him I told you. Don\'92t tell him, for anything.\'94\
\
\'93You are right,\'94 Alyosha pronounced; \'93it\'92s impossible to decide anything\
before the trial is over. After the trial you\'92ll decide of yourself. Then\
you\'92ll find that new man in yourself and he will decide.\'94\
\
\'93A new man, or a Bernard who\'92ll decide _\'e0 la_ Bernard, for I believe I\'92m a\
contemptible Bernard myself,\'94 said Mitya, with a bitter grin.\
\
\'93But, brother, have you no hope then of being acquitted?\'94\
\
Mitya shrugged his shoulders nervously and shook his head. \'93Alyosha,\
darling, it\'92s time you were going,\'94 he said, with a sudden haste. \'93There\'92s\
the superintendent shouting in the yard. He\'92ll be here directly. We are\
late; it\'92s irregular. Embrace me quickly. Kiss me! Sign me with the cross,\
