\
They embraced and kissed.\
\
\'93Ivan,\'94 said Mitya suddenly, \'93suggests my escaping; but, of course, he\
believes I did it.\'94\
\
A mournful smile came on to his lips.\
\
\'93Have you asked him whether he believes it?\'94 asked Alyosha.\
\
\'93No, I haven\'92t. I wanted to, but I couldn\'92t. I hadn\'92t the courage. But I\
saw it from his eyes. Well, good\uc0\u8208 by!\'94\
\
Once more they kissed hurriedly, and Alyosha was just going out, when\
Mitya suddenly called him back.\
\
\'93Stand facing me! That\'92s right!\'94 And again he seized Alyosha, putting both\
hands on his shoulders. His face became suddenly quite pale, so that it\
was dreadfully apparent, even through the gathering darkness. His lips\
twitched, his eyes fastened upon Alyosha.\
\
\'93Alyosha, tell me the whole truth, as you would before God. Do you believe\
I did it? Do you, do you in yourself, believe it? The whole truth, don\'92t\
lie!\'94 he cried desperately.\
\
Everything seemed heaving before Alyosha, and he felt something like a\
stab at his heart.\
\
\'93Hush! What do you mean?\'94 he faltered helplessly.\
\
\'93The whole truth, the whole, don\'92t lie!\'94 repeated Mitya.\
\
\'93I\'92ve never for one instant believed that you were the murderer!\'94 broke in\
a shaking voice from Alyosha\'92s breast, and he raised his right hand in the\
air, as though calling God to witness his words.\
\
Mitya\'92s whole face was lighted up with bliss.\
\
\'93Thank you!\'94 he articulated slowly, as though letting a sigh escape him\
after fainting. \'93Now you have given me new life. Would you believe it,\
till this moment I\'92ve been afraid to ask you, you, even you. Well, go!\
You\'92ve given me strength for to\uc0\u8208 morrow. God bless you! Come, go along!\
Love Ivan!\'94 was Mitya\'92s last word.\
\
Alyosha went out in tears. Such distrustfulness in Mitya, such lack of\
confidence even to him, to Alyosha\'97all this suddenly opened before Alyosha\
an unsuspected depth of hopeless grief and despair in the soul of his\
unhappy brother. Intense, infinite compassion overwhelmed him instantly.\
There was a poignant ache in his torn heart. \'93Love Ivan!\'94\'97he suddenly\
recalled Mitya\'92s words. And he was going to Ivan. He badly wanted to see\
Ivan all day. He was as much worried about Ivan as about Mitya, and more\
than ever now.\
\
\
\
Chapter V. Not You, Not You!\
\
\
On the way to Ivan he had to pass the house where Katerina Ivanovna was\
living. There was light in the windows. He suddenly stopped and resolved\
to go in. He had not seen Katerina Ivanovna for more than a week. But now\
it struck him that Ivan might be with her, especially on the eve of the\
terrible day. Ringing, and mounting the staircase, which was dimly lighted\
by a Chinese lantern, he saw a man coming down, and as they met, he\
recognized him as his brother. So he was just coming from Katerina\
Ivanovna.\
\
\'93Ah, it\'92s only you,\'94 said Ivan dryly. \'93Well, good\uc0\u8208 by! You are going to\
her?\'94\
\
\'93Yes.\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t advise you to; she\'92s upset and you\'92ll upset her more.\'94\
\
A door was instantly flung open above, and a voice cried suddenly:\
\
\'93No, no! Alexey Fyodorovitch, have you come from him?\'94\
\
\'93Yes, I have been with him.\'94\
\
\'93Has he sent me any message? Come up, Alyosha, and you, Ivan Fyodorovitch,\
you must come back, you must. Do you hear?\'94\
\
There was such a peremptory note in Katya\'92s voice that Ivan, after a\
moment\'92s hesitation, made up his mind to go back with Alyosha.\
\
\'93She was listening,\'94 he murmured angrily to himself, but Alyosha heard it.\
\
\'93Excuse my keeping my greatcoat on,\'94 said Ivan, going into the drawing\uc0\u8208 \
room. \'93I won\'92t sit down. I won\'92t stay more than a minute.\'94\
\
\'93Sit down, Alexey Fyodorovitch,\'94 said Katerina Ivanovna, though she\
remained standing. She had changed very little during this time, but there\
was an ominous gleam in her dark eyes. Alyosha remembered afterwards that\
she had struck him as particularly handsome at that moment.\
\
\'93What did he ask you to tell me?\'94\
\
\'93Only one thing,\'94 said Alyosha, looking her straight in the face, \'93that\
you would spare yourself and say nothing at the trial of what\'94 (he was a\
little confused) \'93... passed between you ... at the time of your first\
acquaintance ... in that town.\'94\
\
\'93Ah! that I bowed down to the ground for that money!\'94 She broke into a\
bitter laugh. \'93Why, is he afraid for me or for himself? He asks me to\
spare\'97whom? Him or myself? Tell me, Alexey Fyodorovitch!\'94\
\
Alyosha watched her intently, trying to understand her.\
\
\'93Both yourself and him,\'94 he answered softly.\
\
\'93I am glad to hear it,\'94 she snapped out maliciously, and she suddenly\
blushed.\
\
\'93You don\'92t know me yet, Alexey Fyodorovitch,\'94 she said menacingly. \'93And I\
don\'92t know myself yet. Perhaps you\'92ll want to trample me under foot after\
my examination to\uc0\u8208 morrow.\'94\
\
\'93You will give your evidence honorably,\'94 said Alyosha; \'93that\'92s all that\'92s\
wanted.\'94\
\
\'93Women are often dishonorable,\'94 she snarled. \'93Only an hour ago I was\
thinking I felt afraid to touch that monster ... as though he were a\
reptile ... but no, he is still a human being to me! But did he do it? Is\
he the murderer?\'94 she cried, all of a sudden, hysterically, turning\
quickly to Ivan. Alyosha saw at once that she had asked Ivan that question\
before, perhaps only a moment before he came in, and not for the first\
time, but for the hundredth, and that they had ended by quarreling.\
\
\'93I\'92ve been to see Smerdyakov.... It was you, you who persuaded me that he\
murdered his father. It\'92s only you I believed!\'94 she continued, still\
addressing Ivan. He gave her a sort of strained smile. Alyosha started at\
her tone. He had not suspected such familiar intimacy between them.\
\
\'93Well, that\'92s enough, anyway,\'94 Ivan cut short the conversation. \'93I am\
going. I\'92ll come to\uc0\u8208 morrow.\'94 And turning at once, he walked out of the\
room and went straight downstairs.\
\
With an imperious gesture, Katerina Ivanovna seized Alyosha by both hands.\
\
\'93Follow him! Overtake him! Don\'92t leave him alone for a minute!\'94 she said,\
in a hurried whisper. \'93He\'92s mad! Don\'92t you know that he\'92s mad? He is in a\
fever, nervous fever. The doctor told me so. Go, run after him....\'94\
\
Alyosha jumped up and ran after Ivan, who was not fifty paces ahead of\
him.\
\
\'93What do you want?\'94 He turned quickly on Alyosha, seeing that he was\
running after him. \'93She told you to catch me up, because I\'92m mad. I know\
it all by heart,\'94 he added irritably.\
\
\'93She is mistaken, of course; but she is right that you are ill,\'94 said\
Alyosha. \'93I was looking at your face just now. You look very ill, Ivan.\'94\
\
Ivan walked on without stopping. Alyosha followed him.\
\
\'93And do you know, Alexey Fyodorovitch, how people do go out of their\
mind?\'94 Ivan asked in a voice suddenly quiet, without a trace of\
irritation, with a note of the simplest curiosity.\
\
\'93No, I don\'92t. I suppose there are all kinds of insanity.\'94\
\
\'93And can one observe that one\'92s going mad oneself?\'94\
\
\'93I imagine one can\'92t see oneself clearly in such circumstances,\'94 Alyosha\
answered with surprise.\
\
Ivan paused for half a minute.\
\
\'93If you want to talk to me, please change the subject,\'94 he said suddenly.\
\
\'93Oh, while I think of it, I have a letter for you,\'94 said Alyosha timidly,\
and he took Lise\'92s note from his pocket and held it out to Ivan. They were\
just under a lamp\uc0\u8208 post. Ivan recognized the handwriting at once.\
\
\'93Ah, from that little demon!\'94 he laughed maliciously, and, without opening\
the envelope, he tore it into bits and threw it in the air. The bits were\
scattered by the wind.\
\
\'93She\'92s not sixteen yet, I believe, and already offering herself,\'94 he said\
contemptuously, striding along the street again.\
\
\'93How do you mean, offering herself?\'94 exclaimed Alyosha.\
\
\'93As wanton women offer themselves, to be sure.\'94\
\
\'93How can you, Ivan, how can you?\'94 Alyosha cried warmly, in a grieved\
voice. \'93She is a child; you are insulting a child! She is ill; she is very\
ill, too. She is on the verge of insanity, too, perhaps.... I had hoped to\
hear something from you ... that would save her.\'94\
\
\'93You\'92ll hear nothing from me. If she is a child I am not her nurse. Be\
quiet, Alexey. Don\'92t go on about her. I am not even thinking about it.\'94\
\
They were silent again for a moment.\
\
\'93She will be praying all night now to the Mother of God to show her how to\
act to\uc0\u8208 morrow at the trial,\'94 he said sharply and angrily again.\
\
\'93You ... you mean Katerina Ivanovna?\'94\
\
\'93Yes. Whether she\'92s to save Mitya or ruin him. She\'92ll pray for light from\
above. She can\'92t make up her mind for herself, you see. She has not had\
time to decide yet. She takes me for her nurse, too. She wants me to sing\
lullabies to her.\'94\
\
\'93Katerina Ivanovna loves you, brother,\'94 said Alyosha sadly.\
\
\'93Perhaps; but I am not very keen on her.\'94\
\
\'93She is suffering. Why do you ... sometimes say things to her that give\
her hope?\'94 Alyosha went on, with timid reproach. \'93I know that you\'92ve given\
her hope. Forgive me for speaking to you like this,\'94 he added.\
\
\'93I can\'92t behave to her as I ought\'97break off altogether and tell her so\
straight out,\'94 said Ivan, irritably. \'93I must wait till sentence is passed\
on the murderer. If I break off with her now, she will avenge herself on\
me by ruining that scoundrel to\uc0\u8208 morrow at the trial, for she hates him and\
knows she hates him. It\'92s all a lie\'97lie upon lie! As long as I don\'92t break\
off with her, she goes on hoping, and she won\'92t ruin that monster, knowing\
how I want to get him out of trouble. If only that damned verdict would\
come!\'94\
\
The words \'93murderer\'94 and \'93monster\'94 echoed painfully in Alyosha\'92s heart.\
\
\'93But how can she ruin Mitya?\'94 he asked, pondering on Ivan\'92s words. \'93What\
evidence can she give that would ruin Mitya?\'94\
\
\'93You don\'92t know that yet. She\'92s got a document in her hands, in Mitya\'92s\
own writing, that proves conclusively that he did murder Fyodor\
Pavlovitch.\'94\
\
\'93That\'92s impossible!\'94 cried Alyosha.\
\
\'93Why is it impossible? I\'92ve read it myself.\'94\
\
\'93There can\'92t be such a document!\'94 Alyosha repeated warmly. \'93There can\'92t\
be, because he\'92s not the murderer. It\'92s not he murdered father, not he!\'94\
\
Ivan suddenly stopped.\
\
\'93Who is the murderer then, according to you?\'94 he asked, with apparent\
coldness. There was even a supercilious note in his voice.\
\
\'93You know who,\'94 Alyosha pronounced in a low, penetrating voice.\
\
\'93Who? You mean the myth about that crazy idiot, the epileptic,\
Smerdyakov?\'94\
\
Alyosha suddenly felt himself trembling all over.\
\
\'93You know who,\'94 broke helplessly from him. He could scarcely breathe.\
\
\'93Who? Who?\'94 Ivan cried almost fiercely. All his restraint suddenly\
vanished.\
\
\'93I only know one thing,\'94 Alyosha went on, still almost in a whisper, \'93_it\
wasn\'92t you_ killed father.\'94\
\
\'93 \'91Not you\'92! What do you mean by \'91not you\'92?\'94 Ivan was thunderstruck.\
\
\'93It was not you killed father, not you!\'94 Alyosha repeated firmly.\
\
The silence lasted for half a minute.\
\
\'93I know I didn\'92t. Are you raving?\'94 said Ivan, with a pale, distorted\
smile. His eyes were riveted on Alyosha. They were standing again under a\
lamp\uc0\u8208 post.\
\
\'93No, Ivan. You\'92ve told yourself several times that you are the murderer.\'94\
\
\'93When did I say so? I was in Moscow.... When have I said so?\'94 Ivan\
faltered helplessly.\
\
\'93You\'92ve said so to yourself many times, when you\'92ve been alone during\
these two dreadful months,\'94 Alyosha went on softly and distinctly as\
before. Yet he was speaking now, as it were, not of himself, not of his\
own will, but obeying some irresistible command. \'93You have accused\
yourself and have confessed to yourself that you are the murderer and no\
one else. But you didn\'92t do it: you are mistaken: you are not the\
murderer. Do you hear? It was not you! God has sent me to tell you so.\'94\
\
They were both silent. The silence lasted a whole long minute. They were\
both standing still, gazing into each other\'92s eyes. They were both pale.\
Suddenly Ivan began trembling all over, and clutched Alyosha\'92s shoulder.\
\
\'93You\'92ve been in my room!\'94 he whispered hoarsely. \'93You\'92ve been there at\
night, when he came.... Confess ... have you seen him, have you seen him?\'94\
\
\'93Whom do you mean\'97Mitya?\'94 Alyosha asked, bewildered.\
\
\'93Not him, damn the monster!\'94 Ivan shouted, in a frenzy. \'93Do you know that\
he visits me? How did you find out? Speak!\'94\
\
\'93Who is _he_! I don\'92t know whom you are talking about,\'94 Alyosha faltered,\
beginning to be alarmed.\
\
\'93Yes, you do know ... or how could you\'97? It\'92s impossible that you don\'92t\
know.\'94\
\
Suddenly he seemed to check himself. He stood still and seemed to reflect.\
A strange grin contorted his lips.\
\
\'93Brother,\'94 Alyosha began again, in a shaking voice, \'93I have said this to\
you, because you\'92ll believe my word, I know that. I tell you once and for\
all, it\'92s not you. You hear, once for all! God has put it into my heart to\
say this to you, even though it may make you hate me from this hour.\'94\
\
But by now Ivan had apparently regained his self\uc0\u8208 control.\
\
\'93Alexey Fyodorovitch,\'94 he said, with a cold smile, \'93I can\'92t endure\
prophets and epileptics\'97messengers from God especially\'97and you know that\
only too well. I break off all relations with you from this moment and\
probably for ever. I beg you to leave me at this turning. It\'92s the way to\
your lodgings, too. You\'92d better be particularly careful not to come to me\
to\uc0\u8208 day! Do you hear?\'94\
\
He turned and walked on with a firm step, not looking back.\
\
\'93Brother,\'94 Alyosha called after him, \'93if anything happens to you to\uc0\u8208 day,\
turn to me before any one!\'94\
\
But Ivan made no reply. Alyosha stood under the lamp\uc0\u8208 post at the cross\
roads, till Ivan had vanished into the darkness. Then he turned and walked\
slowly homewards. Both Alyosha and Ivan were living in lodgings; neither\
of them was willing to live in Fyodor Pavlovitch\'92s empty house. Alyosha\
had a furnished room in the house of some working people. Ivan lived some\
distance from him. He had taken a roomy and fairly comfortable lodge\
attached to a fine house that belonged to a well\uc0\u8208 to\u8208 do lady, the widow of\
an official. But his only attendant was a deaf and rheumatic old crone who\
went to bed at six o\'92clock every evening and got up at six in the morning.\
Ivan had become remarkably indifferent to his comforts of late, and very\
fond of being alone. He did everything for himself in the one room he\
lived in, and rarely entered any of the other rooms in his abode.\
\
He reached the gate of the house and had his hand on the bell, when he\
suddenly stopped. He felt that he was trembling all over with anger.\
Suddenly he let go of the bell, turned back with a curse, and walked with\
rapid steps in the opposite direction. He walked a mile and a half to a\
tiny, slanting, wooden house, almost a hut, where Marya Kondratyevna, the\
neighbor who used to come to Fyodor Pavlovitch\'92s kitchen for soup and to\
whom Smerdyakov had once sung his songs and played on the guitar, was now\
lodging. She had sold their little house, and was now living here with her\
mother. Smerdyakov, who was ill\'97almost dying\'97had been with them ever since\
Fyodor Pavlovitch\'92s death. It was to him Ivan was going now, drawn by a\
sudden and irresistible prompting.\
\
\
\
Chapter VI. The First Interview With Smerdyakov\
\
\
This was the third time that Ivan had been to see Smerdyakov since his\
return from Moscow. The first time he had seen him and talked to him was\
on the first day of his arrival, then he had visited him once more, a\
fortnight later. But his visits had ended with that second one, so that it\
was now over a month since he had seen him. And he had scarcely heard\
anything of him.\
\
Ivan had only returned five days after his father\'92s death, so that he was\
not present at the funeral, which took place the day before he came back.\
The cause of his delay was that Alyosha, not knowing his Moscow address,\
had to apply to Katerina Ivanovna to telegraph to him, and she, not\
knowing his address either, telegraphed to her sister and aunt, reckoning\
on Ivan\'92s going to see them as soon as he arrived in Moscow. But he did\
not go to them till four days after his arrival. When he got the telegram,\
he had, of course, set off post\uc0\u8208 haste to our town. The first to meet him\
was Alyosha, and Ivan was greatly surprised to find that, in opposition to\
the general opinion of the town, he refused to entertain a suspicion\
against Mitya, and spoke openly of Smerdyakov as the murderer. Later on,\
after seeing the police captain and the prosecutor, and hearing the\
details of the charge and the arrest, he was still more surprised at\
Alyosha, and ascribed his opinion only to his exaggerated brotherly\
feeling and sympathy with Mitya, of whom Alyosha, as Ivan knew, was very\
fond.\
\
By the way, let us say a word or two of Ivan\'92s feeling to his brother\
Dmitri. He positively disliked him; at most, felt sometimes a compassion\
for him, and even that was mixed with great contempt, almost repugnance.\
Mitya\'92s whole personality, even his appearance, was extremely unattractive\
to him. Ivan looked with indignation on Katerina Ivanovna\'92s love for his\
brother. Yet he went to see Mitya on the first day of his arrival, and\
that interview, far from shaking Ivan\'92s belief in his guilt, positively\
strengthened it. He found his brother agitated, nervously excited. Mitya\
had been talkative, but very absent\uc0\u8208 minded and incoherent. He used violent\
language, accused Smerdyakov, and was fearfully muddled. He talked\
principally about the three thousand roubles, which he said had been\
\'93stolen\'94 from him by his father.\
\
\'93The money was mine, it was my money,\'94 Mitya kept repeating. \'93Even if I\
had stolen it, I should have had the right.\'94\
\
He hardly contested the evidence against him, and if he tried to turn a\
fact to his advantage, it was in an absurd and incoherent way. He hardly\
seemed to wish to defend himself to Ivan or any one else. Quite the\
contrary, he was angry and proudly scornful of the charges against him; he\
was continually firing up and abusing every one. He only laughed\
contemptuously at Grigory\'92s evidence about the open door, and declared\
that it was \'93the devil that opened it.\'94 But he could not bring forward any\
coherent explanation of the fact. He even succeeded in insulting Ivan\
during their first interview, telling him sharply that it was not for\
people who declared that \'93everything was lawful,\'94 to suspect and question\
him. Altogether he was anything but friendly with Ivan on that occasion.\
Immediately after that interview with Mitya, Ivan went for the first time\
to see Smerdyakov.\
\
In the railway train on his way from Moscow, he kept thinking of\
Smerdyakov and of his last conversation with him on the evening before he\
went away. Many things seemed to him puzzling and suspicious. But when he\
gave his evidence to the investigating lawyer Ivan said nothing, for the\
time, of that conversation. He put that off till he had seen Smerdyakov,\
who was at that time in the hospital.\
\
Doctor Herzenstube and Varvinsky, the doctor he met in the hospital,\
confidently asserted in reply to Ivan\'92s persistent questions, that\
Smerdyakov\'92s epileptic attack was unmistakably genuine, and were surprised\
indeed at Ivan asking whether he might not have been shamming on the day\
of the catastrophe. They gave him to understand that the attack was an\
exceptional one, the fits persisting and recurring several times, so that\
the patient\'92s life was positively in danger, and it was only now, after\
they had applied remedies, that they could assert with confidence that the\
patient would survive. \'93Though it might well be,\'94 added Doctor\
Herzenstube, \'93that his reason would be impaired for a considerable period,\
if not permanently.\'94 On Ivan\'92s asking impatiently whether that meant that\
he was now mad, they told him that this was not yet the case, in the full\
sense of the word, but that certain abnormalities were perceptible. Ivan\
decided to find out for himself what those abnormalities were.\
\
At the hospital he was at once allowed to see the patient. Smerdyakov was\
lying on a truckle\uc0\u8208 bed in a separate ward. There was only one other bed in\
the room, and in it lay a tradesman of the town, swollen with dropsy, who\
was obviously almost dying; he could be no hindrance to their\
conversation. Smerdyakov grinned uncertainly on seeing Ivan, and for the\
first instant seemed nervous. So at least Ivan fancied. But that was only\
momentary. For the rest of the time he was struck, on the contrary, by\
Smerdyakov\'92s composure. From the first glance Ivan had no doubt that he\
was very ill. He was very weak; he spoke slowly, seeming to move his\
tongue with difficulty; he was much thinner and sallower. Throughout the\
interview, which lasted twenty minutes, he kept complaining of headache\
and of pain in all his limbs. His thin emasculate face seemed to have\
become so tiny; his hair was ruffled, and his crest of curls in front\
stood up in a thin tuft. But in the left eye, which was screwed up and\
seemed to be insinuating something, Smerdyakov showed himself unchanged.\
\'93It\'92s always worth while speaking to a clever man.\'94 Ivan was reminded of\
that at once. He sat down on the stool at his feet. Smerdyakov, with\
painful effort, shifted his position in bed, but he was not the first to\
speak. He remained dumb, and did not even look much interested.\
\
\'93Can you talk to me?\'94 asked Ivan. \'93I won\'92t tire you much.\'94\
\
\'93Certainly I can,\'94 mumbled Smerdyakov, in a faint voice. \'93Has your honor\
been back long?\'94 he added patronizingly, as though encouraging a nervous\
visitor.\
\
\'93I only arrived to\uc0\u8208 day.... To see the mess you are in here.\'94 Smerdyakov\
sighed.\
\
\'93Why do you sigh? You knew of it all along,\'94 Ivan blurted out.\
\
Smerdyakov was stolidly silent for a while.\
\
\'93How could I help knowing? It was clear beforehand. But how could I tell\
it would turn out like that?\'94\
\
\'93What would turn out? Don\'92t prevaricate! You\'92ve foretold you\'92d have a fit;\
on the way down to the cellar, you know. You mentioned the very spot.\'94\
\
\'93Have you said so at the examination yet?\'94 Smerdyakov queried with\
composure.\
\
Ivan felt suddenly angry.\
\
\'93No, I haven\'92t yet, but I certainly shall. You must explain a great deal\
to me, my man; and let me tell you, I am not going to let you play with\
me!\'94\
\
\'93Why should I play with you, when I put my whole trust in you, as in God\
Almighty?\'94 said Smerdyakov, with the same composure, only for a moment\
closing his eyes.\
\
\'93In the first place,\'94 began Ivan, \'93I know that epileptic fits can\'92t be\
told beforehand. I\'92ve inquired; don\'92t try and take me in. You can\'92t\
foretell the day and the hour. How was it you told me the day and the hour\
beforehand, and about the cellar, too? How could you tell that you would\
fall down the cellar stairs in a fit, if you didn\'92t sham a fit on\
purpose?\'94\
\
\'93I had to go to the cellar anyway, several times a day, indeed,\'94\
Smerdyakov drawled deliberately. \'93I fell from the garret just in the same\
way a year ago. It\'92s quite true you can\'92t tell the day and hour of a fit\
beforehand, but you can always have a presentiment of it.\'94\
\
\'93But you did foretell the day and the hour!\'94\
\
\'93In regard to my epilepsy, sir, you had much better inquire of the doctors\
here. You can ask them whether it was a real fit or a sham; it\'92s no use my\
saying any more about it.\'94\
\
\'93And the cellar? How could you know beforehand of the cellar?\'94\
\
\'93You don\'92t seem able to get over that cellar! As I was going down to the\
cellar, I was in terrible dread and doubt. What frightened me most was\
losing you and being left without defense in all the world. So I went down\
into the cellar thinking, \'91Here, it\'92ll come on directly, it\'92ll strike me\
down directly, shall I fall?\'92 And it was through this fear that I suddenly\
felt the spasm that always comes ... and so I went flying. All that and\
all my previous conversation with you at the gate the evening before, when\
I told you how frightened I was and spoke of the cellar, I told all that\
to Doctor Herzenstube and Nikolay Parfenovitch, the investigating lawyer,\
and it\'92s all been written down in the protocol. And the doctor here, Mr.\
Varvinsky, maintained to all of them that it was just the thought of it\
brought it on, the apprehension that I might fall. It was just then that\
the fit seized me. And so they\'92ve written it down, that it\'92s just how it\
must have happened, simply from my fear.\'94\
\
As he finished, Smerdyakov drew a deep breath, as though exhausted.\
\
\'93Then you have said all that in your evidence?\'94 said Ivan, somewhat taken\
aback. He had meant to frighten him with the threat of repeating their\
conversation, and it appeared that Smerdyakov had already reported it all\
himself.\
\
\'93What have I to be afraid of? Let them write down the whole truth,\'94\
Smerdyakov pronounced firmly.\
\
\'93And have you told them every word of our conversation at the gate?\'94\
\
\'93No, not to say every word.\'94\
\
\'93And did you tell them that you can sham fits, as you boasted then?\'94\
\
\'93No, I didn\'92t tell them that either.\'94\
\
\'93Tell me now, why did you send me then to Tchermashnya?\'94\
\
\'93I was afraid you\'92d go away to Moscow; Tchermashnya is nearer, anyway.\'94\
\
\'93You are lying; you suggested my going away yourself; you told me to get\
out of the way of trouble.\'94\
\
\'93That was simply out of affection and my sincere devotion to you,\
foreseeing trouble in the house, to spare you. Only I wanted to spare\
myself even more. That\'92s why I told you to get out of harm\'92s way, that you\
might understand that there would be trouble in the house, and would\
remain at home to protect your father.\'94\
\
\'93You might have said it more directly, you blockhead!\'94 Ivan suddenly fired\
up.\
\
\'93How could I have said it more directly then? It was simply my fear that\
made me speak, and you might have been angry, too. I might well have been\
apprehensive that Dmitri Fyodorovitch would make a scene and carry away\
that money, for he considered it as good as his own; but who could tell\
that it would end in a murder like this? I thought that he would only\
carry off the three thousand that lay under the master\'92s mattress in the\
envelope, and you see, he\'92s murdered him. How could you guess it either,\
sir?\'94\
\
\'93But if you say yourself that it couldn\'92t be guessed, how could I have\
guessed and stayed at home? You contradict yourself!\'94 said Ivan,\
pondering.\
\
\'93You might have guessed from my sending you to Tchermashnya and not to\
Moscow.\'94\
\
\'93How could I guess it from that?\'94\
\
Smerdyakov seemed much exhausted, and again he was silent for a minute.\
\
\'93You might have guessed from the fact of my asking you not to go to\
Moscow, but to Tchermashnya, that I wanted to have you nearer, for\
Moscow\'92s a long way off, and Dmitri Fyodorovitch, knowing you are not far\
off, would not be so bold. And if anything had happened, you might have\
come to protect me, too, for I warned you of Grigory Vassilyevitch\'92s\
illness, and that I was afraid of having a fit. And when I explained those\
knocks to you, by means of which one could go in to the deceased, and that\
Dmitri Fyodorovitch knew them all through me, I thought that you would\
guess yourself that he would be sure to do something, and so wouldn\'92t go\
to Tchermashnya even, but would stay.\'94\
\
\'93He talks very coherently,\'94 thought Ivan, \'93though he does mumble; what\'92s\
the derangement of his faculties that Herzenstube talked of?\'94\
\
\'93You are cunning with me, damn you!\'94 he exclaimed, getting angry.\
\
\'93But I thought at the time that you quite guessed,\'94 Smerdyakov parried\
with the simplest air.\
\
\'93If I\'92d guessed, I should have stayed,\'94 cried Ivan.\
\
\'93Why, I thought that it was because you guessed, that you went away in\
such a hurry, only to get out of trouble, only to run away and save\
yourself in your fright.\'94\
\
\'93You think that every one is as great a coward as yourself?\'94\
\
\'93Forgive me, I thought you were like me.\'94\
\
\'93Of course, I ought to have guessed,\'94 Ivan said in agitation; \'93and I did\
guess there was some mischief brewing on your part ... only you are lying,\
you are lying again,\'94 he cried, suddenly recollecting. \'93Do you remember\
how you went up to the carriage and said to me, \'91It\'92s always worth while\
speaking to a clever man\'92? So you were glad I went away, since you praised\
me?\'94\
\
Smerdyakov sighed again and again. A trace of color came into his face.\
\
\'93If I was pleased,\'94 he articulated rather breathlessly, \'93it was simply\
because you agreed not to go to Moscow, but to Tchermashnya. For it was\
nearer, anyway. Only when I said these words to you, it was not by way of\
praise, but of reproach. You didn\'92t understand it.\'94\
\
\'93What reproach?\'94\
\
\'93Why, that foreseeing such a calamity you deserted your own father, and\
would not protect us, for I might have been taken up any time for stealing\
that three thousand.\'94\
\
\'93Damn you!\'94 Ivan swore again. \'93Stay, did you tell the prosecutor and the\
investigating lawyer about those knocks?\'94\
\
\'93I told them everything just as it was.\'94\
\
Ivan wondered inwardly again.\
\
\'93If I thought of anything then,\'94 he began again, \'93it was solely of some\
wickedness on your part. Dmitri might kill him, but that he would steal\'97I\
did not believe that then.... But I was prepared for any wickedness from\
you. You told me yourself you could sham a fit. What did you say that\
for?\'94\
\
\'93It was just through my simplicity, and I never have shammed a fit on\
purpose in my life. And I only said so then to boast to you. It was just\
foolishness. I liked you so much then, and was open\uc0\u8208 hearted with you.\'94\
\
\'93My brother directly accuses you of the murder and theft.\'94\
\
\'93What else is left for him to do?\'94 said Smerdyakov, with a bitter grin.\
\'93And who will believe him with all the proofs against him? Grigory\
Vassilyevitch saw the door open. What can he say after that? But never\
mind him! He is trembling to save himself.\'94\
\
He slowly ceased speaking; then suddenly, as though on reflection, added:\
\
\'93And look here again. He wants to throw it on me and make out that it is\
the work of my hands\'97I\'92ve heard that already. But as to my being clever at\
shamming a fit: should I have told you beforehand that I could sham one,\
if I really had had such a design against your father? If I had been\
planning such a murder could I have been such a fool as to give such\
evidence against myself beforehand? And to his son, too! Upon my word! Is\
that likely? As if that could be, such a thing has never happened. No one\
hears this talk of ours now, except Providence itself, and if you were to\
tell of it to the prosecutor and Nikolay Parfenovitch you might defend me\
completely by doing so, for who would be likely to be such a criminal, if\
he is so open\uc0\u8208 hearted beforehand? Any one can see that.\'94\
\
\'93Well,\'94 and Ivan got up to cut short the conversation, struck by\
Smerdyakov\'92s last argument. \'93I don\'92t suspect you at all, and I think it\'92s\
absurd, indeed, to suspect you. On the contrary, I am grateful to you for\
setting my mind at rest. Now I am going, but I\'92ll come again. Meanwhile,\
good\uc0\u8208 by. Get well. Is there anything you want?\'94\
\
\'93I am very thankful for everything. Marfa Ignatyevna does not forget me,\
and provides me anything I want, according to her kindness. Good people\
visit me every day.\'94\
\
\'93Good\uc0\u8208 by. But I shan\'92t say anything of your being able to sham a fit, and\
I don\'92t advise you to, either,\'94 something made Ivan say suddenly.\
\
\'93I quite understand. And if you don\'92t speak of that, I shall say nothing\
of that conversation of ours at the gate.\'94\
\
Then it happened that Ivan went out, and only when he had gone a dozen\
steps along the corridor, he suddenly felt that there was an insulting\
significance in Smerdyakov\'92s last words. He was almost on the point of\
turning back, but it was only a passing impulse, and muttering,\
\'93Nonsense!\'94 he went out of the hospital.\
\
His chief feeling was one of relief at the fact that it was not\
Smerdyakov, but Mitya, who had committed the murder, though he might have\
been expected to feel the opposite. He did not want to analyze the reason\
for this feeling, and even felt a positive repugnance at prying into his\
sensations. He felt as though he wanted to make haste to forget something.\
In the following days he became convinced of Mitya\'92s guilt, as he got to\
know all the weight of evidence against him. There was evidence of people\
of no importance, Fenya and her mother, for instance, but the effect of it\
was almost overpowering. As to Perhotin, the people at the tavern, and at\
Plotnikov\'92s shop, as well as the witnesses at Mokroe, their evidence\
seemed conclusive. It was the details that were so damning. The secret of\
the knocks impressed the lawyers almost as much as Grigory\'92s evidence as\
to the open door. Grigory\'92s wife, Marfa, in answer to Ivan\'92s questions,\
declared that Smerdyakov had been lying all night the other side of the\
partition wall. \'93He was not three paces from our bed,\'94 and that although\
she was a sound sleeper she waked several times and heard him moaning, \'93He\
was moaning the whole time, moaning continually.\'94\
\
Talking to Herzenstube, and giving it as his opinion that Smerdyakov was\
not mad, but only rather weak, Ivan only evoked from the old man a subtle\
smile.\
\
\'93Do you know how he spends his time now?\'94 he asked; \'93learning lists of\
French words by heart. He has an exercise\uc0\u8208 book under his pillow with the\
French words written out in Russian letters for him by some one, he he\
he!\'94\
\
Ivan ended by dismissing all doubts. He could not think of Dmitri without\
repulsion. Only one thing was strange, however. Alyosha persisted that\
Dmitri was not the murderer, and that \'93in all probability\'94 Smerdyakov was.\
Ivan always felt that Alyosha\'92s opinion meant a great deal to him, and so\
he was astonished at it now. Another thing that was strange was that\
Alyosha did not make any attempt to talk about Mitya with Ivan, that he\
never began on the subject and only answered his questions. This, too,\
struck Ivan particularly.\
\
But he was very much preoccupied at that time with something quite apart\
from that. On his return from Moscow, he abandoned himself hopelessly to\
his mad and consuming passion for Katerina Ivanovna. This is not the time\
to begin to speak of this new passion of Ivan\'92s, which left its mark on\
all the rest of his life: this would furnish the subject for another\
novel, which I may perhaps never write. But I cannot omit to mention here\
that when Ivan, on leaving Katerina Ivanovna with Alyosha, as I\'92ve related\
already, told him, \'93I am not keen on her,\'94 it was an absolute lie: he\
loved her madly, though at times he hated her so that he might have\
murdered her. Many causes helped to bring about this feeling. Shattered by\
what had happened with Mitya, she rushed on Ivan\'92s return to meet him as\
her one salvation. She was hurt, insulted and humiliated in her feelings.\
And here the man had come back to her, who had loved her so ardently\
before (oh! she knew that very well), and whose heart and intellect she\
considered so superior to her own. But the sternly virtuous girl did not\
abandon herself altogether to the man she loved, in spite of the Karamazov\
violence of his passions and the great fascination he had for her. She was\
continually tormented at the same time by remorse for having deserted\
Mitya, and in moments of discord and violent anger (and they were\
numerous) she told Ivan so plainly. This was what he had called to Alyosha\
\'93lies upon lies.\'94 There was, of course, much that was false in it, and\
that angered Ivan more than anything.... But of all this later.\
\
He did, in fact, for a time almost forget Smerdyakov\'92s existence, and yet,\
a fortnight after his first visit to him, he began to be haunted by the\
same strange thoughts as before. It\'92s enough to say that he was\
continually asking himself, why was it that on that last night in Fyodor\
Pavlovitch\'92s house he had crept out on to the stairs like a thief and\
listened to hear what his father was doing below? Why had he recalled that\
afterwards with repulsion? Why next morning, had he been suddenly so\
depressed on the journey? Why, as he reached Moscow, had he said to\
himself, \'93I am a scoundrel\'94? And now he almost fancied that these\
tormenting thoughts would make him even forget Katerina Ivanovna, so\
completely did they take possession of him again. It was just after\
fancying this, that he met Alyosha in the street. He stopped him at once,\
and put a question to him:\
\
\'93Do you remember when Dmitri burst in after dinner and beat father, and\
afterwards I told you in the yard that I reserved \'91the right to\
desire\'92?... Tell me, did you think then that I desired father\'92s death or\
not?\'94\
\
\'93I did think so,\'94 answered Alyosha, softly.\
\
\'93It was so, too; it was not a matter of guessing. But didn\'92t you fancy\
then that what I wished was just that \'91one reptile should devour another\'92;\
that is, just that Dmitri should kill father, and as soon as possible ...\
and that I myself was even prepared to help to bring that about?\'94\
\
Alyosha turned rather pale, and looked silently into his brother\'92s face.\
\
\'93Speak!\'94 cried Ivan, \'93I want above everything to know what you thought\
then. I want the truth, the truth!\'94\
\
He drew a deep breath, looking angrily at Alyosha before his answer came.\
\
\'93Forgive me, I did think that, too, at the time,\'94 whispered Alyosha, and\
he did not add one softening phrase.\
\
\'93Thanks,\'94 snapped Ivan, and, leaving Alyosha, he went quickly on his way.\
From that time Alyosha noticed that Ivan began obviously to avoid him and\
seemed even to have taken a dislike to him, so much so that Alyosha gave\
up going to see him. Immediately after that meeting with him, Ivan had not\
gone home, but went straight to Smerdyakov again.\
\
\
\
Chapter VII. The Second Visit To Smerdyakov\
\
\
By that time Smerdyakov had been discharged from the hospital. Ivan knew\
his new lodging, the dilapidated little wooden house, divided in two by a\
passage on one side of which lived Marya Kondratyevna and her mother, and\
on the other, Smerdyakov. No one knew on what terms he lived with them,\
whether as a friend or as a lodger. It was supposed afterwards that he had\
come to stay with them as Marya Kondratyevna\'92s betrothed, and was living\
there for a time without paying for board or lodging. Both mother and\
daughter had the greatest respect for him and looked upon him as greatly\
superior to themselves.\
\
Ivan knocked, and, on the door being opened, went straight into the\
passage. By Marya Kondratyevna\'92s directions he went straight to the better\
room on the left, occupied by Smerdyakov. There was a tiled stove in the\
room and it was extremely hot. The walls were gay with blue paper, which\
was a good deal used however, and in the cracks under it cockroaches\
swarmed in amazing numbers, so that there was a continual rustling from\
them. The furniture was very scanty: two benches against each wall and two\
chairs by the table. The table of plain wood was covered with a cloth with\
pink patterns on it. There was a pot of geranium on each of the two little\
windows. In the corner there was a case of ikons. On the table stood a\
little copper samovar with many dents in it, and a tray with two cups. But\
Smerdyakov had finished tea and the samovar was out. He was sitting at the\
table on a bench. He was looking at an exercise\uc0\u8208 book and slowly writing\
with a pen. There was a bottle of ink by him and a flat iron candlestick,\
but with a composite candle. Ivan saw at once from Smerdyakov\'92s face that\
he had completely recovered from his illness. His face was fresher,\
fuller, his hair stood up jauntily in front, and was plastered down at the\
sides. He was sitting in a parti\uc0\u8208 colored, wadded dressing\u8208 gown, rather\
dirty and frayed, however. He had spectacles on his nose, which Ivan had\
never seen him wearing before. This trifling circumstance suddenly\
redoubled Ivan\'92s anger: \'93A creature like that and wearing spectacles!\'94\
\
Smerdyakov slowly raised his head and looked intently at his visitor\
through his spectacles; then he slowly took them off and rose from the\
bench, but by no means respectfully, almost lazily, doing the least\
possible required by common civility. All this struck Ivan instantly; he\
took it all in and noted it at once\'97most of all the look in Smerdyakov\'92s\
eyes, positively malicious, churlish and haughty. \'93What do you want to\
intrude for?\'94 it seemed to say; \'93we settled everything then; why have you\
come again?\'94 Ivan could scarcely control himself.\
\
\'93It\'92s hot here,\'94 he said, still standing, and unbuttoned his overcoat.\
\
\'93Take off your coat,\'94 Smerdyakov conceded.\
\
Ivan took off his coat and threw it on a bench with trembling hands. He\
took a chair, moved it quickly to the table and sat down. Smerdyakov\
managed to sit down on his bench before him.\
\
\'93To begin with, are we alone?\'94 Ivan asked sternly and impulsively. \'93Can\
they overhear us in there?\'94\
\
\'93No one can hear anything. You\'92ve seen for yourself: there\'92s a passage.\'94\
\
\'93Listen, my good fellow; what was that you babbled, as I was leaving the\
hospital, that if I said nothing about your faculty of shamming fits, you\
wouldn\'92t tell the investigating lawyer all our conversation at the gate?\
What do you mean by _all_? What could you mean by it? Were you threatening\
me? Have I entered into some sort of compact with you? Do you suppose I am\
afraid of you?\'94\
\
Ivan said this in a perfect fury, giving him to understand with obvious\
intention that he scorned any subterfuge or indirectness and meant to show\
his cards. Smerdyakov\'92s eyes gleamed resentfully, his left eye winked, and\
he at once gave his answer, with his habitual composure and deliberation.\
\'93You want to have everything above\uc0\u8208 board; very well, you shall have it,\'94\
he seemed to say.\
\
\'93This is what I meant then, and this is why I said that, that you, knowing\
beforehand of this murder of your own parent, left him to his fate, and\
that people mightn\'92t after that conclude any evil about your feelings and\
perhaps of something else, too\'97that\'92s what I promised not to tell the\
authorities.\'94\
\
Though Smerdyakov spoke without haste and obviously controlling himself,\
yet there was something in his voice, determined and emphatic, resentful\
and insolently defiant. He stared impudently at Ivan. A mist passed before\
Ivan\'92s eyes for the first moment.\
\
\'93How? What? Are you out of your mind?\'94\
\
\'93I\'92m perfectly in possession of all my faculties.\'94\
\
\'93Do you suppose I _knew_ of the murder?\'94 Ivan cried at last, and he\
brought his fist violently on the table. \'93What do you mean by \'91something\
else, too\'92? Speak, scoundrel!\'94\
\
Smerdyakov was silent and still scanned Ivan with the same insolent stare.\
\
\'93Speak, you stinking rogue, what is that \'91something else, too\'92?\'94\
\
\'93The \'91something else\'92 I meant was that you probably, too, were very\
desirous of your parent\'92s death.\'94\
\
Ivan jumped up and struck him with all his might on the shoulder, so that\
he fell back against the wall. In an instant his face was bathed in tears.\
Saying, \'93It\'92s a shame, sir, to strike a sick man,\'94 he dried his eyes with\
a very dirty blue check handkerchief and sank into quiet weeping. A minute\
passed.\
\
\'93That\'92s enough! Leave off,\'94 Ivan said peremptorily, sitting down again.\
\'93Don\'92t put me out of all patience.\'94\
\
Smerdyakov took the rag from his eyes. Every line of his puckered face\
reflected the insult he had just received.\
\
\'93So you thought then, you scoundrel, that together with Dmitri I meant to\
kill my father?\'94\
\
\'93I didn\'92t know what thoughts were in your mind then,\'94 said Smerdyakov\
resentfully; \'93and so I stopped you then at the gate to sound you on that\
very point.\'94\
\
\'93To sound what, what?\'94\
\
\'93Why, that very circumstance, whether you wanted your father to be\
murdered or not.\'94\
\
What infuriated Ivan more than anything was the aggressive, insolent tone\
to which Smerdyakov persistently adhered.\
\
\'93It was you murdered him?\'94 he cried suddenly.\
\
Smerdyakov smiled contemptuously.\
\
\'93You know of yourself, for a fact, that it wasn\'92t I murdered him. And I\
should have thought that there was no need for a sensible man to speak of\
it again.\'94\
\
\'93But why, why had you such a suspicion about me at the time?\'94\
\
\'93As you know already, it was simply from fear. For I was in such a\
position, shaking with fear, that I suspected every one. I resolved to\
sound you, too, for I thought if you wanted the same as your brother, then\
the business was as good as settled and I should be crushed like a fly,\
too.\'94\
\
\'93Look here, you didn\'92t say that a fortnight ago.\'94\
\
\'93I meant the same when I talked to you in the hospital, only I thought\
you\'92d understand without wasting words, and that being such a sensible man\
you wouldn\'92t care to talk of it openly.\'94\
\
\'93What next! Come answer, answer, I insist: what was it ... what could I\
have done to put such a degrading suspicion into your mean soul?\'94\
\
\'93As for the murder, you couldn\'92t have done that and didn\'92t want to, but as\
for wanting some one else to do it, that was just what you did want.\'94\
\
\'93And how coolly, how coolly he speaks! But why should I have wanted it;\
what grounds had I for wanting it?\'94\
\
\'93What grounds had you? What about the inheritance?\'94 said Smerdyakov\
sarcastically, and, as it were, vindictively. \'93Why, after your parent\'92s\
death there was at least forty thousand to come to each of you, and very\
likely more, but if Fyodor Pavlovitch got married then to that lady,\
Agrafena Alexandrovna, she would have had all his capital made over to her\
directly after the wedding, for she\'92s plenty of sense, so that your parent\
would not have left you two roubles between the three of you. And were\
they far from a wedding, either? Not a hair\'92s\uc0\u8208 breadth: that lady had only\
to lift her little finger and he would have run after her to church, with\
his tongue out.\'94\
\
Ivan restrained himself with painful effort.\
\
\'93Very good,\'94 he commented at last. \'93You see, I haven\'92t jumped up, I\
haven\'92t knocked you down, I haven\'92t killed you. Speak on. So, according to\
you, I had fixed on Dmitri to do it; I was reckoning on him?\'94\
\
\'93How could you help reckoning on him? If he killed him, then he would lose\
all the rights of a nobleman, his rank and property, and would go off to\
exile; so his share of the inheritance would come to you and your brother\
Alexey Fyodorovitch in equal parts; so you\'92d each have not forty, but\
sixty thousand each. There\'92s not a doubt you did reckon on Dmitri\
Fyodorovitch.\'94\
\
\'93What I put up with from you! Listen, scoundrel, if I had reckoned on any\
one then, it would have been on you, not on Dmitri, and I swear I did\
expect some wickedness from you ... at the time.... I remember my\
impression!\'94\
\
\'93I thought, too, for a minute, at the time, that you were reckoning on me\
as well,\'94 said Smerdyakov, with a sarcastic grin. \'93So that it was just by\
that more than anything you showed me what was in your mind. For if you\
had a foreboding about me and yet went away, you as good as said to me,\
\'91You can murder my parent, I won\'92t hinder you!\'92 \'94\
\
\'93You scoundrel! So that\'92s how you understood it!\'94\
\
\'93It was all that going to Tchermashnya. Why! You were meaning to go to\
Moscow and refused all your father\'92s entreaties to go to Tchermashnya\'97and\
simply at a foolish word from me you consented at once! What reason had\
you to consent to Tchermashnya? Since you went to Tchermashnya with no\
reason, simply at my word, it shows that you must have expected something\
from me.\'94\
\
\'93No, I swear I didn\'92t!\'94 shouted Ivan, grinding his teeth.\
\
\'93You didn\'92t? Then you ought, as your father\'92s son, to have had me taken to\
the lock\uc0\u8208 up and thrashed at once for my words then ... or at least, to\
have given me a punch in the face on the spot, but you were not a bit\
angry, if you please, and at once in a friendly way acted on my foolish\
word and went away, which was utterly absurd, for you ought to have stayed\
to save your parent\'92s life. How could I help drawing my conclusions?\'94\
\
Ivan sat scowling, both his fists convulsively pressed on his knees.\
\
\'93Yes, I am sorry I didn\'92t punch you in the face,\'94 he said with a bitter\
smile. \'93I couldn\'92t have taken you to the lock\uc0\u8208 up just then. Who would have\
believed me and what charge could I bring against you? But the punch in\
the face ... oh, I\'92m sorry I didn\'92t think of it. Though blows are\
forbidden, I should have pounded your ugly face to a jelly.\'94\
\
Smerdyakov looked at him almost with relish.\
\
\'93In the ordinary occasions of life,\'94 he said in the same complacent and\
sententious tone in which he had taunted Grigory and argued with him about\
religion at Fyodor Pavlovitch\'92s table, \'93in the ordinary occasions of life,\
blows on the face are forbidden nowadays by law, and people have given\
them up, but in exceptional occasions of life people still fly to blows,\
not only among us but all over the world, be it even the fullest Republic\
of France, just as in the time of Adam and Eve, and they never will leave\
off, but you, even in an exceptional case, did not dare.\'94\
\
\'93What are you learning French words for?\'94 Ivan nodded towards the\
exercise\uc0\u8208 book lying on the table.\
\
\'93Why shouldn\'92t I learn them so as to improve my education, supposing that\
I may myself chance to go some day to those happy parts of Europe?\'94\
\
\'93Listen, monster.\'94 Ivan\'92s eyes flashed and he trembled all over. \'93I am not\
afraid of your accusations; you can say what you like about me, and if I\
don\'92t beat you to death, it\'92s simply because I suspect you of that crime\
and I\'92ll drag you to justice. I\'92ll unmask you.\'94\
\
\'93To my thinking, you\'92d better keep quiet, for what can you accuse me of,\
considering my absolute innocence? and who would believe you? Only if you\
begin, I shall tell everything, too, for I must defend myself.\'94\
\
\'93Do you think I am afraid of you now?\'94\
\
\'93If the court doesn\'92t believe all I\'92ve said to you just now, the public\
will, and you will be ashamed.\'94\
\
\'93That\'92s as much as to say, \'91It\'92s always worth while speaking to a sensible\
man,\'92 eh?\'94 snarled Ivan.\
\
\'93You hit the mark, indeed. And you\'92d better be sensible.\'94\
\
Ivan got up, shaking all over with indignation, put on his coat, and\
without replying further to Smerdyakov, without even looking at him,\
walked quickly out of the cottage. The cool evening air refreshed him.\
There was a bright moon in the sky. A nightmare of ideas and sensations\
filled his soul. \'93Shall I go at once and give information against\
Smerdyakov? But what information can I give? He is not guilty, anyway. On\
the contrary, he\'92ll accuse me. And in fact, why did I set off for\
Tchermashnya then? What for? What for?\'94 Ivan asked himself. \'93Yes, of\
course, I was expecting something and he is right....\'94 And he remembered\
for the hundredth time how, on the last night in his father\'92s house, he\
had listened on the stairs. But he remembered it now with such anguish\
that he stood still on the spot as though he had been stabbed. \'93Yes, I\
expected it then, that\'92s true! I wanted the murder, I did want the murder!\
Did I want the murder? Did I want it? I must kill Smerdyakov! If I don\'92t\
dare kill Smerdyakov now, life is not worth living!\'94\
\
Ivan did not go home, but went straight to Katerina Ivanovna and alarmed\
her by his appearance. He was like a madman. He repeated all his\
conversation with Smerdyakov, every syllable of it. He couldn\'92t be calmed,\
however much she tried to soothe him: he kept walking about the room,\
speaking strangely, disconnectedly. At last he sat down, put his elbows on\
the table, leaned his head on his hands and pronounced this strange\
sentence: \'93If it\'92s not Dmitri, but Smerdyakov who\'92s the murderer, I share\
his guilt, for I put him up to it. Whether I did, I don\'92t know yet. But if\
he is the murderer, and not Dmitri, then, of course, I am the murderer,\
too.\'94\
\
When Katerina Ivanovna heard that, she got up from her seat without a\
word, went to her writing\uc0\u8208 table, opened a box standing on it, took out a\
sheet of paper and laid it before Ivan. This was the document of which\
Ivan spoke to Alyosha later on as a \'93conclusive proof\'94 that Dmitri had\
killed his father. It was the letter written by Mitya to Katerina Ivanovna\
when he was drunk, on the very evening he met Alyosha at the crossroads on\
the way to the monastery, after the scene at Katerina Ivanovna\'92s, when\
Grushenka had insulted her. Then, parting from Alyosha, Mitya had rushed\
to Grushenka. I don\'92t know whether he saw her, but in the evening he was\
at the \'93Metropolis,\'94 where he got thoroughly drunk. Then he asked for pen\
and paper and wrote a document of weighty consequences to himself. It was\
a wordy, disconnected, frantic letter, a drunken letter in fact. It was\
like the talk of a drunken man, who, on his return home, begins with\
extraordinary heat telling his wife or one of his household how he has\
just been insulted, what a rascal had just insulted him, what a fine\
fellow he is on the other hand, and how he will pay that scoundrel out;\
and all that at great length, with great excitement and incoherence, with\
drunken tears and blows on the table. The letter was written on a dirty\
piece of ordinary paper of the cheapest kind. It had been provided by the\
tavern and there were figures scrawled on the back of it. There was\
evidently not space enough for his drunken verbosity and Mitya not only\
filled the margins but had written the last line right across the rest.\
The letter ran as follows:\
\
\
    FATAL KATYA: To\uc0\u8208 morrow I will get the money and repay your three\
    thousand and farewell, woman of great wrath, but farewell, too, my\
    love! Let us make an end! To\uc0\u8208 morrow I shall try and get it from\
    every one, and if I can\'92t borrow it, I give you my word of honor I\
    shall go to my father and break his skull and take the money from\
    under the pillow, if only Ivan has gone. If I have to go to\
    Siberia for it, I\'92ll give you back your three thousand. And\
    farewell. I bow down to the ground before you, for I\'92ve been a\
    scoundrel to you. Forgive me! No, better not forgive me, you\'92ll be\
    happier and so shall I! Better Siberia than your love, for I love\
    another woman and you got to know her too well to\uc0\u8208 day, so how can\
    you forgive? I will murder the man who\'92s robbed me! I\'92ll leave you\
    all and go to the East so as to see no one again. Not _her_\
    either, for you are not my only tormentress; she is too. Farewell!\
\
    P.S.\'97I write my curse, but I adore you! I hear it in my heart. One\
    string is left, and it vibrates. Better tear my heart in two! I\
    shall kill myself, but first of all that cur. I shall tear three\
    thousand from him and fling it to you. Though I\'92ve been a\
    scoundrel to you, I am not a thief! You can expect three thousand.\
    The cur keeps it under his mattress, in pink ribbon. I am not a\
    thief, but I\'92ll murder my thief. Katya, don\'92t look disdainful.\
    Dmitri is not a thief! but a murderer! He has murdered his father\
    and ruined himself to hold his ground, rather than endure your\
    pride. And he doesn\'92t love you.\
\
    P.P.S.\'97I kiss your feet, farewell! P.P.P.S.\'97Katya, pray to God\
    that some one\'92ll give me the money. Then I shall not be steeped in\
    gore, and if no one does\'97I shall! Kill me!\
\
    Your slave and enemy,\
\
    D. KARAMAZOV.\
\
\
When Ivan read this \'93document\'94 he was convinced. So then it was his\
brother, not Smerdyakov. And if not Smerdyakov, then not he, Ivan. This\
letter at once assumed in his eyes the aspect of a logical proof. There\
could be no longer the slightest doubt of Mitya\'92s guilt. The suspicion\
never occurred to Ivan, by the way, that Mitya might have committed the\
murder in conjunction with Smerdyakov, and, indeed, such a theory did not\
fit in with the facts. Ivan was completely reassured. The next morning he\
only thought of Smerdyakov and his gibes with contempt. A few days later\
he positively wondered how he could have been so horribly distressed at\
his suspicions. He resolved to dismiss him with contempt and forget him.\
So passed a month. He made no further inquiry about Smerdyakov, but twice\
he happened to hear that he was very ill and out of his mind.\
\
\'93He\'92ll end in madness,\'94 the young doctor Varvinsky observed about him, and\
Ivan remembered this. During the last week of that month Ivan himself\
began to feel very ill. He went to consult the Moscow doctor who had been\
sent for by Katerina Ivanovna just before the trial. And just at that time\
his relations with Katerina Ivanovna became acutely strained. They were\
like two enemies in love with one another. Katerina Ivanovna\'92s \'93returns\'94\
to Mitya, that is, her brief but violent revulsions of feeling in his\
favor, drove Ivan to perfect frenzy. Strange to say, until that last scene\
described above, when Alyosha came from Mitya to Katerina Ivanovna, Ivan\
had never once, during that month, heard her express a doubt of Mitya\'92s\
guilt, in spite of those \'93returns\'94 that were so hateful to him. It is\
remarkable, too, that while he felt that he hated Mitya more and more\
every day, he realized that it was not on account of Katya\'92s \'93returns\'94\
that he hated him, but just _because he was the murderer of his father_.\
He was conscious of this and fully recognized it to himself.\
\
Nevertheless, he went to see Mitya ten days before the trial and proposed\
to him a plan of escape\'97a plan he had obviously thought over a long time.\
He was partly impelled to do this by a sore place still left in his heart\
from a phrase of Smerdyakov\'92s, that it was to his, Ivan\'92s, advantage that\
his brother should be convicted, as that would increase his inheritance\
and Alyosha\'92s from forty to sixty thousand roubles. He determined to\
sacrifice thirty thousand on arranging Mitya\'92s escape. On his return from\
seeing him, he was very mournful and dispirited; he suddenly began to feel\
that he was anxious for Mitya\'92s escape, not only to heal that sore place\
by sacrificing thirty thousand, but for another reason. \'93Is it because I\
am as much a murderer at heart?\'94 he asked himself. Something very deep\
down seemed burning and rankling in his soul. His pride above all suffered\
cruelly all that month. But of that later....\
\
When, after his conversation with Alyosha, Ivan suddenly decided with his\
hand on the bell of his lodging to go to Smerdyakov, he obeyed a sudden\
and peculiar impulse of indignation. He suddenly remembered how Katerina\
Ivanovna had only just cried out to him in Alyosha\'92s presence: \'93It was\
you, you, persuaded me of his\'94 (that is, Mitya\'92s) \'93guilt!\'94 Ivan was\
thunderstruck when he recalled it. He had never once tried to persuade her\
that Mitya was the murderer; on the contrary, he had suspected himself in\
her presence, that time when he came back from Smerdyakov. It was _she_,\
she, who had produced that \'93document\'94 and proved his brother\'92s guilt. And\
now she suddenly exclaimed: \'93I\'92ve been at Smerdyakov\'92s myself!\'94 When had\
she been there? Ivan had known nothing of it. So she was not at all so\
sure of Mitya\'92s guilt! And what could Smerdyakov have told her? What,\
what, had he said to her? His heart burned with violent anger. He could\
not understand how he could, half an hour before, have let those words\
pass and not have cried out at the moment. He let go of the bell and\
rushed off to Smerdyakov. \'93I shall kill him, perhaps, this time,\'94 he\
thought on the way.\
\
\
\
Chapter VIII. The Third And Last Interview With Smerdyakov\
\
\
When he was half\uc0\u8208 way there, the keen dry wind that had been blowing early\
that morning rose again, and a fine dry snow began falling thickly. It did\
not lie on the ground, but was whirled about by the wind, and soon there\
was a regular snowstorm. There were scarcely any lamp\uc0\u8208 posts in the part of\
the town where Smerdyakov lived. Ivan strode alone in the darkness,\
unconscious of the storm, instinctively picking out his way. His head\
ached and there was a painful throbbing in his temples. He felt that his\
hands were twitching convulsively. Not far from Marya Kondratyevna\'92s\
cottage, Ivan suddenly came upon a solitary drunken little peasant. He was\
wearing a coarse and patched coat, and was walking in zigzags, grumbling\
and swearing to himself. Then suddenly he would begin singing in a husky\
drunken voice:\
\
\
    \'93Ach, Vanka\'92s gone to Petersburg;\
    I won\'92t wait till he comes back.\'94\
\
\
But he broke off every time at the second line and began swearing again;\
then he would begin the same song again. Ivan felt an intense hatred for\
him before he had thought about him at all. Suddenly he realized his\
presence and felt an irresistible impulse to knock him down. At that\
moment they met, and the peasant with a violent lurch fell full tilt\
against Ivan, who pushed him back furiously. The peasant went flying\
backwards and fell like a log on the frozen ground. He uttered one\
plaintive \'93O\'97oh!\'94 and then was silent. Ivan stepped up to him. He was\
lying on his back, without movement or consciousness. \'93He will be frozen,\'94\
thought Ivan, and he went on his way to Smerdyakov\'92s.\
\
In the passage, Marya Kondratyevna, who ran out to open the door with a\
candle in her hand, whispered that Smerdyakov was very ill, \'93It\'92s not that\
he\'92s laid up, but he seems not himself, and he even told us to take the\
tea away; he wouldn\'92t have any.\'94\
\
\'93Why, does he make a row?\'94 asked Ivan coarsely.\
\
\'93Oh, dear, no, quite the contrary, he\'92s very quiet. Only please don\'92t talk\
to him too long,\'94 Marya Kondratyevna begged him. Ivan opened the door and\
stepped into the room.\
\
It was over\uc0\u8208 heated as before, but there were changes in the room. One of\
the benches at the side had been removed, and in its place had been put a\
large old mahogany leather sofa, on which a bed had been made up, with\
fairly clean white pillows. Smerdyakov was sitting on the sofa, wearing\
the same dressing\uc0\u8208 gown. The table had been brought out in front of the\
sofa, so that there was hardly room to move. On the table lay a thick book\
in yellow cover, but Smerdyakov was not reading it. He seemed to be\
sitting doing nothing. He met Ivan with a slow silent gaze, and was\
apparently not at all surprised at his coming. There was a great change in\
his face; he was much thinner and sallower. His eyes were sunken and there\
were blue marks under them.\
\
\'93Why, you really are ill?\'94 Ivan stopped short. \'93I won\'92t keep you long, I\
won\'92t even take off my coat. Where can one sit down?\'94\
\
He went to the other end of the table, moved up a chair and sat down on\
it.\
\
\'93Why do you look at me without speaking? I\'92ve only come with one question,\
and I swear I won\'92t go without an answer. Has the young lady, Katerina\
Ivanovna, been with you?\'94\
\
Smerdyakov still remained silent, looking quietly at Ivan as before.\
Suddenly, with a motion of his hand, he turned his face away.\
\
\'93What\'92s the matter with you?\'94 cried Ivan.\
\
\'93Nothing.\'94\
\
\'93What do you mean by \'91nothing\'92?\'94\
\
\'93Yes, she has. It\'92s no matter to you. Let me alone.\'94\
\
\'93No, I won\'92t let you alone. Tell me, when was she here?\'94\
\
\'93Why, I\'92d quite forgotten about her,\'94 said Smerdyakov, with a scornful\
smile, and turning his face to Ivan again, he stared at him with a look of\
frenzied hatred, the same look that he had fixed on him at their last\
interview, a month before.\
\
\'93You seem very ill yourself, your face is sunken; you don\'92t look like\
yourself,\'94 he said to Ivan.\
\
\'93Never mind my health, tell me what I ask you.\'94\
\
\'93But why are your eyes so yellow? The whites are quite yellow. Are you so\
worried?\'94 He smiled contemptuously and suddenly laughed outright.\
\
\'93Listen; I\'92ve told you I won\'92t go away without an answer!\'94 Ivan cried,\
intensely irritated.\
\
\'93Why do you keep pestering me? Why do you torment me?\'94 said Smerdyakov,\
with a look of suffering.\
\
\'93Damn it! I\'92ve nothing to do with you. Just answer my question and I\'92ll go\
away.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92ve no answer to give you,\'94 said Smerdyakov, looking down again.\
\
\'93You may be sure I\'92ll make you answer!\'94\
\
\'93Why are you so uneasy?\'94 Smerdyakov stared at him, not simply with\
contempt, but almost with repulsion. \'93Is this because the trial begins to\uc0\u8208 \
morrow? Nothing will happen to you; can\'92t you believe that at last? Go\
home, go to bed and sleep in peace, don\'92t be afraid of anything.\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t understand you.... What have I to be afraid of to\uc0\u8208 morrow?\'94 Ivan\
articulated in astonishment, and suddenly a chill breath of fear did in\
fact pass over his soul. Smerdyakov measured him with his eyes.\
\
\'93You don\'92t understand?\'94 he drawled reproachfully. \'93It\'92s a strange thing a\
sensible man should care to play such a farce!\'94\
\
Ivan looked at him speechless. The startling, incredibly supercilious tone\
of this man who had once been his valet, was extraordinary in itself. He\
had not taken such a tone even at their last interview.\
\
\'93I tell you, you\'92ve nothing to be afraid of. I won\'92t say anything about\
you; there\'92s no proof against you. I say, how your hands are trembling!\
Why are your fingers moving like that? Go home, _you_ did not murder him.\'94\
\
Ivan started. He remembered Alyosha.\
\
\'93I know it was not I,\'94 he faltered.\
\
\'93Do you?\'94 Smerdyakov caught him up again.\
\
Ivan jumped up and seized him by the shoulder.\
\
\'93Tell me everything, you viper! Tell me everything!\'94\
\
Smerdyakov was not in the least scared. He only riveted his eyes on Ivan\
with insane hatred.\
\
\'93Well, it was you who murdered him, if that\'92s it,\'94 he whispered furiously.\
\
Ivan sank back on his chair, as though pondering something. He laughed\
malignantly.\
\
\'93You mean my going away. What you talked about last time?\'94\
\
\'93You stood before me last time and understood it all, and you understand\
it now.\'94\
\
\'93All I understand is that you are mad.\'94\
\
\'93Aren\'92t you tired of it? Here we are face to face; what\'92s the use of going\
on keeping up a farce to each other? Are you still trying to throw it all\
on me, to my face? _You_ murdered him; you are the real murderer, I was\
only your instrument, your faithful servant, and it was following your\
words I did it.\'94\
\
\'93_Did_ it? Why, did you murder him?\'94 Ivan turned cold.\
\
Something seemed to give way in his brain, and he shuddered all over with\
a cold shiver. Then Smerdyakov himself looked at him wonderingly; probably\
the genuineness of Ivan\'92s horror struck him.\
\
\'93You don\'92t mean to say you really did not know?\'94 he faltered\
mistrustfully, looking with a forced smile into his eyes. Ivan still gazed\
at him, and seemed unable to speak.\
\
\
    Ach, Vanka\'92s gone to Petersburg;\
    I won\'92t wait till he comes back,\
\
\
suddenly echoed in his head.\
\
\'93Do you know, I am afraid that you are a dream, a phantom sitting before\
me,\'94 he muttered.\
\
\'93There\'92s no phantom here, but only us two and one other. No doubt he is\
here, that third, between us.\'94\
\
\'93Who is he? Who is here? What third person?\'94 Ivan cried in alarm, looking\
about him, his eyes hastily searching in every corner.\
\
\'93That third is God Himself\'97Providence. He is the third beside us now. Only\
don\'92t look for Him, you won\'92t find Him.\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s a lie that you killed him!\'94 Ivan cried madly. \'93You are mad, or\
teasing me again!\'94\
\
Smerdyakov, as before, watched him curiously, with no sign of fear. He\
could still scarcely get over his incredulity; he still fancied that Ivan\
knew everything and was trying to \'93throw it all on him to his face.\'94\
\
\'93Wait a minute,\'94 he said at last in a weak voice, and suddenly bringing up\
his left leg from under the table, he began turning up his trouser leg. He\
was wearing long white stockings and slippers. Slowly he took off his\
garter and fumbled to the bottom of his stocking. Ivan gazed at him, and\
suddenly shuddered in a paroxysm of terror.\
\
\'93He\'92s mad!\'94 he cried, and rapidly jumping up, he drew back, so that he\
knocked his back against the wall and stood up against it, stiff and\
straight. He looked with insane terror at Smerdyakov, who, entirely\
unaffected by his terror, continued fumbling in his stocking, as though he\
were making an effort to get hold of something with his fingers and pull\
it out. At last he got hold of it and began pulling it out. Ivan saw that\
it was a piece of paper, or perhaps a roll of papers. Smerdyakov pulled it\
out and laid it on the table.\
\
\'93Here,\'94 he said quietly.\
\
\'93What is it?\'94 asked Ivan, trembling.\
\
\'93Kindly look at it,\'94 Smerdyakov answered, still in the same low tone.\
\
Ivan stepped up to the table, took up the roll of paper and began\
unfolding it, but suddenly he drew back his fingers, as though from\
contact with a loathsome reptile.\
\
\'93Your hands keep twitching,\'94 observed Smerdyakov, and he deliberately\
unfolded the bundle himself. Under the wrapper were three packets of\
hundred\uc0\u8208 rouble notes.\
\
\'93They are all here, all the three thousand roubles; you need not count\
them. Take them,\'94 Smerdyakov suggested to Ivan, nodding at the notes. Ivan\
sank back in his chair. He was as white as a handkerchief.\
\
\'93You frightened me ... with your stocking,\'94 he said, with a strange grin.\
\
\'93Can you really not have known till now?\'94 Smerdyakov asked once more.\
\
\'93No, I did not know. I kept thinking of Dmitri. Brother, brother! Ach!\'94 He\
suddenly clutched his head in both hands.\
\
\'93Listen. Did you kill him alone? With my brother\'92s help or without?\'94\
\
\'93It was only with you, with your help, I killed him, and Dmitri\
Fyodorovitch is quite innocent.\'94\
\
\'93All right, all right. Talk about me later. Why do I keep on trembling? I\
can\'92t speak properly.\'94\
\
\'93You were bold enough then. You said \'91everything was lawful,\'92 and how\
frightened you are now,\'94 Smerdyakov muttered in surprise. \'93Won\'92t you have\
some lemonade? I\'92ll ask for some at once. It\'92s very refreshing. Only I\
must hide this first.\'94\
\
And again he motioned at the notes. He was just going to get up and call\
at the door to Marya Kondratyevna to make some lemonade and bring it them,\
but, looking for something to cover up the notes that she might not see\
them, he first took out his handkerchief, and as it turned out to be very\
dirty, took up the big yellow book that Ivan had noticed at first lying on\
the table, and put it over the notes. The book was _The Sayings of the\
Holy Father Isaac the Syrian_. Ivan read it mechanically.\
\
\'93I won\'92t have any lemonade,\'94 he said. \'93Talk of me later. Sit down and tell\
me how you did it. Tell me all about it.\'94\
\
\'93You\'92d better take off your greatcoat, or you\'92ll be too hot.\'94 Ivan, as\
though he\'92d only just thought of it, took off his coat, and, without\
getting up from his chair, threw it on the bench.\
\
\'93Speak, please, speak.\'94\
\
He seemed calmer. He waited, feeling sure that Smerdyakov would tell him\
_all_ about it.\
\
\'93How it was done?\'94 sighed Smerdyakov. \'93It was done in a most natural way,\
following your very words.\'94\
\
\'93Of my words later,\'94 Ivan broke in again, apparently with complete self\uc0\u8208 \
possession, firmly uttering his words, and not shouting as before. \'93Only\
tell me in detail how you did it. Everything, as it happened. Don\'92t forget\
anything. The details, above everything, the details, I beg you.\'94\
\
\'93You\'92d gone away, then I fell into the cellar.\'94\
\
\'93In a fit or in a sham one?\'94\
\
\'93A sham one, naturally. I shammed it all. I went quietly down the steps to\
the very bottom and lay down quietly, and as I lay down I gave a scream,\
and struggled, till they carried me out.\'94\
\
\'93Stay! And were you shamming all along, afterwards, and in the hospital?\'94\
\
\'93No, not at all. Next day, in the morning, before they took me to the\
hospital, I had a real attack and a more violent one than I\'92ve had for\
years. For two days I was quite unconscious.\'94\
\
\'93All right, all right. Go on.\'94\
\
\'93They laid me on the bed. I knew I\'92d be the other side of the partition,\
for whenever I was ill, Marfa Ignatyevna used to put me there, near them.\
She\'92s always been very kind to me, from my birth up. At night I moaned,\
but quietly. I kept expecting Dmitri Fyodorovitch to come.\'94\
\
\'93Expecting him? To come to you?\'94\
\
\'93Not to me. I expected him to come into the house, for I\'92d no doubt that\
he\'92d come that night, for being without me and getting no news, he\'92d be\
sure to come and climb over the fence, as he used to, and do something.\'94\
\
\'93And if he hadn\'92t come?\'94\
\
\'93Then nothing would have happened. I should never have brought myself to\
it without him.\'94\
\
\'93All right, all right ... speak more intelligibly, don\'92t hurry; above all,\
don\'92t leave anything out!\'94\
\
\'93I expected him to kill Fyodor Pavlovitch. I thought that was certain, for\
I had prepared him for it ... during the last few days.... He knew about\
the knocks, that was the chief thing. With his suspiciousness and the fury\
which had been growing in him all those days, he was bound to get into the\
house by means of those taps. That was inevitable, so I was expecting\
him.\'94\
\
\'93Stay,\'94 Ivan interrupted; \'93if he had killed him, he would have taken the\
money and carried it away; you must have considered that. What would you\
have got by it afterwards? I don\'92t see.\'94\
\
\'93But he would never have found the money. That was only what I told him,\
that the money was under the mattress. But that wasn\'92t true. It had been\
lying in a box. And afterwards I suggested to Fyodor Pavlovitch, as I was\
the only person he trusted, to hide the envelope with the notes in the\
corner behind the ikons, for no one would have guessed that place,\
especially if they came in a hurry. So that\'92s where the envelope lay, in\
the corner behind the ikons. It would have been absurd to keep it under\
the mattress; the box, anyway, could be locked. But all believe it was\
under the mattress. A stupid thing to believe. So if Dmitri Fyodorovitch\
had committed the murder, finding nothing, he would either have run away\
in a hurry, afraid of every sound, as always happens with murderers, or he\
would have been arrested. So I could always have clambered up to the ikons\
and have taken away the money next morning or even that night, and it\
would have all been put down to Dmitri Fyodorovitch. I could reckon upon\
that.\'94\
\
\'93But what if he did not kill him, but only knocked him down?\'94\
\
\'93If he did not kill him, of course, I would not have ventured to take the\
money, and nothing would have happened. But I calculated that he would\
beat him senseless, and I should have time to take it then, and then I\'92d\
make out to Fyodor Pavlovitch that it was no one but Dmitri Fyodorovitch\
who had taken the money after beating him.\'94\
\
\'93Stop ... I am getting mixed. Then it was Dmitri after all who killed him;\
you only took the money?\'94\
\
\'93No, he didn\'92t kill him. Well, I might as well have told you now that he\
was the murderer.... But I don\'92t want to lie to you now, because ...\
because if you really haven\'92t understood till now, as I see for myself,\
and are not pretending, so as to throw your guilt on me to my very face,\
you are still responsible for it all, since you knew of the murder and\
charged me to do it, and went away knowing all about it. And so I want to\
prove to your face this evening that you are the only real murderer in the\
whole affair, and I am not the real murderer, though I did kill him. You\
are the rightful murderer.\'94\
\
\'93Why, why, am I a murderer? Oh, God!\'94 Ivan cried, unable to restrain\
himself at last, and forgetting that he had put off discussing himself\
till the end of the conversation. \'93You still mean that Tchermashnya? Stay,\
tell me, why did you want my consent, if you really took Tchermashnya for\
consent? How will you explain that now?\'94\
\
\'93Assured of your consent, I should have known that you wouldn\'92t have made\
an outcry over those three thousand being lost, even if I\'92d been\
suspected, instead of Dmitri Fyodorovitch, or as his accomplice; on the\
contrary, you would have protected me from others.... And when you got\
your inheritance you would have rewarded me when you were able, all the\
rest of your life. For you\'92d have received your inheritance through me,\
seeing that if he had married Agrafena Alexandrovna, you wouldn\'92t have had\
a farthing.\'94\
\
\'93Ah! Then you intended to worry me all my life afterwards,\'94 snarled Ivan.\
\'93And what if I hadn\'92t gone away then, but had informed against you?\'94\
\
\'93What could you have informed? That I persuaded you to go to Tchermashnya?\
That\'92s all nonsense. Besides, after our conversation you would either have\
gone away or have stayed. If you had stayed, nothing would have happened.\
I should have known that you didn\'92t want it done, and should have\
attempted nothing. As you went away, it meant you assured me that you\
wouldn\'92t dare to inform against me at the trial, and that you\'92d overlook\
my having the three thousand. And, indeed, you couldn\'92t have prosecuted me\
afterwards, because then I should have told it all in the court; that is,\
not that I had stolen the money or killed him\'97I shouldn\'92t have said\
that\'97but that you\'92d put me up to the theft and the murder, though I didn\'92t\
consent to it. That\'92s why I needed your consent, so that you couldn\'92t have\
cornered me afterwards, for what proof could you have had? I could always\
have cornered you, revealing your eagerness for your father\'92s death, and I\
tell you the public would have believed it all, and you would have been\
ashamed for the rest of your life.\'94\
\
\'93Was I then so eager, was I?\'94 Ivan snarled again.\
\
\'93To be sure you were, and by your consent you silently sanctioned my doing\
it.\'94 Smerdyakov looked resolutely at Ivan. He was very weak and spoke\
slowly and wearily, but some hidden inner force urged him on. He evidently\
had some design. Ivan felt that.\
\
\'93Go on,\'94 he said. \'93Tell me what happened that night.\'94\
\
\'93What more is there to tell! I lay there and I thought I heard the master\
shout. And before that Grigory Vassilyevitch had suddenly got up and came\
out, and he suddenly gave a scream, and then all was silence and darkness.\
I lay there waiting, my heart beating; I couldn\'92t bear it. I got up at\
last, went out. I saw the window open on the left into the garden, and I\
stepped to the left to listen whether he was sitting there alive, and I\
heard the master moving about, sighing, so I knew he was alive. \'91Ech!\'92 I\
thought. I went to the window and shouted to the master, \'91It\'92s I.\'92 And he\
shouted to me, \'91He\'92s been, he\'92s been; he\'92s run away.\'92 He meant Dmitri\
Fyodorovitch had been. \'91He\'92s killed Grigory!\'92 \'91Where?\'92 I whispered.\
\'91There, in the corner,\'92 he pointed. He was whispering, too. \'91Wait a bit,\'92\
I said. I went to the corner of the garden to look, and there I came upon\
Grigory Vassilyevitch lying by the wall, covered with blood, senseless. So\
it\'92s true that Dmitri Fyodorovitch has been here, was the thought that\
came into my head, and I determined on the spot to make an end of it, as\
Grigory Vassilyevitch, even if he were alive, would see nothing of it, as\
he lay there senseless. The only risk was that Marfa Ignatyevna might wake\
up. I felt that at the moment, but the longing to get it done came over\
me, till I could scarcely breathe. I went back to the window to the master\
and said, \'91She\'92s here, she\'92s come; Agrafena Alexandrovna has come, wants\
to be let in.\'92 And he started like a baby. \'91Where is she?\'92 he fairly\
gasped, but couldn\'92t believe it. \'91She\'92s standing there,\'92 said I. \'91Open.\'92\
He looked out of the window at me, half believing and half distrustful,\
but afraid to open. \'91Why, he is afraid of me now,\'92 I thought. And it was\
funny. I bethought me to knock on the window\uc0\u8208 frame those taps we\'92d agreed\
upon as a signal that Grushenka had come, in his presence, before his\
eyes. He didn\'92t seem to believe my word, but as soon as he heard the taps,\
he ran at once to open the door. He opened it. I would have gone in, but\
he stood in the way to prevent me passing. \'91Where is she? Where is she?\'92\
He looked at me, all of a tremble. \'91Well,\'92 thought I, \'91if he\'92s so\
frightened of me as all that, it\'92s a bad look out!\'92 And my legs went weak\
with fright that he wouldn\'92t let me in or would call out, or Marfa\
Ignatyevna would run up, or something else might happen. I don\'92t remember\
now, but I must have stood pale, facing him. I whispered to him, \'91Why,\
she\'92s there, there, under the window; how is it you don\'92t see her?\'92 I\
said. \'91Bring her then, bring her.\'92 \'91She\'92s afraid,\'92 said I; \'91she was\
frightened at the noise, she\'92s hidden in the bushes; go and call to her\
yourself from the study.\'92 He ran to the window, put the candle in the\
window. \'91Grushenka,\'92 he cried, \'91Grushenka, are you here?\'92 Though he cried\
that, he didn\'92t want to lean out of the window, he didn\'92t want to move\
away from me, for he was panic\uc0\u8208 stricken; he was so frightened he didn\'92t\
dare to turn his back on me. \'91Why, here she is,\'92 said I. I went up to the\
window and leaned right out of it. \'91Here she is; she\'92s in the bush,\
laughing at you, don\'92t you see her?\'92 He suddenly believed it; he was all\
of a shake\'97he was awfully crazy about her\'97and he leaned right out of the\
window. I snatched up that iron paper\uc0\u8208 weight from his table; do you\
remember, weighing about three pounds? I swung it and hit him on the top\
of the skull with the corner of it. He didn\'92t even cry out. He only sank\
down suddenly, and I hit him again and a third time. And the third time I\
knew I\'92d broken his skull. He suddenly rolled on his back, face upwards,\
covered with blood. I looked round. There was no blood on me, not a spot.\
I wiped the paper\uc0\u8208 weight, put it back, went up to the ikons, took the\
money out of the envelope, and flung the envelope on the floor and the\
pink ribbon beside it. I went out into the garden all of a tremble,\
straight to the apple\uc0\u8208 tree with a hollow in it\'97you know that hollow. I\'92d\
marked it long before and put a rag and a piece of paper ready in it. I\
wrapped all the notes in the rag and stuffed it deep down in the hole. And\
there it stayed for over a fortnight. I took it out later, when I came out\
of the hospital. I went back to my bed, lay down and thought, \'91If Grigory\
Vassilyevitch has been killed outright it may be a bad job for me, but if\
he is not killed and recovers, it will be first\uc0\u8208 rate, for then he\'92ll bear\
witness that Dmitri Fyodorovitch has been here, and so he must have killed\
him and taken the money.\'92 Then I began groaning with suspense and\
impatience, so as to wake Marfa Ignatyevna as soon as possible. At last\
she got up and she rushed to me, but when she saw Grigory Vassilyevitch\
was not there, she ran out, and I heard her scream in the garden. And that\
set it all going and set my mind at rest.\'94\
\
He stopped. Ivan had listened all the time in dead silence without\
stirring or taking his eyes off him. As he told his story Smerdyakov\
glanced at him from time to time, but for the most part kept his eyes\
averted. When he had finished he was evidently agitated and was breathing\
hard. The perspiration stood out on his face. But it was impossible to\
tell whether it was remorse he was feeling, or what.\
\
\'93Stay,\'94 cried Ivan, pondering. \'93What about the door? If he only opened the\
door to you, how could Grigory have seen it open before? For Grigory saw\
it before you went.\'94\
\
It was remarkable that Ivan spoke quite amicably, in a different tone, not\
angry as before, so if any one had opened the door at that moment and\
peeped in at them, he would certainly have concluded that they were\
talking peaceably about some ordinary, though interesting, subject.\
\
\'93As for that door and Grigory Vassilyevitch\'92s having seen it open, that\'92s\
only his fancy,\'94 said Smerdyakov, with a wry smile. \'93He is not a man, I\
assure you, but an obstinate mule. He didn\'92t see it, but fancied he had\
seen it, and there\'92s no shaking him. It\'92s just our luck he took that\
notion into his head, for they can\'92t fail to convict Dmitri Fyodorovitch\
after that.\'94\
\
\'93Listen ...\'94 said Ivan, beginning to seem bewildered again and making an\
effort to grasp something. \'93Listen. There are a lot of questions I want to\
ask you, but I forget them ... I keep forgetting and getting mixed up.\
Yes. Tell me this at least, why did you open the envelope and leave it\
there on the floor? Why didn\'92t you simply carry off the envelope?... When\
you were telling me, I thought you spoke about it as though it were the\
right thing to do ... but why, I can\'92t understand....\'94\
\
\'93I did that for a good reason. For if a man had known all about it, as I\
did for instance, if he\'92d seen those notes before, and perhaps had put\
them in that envelope himself, and had seen the envelope sealed up and\
addressed, with his own eyes, if such a man had done the murder, what\
should have made him tear open the envelope afterwards, especially in such\
desperate haste, since he\'92d know for certain the notes must be in the\
envelope? No, if the robber had been some one like me, he\'92d simply have\
put the envelope straight in his pocket and got away with it as fast as he\
could. But it\'92d be quite different with Dmitri Fyodorovitch. He only knew\
about the envelope by hearsay; he had never seen it, and if he\'92d found it,\
for instance, under the mattress, he\'92d have torn it open as quickly as\
possible to make sure the notes were in it. And he\'92d have thrown the\
envelope down, without having time to think that it would be evidence\
against him. Because he was not an habitual thief and had never directly\
stolen anything before, for he is a gentleman born, and if he did bring\
himself to steal, it would not be regular stealing, but simply taking what\
was his own, for he\'92d told the whole town he meant to before, and had even\
bragged aloud before every one that he\'92d go and take his property from\
Fyodor Pavlovitch. I didn\'92t say that openly to the prosecutor when I was\
being examined, but quite the contrary, I brought him to it by a hint, as\
though I didn\'92t see it myself, and as though he\'92d thought of it himself\
and I hadn\'92t prompted him; so that Mr. Prosecutor\'92s mouth positively\
watered at my suggestion.\'94\
\
\'93But can you possibly have thought of all that on the spot?\'94 cried Ivan,\
overcome with astonishment. He looked at Smerdyakov again with alarm.\
\
\'93Mercy on us! Could any one think of it all in such a desperate hurry? It\
was all thought out beforehand.\'94\
\
\'93Well ... well, it was the devil helped you!\'94 Ivan cried again. \'93No, you\
are not a fool, you are far cleverer than I thought....\'94\
\
He got up, obviously intending to walk across the room. He was in terrible\
distress. But as the table blocked his way, and there was hardly room to\
pass between the table and the wall, he only turned round where he stood\
and sat down again. Perhaps the impossibility of moving irritated him, as\
he suddenly cried out almost as furiously as before.\
\
\'93Listen, you miserable, contemptible creature! Don\'92t you understand that\
if I haven\'92t killed you, it\'92s simply because I am keeping you to answer\
to\uc0\u8208 morrow at the trial. God sees,\'94 Ivan raised his hand, \'93perhaps I, too,\
was guilty; perhaps I really had a secret desire for my father\'92s ...\
death, but I swear I was not as guilty as you think, and perhaps I didn\'92t\
urge you on at all. No, no, I didn\'92t urge you on! But no matter, I will\
give evidence against myself to\uc0\u8208 morrow at the trial. I\'92m determined to! I\
shall tell everything, everything. But we\'92ll make our appearance together.\
And whatever you may say against me at the trial, whatever evidence you\
give, I\'92ll face it; I am not afraid of you. I\'92ll confirm it all myself!\
But you must confess, too! You must, you must; we\'92ll go together. That\'92s\
how it shall be!\'94\
\
Ivan said this solemnly and resolutely and from his flashing eyes alone it\
could be seen that it would be so.\
\
\'93You are ill, I see; you are quite ill. Your eyes are yellow,\'94 Smerdyakov\
commented, without the least irony, with apparent sympathy in fact.\
\
\'93We\'92ll go together,\'94 Ivan repeated. \'93And if you won\'92t go, no matter, I\'92ll\
go alone.\'94\
\
Smerdyakov paused as though pondering.\
\
\'93There\'92ll be nothing of the sort, and you won\'92t go,\'94 he concluded at last\
positively.\
\
\'93You don\'92t understand me,\'94 Ivan exclaimed reproachfully.\
\
\'93You\'92ll be too much ashamed, if you confess it all. And, what\'92s more, it\
will be no use at all, for I shall say straight out that I never said\
anything of the sort to you, and that you are either ill (and it looks\
like it, too), or that you\'92re so sorry for your brother that you are\
sacrificing yourself to save him and have invented it all against me, for\
you\'92ve always thought no more of me than if I\'92d been a fly. And who will\
believe you, and what single proof have you got?\'94\
\
\'93Listen, you showed me those notes just now to convince me.\'94\
\
Smerdyakov lifted the book off the notes and laid it on one side.\
\
\'93Take that money away with you,\'94 Smerdyakov sighed.\
\
\'93Of course, I shall take it. But why do you give it to me, if you\
committed the murder for the sake of it?\'94 Ivan looked at him with great\
surprise.\
\
\'93I don\'92t want it,\'94 Smerdyakov articulated in a shaking voice, with a\
gesture of refusal. \'93I did have an idea of beginning a new life with that\
money in Moscow or, better still, abroad. I did dream of it, chiefly\
because \'91all things are lawful.\'92 That was quite right what you taught me,\
for you talked a lot to me about that. For if there\'92s no everlasting God,\
there\'92s no such thing as virtue, and there\'92s no need of it. You were right\
there. So that\'92s how I looked at it.\'94\
\
\'93Did you come to that of yourself?\'94 asked Ivan, with a wry smile.\
\
\'93With your guidance.\'94\
\
\'93And now, I suppose, you believe in God, since you are giving back the\
money?\'94\
\
\'93No, I don\'92t believe,\'94 whispered Smerdyakov.\
\
\'93Then why are you giving it back?\'94\
\
\'93Leave off ... that\'92s enough!\'94 Smerdyakov waved his hand again. \'93You used\
to say yourself that everything was lawful, so now why are you so upset,\
too? You even want to go and give evidence against yourself.... Only\
there\'92ll be nothing of the sort! You won\'92t go to give evidence,\'94\
Smerdyakov decided with conviction.\
\
\'93You\'92ll see,\'94 said Ivan.\
\
\'93It isn\'92t possible. You are very clever. You are fond of money, I know\
that. You like to be respected, too, for you\'92re very proud; you are far\
too fond of female charms, too, and you mind most of all about living in\
undisturbed comfort, without having to depend on any one\'97that\'92s what you\
care most about. You won\'92t want to spoil your life for ever by taking such\
a disgrace on yourself. You are like Fyodor Pavlovitch, you are more like\
him than any of his children; you\'92ve the same soul as he had.\'94\
\
\'93You are not a fool,\'94 said Ivan, seeming struck. The blood rushed to his\
face. \'93You are serious now!\'94 he observed, looking suddenly at Smerdyakov\
with a different expression.\
\
\'93It was your pride made you think I was a fool. Take the money.\'94\
\
Ivan took the three rolls of notes and put them in his pocket without\
wrapping them in anything.\
\
\'93I shall show them at the court to\uc0\u8208 morrow,\'94 he said.\
\
\'93Nobody will believe you, as you\'92ve plenty of money of your own; you may\
simply have taken it out of your cash\uc0\u8208 box and brought it to the court.\'94\
\
Ivan rose from his seat.\
\
\'93I repeat,\'94 he said, \'93the only reason I haven\'92t killed you is that I need\
you for to\uc0\u8208 morrow, remember that, don\'92t forget it!\'94\
\
\'93Well, kill me. Kill me now,\'94 Smerdyakov said, all at once looking\
strangely at Ivan. \'93You won\'92t dare do that even!\'94 he added, with a bitter\
smile. \'93You won\'92t dare to do anything, you, who used to be so bold!\'94\
\
\'93Till to\uc0\u8208 morrow,\'94 cried Ivan, and moved to go out.\
\
\'93Stay a moment.... Show me those notes again.\'94\
\
Ivan took out the notes and showed them to him. Smerdyakov looked at them\
for ten seconds.\
\
\'93Well, you can go,\'94 he said, with a wave of his hand. \'93Ivan Fyodorovitch!\'94\
he called after him again.\
\
\'93What do you want?\'94 Ivan turned without stopping.\
\
\'93Good\uc0\u8208 by!\'94\
\
\'93Till to\uc0\u8208 morrow!\'94 Ivan cried again, and he walked out of the cottage.\
\
The snowstorm was still raging. He walked the first few steps boldly, but\
suddenly began staggering. \'93It\'92s something physical,\'94 he thought with a\
grin. Something like joy was springing up in his heart. He was conscious\
of unbounded resolution; he would make an end of the wavering that had so\
tortured him of late. His determination was taken, \'93and now it will not be\
changed,\'94 he thought with relief. At that moment he stumbled against\
something and almost fell down. Stopping short, he made out at his feet\
the peasant he had knocked down, still lying senseless and motionless. The\
snow had almost covered his face. Ivan seized him and lifted him in his\
arms. Seeing a light in the little house to the right he went up, knocked\
at the shutters, and asked the man to whom the house belonged to help him\
carry the peasant to the police\uc0\u8208 station, promising him three roubles. The\
man got ready and came out. I won\'92t describe in detail how Ivan succeeded\
in his object, bringing the peasant to the police\uc0\u8208 station and arranging\
for a doctor to see him at once, providing with a liberal hand for the\
expenses. I will only say that this business took a whole hour, but Ivan\
was well content with it. His mind wandered and worked incessantly.\
\
\'93If I had not taken my decision so firmly for to\uc0\u8208 morrow,\'94 he reflected\
with satisfaction, \'93I should not have stayed a whole hour to look after\
the peasant, but should have passed by, without caring about his being\
frozen. I am quite capable of watching myself, by the way,\'94 he thought at\
the same instant, with still greater satisfaction, \'93although they have\
decided that I am going out of my mind!\'94\
\
Just as he reached his own house he stopped short, asking himself suddenly\
hadn\'92t he better go at once to the prosecutor and tell him everything. He\
decided the question by turning back to the house. \'93Everything together\
to\uc0\u8208 morrow!\'94 he whispered to himself, and, strange to say, almost all his\
gladness and self\uc0\u8208 satisfaction passed in one instant.\
\
As he entered his own room he felt something like a touch of ice on his\
heart, like a recollection or, more exactly, a reminder, of something\
agonizing and revolting that was in that room now, at that moment, and had\
been there before. He sank wearily on his sofa. The old woman brought him\
a samovar; he made tea, but did not touch it. He sat on the sofa and felt\
giddy. He felt that he was ill and helpless. He was beginning to drop\
asleep, but got up uneasily and walked across the room to shake off his\
drowsiness. At moments he fancied he was delirious, but it was not illness\
that he thought of most. Sitting down again, he began looking round, as\
though searching for something. This happened several times. At last his\
eyes were fastened intently on one point. Ivan smiled, but an angry flush\
suffused his face. He sat a long time in his place, his head propped on\
both arms, though he looked sideways at the same point, at the sofa that\
stood against the opposite wall. There was evidently something, some\
object, that irritated him there, worried him and tormented him.\
\
\
\
Chapter IX. The Devil. Ivan\'92s Nightmare\
\
\
I am not a doctor, but yet I feel that the moment has come when I must\
inevitably give the reader some account of the nature of Ivan\'92s illness.\
Anticipating events I can say at least one thing: he was at that moment on\
the very eve of an attack of brain fever. Though his health had long been\
affected, it had offered a stubborn resistance to the fever which in the\
end gained complete mastery over it. Though I know nothing of medicine, I\
venture to hazard the suggestion that he really had perhaps, by a terrible\
effort of will, succeeded in delaying the attack for a time, hoping, of\
course, to check it completely. He knew that he was unwell, but he loathed\
the thought of being ill at that fatal time, at the approaching crisis in\
his life, when he needed to have all his wits about him, to say what he\
had to say boldly and resolutely and \'93to justify himself to himself.\'94\
\
He had, however, consulted the new doctor, who had been brought from\
Moscow by a fantastic notion of Katerina Ivanovna\'92s to which I have\
referred already. After listening to him and examining him the doctor came\
to the conclusion that he was actually suffering from some disorder of the\
brain, and was not at all surprised by an admission which Ivan had\
reluctantly made him. \'93Hallucinations are quite likely in your condition,\'94\
the doctor opined, \'93though it would be better to verify them ... you must\
take steps at once, without a moment\'92s delay, or things will go badly with\
you.\'94 But Ivan did not follow this judicious advice and did not take to\
his bed to be nursed. \'93I am walking about, so I am strong enough, if I\
drop, it\'92ll be different then, any one may nurse me who likes,\'94 he\
decided, dismissing the subject.\
\
And so he was sitting almost conscious himself of his delirium and, as I\
have said already, looking persistently at some object on the sofa against\
the opposite wall. Some one appeared to be sitting there, though goodness\
knows how he had come in, for he had not been in the room when Ivan came\
into it, on his return from Smerdyakov. This was a person or, more\
accurately speaking, a Russian gentleman of a particular kind, no longer\
young, _qui faisait la cinquantaine_, as the French say, with rather long,\
still thick, dark hair, slightly streaked with gray and a small pointed\
beard. He was wearing a brownish reefer jacket, rather shabby, evidently\
made by a good tailor though, and of a fashion at least three years old,\
that had been discarded by smart and well\uc0\u8208 to\u8208 do people for the last two\
years. His linen and his long scarf\uc0\u8208 like neck\u8208 tie were all such as are\
worn by people who aim at being stylish, but on closer inspection his\
linen was not over\uc0\u8208 clean and his wide scarf was very threadbare. The\
visitor\'92s check trousers were of excellent cut, but were too light in\
color and too tight for the present fashion. His soft fluffy white hat was\
out of keeping with the season.\
\
In brief there was every appearance of gentility on straitened means. It\
looked as though the gentleman belonged to that class of idle landowners\
who used to flourish in the times of serfdom. He had unmistakably been, at\
some time, in good and fashionable society, had once had good connections,\
had possibly preserved them indeed, but, after a gay youth, becoming\
gradually impoverished on the abolition of serfdom, he had sunk into the\
position of a poor relation of the best class, wandering from one good old\
friend to another and received by them for his companionable and\
accommodating disposition and as being, after all, a gentleman who could\
be asked to sit down with any one, though, of course, not in a place of\
honor. Such gentlemen of accommodating temper and dependent position, who\
can tell a story, take a hand at cards, and who have a distinct aversion\
for any duties that may be forced upon them, are usually solitary\
creatures, either bachelors or widowers. Sometimes they have children, but\
if so, the children are always being brought up at a distance, at some\
aunt\'92s, to whom these gentlemen never allude in good society, seeming\
ashamed of the relationship. They gradually lose sight of their children\
altogether, though at intervals they receive a birthday or Christmas\
letter from them and sometimes even answer it.\
\
The countenance of the unexpected visitor was not so much good\uc0\u8208 natured, as\
accommodating and ready to assume any amiable expression as occasion might\
arise. He had no watch, but he had a tortoise\uc0\u8208 shell lorgnette on a black\
ribbon. On the middle finger of his right hand was a massive gold ring\
with a cheap opal stone in it.\
\
Ivan was angrily silent and would not begin the conversation. The visitor\
waited and sat exactly like a poor relation who had come down from his\
room to keep his host company at tea, and was discreetly silent, seeing\
that his host was frowning and preoccupied. But he was ready for any\
affable conversation as soon as his host should begin it. All at once his\
face expressed a sudden solicitude.\
\
\'93I say,\'94 he began to Ivan, \'93excuse me, I only mention it to remind you.\
You went to Smerdyakov\'92s to find out about Katerina Ivanovna, but you came\
away without finding out anything about her, you probably forgot\'97\'94\
\
\'93Ah, yes,\'94 broke from Ivan and his face grew gloomy with uneasiness. \'93Yes,\
I\'92d forgotten ... but it doesn\'92t matter now, never mind, till to\uc0\u8208 morrow,\'94\
he muttered to himself, \'93and you,\'94 he added, addressing his visitor, \'93I\
should have remembered that myself in a minute, for that was just what was\
tormenting me! Why do you interfere, as if I should believe that you\
prompted me, and that I didn\'92t remember it of myself?\'94\
\
\'93Don\'92t believe it then,\'94 said the gentleman, smiling amicably, \'93what\'92s the\
good of believing against your will? Besides, proofs are no help to\
believing, especially material proofs. Thomas believed, not because he saw\
Christ risen, but because he wanted to believe, before he saw. Look at the\
spiritualists, for instance.... I am very fond of them ... only fancy,\
they imagine that they are serving the cause of religion, because the\
devils show them their horns from the other world. That, they say, is a\
material proof, so to speak, of the existence of another world. The other\
world and material proofs, what next! And if you come to that, does\
proving there\'92s a devil prove that there\'92s a God? I want to join an\
idealist society, I\'92ll lead the opposition in it, I\'92ll say I am a realist,\
but not a materialist, he he!\'94\
\
\'93Listen,\'94 Ivan suddenly got up from the table. \'93I seem to be delirious....\
I am delirious, in fact, talk any nonsense you like, I don\'92t care! You\
won\'92t drive me to fury, as you did last time. But I feel somehow\
ashamed.... I want to walk about the room.... I sometimes don\'92t see you\
and don\'92t even hear your voice as I did last time, but I always guess what\
you are prating, for it\'92s I, _I myself speaking, not you_. Only I don\'92t\
know whether I was dreaming last time or whether I really saw you. I\'92ll\
wet a towel and put it on my head and perhaps you\'92ll vanish into air.\'94\
\
Ivan went into the corner, took a towel, and did as he said, and with a\
wet towel on his head began walking up and down the room.\
\
\'93I am so glad you treat me so familiarly,\'94 the visitor began.\
\
\'93Fool,\'94 laughed Ivan, \'93do you suppose I should stand on ceremony with you?\
I am in good spirits now, though I\'92ve a pain in my forehead ... and in the\
top of my head ... only please don\'92t talk philosophy, as you did last\
time. If you can\'92t take yourself off, talk of something amusing. Talk\
gossip, you are a poor relation, you ought to talk gossip. What a\
nightmare to have! But I am not afraid of you. I\'92ll get the better of you.\
I won\'92t be taken to a mad\uc0\u8208 house!\'94\
\
\'93_C\'92est charmant_, poor relation. Yes, I am in my natural shape. For what\
am I on earth but a poor relation? By the way, I am listening to you and\
am rather surprised to find you are actually beginning to take me for\
something real, not simply your fancy, as you persisted in declaring last\
time\'97\'94\
\
\'93Never for one minute have I taken you for reality,\'94 Ivan cried with a\
sort of fury. \'93You are a lie, you are my illness, you are a phantom. It\'92s\
only that I don\'92t know how to destroy you and I see I must suffer for a\
time. You are my hallucination. You are the incarnation of myself, but\
only of one side of me ... of my thoughts and feelings, but only the\
nastiest and stupidest of them. From that point of view you might be of\
interest to me, if only I had time to waste on you\'97\'94\
\
\'93Excuse me, excuse me, I\'92ll catch you. When you flew out at Alyosha under\
the lamp\uc0\u8208 post this evening and shouted to him, \'91You learnt it from _him_!\
How do you know that _he_ visits me?\'92 you were thinking of me then. So for\
one brief moment you did believe that I really exist,\'94 the gentleman\
laughed blandly.\
\
\'93Yes, that was a moment of weakness ... but I couldn\'92t believe in you. I\
don\'92t know whether I was asleep or awake last time. Perhaps I was only\
dreaming then and didn\'92t see you really at all\'97\'94\
\
\'93And why were you so surly with Alyosha just now? He is a dear; I\'92ve\
treated him badly over Father Zossima.\'94\
\
\'93Don\'92t talk of Alyosha! How dare you, you flunkey!\'94 Ivan laughed again.\
\
\'93You scold me, but you laugh\'97that\'92s a good sign. But you are ever so much\
more polite than you were last time and I know why: that great resolution\
of yours\'97\'94\
\
\'93Don\'92t speak of my resolution,\'94 cried Ivan, savagely.\
\
\'93I understand, I understand, _c\'92est noble, c\'92est charmant_, you are going\
to defend your brother and to sacrifice yourself ... _C\'92est\
chevaleresque_.\'94\
\
\'93Hold your tongue, I\'92ll kick you!\'94\
\
\'93I shan\'92t be altogether sorry, for then my object will be attained. If you\
kick me, you must believe in my reality, for people don\'92t kick ghosts.\
Joking apart, it doesn\'92t matter to me, scold if you like, though it\'92s\
better to be a trifle more polite even to me. \'91Fool, flunkey!\'92 what\
words!\'94\
\
\'93Scolding you, I scold myself,\'94 Ivan laughed again, \'93you are myself,\
myself, only with a different face. You just say what I am thinking ...\
and are incapable of saying anything new!\'94\
\
\'93If I am like you in my way of thinking, it\'92s all to my credit,\'94 the\
gentleman declared, with delicacy and dignity.\
\
\'93You choose out only my worst thoughts, and what\'92s more, the stupid ones.\
You are stupid and vulgar. You are awfully stupid. No, I can\'92t put up with\
you! What am I to do, what am I to do?\'94 Ivan said through his clenched\
teeth.\
\
\'93My dear friend, above all things I want to behave like a gentleman and to\
be recognized as such,\'94 the visitor began in an excess of deprecating and\
simple\uc0\u8208 hearted pride, typical of a poor relation. \'93I am poor, but ... I\
won\'92t say very honest, but ... it\'92s an axiom generally accepted in society\
that I am a fallen angel. I certainly can\'92t conceive how I can ever have\
been an angel. If I ever was, it must have been so long ago that there\'92s\
no harm in forgetting it. Now I only prize the reputation of being a\
gentlemanly person and live as I can, trying to make myself agreeable. I\
love men genuinely, I\'92ve been greatly calumniated! Here when I stay with\
you from time to time, my life gains a kind of reality and that\'92s what I\
like most of all. You see, like you, I suffer from the fantastic and so I\
love the realism of earth. Here, with you, everything is circumscribed,\
here all is formulated and geometrical, while we have nothing but\
indeterminate equations! I wander about here dreaming. I like dreaming.\
Besides, on earth I become superstitious. Please don\'92t laugh, that\'92s just\
what I like, to become superstitious. I adopt all your habits here: I\'92ve\
grown fond of going to the public baths, would you believe it? and I go\
and steam myself with merchants and priests. What I dream of is becoming\
incarnate once for all and irrevocably in the form of some merchant\'92s wife\
weighing eighteen stone, and of believing all she believes. My ideal is to\
go to church and offer a candle in simple\uc0\u8208 hearted faith, upon my word it\
is. Then there would be an end to my sufferings. I like being doctored\
too; in the spring there was an outbreak of smallpox and I went and was\
vaccinated in a foundling hospital\'97if only you knew how I enjoyed myself\
that day. I subscribed ten roubles in the cause of the Slavs!... But you\
are not listening. Do you know, you are not at all well this evening? I\
know you went yesterday to that doctor ... well, what about your health?\
What did the doctor say?\'94\
\
\'93Fool!\'94 Ivan snapped out.\
\
\'93But you are clever, anyway. You are scolding again? I didn\'92t ask out of\
sympathy. You needn\'92t answer. Now rheumatism has come in again\'97\'94\
\
\'93Fool!\'94 repeated Ivan.\
\
\'93You keep saying the same thing; but I had such an attack of rheumatism\
last year that I remember it to this day.\'94\
\
\'93The devil have rheumatism!\'94\
\
\'93Why not, if I sometimes put on fleshly form? I put on fleshly form and I\
take the consequences. Satan _sum et nihil humanum a me alienum puto_.\'94\
\
\'93What, what, Satan _sum et nihil humanum_ ... that\'92s not bad for the\
devil!\'94\
\
\'93I am glad I\'92ve pleased you at last.\'94\
\
\'93But you didn\'92t get that from me.\'94 Ivan stopped suddenly, seeming struck.\
\'93That never entered my head, that\'92s strange.\'94\
\
\'93_C\'92est du nouveau, n\'92est\uc0\u8208 ce pas?_ This time I\'92ll act honestly and explain\
to you. Listen, in dreams and especially in nightmares, from indigestion\
or anything, a man sees sometimes such artistic visions, such complex and\
real actuality, such events, even a whole world of events, woven into such\
a plot, with such unexpected details from the most exalted matters to the\
last button on a cuff, as I swear Leo Tolstoy has never invented. Yet such\
dreams are sometimes seen not by writers, but by the most ordinary people,\
officials, journalists, priests.... The subject is a complete enigma. A\
statesman confessed to me, indeed, that all his best ideas came to him\
when he was asleep. Well, that\'92s how it is now, though I am your\
hallucination, yet just as in a nightmare, I say original things which had\
not entered your head before. So I don\'92t repeat your ideas, yet I am only\
your nightmare, nothing more.\'94\
\
\'93You are lying, your aim is to convince me you exist apart and are not my\
nightmare, and now you are asserting you are a dream.\'94\
\
\'93My dear fellow, I\'92ve adopted a special method to\uc0\u8208 day, I\'92ll explain it to\
you afterwards. Stay, where did I break off? Oh, yes! I caught cold then,\
only not here but yonder.\'94\
\
\'93Where is yonder? Tell me, will you be here long? Can\'92t you go away?\'94 Ivan\
exclaimed almost in despair. He ceased walking to and fro, sat down on the\
sofa, leaned his elbows on the table again and held his head tight in both\
hands. He pulled the wet towel off and flung it away in vexation. It was\
evidently of no use.\
\
\'93Your nerves are out of order,\'94 observed the gentleman, with a carelessly\
easy, though perfectly polite, air. \'93You are angry with me even for being\
able to catch cold, though it happened in a most natural way. I was\
hurrying then to a diplomatic _soir\'e9e_ at the house of a lady of high rank\
in Petersburg, who was aiming at influence in the Ministry. Well, an\
evening suit, white tie, gloves, though I was God knows where and had to\
fly through space to reach your earth.... Of course, it took only an\
instant, but you know a ray of light from the sun takes full eight\
minutes, and fancy in an evening suit and open waistcoat. Spirits don\'92t\
freeze, but when one\'92s in fleshly form, well ... in brief, I didn\'92t think,\
and set off, and you know in those ethereal spaces, in the water that is\
above the firmament, there\'92s such a frost ... at least one can\'92t call it\
frost, you can fancy, 150 degrees below zero! You know the game the\
village girls play\'97they invite the unwary to lick an ax in thirty degrees\
of frost, the tongue instantly freezes to it and the dupe tears the skin\
off, so it bleeds. But that\'92s only in 30 degrees, in 150 degrees I imagine\
it would be enough to put your finger on the ax and it would be the end of\
it ... if only there could be an ax there.\'94\
\
\'93And can there be an ax there?\'94 Ivan interrupted, carelessly and\
disdainfully. He was exerting himself to the utmost not to believe in the\
delusion and not to sink into complete insanity.\
\
\'93An ax?\'94 the guest interrupted in surprise.\
\
\'93Yes, what would become of an ax there?\'94 Ivan cried suddenly, with a sort\
of savage and insistent obstinacy.\
\
\'93What would become of an ax in space? _Quelle id\'e9e!_ If it were to fall to\
any distance, it would begin, I think, flying round the earth without\
knowing why, like a satellite. The astronomers would calculate the rising\
and the setting of the ax, _Gatzuk_ would put it in his calendar, that\'92s\
all.\'94\
\
\'93You are stupid, awfully stupid,\'94 said Ivan peevishly. \'93Fib more cleverly\
or I won\'92t listen. You want to get the better of me by realism, to\
convince me that you exist, but I don\'92t want to believe you exist! I won\'92t\
believe it!\'94\
\
\'93But I am not fibbing, it\'92s all the truth; the truth is unhappily hardly\
ever amusing. I see you persist in expecting something big of me, and\
perhaps something fine. That\'92s a great pity, for I only give what I can\'97\'94\
\
\'93Don\'92t talk philosophy, you ass!\'94\
\
\'93Philosophy, indeed, when all my right side is numb and I am moaning and\
groaning. I\'92ve tried all the medical faculty: they can diagnose\
beautifully, they have the whole of your disease at their finger\uc0\u8208 tips, but\
they\'92ve no idea how to cure you. There was an enthusiastic little student\
here, \'91You may die,\'92 said he, \'91but you\'92ll know perfectly what disease you\
are dying of!\'92 And then what a way they have sending people to\
specialists! \'91We only diagnose,\'92 they say, \'91but go to such\uc0\u8208 and\u8208 such a\
specialist, he\'92ll cure you.\'92 The old doctor who used to cure all sorts of\
disease has completely disappeared, I assure you, now there are only\
specialists and they all advertise in the newspapers. If anything is wrong\
with your nose, they send you to Paris: there, they say, is a European\
specialist who cures noses. If you go to Paris, he\'92ll look at your nose; I\
can only cure your right nostril, he\'92ll tell you, for I don\'92t cure the\
left nostril, that\'92s not my speciality, but go to Vienna, there there\'92s a\
specialist who will cure your left nostril. What are you to do? I fell\
back on popular remedies, a German doctor advised me to rub myself with\
honey and salt in the bath\uc0\u8208 house. Solely to get an extra bath I went,\
