to Count Mattei in Milan. He sent me a book and some drops, bless him,\
and, only fancy, Hoff\'92s malt extract cured me! I bought it by accident,\
drank a bottle and a half of it, and I was ready to dance, it took it away\
completely. I made up my mind to write to the papers to thank him, I was\
prompted by a feeling of gratitude, and only fancy, it led to no end of a\
bother: not a single paper would take my letter. \'91It would be very\
reactionary,\'92 they said, \'91no one will believe it. _Le diable n\'92existe\
point._ You\'92d better remain anonymous,\'92 they advised me. What use is a\
letter of thanks if it\'92s anonymous? I laughed with the men at the\
newspaper office; \'91It\'92s reactionary to believe in God in our days,\'92 I\
said, \'91but I am the devil, so I may be believed in.\'92 \'91We quite understand\
that,\'92 they said. \'91Who doesn\'92t believe in the devil? Yet it won\'92t do, it\
might injure our reputation. As a joke, if you like.\'92 But I thought as a\
joke it wouldn\'92t be very witty. So it wasn\'92t printed. And do you know, I\
have felt sore about it to this day. My best feelings, gratitude, for\
instance, are literally denied me simply from my social position.\'94\
\
\'93Philosophical reflections again?\'94 Ivan snarled malignantly.\
\
\'93God preserve me from it, but one can\'92t help complaining sometimes. I am a\
slandered man. You upbraid me every moment with being stupid. One can see\
you are young. My dear fellow, intelligence isn\'92t the only thing! I have\
naturally a kind and merry heart. \'91I also write vaudevilles of all sorts.\'92\
You seem to take me for Hlestakov grown old, but my fate is a far more\
serious one. Before time was, by some decree which I could never make out,\
I was pre\uc0\u8208 destined \'91to deny\'92 and yet I am genuinely good\u8208 hearted and not\
at all inclined to negation. \'91No, you must go and deny, without denial\
there\'92s no criticism and what would a journal be without a column of\
criticism?\'92 Without criticism it would be nothing but one \'91hosannah.\'92 But\
nothing but hosannah is not enough for life, the hosannah must be tried in\
the crucible of doubt and so on, in the same style. But I don\'92t meddle in\
that, I didn\'92t create it, I am not answerable for it. Well, they\'92ve chosen\
their scapegoat, they\'92ve made me write the column of criticism and so life\
was made possible. We understand that comedy; I, for instance, simply ask\
for annihilation. No, live, I am told, for there\'92d be nothing without you.\
If everything in the universe were sensible, nothing would happen. There\
would be no events without you, and there must be events. So against the\
grain I serve to produce events and do what\'92s irrational because I am\
commanded to. For all their indisputable intelligence, men take this farce\
as something serious, and that is their tragedy. They suffer, of course\
... but then they live, they live a real life, not a fantastic one, for\
suffering is life. Without suffering what would be the pleasure of it? It\
would be transformed into an endless church service; it would be holy, but\
tedious. But what about me? I suffer, but still, I don\'92t live. I am x in\
an indeterminate equation. I am a sort of phantom in life who has lost all\
beginning and end, and who has even forgotten his own name. You are\
laughing\'97 no, you are not laughing, you are angry again. You are for ever\
angry, all you care about is intelligence, but I repeat again that I would\
give away all this super\uc0\u8208 stellar life, all the ranks and honors, simply to\
be transformed into the soul of a merchant\'92s wife weighing eighteen stone\
and set candles at God\'92s shrine.\'94\
\
\'93Then even you don\'92t believe in God?\'94 said Ivan, with a smile of hatred.\
\
\'93What can I say?\'97that is, if you are in earnest\'97\'94\
\
\'93Is there a God or not?\'94 Ivan cried with the same savage intensity.\
\
\'93Ah, then you are in earnest! My dear fellow, upon my word I don\'92t know.\
There! I\'92ve said it now!\'94\
\
\'93You don\'92t know, but you see God? No, you are not some one apart, you are\
myself, you are I and nothing more! You are rubbish, you are my fancy!\'94\
\
\'93Well, if you like, I have the same philosophy as you, that would be true.\
_Je pense, donc je suis_, I know that for a fact; all the rest, all these\
worlds, God and even Satan\'97all that is not proved, to my mind. Does all\
that exist of itself, or is it only an emanation of myself, a logical\
development of my ego which alone has existed for ever: but I make haste\
to stop, for I believe you will be jumping up to beat me directly.\'94\
\
\'93You\'92d better tell me some anecdote!\'94 said Ivan miserably.\
\
\'93There is an anecdote precisely on our subject, or rather a legend, not an\
anecdote. You reproach me with unbelief, you see, you say, yet you don\'92t\
believe. But, my dear fellow, I am not the only one like that. We are all\
in a muddle over there now and all through your science. Once there used\
to be atoms, five senses, four elements, and then everything hung together\
somehow. There were atoms in the ancient world even, but since we\'92ve\
learned that you\'92ve discovered the chemical molecule and protoplasm and\
the devil knows what, we had to lower our crest. There\'92s a regular muddle,\
and, above all, superstition, scandal; there\'92s as much scandal among us as\
among you, you know; a little more in fact, and spying, indeed, for we\
have our secret police department where private information is received.\
Well, this wild legend belongs to our middle ages\'97not yours, but ours\'97and\
no one believes it even among us, except the old ladies of eighteen stone,\
not your old ladies I mean, but ours. We\'92ve everything you have, I am\
revealing one of our secrets out of friendship for you; though it\'92s\
forbidden. This legend is about Paradise. There was, they say, here on\
earth a thinker and philosopher. He rejected everything, \'91laws,\
conscience, faith,\'92 and, above all, the future life. He died; he expected\
to go straight to darkness and death and he found a future life before\
