ruin thousands for the sake of saving one. How many souls have had to be\
ruined and how many honorable reputations destroyed for the sake of that\
one righteous man, Job, over whom they made such a fool of me in old days!\
Yes, till the secret is revealed, there are two sorts of truths for\
me\'97one, their truth, yonder, which I know nothing about so far, and the\
other my own. And there\'92s no knowing which will turn out the better....\
Are you asleep?\'94\
\
\'93I might well be,\'94 Ivan groaned angrily. \'93All my stupid ideas\'97outgrown,\
thrashed out long ago, and flung aside like a dead carcass\'97you present to\
me as something new!\'94\
\
\'93There\'92s no pleasing you! And I thought I should fascinate you by my\
literary style. That hosannah in the skies really wasn\'92t bad, was it? And\
then that ironical tone _\'e0 la_ Heine, eh?\'94\
\
\'93No, I was never such a flunkey! How then could my soul beget a flunkey\
like you?\'94\
\
\'93My dear fellow, I know a most charming and attractive young Russian\
gentleman, a young thinker and a great lover of literature and art, the\
author of a promising poem entitled _The Grand Inquisitor_. I was only\
thinking of him!\'94\
\
\'93I forbid you to speak of _The Grand Inquisitor_,\'94 cried Ivan, crimson\
with shame.\
\
\'93And the _Geological Cataclysm_. Do you remember? That was a poem, now!\'94\
\
\'93Hold your tongue, or I\'92ll kill you!\'94\
\
\'93You\'92ll kill me? No, excuse me, I will speak. I came to treat myself to\
that pleasure. Oh, I love the dreams of my ardent young friends, quivering\
with eagerness for life! \'91There are new men,\'92 you decided last spring,\
when you were meaning to come here, \'91they propose to destroy everything\
and begin with cannibalism. Stupid fellows! they didn\'92t ask my advice! I\
maintain that nothing need be destroyed, that we only need to destroy the\
idea of God in man, that\'92s how we have to set to work. It\'92s that, that we\
must begin with. Oh, blind race of men who have no understanding! As soon\
as men have all of them denied God\'97and I believe that period, analogous\
with geological periods, will come to pass\'97the old conception of the\
universe will fall of itself without cannibalism, and, what\'92s more, the\
old morality, and everything will begin anew. Men will unite to take from\
