\
\'93Brother,\'94 he cried suddenly, \'93you must be terribly ill. You look and\
don\'92t seem to understand what I tell you.\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s a good thing you came,\'94 said Ivan, as though brooding, and not\
hearing Alyosha\'92s exclamation. \'93I knew he had hanged himself.\'94\
\
\'93From whom?\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t know. But I knew. Did I know? Yes, he told me. He told me so just\
now.\'94\
\
Ivan stood in the middle of the room, and still spoke in the same brooding\
tone, looking at the ground.\
\
\'93Who is _he_?\'94 asked Alyosha, involuntarily looking round.\
\
\'93He\'92s slipped away.\'94\
\
Ivan raised his head and smiled softly.\
\
\'93He was afraid of you, of a dove like you. You are a \'91pure cherub.\'92 Dmitri\
calls you a cherub. Cherub!... the thunderous rapture of the seraphim.\
What are seraphim? Perhaps a whole constellation. But perhaps that\
constellation is only a chemical molecule. There\'92s a constellation of the\
Lion and the Sun. Don\'92t you know it?\'94\
\
\'93Brother, sit down,\'94 said Alyosha in alarm. \'93For goodness\'92 sake, sit down\
on the sofa! You are delirious; put your head on the pillow, that\'92s right.\
Would you like a wet towel on your head? Perhaps it will do you good.\'94\
\
\'93Give me the towel: it\'92s here on the chair. I just threw it down there.\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s not here. Don\'92t worry yourself. I know where it is\'97here,\'94 said\
Alyosha, finding a clean towel, folded up and unused, by Ivan\'92s dressing\uc0\u8208 \
table in the other corner of the room. Ivan looked strangely at the towel:\
