\
\'93And you are quite convinced that there has been some one here?\'94 asked\
Alyosha.\
\
\'93Yes, on that sofa in the corner. You would have driven him away. You did\
drive him away: he disappeared when you arrived. I love your face,\
Alyosha. Did you know that I loved your face? And _he_ is myself, Alyosha.\
All that\'92s base in me, all that\'92s mean and contemptible. Yes, I am a\
romantic. He guessed it ... though it\'92s a libel. He is frightfully stupid;\
but it\'92s to his advantage. He has cunning, animal cunning\'97he knew how to\
infuriate me. He kept taunting me with believing in him, and that was how\
he made me listen to him. He fooled me like a boy. He told me a great deal\
that was true about myself, though. I should never have owned it to\
myself. Do you know, Alyosha,\'94 Ivan added in an intensely earnest and\
confidential tone, \'93I should be awfully glad to think that it was _he_ and\
not I.\'94\
\
\'93He has worn you out,\'94 said Alyosha, looking compassionately at his\
brother.\
\
\'93He\'92s been teasing me. And you know he does it so cleverly, so cleverly.\
\'91Conscience! What is conscience? I make it up for myself. Why am I\
tormented by it? From habit. From the universal habit of mankind for the\
seven thousand years. So let us give it up, and we shall be gods.\'92 It was\
he said that, it was he said that!\'94\
\
\'93And not you, not you?\'94 Alyosha could not help crying, looking frankly at\
his brother. \'93Never mind him, anyway; have done with him and forget him.\
And let him take with him all that you curse now, and never come back!\'94\
\
\'93Yes, but he is spiteful. He laughed at me. He was impudent, Alyosha,\'94\
Ivan said, with a shudder of offense. \'93But he was unfair to me, unfair to\
me about lots of things. He told lies about me to my face. \'91Oh, you are\
going to perform an act of heroic virtue: to confess you murdered your\
father, that the valet murdered him at your instigation.\'92 \'94\
\
\'93Brother,\'94 Alyosha interposed, \'93restrain yourself. It was not you murdered\
him. It\'92s not true!\'94\
\
\'93That\'92s what he says, he, and he knows it. \'91You are going to perform an\
act of heroic virtue, and you don\'92t believe in virtue; that\'92s what\
tortures you and makes you angry, that\'92s why you are so vindictive.\'92 He\
said that to me about me and he knows what he says.\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s you say that, not he,\'94 exclaimed Alyosha mournfully, \'93and you say it\
because you are ill and delirious, tormenting yourself.\'94\
\
\'93No, he knows what he says. \'91You are going from pride,\'92 he says. \'91You\'92ll\
stand up and say it was I killed him, and why do you writhe with horror?\
You are lying! I despise your opinion, I despise your horror!\'92 He said\
that about me. \'91And do you know you are longing for their praise\'97\'93he is a\
criminal, a murderer, but what a generous soul; he wanted to save his\
brother and he confessed.\'94 \'92 That\'92s a lie, Alyosha!\'94 Ivan cried suddenly,\
with flashing eyes. \'93I don\'92t want the low rabble to praise me, I swear I\
don\'92t! That\'92s a lie! That\'92s why I threw the glass at him and it broke\
against his ugly face.\'94\
\
\'93Brother, calm yourself, stop!\'94 Alyosha entreated him.\
\
\'93Yes, he knows how to torment one. He\'92s cruel,\'94 Ivan went on, unheeding.\
\'93I had an inkling from the first what he came for. \'91Granting that you go\
through pride, still you had a hope that Smerdyakov might be convicted and\
sent to Siberia, and Mitya would be acquitted, while you would only be\
punished with moral condemnation\'92 (\'91Do you hear?\'92 he laughed then)\'97\'91and\
some people will praise you. But now Smerdyakov\'92s dead, he has hanged\
himself, and who\'92ll believe you alone? But yet you are going, you are\
going, you\'92ll go all the same, you\'92ve decided to go. What are you going\
for now?\'92 That\'92s awful, Alyosha. I can\'92t endure such questions. Who dare\
ask me such questions?\'94\
\
\'93Brother,\'94 interposed Alyosha\'97his heart sank with terror, but he still\
seemed to hope to bring Ivan to reason\'97\'93how could he have told you of\
Smerdyakov\'92s death before I came, when no one knew of it and there was no\
time for any one to know of it?\'94\
\
\'93He told me,\'94 said Ivan firmly, refusing to admit a doubt. \'93It was all he\
did talk about, if you come to that. \'91And it would be all right if you\
believed in virtue,\'92 he said. \'91No matter if they disbelieve you, you are\
going for the sake of principle. But you are a little pig like Fyodor\
Pavlovitch, and what do you want with virtue? Why do you want to go\
meddling if your sacrifice is of no use to any one? Because you don\'92t know\
yourself why you go! Oh, you\'92d give a great deal to know yourself why you\
go! And can you have made up your mind? You\'92ve not made up your mind.\
You\'92ll sit all night deliberating whether to go or not. But you will go;\
you know you\'92ll go. You know that whichever way you decide, the decision\
does not depend on you. You\'92ll go because you won\'92t dare not to go. Why\
won\'92t you dare? You must guess that for yourself. That\'92s a riddle for\
you!\'92 He got up and went away. You came and he went. He called me a\
coward, Alyosha! _Le mot de l\'92\'e9nigme_ is that I am a coward. \'91It is not\
for such eagles to soar above the earth.\'92 It was he added that\'97he! And\
Smerdyakov said the same. He must be killed! Katya despises me. I\'92ve seen\
that for a month past. Even Lise will begin to despise me! \'91You are going\
in order to be praised.\'92 That\'92s a brutal lie! And you despise me too,\
Alyosha. Now I am going to hate you again! And I hate the monster, too! I\
hate the monster! I don\'92t want to save the monster. Let him rot in\
Siberia! He\'92s begun singing a hymn! Oh, to\uc0\u8208 morrow I\'92ll go, stand before\
them, and spit in their faces!\'94\
\
He jumped up in a frenzy, flung off the towel, and fell to pacing up and\
down the room again. Alyosha recalled what he had just said. \'93I seem to be\
sleeping awake.... I walk, I speak, I see, but I am asleep.\'94 It seemed to\
be just like that now. Alyosha did not leave him. The thought passed\
through his mind to run for a doctor, but he was afraid to leave his\
brother alone: there was no one to whom he could leave him. By degrees\
Ivan lost consciousness completely at last. He still went on talking,\
talking incessantly, but quite incoherently, and even articulated his\
words with difficulty. Suddenly he staggered violently; but Alyosha was in\
time to support him. Ivan let him lead him to his bed. Alyosha undressed\
him somehow and put him to bed. He sat watching over him for another two\
hours. The sick man slept soundly, without stirring, breathing softly and\
evenly. Alyosha took a pillow and lay down on the sofa, without\
undressing.\
\
As he fell asleep he prayed for Mitya and Ivan. He began to understand\
Ivan\'92s illness. \'93The anguish of a proud determination. An earnest\
conscience!\'94 God, in Whom he disbelieved, and His truth were gaining\
mastery over his heart, which still refused to submit. \'93Yes,\'94 the thought\
floated through Alyosha\'92s head as it lay on the pillow, \'93yes, if\
Smerdyakov is dead, no one will believe Ivan\'92s evidence; but he will go\
and give it.\'94 Alyosha smiled softly. \'93God will conquer!\'94 he thought. \'93He\
will either rise up in the light of truth, or ... he\'92ll perish in hate,\
revenging on himself and on every one his having served the cause he does\
not believe in,\'94 Alyosha added bitterly, and again he prayed for Ivan.\
\
